var __index = {"config":{"lang":["en"],"separator":"[\\s\\-]+","pipeline":["stopWordFilter"],"fields":{"title":{"boost":1000.0},"text":{"boost":1.0},"tags":{"boost":1000000.0}}},"docs":[{"location":"index.html","title":"CC4PMs Reference","text":"<p>Your companion site for Claude Code for Product Managers. Look up concepts, follow workflows, grab resources.</p> <p>This site is organized around how you'll actually use it: learn the concepts in Reference, follow step-by-step workflows in Playbooks, pick up surrounding tools in Tool Guides, internalize the mental models in Patterns, and grab ready-to-use files in Plug &amp; Play.</p> <ul> <li> <p> Reference</p> <p>Opinionated guides to every Claude Code concept: CLAUDE.md, context management, sub-agents, skills, connections, customization. Written for how PMs actually work.</p> <p> Start reading</p> </li> <li> <p> PM Playbooks</p> <p>End-to-end workflow guides: user research, competitive intel, building, data analysis, documents, meetings, your PM OS, and collaboration.</p> <p> See playbooks</p> </li> <li> <p> Tool Guides</p> <p>Technical tools Claude Code makes accessible: Git &amp; GitHub, Jupyter notebooks, diagrams and visuals. No engineering background needed.</p> <p> Open toolkit</p> </li> <li> <p> Patterns &amp; Techniques</p> <p>Cross-cutting mental models: Builder-Validator, Adversarial Review, Composable Workflows, Doc-as-Context, the Compounding System.</p> <p> See patterns</p> </li> <li> <p> Plug &amp; Play</p> <p>Grab and go. 27 skills, starter kits, templates, agent configs, hooks, and worked examples. Copy what you need.</p> <p> Browse resources</p> </li> </ul>"},{"location":"patterns/index.html","title":"Patterns &amp; Techniques","text":"<p>Cross-cutting mental models for getting more from Claude Code.</p> <p>Patterns are reusable strategies that apply across workflows. They're the thinking tools that separate someone who uses Claude Code from someone who's built a system around it. Each pattern shows up in multiple playbooks. Learning them once pays off everywhere.</p>"},{"location":"patterns/index.html#whats-here","title":"What's here","text":"<ul> <li> <p> Builder-Validator</p> <p>One agent builds. A separate agent validates with fresh context and no investment in the output being good. Quality assurance by default.</p> </li> <li> <p> Adversarial Review</p> <p>Assign Claude a hostile persona and attack your own work. Find the weaknesses before your stakeholders do.</p> </li> <li> <p> Composable Workflows</p> <p>Chain skills and agents together into pipelines. Small, focused tools that combine into powerful sequences.</p> </li> <li> <p> Doc-as-Context</p> <p>Use documents as input to Claude instead of describing things from memory. The document is the prompt.</p> </li> <li> <p> The Compounding System</p> <p>Build a workspace that gets smarter over time. Every meeting, every research cycle, every decision adds to the system's knowledge.</p> </li> <li> <p> Anti-Patterns</p> <p>Common mistakes that waste context, produce bad output, or create fragile setups. Know what to avoid.</p> </li> </ul>"},{"location":"patterns/adversarial-review.html","title":"Adversarial Review","text":"<p>Persona-based stress testing of any deliverable. Spawn parallel sub-agents loaded with specific people, not generic archetypes.</p> <p>Quick Answer</p> <p>Use this when: You have a draft deliverable (PRD, research plan, experiment brief, presentation) and want to find gaps before stakeholders do.</p> <p>Avoid this when: The draft is not structurally sound yet. Run a reverse outline or structural review first. Adversarial review is for stress-testing a solid argument, not fixing a broken one.</p> <p>What CC changes: You can spawn parallel sub-agents, each loaded with a person file and the document. Three stakeholders review your PRD simultaneously in under a minute. Without CC, you either schedule three separate pre-reads or walk into the meeting and find out what they think live.</p> <p>Default move: Build person files for your 2-3 key stakeholders. Run them against any document before the real meeting. Update the person files after each meeting so they get sharper over time.</p>"},{"location":"patterns/adversarial-review.html#the-pattern","title":"The Pattern","text":"<p>Adversarial review is not \"ask Claude to find problems.\" It is loading Claude with a specific person's perspective and having that person react to your work. Each reviewer gets their own sub-agent with their own context, and they all run in parallel.</p> <pre><code>flowchart TD\n    D[\"Your Deliverable\\n(PRD, brief, plan)\"] --&gt; A1[\"Sub-agent 1\\nLoaded with\\nlisa-chen.md\"]\n    D --&gt; A2[\"Sub-agent 2\\nLoaded with\\njames-torres.md\"]\n    D --&gt; A3[\"Sub-agent 3\\nLoaded with\\npriya-sharma.md\"]\n    A1 --&gt; R[\"Combined\\nReview Output\"]\n    A2 --&gt; R\n    A3 --&gt; R\n    R --&gt; T[\"You triage:\\nAct on / Set aside /\\nNote for meeting\"]</code></pre> <p>The key: these are not generic archetypes (\"the skeptic,\" \"the executive\"). They are specific people with specific patterns, built from real meeting data.</p>"},{"location":"patterns/adversarial-review.html#building-person-files","title":"Building Person Files","text":"<p>A person file captures how a specific stakeholder thinks, what they care about, and how they typically react. It lives in your project's <code>Knowledge/People/</code> folder.</p> <p>What goes in a person file:</p> <pre><code># Lisa Chen - VP Engineering\n\n## Role &amp; Responsibilities\nVP of Engineering. Owns the technical roadmap and eng resource allocation.\n\n## What She Cares About\n- Engineering cost and timeline above everything else\n- Wants minimum viable scope, not maximum\n- Prefers weekly check-ins over big reveals\n- Pushes back hard on vague technical requirements\n\n## Communication Style\n- Asks pointed questions, expects specific answers\n- Gets frustrated by hand-waving about \"we'll figure it out\"\n- Respects PMs who preemptively address eng concerns\n- Reads docs bottom-up (starts with timeline and resources)\n\n## Patterns From Past Meetings\n- 2024-01-15: Pushed back on wizard timeline, wanted phased rollout\n- 2024-02-03: Asked about Q3 headcount impact before anything else\n- 2024-03-10: Supported aggressive timeline when data backed it up\n</code></pre>  Bad Person File  Good Person File \"Lisa is an executive who cares about engineering\" \"Lisa reads docs bottom-up, starts with timeline, and asks 'what's the eng cost' before anything else\" Generic archetype: \"The Technical Skeptic\" Specific person with real meeting patterns Static description that never changes Updated after each meeting with new patterns Long narrative paragraphs Structured sections Claude can parse quickly"},{"location":"patterns/adversarial-review.html#running-the-review","title":"Running the Review","text":"<p>The prompt is straightforward. You point Claude at the person files and the document.</p> <pre><code>Run @lisa-chen.md, @james-torres.md, and @priya-sharma.md\nagainst @team-wizard-prd.md. Each reviews from their perspective.\n</code></pre> <p>Claude spawns three sub-agents, each loaded with one person file plus the document. They run in parallel and return reviews from each perspective.</p> <p>What you get back:</p> <ul> <li>Lisa (VP Eng): \"Timeline is aggressive for current headcount. What's the rollback plan if wizard adoption is low?\"</li> <li>James (CEO): \"Where's the competitive framing? Why this over what Linear just shipped?\"</li> <li>Priya (Head of Support): \"What happens to users mid-migration from the old invite flow? Edge case: team admin leaves during setup.\"</li> </ul>"},{"location":"patterns/adversarial-review.html#triaging-the-feedback","title":"Triaging the Feedback","text":"<p>Not every flag is worth fixing. Eight concerns does not mean eight changes. Part of your job is deciding which feedback matters and which is noise.</p> <pre><code>flowchart TD\n    F[\"Persona Flag\"] --&gt; D{Your Decision}\n    D --&gt;|\"Critical gap\"| A[\"Act on it\\nFix in the document\"]\n    D --&gt;|\"Valid but minor\"| N[\"Note for meeting\\nPrepare the answer\"]\n    D --&gt;|\"Not relevant\"| S[\"Set aside\\nKnow your reasoning\"]</code></pre> <p>Use structured triage (Claude walks through each flag and asks you for a decision: fix it, note it, or skip it): walk through each flag, decide act/note/set-aside, and document your reasoning. The reasoning matters -- when the real person raises it in the meeting, you already have your answer ready.</p>"},{"location":"patterns/adversarial-review.html#cross-domain-applications","title":"Cross-Domain Applications","text":"<p>Adversarial review works for any deliverable where stakeholders will have opinions. The pattern is the same: person files + document + parallel sub-agents.</p> Deliverable Who Reviews What They Catch PRD VP Eng, CEO, Head of Support Eng cost, strategic fit, edge cases Research plan Research lead, PM director, legal Methodology gaps, scope creep, compliance Experiment brief Data scientist, eng lead, design Statistical validity, implementation cost, UX impact Presentation The actual audience members Where the argument loses them, what questions they will ask Project proposal Budget owner, affected team leads Resource conflicts, priority alignment"},{"location":"patterns/adversarial-review.html#the-compounding-effect","title":"The Compounding Effect","text":"<p>Person files get better with use. After each real meeting, compare what the personas predicted to what actually happened. The gaps tell you what to update.</p> <pre><code>flowchart LR\n    PP[\"Persona\\nprediction\"] --&gt; M[\"Real\\nmeeting\"]\n    M --&gt; GAP[\"Gap\\nanalysis\"]\n    GAP --&gt; UP[\"Update\\nperson file\"]\n    UP --&gt; PP2[\"Better\\nprediction\\nnext time\"]</code></pre> <p>After three or four meetings, your person files know exactly what each stakeholder cares about -- not because you told them, but because the meetings told them.</p> <p>This is the connection to The Compounding System. Each cycle of predict-meet-update makes the next review more accurate. The adversarial review is not a one-shot technique. It is part of the feedback loop.</p>"},{"location":"patterns/adversarial-review.html#honest-caveat","title":"Honest Caveat","text":"<p>These are educated guesses, not mind-reading. Even imperfect personas catch things you would miss. The value is not perfect prediction. The value is structured preparation that improves with every meeting.</p>  Bad  Good \"Claude predicted exactly what Lisa would say\" \"The persona flagged eng cost, which reminded me to prepare the headcount numbers\" Treating persona output as truth Treating persona output as structured prep Never updating person files after meetings Comparing predictions to reality after every meeting"},{"location":"patterns/adversarial-review.html#plug-play","title":"Plug &amp; Play","text":"<p><code>/review-comments</code> Runs adversarial review using person files from your project context.</p> <p><code>/reality-check</code> Compares persona predictions to real meeting outcomes and generates update suggestions.</p>"},{"location":"patterns/adversarial-review.html#references","title":"References","text":"<p>Internal:</p> <ul> <li>The Compounding System : How adversarial review fits into the larger feedback loop</li> <li>Composable Workflows : Chain adversarial review with meeting aftermath processing</li> <li>Doc-as-Context : The document structure that adversarial review stress-tests</li> </ul> <p>External:</p> <ul> <li>Anthropic: Sub-agents : How parallel sub-agents work</li> <li>Anthropic: Claude Code best practices : Foundation for effective Claude Code usage</li> </ul>"},{"location":"patterns/anti-patterns.html","title":"Anti-Patterns","text":"<p>The five things to stop doing \u2014 common mistakes that waste context and produce bad output.</p> <p>Coming Soon</p> <p>This guide is under development. Check back soon.</p>"},{"location":"patterns/builder-validator.html","title":"Builder-Validator","text":"<p>One agent builds. A separate agent validates. The validator has fresh context, no memory of the trade-offs made during building, and no investment in the output being good. That's the whole pattern.</p> <p>Quick Answer</p> <p>Use this when: Output quality matters and you can't afford to ship unchecked work.</p> <p>Avoid this when: You're exploring or prototyping. Early drafts don't need validation.</p> <p>What CC changes: Sub-agents (separate Claude Code sessions you can spawn from your conversation) give you truly separate context windows. The validator literally can't see what the builder struggled with. Fresh eyes by default.</p> <p>Default move: Build in one agent, validate in a separate agent with a specific lens (\"review as VP of Sales\").</p>"},{"location":"patterns/builder-validator.html#why-it-works","title":"Why It Works","text":"<p>When Claude builds something, it accumulates context: the trade-offs it made, the shortcuts it took, the things it convinced itself were fine. If you ask it to review its own work in the same session, it's biased. It remembers why it made those choices.</p> <p>A separate agent doesn't have that baggage. It sees only the output. That's what makes the feedback useful.</p> <pre><code>flowchart LR\n    B[\"Builder\\n(full context)\"] --&gt;|output| V[\"Validator\\n(fresh context)\"]\n    V --&gt;|\"passes\"| S[Ship]\n    V --&gt;|\"feedback\"| B</code></pre> <p>The builder knows the journey. The validator only sees the destination. This is the feature, not a limitation.</p>"},{"location":"patterns/builder-validator.html#the-basic-version","title":"The Basic Version","text":"<p>Run a sub-agent to review something you just created:</p> <pre><code>I just drafted a competitive positioning brief in docs/positioning.md.\n\nSpawn a sub-agent to review it. The reviewer should evaluate as a\nVP of Sales who needs to use this in customer calls. Flag anything\nthat's too vague, too technical, or that a prospect would push\nback on.\n</code></pre> <p>That's it. Claude spawns a separate agent with its own context window. The reviewer reads only the brief and evaluates with fresh eyes.</p>"},{"location":"patterns/builder-validator.html#what-makes-a-good-validation-prompt","title":"What Makes a Good Validation Prompt","text":"<p>The validator needs two things: the output and a specific lens.</p>  Bad  Good \"Review this document\" \"Review this as a VP of Sales who needs to use it in customer calls\" \"Check for errors\" \"Verify every quote against the original transcript. Classify as VERIFIED, PARAPHRASE, or NOT FOUND\" \"Is this good?\" \"Flag anything a Series A investor would challenge in a pitch meeting\" <p>\"Review this\" is almost useless. The validator needs to know whose eyes it's looking through and what specifically to check.</p>"},{"location":"patterns/builder-validator.html#where-it-shows-up","title":"Where It Shows Up","text":"<p>The pattern applies anywhere you need quality assurance. Here are the most common PM uses:</p>"},{"location":"patterns/builder-validator.html#research-verification","title":"Research Verification","text":"<p>One agent extracts findings from interview transcripts. A separate agent checks every claim against the original source.</p> <pre><code>I have extraction files in extractions/ and original transcripts\nin transcripts/.\n\nSpawn a validator agent. For each claim in the extractions, check\nit against the original transcript. Classify each as:\n- VERIFIED: exact quote found\n- PARAPHRASE: meaning is right, wording shifted\n- NOT FOUND: can't trace it back\n\nSave the verification report to synthesis/verification.md\n</code></pre> <p>This catches hallucinated quotes, over-interpreted findings, and unsupported claims. Without verification, you might present \"findings\" that came from Claude's pattern-matching rather than from what participants actually said.</p>"},{"location":"patterns/builder-validator.html#document-review","title":"Document Review","text":"<p>One agent writes a PRD. Separate agents review from different stakeholder perspectives.</p> <pre><code>Read docs/prd-v1.md. Spawn three parallel review agents:\n\n1. Engineering lead: Flag anything unscoped, technically ambiguous,\n   or missing acceptance criteria\n2. Designer: Flag UX assumptions, missing edge cases, accessibility\n   gaps\n3. VP of Product: Flag weak prioritization rationale, missing\n   competitive context, unclear success metrics\n</code></pre> <p>Three reviews running in parallel, each with a different lens, all with fresh context. You get feedback in minutes that would normally require scheduling three meetings.</p>"},{"location":"patterns/builder-validator.html#code-review","title":"Code Review","text":"<p>One agent writes code. A separate agent reviews it with read-only permissions.</p> <pre><code>---\nname: code-reviewer\nallowed-tools: Read, Grep, Glob\n---\n\nReview the most recent changes (run git diff). Check for:\n- Unclear naming or logic\n- Missing error handling\n- Security issues (exposed secrets, injection risks)\n- Duplicated code\n- Missing tests\n</code></pre> <p>The <code>allowed-tools</code> restriction matters here. The reviewer can read and search but can't edit. It evaluates without being tempted to \"just fix it.\"</p>"},{"location":"patterns/builder-validator.html#visual-review","title":"Visual Review","text":"<p>One agent builds a page, slide deck, or UI. A separate agent takes a screenshot and reviews what it actually looks like.</p> <p>Claude Code can take screenshots of rendered pages using Playwright (a browser automation tool available as an MCP server).</p> <pre><code>Build the landing page from the spec in docs/landing-page.md.\n\nWhen you're done, take a screenshot with Playwright and spawn a\nvalidator agent. Give it the screenshot and the original spec.\nHave it check:\n- Does the visual hierarchy match the spec's priority order?\n- Is the CTA prominent enough?\n- Are there any layout issues, overlapping elements, or broken\n  responsive behavior?\n- Does it match the brand guidelines in docs/brand.md?\n</code></pre> <p>This catches problems that only show up visually. Claude can write correct HTML that still looks wrong. The validator sees the rendered output the way a user would, not the code that produced it.</p>"},{"location":"patterns/builder-validator.html#variations","title":"Variations","text":""},{"location":"patterns/builder-validator.html#single-validator","title":"Single Validator","text":"<p>The basic version. One builder, one reviewer with a specific lens. Good for most work.</p> <pre><code>flowchart LR\n    B[Builder] --&gt;|output| V[Validator]\n    V --&gt;|\"passes\"| S[Ship]\n    V --&gt;|\"feedback\"| B</code></pre>"},{"location":"patterns/builder-validator.html#multi-validator-parallel","title":"Multi-Validator (Parallel)","text":"<p>One builder, multiple reviewers running at the same time. Each reviewer checks from a different angle. Good for documents that need to survive multiple stakeholders.</p> <pre><code>flowchart TD\n    B[Builder] --&gt; V1[Sales review]\n    B --&gt; V2[Engineering review]\n    B --&gt; V3[Legal review]\n    V1 --&gt; S[Synthesize feedback]\n    V2 --&gt; S\n    V3 --&gt; S\n    S --&gt;|\"passes\"| D[Ship]\n    S --&gt;|\"feedback\"| B</code></pre>"},{"location":"patterns/builder-validator.html#staged-validation","title":"Staged Validation","text":"<p>First a strategic review (is the structure right?), then a tactical review (is the execution clean?). Don't waste time polishing something that's structurally broken.</p> <pre><code>flowchart LR\n    B[Builder] --&gt;|output| S[\"Strategic\\nreview\"]\n    S --&gt;|\"structure broken\"| B\n    S --&gt;|\"structure solid\"| T[\"Tactical\\nreview\"]\n    T --&gt;|\"needs polish\"| B\n    T --&gt;|\"clean\"| D[Ship]</code></pre> Stage What It Checks Why This Order Strategic Structure, argument, completeness No point polishing a broken structure Tactical Prose, formatting, consistency Only matters after structure is solid <pre><code>First, spawn a sub-agent to do a structural review of docs/prd-v2.md.\nCheck: Is the argument coherent? Are sections in the right order?\nIs anything missing that a VP would ask about?\n\nOnly after that passes, spawn a second sub-agent for tactical review:\ntone, formatting, consistency, and grammar.\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"patterns/builder-validator.html#verification-source-checking","title":"Verification (Source Checking)","text":"<p>A specific variant where the validator checks claims against source material. Not \"is this good?\" but \"is this true?\" Used for research findings, citations, data claims.</p>"},{"location":"patterns/builder-validator.html#when-not-to-use-it","title":"When Not to Use It","text":"<ul> <li>Exploratory work. If you're brainstorming or prototyping, validation adds overhead without value. Ship the rough draft.</li> <li>Highly iterative tasks. If you need constant back-and-forth, keep it in the main conversation. Sub-agent round trips are slower than inline revision.</li> <li>Simple tasks. If you asked Claude to rename a variable, you don't need a validator.</li> <li>When speed matters more than quality. Validation adds latency. A Slack update doesn't need three reviewers.</li> </ul> <p>The pattern is for work that ships to stakeholders, gets cited in decisions, or can't be easily corrected later.</p>"},{"location":"patterns/builder-validator.html#the-validation-hierarchy","title":"The Validation Hierarchy","text":"<p>Builder-validator is one level in a broader system. Match the level to the stakes:</p> Level What It Is When to Use It Example Quick self-review \"Review what you just wrote\" (same context) Low stakes, catching obvious gaps Internal notes, draft outlines Builder-validator Separate agent, fresh eyes, specific lens Medium-high stakes, stakeholder-facing PRDs, research findings, positioning Skills-based validation Baked into a workflow, runs automatically Repeatable processes <code>/mom-test-filter</code> checks every interview guide <p>The principle: Never ship the first draft of anything that matters.</p>"},{"location":"patterns/builder-validator.html#common-mistakes","title":"Common Mistakes","text":"Mistake What to Do Instead \"Review this\" with no lens Give the validator a specific role and criteria Validating too early Finish the draft first. Don't validate outlines Validating everything Reserve it for work that ships to stakeholders Ignoring validator feedback If you disagree, that's fine, but articulate why. The friction is the value Same-session \"validation\" Use a sub-agent. Same-session review is biased by accumulated context"},{"location":"patterns/builder-validator.html#plug-play","title":"Plug &amp; Play","text":"<p><code>/quote-verification</code> Checks extracted research claims against source transcripts. Classifies each as VERIFIED, PARAPHRASE, or NOT FOUND.</p> <p><code>/code-reviews</code> Read-only code review with a structured checklist. Evaluates recent changes without editing.</p> <p><code>/reality-check</code> Compares persona predictions against real meeting outcomes. A validator for your stakeholder models.</p>"},{"location":"patterns/builder-validator.html#references","title":"References","text":"<p>Internal:</p> <ul> <li>Sub-agents : How sub-agents work, context isolation, background execution</li> <li>Interview Analysis : Where verification is used for research rigor</li> <li>Adversarial Review : Related pattern using persona-based stress testing</li> <li>Building Skills : How to bake validation into reusable skills</li> </ul> <p>External:</p> <ul> <li>Anthropic: Sub-agents documentation : Technical details on spawning and managing sub-agents</li> <li>Anthropic: Best practices : \"Give Claude a way to verify its work\"</li> </ul>"},{"location":"patterns/composable-workflows.html","title":"Composable Workflows","text":"<p>One orchestrator skill calls focused sub-skills in sequence. Each sub-skill works independently AND as part of the chain.</p> <p>Quick Answer</p> <p>Use this when: You have a multi-step workflow where the output of each step feeds the next, and you are tired of running 4-6 separate skills and copy-pasting context between them.</p> <p>Avoid this when: The workflow has only 1-2 steps, or the steps do not share context. A simple skill handles that fine.</p> <p>What CC changes: Instead of running six separate prompts and managing context between them, one command triggers the entire cascade. Each sub-skill pulls from shared project context, so nothing lives in isolation.</p> <p>Default move: Build each step as an independent skill first. Once they all work individually, write an orchestrator that calls them in sequence.</p>"},{"location":"patterns/composable-workflows.html#the-pattern","title":"The Pattern","text":"<p>A composable workflow is one skill (the orchestrator) that calls focused sub-skills in order. Each sub-skill does one thing well. The orchestrator connects them.</p> <pre><code>flowchart TD\n    O[\"/meeting-aftermath\\n(orchestrator)\"] --&gt; S1[\"/process-transcript\"]\n    S1 --&gt; S2[\"/reality-check\"]\n    S2 --&gt; S3[\"/update-people\\n(per stakeholder)\"]\n    S3 --&gt; S4[\"/update-actions\"]\n    S4 --&gt; S5[\"/draft-followups\"]\n    S5 --&gt; S6[\"/status-update\"]\n    S6 --&gt; OUT[\"Proposed updates\\n(PM approves what to write)\"]</code></pre> <p>The critical property: each sub-skill works independently AND as part of the chain. <code>/update-people</code> works on its own when you just need to update one person's file after a quick chat. It also works inside <code>/meeting-aftermath</code> when you want to process an entire meeting.</p>"},{"location":"patterns/composable-workflows.html#manual-vs-composable","title":"Manual vs. Composable","text":"<p>Without composability, a multi-step workflow means running each skill separately and managing context between them.</p>  Bad (Manual)  Good (Composable) <code>/process-transcript</code> -- copy the output <code>/meeting-aftermath</code> -- one command <code>/reality-check</code> -- paste the transcript notes, copy output Each sub-skill reads from the previous step's output <code>/update-people</code> -- paste the reality check, run 3 times The orchestrator handles sequencing <code>/update-actions</code> -- paste from multiple sources Context flows automatically between steps <code>/draft-followups</code> -- paste action items Six steps, one prompt <code>/status-update</code> -- paste everything again 6+ separate prompts, managing context between each One command, full meeting processed"},{"location":"patterns/composable-workflows.html#the-meeting-aftermath-example","title":"The Meeting Aftermath Example","text":"<p>This is the canonical composable workflow. After any important meeting, one command processes the entire aftermath:</p> <pre><code>/meeting-aftermath CASCADE\n\n/process-transcript -- stakeholder-meeting-notes.md\n     |                 --&gt; decisions, actions, quotes\n/reality-check ------- persona predictions vs. reality\n     |                 --&gt; gap analysis per stakeholder\n/update-people ------- lisa-chen.md (+ new context)\n/update-people ------- james-torres.md (+ new context)\n/update-people ------- priya-sharma.md (+ new context)\n     |\n/update-actions ------ new items + completed items\n     |\n/draft-followups ----- Slack/email drafts per action\n     |\n/status-update ------- BLUF meeting summary\n     |\n=========================================\nPROPOSED UPDATES (PM approves what to write)\n=========================================\n</code></pre> <p>Notice the keyword: proposed. The orchestrator does not write anything automatically. It surfaces what changed and suggests updates, and you decide which ones to apply. The system proposes, you bring the judgment.</p>"},{"location":"patterns/composable-workflows.html#architecture-principles","title":"Architecture Principles","text":"<pre><code>flowchart LR\n    subgraph \"Design Principles\"\n        A[\"Each sub-skill\\nis independent\"] --&gt; B[\"Each sub-skill\\nis testable alone\"]\n        B --&gt; C[\"Output of each\\nfeeds the next\"]\n        C --&gt; D[\"Orchestrator defines\\norder, not logic\"]\n    end</code></pre> Principle What It Means Why It Matters Independence Each sub-skill works on its own You can run <code>/update-people</code> after a hallway conversation, not just inside the full cascade Focused scope Each sub-skill does one thing Easier to debug, easier to improve, easier to swap out Context flow Output of each step feeds the next The transcript extraction feeds the people updates, which feed the follow-up drafts Orchestrator is thin The orchestrator defines sequence, not logic All the real work lives in the sub-skills. The orchestrator just connects them  Bad Architecture  Good Architecture One massive skill that does everything -- transcript processing, people updates, follow-ups, status update all in one SKILL.md Orchestrator calls focused sub-skills. Each sub-skill has its own SKILL.md Sub-skills that only work inside the orchestrator Sub-skills that work independently and as part of the chain Orchestrator that contains all the logic Orchestrator that just defines the sequence and passes context Hard-coded for one specific workflow Sub-skills reusable across different orchestrators"},{"location":"patterns/composable-workflows.html#building-your-own-composable-workflow","title":"Building Your Own Composable Workflow","text":"<p>The process:</p> <ol> <li>List the steps. Write down every step in the manual workflow.</li> <li>Build each step as an independent skill. Each one reads from project context and produces a specific output.</li> <li>Test each skill alone. If it does not work standalone, it will not work in a chain.</li> <li>Write the orchestrator. A skill that calls sub-skills in sequence, passing context between them.</li> <li>Add approval gates. For any step that writes to files, surface the proposed change and let the PM decide.</li> </ol> <p>Pattern applies to any multi-step workflow:</p> Workflow Sub-skills Meeting aftermath Process transcript, reality check, update people, update actions, draft followups, status update Daily standup Calendar check, action items, project status, priorities, meeting prep Sprint planning Backlog review, capacity check, sprint goals, task breakdown, risk assessment Weekly reporting Metrics pull, project status, blockers summary, next week preview"},{"location":"patterns/composable-workflows.html#the-compounding-effect","title":"The Compounding Effect","text":"<p>Composable skills compound in two ways:</p> <ol> <li>The sub-skills improve independently. When you improve <code>/draft-followups</code>, every orchestrator that uses it benefits.</li> <li>New orchestrators reuse existing sub-skills. Your <code>/daily-standup</code> might share <code>/update-actions</code> and <code>/calendar-check</code> with <code>/meeting-aftermath</code>. Build once, compose many ways.</li> </ol> <pre><code>flowchart TD\n    MA[\"/meeting-aftermath\"] --&gt; PT[\"/process-transcript\"]\n    MA --&gt; RC[\"/reality-check\"]\n    MA --&gt; UP[\"/update-people\"]\n    MA --&gt; UA[\"/update-actions\"]\n    MA --&gt; DF[\"/draft-followups\"]\n    MA --&gt; SU[\"/status-update\"]\n\n    DS[\"/daily-standup\"] --&gt; CC[\"/calendar-check\"]\n    DS --&gt; UA\n    DS --&gt; PS[\"/project-status\"]\n    DS --&gt; PR[\"/priorities\"]\n\n    style UA fill:#fff4f0,stroke:#f74a4a</code></pre> <p><code>/update-actions</code> appears in both workflows. One skill, two orchestrators, zero duplication.</p>"},{"location":"patterns/composable-workflows.html#plug-play","title":"Plug &amp; Play","text":"<p><code>/meeting-aftermath</code> The canonical composable workflow. Processes an entire meeting into structured updates.</p> <p><code>/draft-followups</code> Drafts follow-up messages from meeting outcomes. Works standalone or as part of <code>/meeting-aftermath</code>.</p> <p><code>/update-people</code> Updates person files with new context from meetings or conversations.</p>"},{"location":"patterns/composable-workflows.html#references","title":"References","text":"<p>Internal:</p> <ul> <li>Adversarial Review : Sub-agents for parallel review (a different kind of composition)</li> <li>The Compounding System : How composable workflows feed the larger feedback loop</li> <li>Building Skills : Fundamentals of skill architecture</li> </ul> <p>External:</p> <ul> <li>Anthropic: Skills : Official skills documentation</li> <li>Anthropic: Sub-agents : How sub-agents work for parallel execution</li> </ul>"},{"location":"patterns/doc-as-context.html","title":"Doc-as-Context","text":"<p>Point Claude at a document and it understands the analysis task. The brief, spec, or plan becomes the interface for recurring work.</p> <p>Quick Answer</p> <p>Use this when: You have an existing document (launch brief, experiment brief, spec) that defines what you care about, and you want Claude to use it as the operating context for analysis.</p> <p>Avoid this when: You do not have a structured document yet. Write the brief first. The document quality determines the analysis quality.</p> <p>What CC changes: Instead of re-explaining what you are measuring and why every time you want an update, you point Claude at one document and it already knows the metrics, data sources, guardrails, and success criteria. The document IS the interface.</p> <p>Default move: Write a brief that defines success metrics, data sources, and guardrails. Point Claude at the brief plus fresh data. Get a structured analysis scoped to exactly what matters.</p>"},{"location":"patterns/doc-as-context.html#the-pattern","title":"The Pattern","text":"<p>Most PMs re-explain context every time they ask Claude for help. \"We launched Growth two weeks ago, the success metrics are adoption, retention, engagement, revenue, and we also need to watch overall conversion as a guardrail...\" Every time.</p> <p>Doc-as-context eliminates this. You point Claude at a document you already have, and the document provides all the context.</p> <pre><code>flowchart LR\n    DOC[\"Your document\\n(brief, spec, plan)\"] --&gt; CLAUDE[\"Claude reads it\\nUnderstands what\\nto measure\"]\n    DATA[\"Fresh data\\n(.csv, .json)\"] --&gt; CLAUDE\n    CLAUDE --&gt; OUT[\"Structured analysis\\nalready scoped to\\nwhat matters\"]</code></pre> <pre><code>brief.md        \"success = adoption, retention,\n                  engagement, revenue\"\n     +\ndata.csv         450 rows of usage data\n     =\nnotebook.ipynb   structured analysis, already scoped\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"patterns/doc-as-context.html#two-variants","title":"Two Variants","text":"<p>Doc-as-context shows up in two forms. Both use the same principle (the document is the interface), but they serve different purposes.</p>"},{"location":"patterns/doc-as-context.html#variant-1-doc-as-input","title":"Variant 1: Doc-as-Input","text":"<p>You have a document that defines an analysis. You pair it with data and get a structured output.</p> <p>Example: Launch brief plus usage data</p> <pre><code>Load @usage-data.csv and create a launch review notebook\nbased on the analysis plan from @growth-launch-brief.md\n</code></pre> <p>Claude reads the brief, finds the success metrics and guardrails, and builds a notebook that evaluates each one against the data. You did not have to re-specify what \"good\" looks like. The brief already defined it.</p>  Bad (No Document Context)  Good (Doc-as-Input) \"Analyze this CSV. Look at adoption, retention, engagement, and revenue. Also check if overall conversion dropped.\" \"Create a launch review based on @growth-launch-brief.md and @usage-data.csv\" You re-explain the analysis plan every time The document carries the plan. You just add fresh data Easy to forget a metric or guardrail All metrics and guardrails are in the brief. Nothing gets missed Different analysis each time depending on what you remember to ask Consistent, structured analysis anchored to the same definitions"},{"location":"patterns/doc-as-context.html#variant-2-doc-as-interface","title":"Variant 2: Doc-as-Interface","text":"<p>The document is not just input for one analysis. It is the persistent interface for recurring check-ins. Every time you want an update, you point Claude at the same document and fresh data.</p> <p>Example: Experiment brief plus weekly data</p> <pre><code>Run a full check-in on the experiment using\n@experiment-brief.md and @week2-experiment-update.csv\n</code></pre> <pre><code>flowchart TD\n    EB[\"experiment-brief.md\"] --&gt; |\"Defines\"| H[\"Hypothesis\"]\n    EB --&gt; |\"Defines\"| M[\"Metrics\\n(primary, secondary,\\nguardrails)\"]\n    EB --&gt; |\"Defines\"| DS[\"Data sources\\n(where to look)\"]\n    EB --&gt; |\"Defines\"| SC[\"Success criteria\\n(when to ship/kill)\"]\n\n    M --&gt; CI[\"Contextual\\nCheck-in\"]\n    DS --&gt; CI\n    SC --&gt; CI\n    DATA[\"Fresh weekly\\ndata\"] --&gt; CI\n\n    CI --&gt; OUT[\"Standard metrics\\n+ support tickets\\n+ cancellation patterns\\n+ segmentation\"]</code></pre> <p>The brief's monitoring plan section lists specific data sources: experiment metrics, support ticket trends, cancellation reason patterns, segmentation cuts. That is what makes this a contextual check-in instead of just a dashboard refresh.</p>  Bad (Dashboard)  Good (Doc-as-Interface) Shows you what you asked to see Shows you what you need to know \"Here's your graph\" \"Here's your graph. Confusion tickets are down in treatment. Stronger for Growth trials. The mechanism is working.\" One data source, one view Multiple data sources cross-referenced in context You interpret Claude interprets, then you decide"},{"location":"patterns/doc-as-context.html#what-makes-the-document-good","title":"What Makes the Document Good","text":"<p>The quality of your analysis depends entirely on the quality of the document. A vague brief produces a vague analysis. A specific brief produces a specific, useful one.</p> Element Why It Matters Success metrics with baselines Claude knows what \"good\" looks like and can compare Guardrail metrics Things that should NOT get worse. Claude checks them proactively Data sources Claude knows where to look, not just what to measure Decision criteria Ship/extend/kill thresholds. Claude can tell you if you are there <pre><code>flowchart TD\n    B[\"Brief Quality\"] --&gt; A[\"Analysis Quality\"]\n\n    subgraph \"What goes in the brief\"\n        SM[\"Success metrics\\n+ baselines\"]\n        GM[\"Guardrail metrics\"]\n        DS2[\"Data sources\"]\n        DC[\"Decision criteria\"]\n    end\n\n    SM --&gt; B\n    GM --&gt; B\n    DS2 --&gt; B\n    DC --&gt; B</code></pre>"},{"location":"patterns/doc-as-context.html#cross-domain-applications","title":"Cross-Domain Applications","text":"<p>Doc-as-context works for any recurring analysis where a document defines what you care about.</p> Document Data Source What You Get Launch brief Usage CSV Structured launch review with guardrail checks Experiment brief Weekly experiment data Contextual check-in with cross-source analysis OKR doc Weekly metrics Progress report scoped to actual objectives Research plan Interview transcripts Analysis structured around research questions Sprint plan Jira export, velocity data Sprint health check against commitments"},{"location":"patterns/doc-as-context.html#the-automation-path","title":"The Automation Path","text":"<p>Doc-as-interface naturally leads to automation. If the check-in is the same document plus fresh data every time, you can schedule it.</p> <pre><code>Manual:     You run the check-in when you remember\nPrompted:   You run it daily as part of your standup\nAutomated:  A GitHub Action runs it every morning and\n            posts the summary to Slack before you open\n            your laptop\n</code></pre> <p>The trajectory: from \"I check on my experiment\" to \"my experiment checks in with me.\"</p>"},{"location":"patterns/doc-as-context.html#plug-play","title":"Plug &amp; Play","text":"<p><code>/experiment-check</code> Runs a contextual check-in against any experiment brief. Reads the brief, pulls from the defined data sources, cross-references support tickets and cancellation patterns.</p> <p>Components: Templates Launch review template, experiment brief template, and other structured documents that work as doc-as-context interfaces.</p>"},{"location":"patterns/doc-as-context.html#references","title":"References","text":"<p>Internal:</p> <ul> <li>Composable Workflows : Chain doc-as-context analysis into larger workflows</li> <li>Adversarial Review : Stress-test the documents you build with this pattern</li> <li>The Compounding System : How documents improve over time through use</li> <li>Jupyter Notebooks : The trust layer for data analysis output</li> </ul> <p>External:</p> <ul> <li>Anthropic: Claude Code best practices : Context management principles</li> <li>Anthropic: Skills : How skills reference documents as context</li> </ul>"},{"location":"patterns/inversion-pattern.html","title":"The Inversion Pattern","text":"<p>The tool prompts you before generating \u2014 flipping the dynamic for better output.</p> <p>Coming Soon</p> <p>This guide is under development. Check back soon.</p>"},{"location":"patterns/the-compounding-system.html","title":"The Compounding System","text":"<p>The meta-principle: each cycle makes the system smarter. Think, show, loop, think better.</p> <p>Quick Answer</p> <p>Use this when: You want to understand why the whole system works, not just individual techniques.</p> <p>Avoid this when: You are looking for a specific technique. Start with Adversarial Review, Composable Workflows, or Doc-as-Context instead.</p> <p>What CC changes: Without Claude Code, learning stays trapped in your head or in scattered notes. With CC, every cycle feeds back into persistent artifacts (person files, templates, skills) that make the next cycle better automatically.</p> <p>Default move: After any significant piece of work, ask: what did I learn that should flow back into the system? Update the relevant person file, template, or skill.</p>"},{"location":"patterns/the-compounding-system.html#the-loop","title":"The Loop","text":"<p>Every pattern in this section connects to a single idea: the system gets smarter with every cycle. Not because the AI improves on its own, but because you feed real outcomes back into the artifacts that drive the next round.</p> <pre><code>flowchart LR\n    T[\"Think\\nBuild the argument\"] --&gt; S[\"Show\\nMake it visible\"]\n    S --&gt; L[\"Loop\\nProcess real outcomes\"]\n    L --&gt; T2[\"Think (better)\\nSharper next time\"]\n    T2 --&gt; S2[\"Show (better)\"]\n    S2 --&gt; L2[\"Loop (better)\"]\n    L2 --&gt; T3[\"...\"]\n\n    style L fill:#fff4f0,stroke:#f74a4a\n    style L2 fill:#fff4f0,stroke:#f74a4a</code></pre> <pre><code>Think --&gt; Show --&gt; Loop --&gt; Think (better)\n\nEach revolution:\n  - Person files get sharper\n  - Templates capture what worked\n  - Skills refine their logic\n  - Your OS learns from use\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"patterns/the-compounding-system.html#where-compounding-happens","title":"Where Compounding Happens","text":"<p>Compounding is not abstract. It happens in specific, concrete places.</p>"},{"location":"patterns/the-compounding-system.html#persona-calibration","title":"Persona Calibration","text":"<p>Person files start as educated guesses. After each real meeting, you compare predictions to what actually happened. The gaps update the files.</p> <pre><code>flowchart TD\n    PF1[\"Person file v1\\n(educated guess)\"] --&gt; PR[\"Persona\\nprediction\"]\n    PR --&gt; MT[\"Real\\nmeeting\"]\n    MT --&gt; GA[\"Gap\\nanalysis\"]\n    GA --&gt; PF2[\"Person file v2\\n(meeting-calibrated)\"]\n    PF2 --&gt; PR2[\"Better\\nprediction\"]\n    PR2 --&gt; MT2[\"Next\\nmeeting\"]\n    MT2 --&gt; GA2[\"Smaller\\ngaps\"]\n    GA2 --&gt; PF3[\"Person file v3\\n(pattern-accurate)\"]</code></pre> <p>After three or four meetings, the system knows what each person cares about -- not because you told it, but because the meetings told it.</p>"},{"location":"patterns/the-compounding-system.html#skill-refinement","title":"Skill Refinement","text":"<p>Skills improve through use. You run a skill, notice an edge case, fix it. The fix benefits every future run.</p> Cycle What Happens Result First run Skill works but misses edge case X You notice and fix the skill Second run Edge case X handled. New pattern Y surfaces You add handling for Y Fifth run Skill covers all common patterns You focus on rare cases Tenth run Skill handles 95% of scenarios correctly Minimal intervention needed"},{"location":"patterns/the-compounding-system.html#template-evolution","title":"Template Evolution","text":"<p>Templates capture what worked. After each document you write, the patterns that landed well get encoded into the template for next time.</p>  Bad (Static Template)  Good (Evolving Template) Generic PRD template downloaded from the internet Template enriched with patterns extracted from your team's best PRDs Same template forever, regardless of what works Template updated after each successful document Blank sections with no guidance Sections with collaborative prompts that push your thinking"},{"location":"patterns/the-compounding-system.html#os-evolution","title":"OS Evolution","text":"<p>Your entire operating system evolves: CLAUDE.md captures new preferences, folder structures adapt to how you actually work, rules tighten based on repeated mistakes.</p>"},{"location":"patterns/the-compounding-system.html#the-full-cycle-in-practice","title":"The Full Cycle in Practice","text":"<p>Here is how the cycle plays out across a real PM workflow:</p> <pre><code>flowchart TD\n    subgraph \"Think\"\n        PE[\"Extract patterns\\nfrom past PRDs\"] --&gt; TE[\"Enrich\\ntemplate\"]\n        TE --&gt; DR[\"Draft PRD via\\ntemplate interview\"]\n        DR --&gt; RO[\"Reverse outline\\n(structural check)\"]\n        RO --&gt; CM[\"{{comment}} refinement\\n(surgical edits)\"]\n        CM --&gt; AR[\"Adversarial review\\n(persona panel)\"]\n    end\n\n    subgraph \"Show\"\n        AR --&gt; MM[\"Mermaid diagrams\\nin the document\"]\n        MM --&gt; SL[\"Slide deck\\nfor the meeting\"]\n    end\n\n    subgraph \"Loop\"\n        SL --&gt; MT2[\"Real meeting\\nhappens\"]\n        MT2 --&gt; MA[\"/meeting-aftermath\"]\n        MA --&gt; UP[\"Update people files\\nfrom real reactions\"]\n        UP --&gt; UA[\"Update action items\"]\n        UA --&gt; DF[\"Draft follow-ups\"]\n    end\n\n    DF --&gt; |\"Next document\\nstarts from better\\nperson files and\\nshaper template\"| PE</code></pre> <p>Each full cycle produces: - A better template (patterns from what worked) - Sharper person files (calibrated from real meetings) - Refined skills (edge cases fixed) - Accumulated project context (decisions, rationale, outcomes)</p>"},{"location":"patterns/the-compounding-system.html#the-anti-pattern-linear-growth","title":"The Anti-Pattern: Linear Growth","text":"<p>Without the feedback loop, your system grows but does not compound. You accumulate more skills and more files, but none of them get better.</p> Linear Growth Compounding Growth 10 skills that each work the same as day one 5 skills that each improve with every use Person files that were guesses on day one and are still guesses Person files calibrated from real meeting data Templates downloaded from the internet Templates enriched with your team's actual patterns More stuff, same quality Same stuff, better quality <p>The compounding system is not about building more. It is about building things that learn from use.</p>"},{"location":"patterns/the-compounding-system.html#making-it-practical","title":"Making It Practical","text":"<p>You do not need to formalize every feedback loop on day one. Start with the highest-value cycle and expand from there.</p> <p>Start here: After your next important meeting, run the comparison: what did the personas predict vs. what actually happened? Update the person files with the gaps. That single habit creates the most valuable compounding loop.</p> <p>Expand to: After shipping a document, note what sections landed well and what got pushback. Update the template.</p> <p>Eventually: The end-of-session habit. Ask Claude: \"Based on what we just did, is there anything we should update in CLAUDE.md or any cleanup you'd suggest?\" Ten seconds. Your OS learns from use.</p>"},{"location":"patterns/the-compounding-system.html#plug-play","title":"Plug &amp; Play","text":"<p><code>/meeting-aftermath</code> The composable workflow that closes the meeting feedback loop. Processes transcript, compares predictions, updates person files.</p> <p><code>/reality-check</code> Compares persona predictions to real outcomes. The core of the persona calibration cycle.</p>"},{"location":"patterns/the-compounding-system.html#references","title":"References","text":"<p>Internal:</p> <ul> <li>Adversarial Review : Persona-based review that compounds through calibration</li> <li>Composable Workflows : The /meeting-aftermath cascade that closes the loop</li> <li>Doc-as-Context : Documents that serve as persistent analytical interfaces</li> <li>Your PM OS : The personal system that evolves through the compounding loop</li> </ul> <p>External:</p> <ul> <li>Anthropic: Claude Code best practices : Context management and iterative improvement</li> </ul>"},{"location":"playbooks/index.html","title":"PM Playbooks","text":"<p>End-to-end workflow guides that show how Claude Code fits into real PM work.</p> <p>Playbooks are complete workflows. Not isolated features, but the full arc from problem to output. Each one walks through a PM scenario and shows how Claude Code accelerates every step.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/index.html#whats-here","title":"What's here","text":"<ul> <li> <p> User Research</p> <p>Design studies, run interviews, analyze transcripts, and synthesize findings. The full research arc.</p> <p>Includes: Research Design | Interview Analysis | Survey &amp; Feedback | Research Synthesis</p> </li> <li> <p> Competitive Intelligence</p> <p>From competitor names to a structured landscape brief. Web research, review scraping, and analysis in one pipeline.</p> </li> <li> <p> Building</p> <p>PMs who build. Explore codebases, modify features, add new ones, ship code.</p> <p>Includes: Exploring Codebases | Modifying &amp; Improving | Adding Features | Shipping Code</p> </li> <li> <p> Data &amp; Analysis</p> <p>Turn raw data into decisions. Analytics, experiments, and building a data-driven case.</p> </li> <li> <p> Creating Documents</p> <p>PRDs, briefs, proposals, and any document a PM needs to produce.</p> </li> <li> <p> Presentations &amp; Visuals</p> <p>Build slide decks and visual artifacts directly in Claude Code.</p> </li> <li> <p> Meeting Processing</p> <p>One command turns a meeting transcript into structured notes, action items, follow-ups, and status updates.</p> </li> <li> <p> Your PM OS</p> <p>Build a personal operating system: people files, action tracking, rituals, and a workspace that compounds over time.</p> </li> <li> <p> Collaboration</p> <p>Share your setup, build team toolkits, drive adoption, and handle governance.</p> </li> </ul>"},{"location":"playbooks/competitive-intelligence.html","title":"Competitive Intelligence","text":"<p>Competitive intelligence answers: what's the market actually doing? Not what competitors say on their marketing pages, but what their customers experience, what they charge, and where they fall short. Claude Code turns this from a weeks-long project into an afternoon.</p> <p>Quick Answer</p> <p>Use this when: You need to understand the competitive landscape, identify positioning gaps, or build honest battlecards.</p> <p>Avoid this when: You need to understand your own users. That's User Research.</p> <p>What CC changes: You can scrape and analyze hundreds of customer reviews, verify claims against primary sources, and segment findings by company size, all in one session.</p> <p>Default move: Start with your research questions. Only collect competitor data that answers a specific question you have.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/competitive-intelligence.html#the-pipeline","title":"The Pipeline","text":"<p>Competitive research without a plan is just browsing. Start with the questions you need answered, then work through five phases:</p> <pre><code>flowchart LR\n    D[\"Discover\\n(web research)\"] --&gt; C[\"Curate\\n(extraction template)\"]\n    C --&gt; E[\"Extract\\n(scrape + segment)\"]\n    E --&gt; A[\"Analyze\\n(code themes)\"]\n    A --&gt; S[\"Synthesize\\n(gap analysis)\"]</code></pre>"},{"location":"playbooks/competitive-intelligence.html#1-discover","title":"1. Discover","text":"<p>Use web research to find what competitors say about themselves. Target primary sources: pricing pages, official docs, changelogs, enterprise feature lists. Not blog posts about them.</p> <p>Exa is an AI-powered search engine available as an MCP server in Claude Code. It targets primary sources over SEO content.</p> <pre><code>Research [Competitor] using Exa. Focus on primary sources:\n- Current pricing page (per-seat costs by tier)\n- Enterprise feature list (what's gated behind higher tiers)\n- Recent changelog (what they've shipped in the last 6 months)\n- Official docs on [specific feature area]\n\nFor each claim, note the source URL and date accessed.\n</code></pre> <p>CC Limitation</p> <p>Claude Code has no way to tell if a pricing page is current or cached from 6 months ago. Always check the date and verify against a second source. Marketing pages describe aspirational positioning, not reality.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/competitive-intelligence.html#2-curate","title":"2. Curate","text":"<p>Don't collect everything. Build an extraction template tied to your actual research questions.</p> Research Question What to Extract Source What do competitors gate behind enterprise tiers? Feature comparison by tier Pricing pages, docs What do mid-market teams actually pay? Per-seat pricing, tier jump multipliers Pricing pages, G2 Where do competitor customers complain most? Review cons, grouped by theme G2 reviews How do competitors position themselves? Taglines, target customer language Homepage, about page <p>If a data point doesn't map to a research question, don't collect it.</p> <p>This table IS your extraction template. Save it as <code>competitive-extraction-template.md</code> in your project folder and point Claude at it when you start research.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/competitive-intelligence.html#3-extract-and-segment","title":"3. Extract and Segment","text":"<p>Scrape customer review data and segment it to your target audience.</p> <p>Apify is a web scraping platform available as an MCP server. It can pull structured review data from sites like G2.</p> <pre><code>Use Apify to scrape G2 reviews for [Competitor]. Pull reviews with\ncompany size, job title, date, star rating, pros, and cons fields.\n\nFilter to mid-market reviews only (51-1000 employees). Save the\nfiltered dataset to data/[competitor]-midmarket-reviews.csv\n</code></pre> <p>Why segmentation matters: A 10-person startup's complaint about onboarding is nothing like a 500-person company's complaint about SSO. Raw reviews mix these together. Filtering to your target segment (e.g., mid-market) gives you signal instead of noise.</p>  Bad  Good Analyze all 200 reviews together Filter to your target segment first (e.g., mid-market 51-1000 employees), then analyze the 30-40 that match \"Users say onboarding is hard\" \"Mid-market teams (50-200 people) consistently cite configuration overhead as the top complaint, appearing in 14 of 32 reviews\""},{"location":"playbooks/competitive-intelligence.html#4-analyze","title":"4. Analyze","text":"<p>Apply inductive coding to the review data. Let themes emerge from the data instead of searching for what you expect to find.</p> <pre><code>Read the filtered reviews in data/[competitor]-midmarket-reviews.csv.\n\nCode the \"cons\" field inductively. Don't use preset categories.\nRead each con, create a code that captures what the reviewer is\nactually saying. Group similar codes as you go.\n\nFor each code, note:\n- How many reviews mention it\n- Representative quotes\n- Intensity (mild annoyance vs. deal-breaker language)\n</code></pre> <p>This is the same inductive coding technique from Survey &amp; Feedback Analysis, applied to competitor review data. If you've done it before, the process is identical, just a different data source.</p> <p>Real example: Coding Jira mid-market reviews might surface:</p> <ul> <li>Configuration Overhead (14 mentions) : too complex to set up and maintain</li> <li>Admin Tax (11 mentions) : requires dedicated Jira administrators</li> <li>Cost at Scale (9 mentions) : pricing gets painful as team grows</li> <li>UX Complexity (8 mentions) : non-technical team members struggle</li> </ul> <p>These codes weren't predetermined. They emerged from what reviewers actually said.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/competitive-intelligence.html#5-synthesize","title":"5. Synthesize","text":"<p>Map competitive findings back to your own user research to find convergence.</p> <pre><code>flowchart TD\n    I[\"Your interview data\"] --&gt; C{Convergence?}\n    S[\"Your survey data\"] --&gt; C\n    R[\"Competitor review data\"] --&gt; C\n    C --&gt;|\"3 sources agree\"| H[\"High-conviction finding\"]\n    C --&gt;|\"1-2 sources\"| M[\"Needs more evidence\"]</code></pre> <p>When three independent data sources point at the same gap, that's a real finding:</p> <ul> <li>Interview signal: Your users say \"we need SSO but it costs too much\"</li> <li>Survey signal: 68% want your product, but only 12% will pay 3x for enterprise features</li> <li>Competitive signal: Every major competitor gates SSO behind enterprise tier, forcing a 3x price jump</li> </ul> <p>One source is a hypothesis. Three sources pointing the same direction is evidence.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/competitive-intelligence.html#confidence-scoring","title":"Confidence Scoring","text":"<p>Every competitive claim gets tagged. This prevents hallucinated findings from looking as credible as verified ones.</p> Level Criteria Example HIGH Company's own website + confirmed by independent source \"Asana charges $30.49/seat for Enterprise\" (pricing page + G2 listing) MEDIUM Single credible primary source, no independent confirmation \"Linear targets engineering-first teams\" (their homepage says it) LOW Blog posts, analyst opinions without data, reviews older than 18 months \"Monday is losing enterprise market share\" (one analyst blog) <p>If the same claim appears in two independent sources, upgrade one tier. A G2 review confirming a pricing page claim moves from MEDIUM to HIGH.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/competitive-intelligence.html#outputs","title":"Outputs","text":"<p>A complete competitive analysis produces:</p> <ul> <li>Positioning map : what competitors say vs. what evidence shows (often different)</li> <li>Pricing comparison : per-seat costs by tier, price jump multipliers</li> <li>Feature tier matrix : which features gated behind which tiers</li> <li>Gap analysis : structural market gaps mapped to your own user evidence</li> <li>Battlecards : one-pager per competitor with honest comparison (including where they win)</li> </ul> <pre><code>## Battlecard: [Competitor Name]\n\n| Dimension | Details |\n|-----------|---------|\n| **Where they win** | [their genuine strengths] |\n| **Where we win** | [our genuine advantages] |\n| **Key differentiator** | [the one thing that matters most] |\n| **Their ideal customer** | [who they're best for] |\n| **Landmine question** | [the question a prospect might ask that favors them] |\n| **Our response** | [honest answer to the landmine] |\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"playbooks/competitive-intelligence.html#common-mistakes","title":"Common Mistakes","text":"Mistake What to Do Instead Collecting everything Only extract data that answers a specific research question Analyzing unsegmented reviews Filter to your target segment first. Mixed-segment findings are meaningless Treating marketing as truth Pricing pages and positioning are aspirational. Verify with customer reviews and third-party data Skipping confidence scoring Tag every claim HIGH/MEDIUM/LOW. Untagged findings all look equally credible Competitive research in isolation Cross-reference with your own user research. Convergence across sources is what makes findings defensible Preset categories for coding Let themes emerge inductively. Searching for \"pricing complaints\" will find pricing complaints whether they're real or not"},{"location":"playbooks/competitive-intelligence.html#plug-play","title":"Plug &amp; Play","text":"<p><code>/competitive-intel</code> Full pipeline: web research, review scraping, segmentation, coding, and synthesis in one orchestrated workflow.</p> <p><code>/scrape-reviews</code> Scrapes G2 reviews for a given product using Apify. Returns structured data with company size, ratings, pros, and cons.</p> <p><code>/segment-reviews</code> Filters scraped reviews by company size to your target segment. Produces a clean dataset for analysis.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/competitive-intelligence.html#references","title":"References","text":"<p>Internal:</p> <ul> <li>User Research : Understanding your own users (the complement to competitive research)</li> <li>Survey &amp; Feedback Analysis : Inductive coding methodology (same technique applied here)</li> <li>Research Synthesis : Combining competitive findings with user research</li> <li>Builder-Validator : The verification pattern used to check extracted claims</li> </ul> <p>External:</p> <ul> <li>The Practical Guide to Competitive Research for Product &amp; GTM Teams : Aatir Abdul Rauf's walkthrough of channels, tools, and processes</li> <li>How to Do Competitor Analysis Using Online Reviews : Practical framework for mining review data</li> <li>Competitive Analysis for Product Managers : Complete guide from Plane covering frameworks and templates</li> <li>G2 Review Platform : Primary source for B2B SaaS customer reviews with structured metadata</li> <li>Exa AI Search : Relevance-scored web search that targets primary sources over SEO content</li> <li>Obviously Awesome by April Dunford : The book on positioning strategy informed by competitive context</li> </ul>"},{"location":"playbooks/creating-documents.html","title":"Creating Documents","text":"<p>Creating documents with Claude Code is not about generating a first draft faster. It's about building a system where templates push your thinking, exemplars define your quality bar, and every document you ship makes the next one better. The methodology: extract patterns from docs that worked, enrich your templates so they ask hard questions, draft through an interactive interview, then stress-test with structural review and calibrated personas.</p> <p>Quick Answer</p> <p>Use this when: You need to write a PRD, spec, brief, decision doc, or any artifact where the thinking matters more than the formatting.</p> <p>Avoid this when: You need a quick one-off draft with no reuse potential. Just ask CC directly.</p> <p>What CC changes: Templates become interactive tools that push your thinking, not blank forms to fill. Pattern extraction captures your team's implicit quality standards. Adversarial personas catch stakeholder objections before the meeting.</p> <p>Default move: If you have a template, enrich it. If you don't, build a skeleton first. Either way, structure before content.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/creating-documents.html#the-document-system","title":"The Document System","text":"<p>Seven techniques, one continuous process. Each step builds on the last.</p> <pre><code>flowchart TD\n    PE[\"1. Pattern Extraction\\nLearn from what worked\"] --&gt; TE[\"2. Template Enrichment\\nUpgrade the template\"]\n    TE --&gt; TI[\"3. Template-Driven Interview\\nDraft through conversation\"]\n    TI --&gt; RO[\"4. Reverse Outline\\nCheck the structure\"]\n    RO --&gt; CC[\"5. {{comment}} Refinement\\nSurgical edits\"]\n    CC --&gt; PE2[\"6. Progressive Elaboration\\n(no template path)\"]\n    CC --&gt; AR[\"7. Adversarial Review\\nStakeholder stress-test\"]</code></pre> <p>You don't always need all seven. Pattern extraction and template enrichment happen once per template type. The interview, reverse outline, comment refinement, and adversarial review happen per document. Progressive elaboration is the path when you don't have a template at all.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/creating-documents.html#pattern-extraction-learn-from-what-works","title":"Pattern Extraction: Learn From What Works","text":"<p>Before building a template from scratch, figure out what already works at your company. Feed CC three or more documents of the same type that actually landed with stakeholders, and extract the patterns that made them effective.</p> <p>These guide files ship with the course in Plug &amp; Play. You can also create your own by saving extraction criteria to a markdown file and referencing it with <code>@</code>.</p> <pre><code>Run @pattern-extraction-guide.md against @example-prd-1.md,\n@example-prd-2.md, and @example-prd-3.md. Save the patterns.\n</code></pre> <p>CC analyzes each document for how it frames problems, handles specificity, surfaces assumptions, defines metrics, and structures scope decisions. The output is a pattern synthesis: what your specific team responds to, not generic best practices.</p>  Bad  Good Download a generic PRD template from the internet Extract patterns from 3 PRDs that actually got approved at your company \"PRDs should have a problem statement\" \"Your approved PRDs lead with quantified pain, include 'not doing this costs X,' and scope decisions are justified, not just stated\" Assume what stakeholders want Let the evidence from past approvals tell you <p>Why this matters: Generic PRD templates are everywhere. The value is YOUR team's patterns. What got approved, what landed with your specific stakeholders. That's worth more than any template you'd download.</p> <p>CC Advantage</p> <p>Pattern extraction uses sub-agents to analyze each exemplar independently, then synthesizes across them. Same parallel isolation pattern as interview analysis. Each document gets analyzed without being influenced by the others.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/creating-documents.html#ai-native-template-enrichment","title":"AI-Native Template Enrichment","text":"<p>A standard template has blank sections with labels. An AI-native template has two kinds of prompts in each section:</p> <ol> <li>Data-pull prompts that CC answers from your project files</li> <li>Judgment-call prompts that CC asks you directly</li> </ol> <p>The template stops being a form and starts pushing back on your thinking.</p>  Bad (Standard Template)  Good (Enriched Template) Problem Statement: Describe the problem. Problem Statement: [Data pull] What specific workflow breaks? What metrics quantify the impact? [Judgment] What happens if we don't fix this in the next quarter? Success Metrics: List metrics. Success Metrics: [Data pull] What's the current baseline from recent analysis? [Judgment] What improvement would make this worth the engineering investment? What's your confidence in that target? Scope: Define what's in and out. Scope: [Judgment] What's the smallest version that tests the hypothesis? What are you explicitly choosing NOT to build, and why? <pre><code>Run @template-enrichment-guide.md against @prd-template.md\nusing @pattern-synthesis.md. Save it.\n</code></pre> <p>CC takes the patterns from your exemplars and embeds them as prompts in the template. Every section now asks the questions that your best documents answered well.</p> <p>The compounding effect: The enriched template gets better over time. Each document you write through it reveals new patterns. Each adversarial review reveals new questions the template should ask. The template evolves.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/creating-documents.html#template-driven-interview","title":"Template-Driven Interview","text":"<p>Running the enriched template is a conversation, not a fill-in-the-blank exercise. CC does two things simultaneously:</p> <ul> <li>Interviews you for the judgment calls (problem framing, scope decisions, non-goals)</li> <li>Pulls from your project files for the evidence (user segments, metric baselines, behavioral data)</li> </ul> <pre><code>flowchart TD\n    TP[\"Template prompt\"] --&gt; JC{\"Type?\"}\n    JC --&gt;|Judgment call| AUQ[\"CC asks you\\n'What's the smallest version\\nthat tests the hypothesis?'\"]\n    JC --&gt;|Data question| CTX[\"CC reads project files\\nExperiment results, notebooks,\\nkickoff notes\"]\n    AUQ --&gt; SEC[\"Section content\\n(your thinking + evidence)\"]\n    CTX --&gt; SEC</code></pre> <pre><code>Run @prd-template.md for the team setup wizard. Interview me\nfor the judgment calls, pull from @my-notes.md, @experiment-brief.md,\nand the analysis notebooks for the data sections.\n</code></pre> <p>You're not staring at a blank doc trying to remember what the experiment showed. The template pulls evidence while you focus on the decisions that require your judgment.</p>  Bad  Good Stare at blank section, try to remember the data Template pulls metrics from notebooks while interviewing you about scope Write the whole thing yourself, then ask CC to \"review\" CC drafts each section from your answers + project context Same generic questions every time Template asks the questions your team's best docs answered well"},{"location":"playbooks/creating-documents.html#reverse-outline-structure-before-details","title":"Reverse Outline: Structure Before Details","text":"<p>When you build a document section by section, especially with AI, each part can read fine while the connections between them quietly break. The problem statement says one thing. The metrics measure another. The scope doesn't match the hypothesis.</p> <p>A reverse outline catches this. Instead of outlining what you plan to write, you outline what you actually wrote.</p> <pre><code>flowchart TD\n    D[\"Draft\"] --&gt; E[\"Extract what each\\nsection actually argues\"]\n    E --&gt; M[\"Map connections\\nbetween sections\"]\n    M --&gt; F[\"Flag structural breaks\\n(misaligned arguments,\\nmissing connections)\"]\n    F --&gt; FIX[\"Fix at the\\narchitecture level\"]</code></pre> <pre><code>Run the reverse outline template against @team-wizard-prd.md\n</code></pre> <p>CC reads each section, extracts what it actually argues (not what the heading says), maps the connections between sections, and flags where the argument breaks.</p>  Bad  Good Skip structural review, go straight to line edits Reverse outline first. Fix architecture before polishing sentences. \"Review and improve the whole doc\" \"Check whether the problem statement, metrics, and scope actually align\" Edit sections that might get rewritten entirely Lock the structure, then do surgical edits <p>Why structure before details: If the reverse outline reveals that your metrics don't connect to your problem statement, you might rewrite that entire section. Every line edit you'd placed there would be wasted work. Forest first, then trees.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/creating-documents.html#the-comment-pattern","title":"The {{comment}} Pattern","text":"<p>Once the structure is solid, mark the weak spots for targeted refinement. Read through the document and drop inline markers where the thinking is soft.</p> <pre><code>The team setup wizard will reduce onboarding time by {{too vague -- by how much?}}\nand improve activation rates {{need specific baseline from experiment data}}.\nUsers who complete the wizard {{is this measurable with current instrumentation?}}\nwill see higher feature adoption.\n</code></pre> <pre><code>Review the {{comments}} in @team-wizard-prd.md\n</code></pre> <p>CC finds every marker, resolves data questions from project files, and asks you about judgment questions. Each comment gets addressed in one sweep.</p>  Bad  Good \"Review and improve the whole doc\" (CC rearranges bullet points into tables and calls it a day) Mark specific weak spots with {{comments}}. CC fixes exactly what you flagged. CC decides what to improve You decide what's weak. Your judgment drives the refinement. Whole-doc review produces scattered improvements Surgical edits targeted at the spots you identified <p>The control principle: CC can review a whole doc. But when you do that, you get scattered improvements driven by CC's judgment about what matters. With {{comments}}, YOU decide what's weak. The refinement is surgical because your PM judgment targets the work.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/creating-documents.html#progressive-elaboration-no-template-path","title":"Progressive Elaboration (No Template Path)","text":"<p>What if you don't have a template? No problem. Skeleton first, content second.</p> <ol> <li>Describe what the document needs to cover</li> <li>CC proposes a skeleton (sections + purpose, not content)</li> <li>You align on the structure</li> <li>Fill it in section by section, same interview pattern</li> <li>Save the skeleton. Now you have a template for next time.</li> </ol> <p>This is how new template types get born. The first time you write a type of document, you build the skeleton interactively. The second time, you start from the skeleton. By the third time, the skeleton has been enriched with patterns from the first two.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/creating-documents.html#adversarial-persona-review","title":"Adversarial Persona Review","text":"<p>Before the real meeting, run the document past calibrated personas. Each persona gets the document and reviews it from their specific perspective, simultaneously.</p> <pre><code>flowchart TD\n    DOC[\"Your PRD\"] --&gt; P1[\"VP Engineering\\n'What's the eng cost?\\nWhat about Q3 headcount?'\"]\n    DOC --&gt; P2[\"CEO\\n'Why now? Give me\\nthe 30-second version.'\"]\n    DOC --&gt; P3[\"Head of Support\\n'What about migration?\\nRollback plan?'\"]\n    P1 --&gt; T[\"Triage:\\nAct on / Set aside /\\nNote for meeting\"]\n    P2 --&gt; T\n    P3 --&gt; T</code></pre> <pre><code>Run @lisa-chen.md, @james-torres.md, and @priya-sharma.md\nagainst @team-wizard-prd.md. Each reviews from their perspective.\n</code></pre> <p>Three perspectives, one document, done in parallel. Each sub-agent gets a persona file and the document. They return reviews from their hardcoded perspectives.</p> <p>The judgment call: Not every flag is worth fixing. Eight concerns doesn't mean eight changes. Part of your job is deciding which feedback matters and which is noise. The personas propose. You decide.</p> <p>The compounding loop: After the real meeting, compare what the personas predicted to what actually happened. Update the persona files. Three meetings in, your system knows exactly what each person cares about because the meetings told it.</p> <p>CC Limitation</p> <p>Personas are educated guesses, not mind-reading. Even imperfect personas catch things you'd miss. They get better over time as you feed them real meeting data through the Meeting Processing loop.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/creating-documents.html#common-mistakes","title":"Common Mistakes","text":"Mistake Why It Happens What to Do Instead Start from a blank page \"I'll just ask CC to write a PRD\" Extract patterns, enrich the template, run the interview Skip pattern extraction \"I know what a good PRD looks like\" You know intuitively. Your templates don't. Extract it. Whole-doc review \"Review and improve this\" Mark weak spots with {{comments}}. Surgical beats scattered. Structure and details simultaneously \"I'll fix it all in one pass\" Reverse outline first. Fix architecture, then polish. Skip adversarial review \"I'll find out in the meeting\" Run personas before the meeting. Prepare for the pushback. Generic personas \"The engineering stakeholder\" Specific people with specific patterns. Calibrate from real meetings."},{"location":"playbooks/creating-documents.html#plug-play","title":"Plug &amp; Play","text":"<p><code>/pattern-extraction</code> Analyze 3+ documents of the same type to extract what made them effective with your specific stakeholders.</p> <p><code>/template-enrichment</code> Upgrade a standard template with data-pull and judgment-call prompts based on extracted patterns.</p> <p><code>/reverse-outline</code> Structural audit of any document. Extracts what each section actually argues and flags where the argument breaks.</p> <p><code>/review-comments</code> Find and resolve {{comment}} markers in a document. Data questions get answered from project files. Judgment questions get asked to you.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/creating-documents.html#references","title":"References","text":"<p>Internal:</p> <ul> <li>Documents &amp; Communication : Hub page for the full Think-Show-Loop arc</li> <li>Presentations &amp; Visuals : Turn documents into visual presentations</li> <li>Meeting Processing : Close the loop after meetings to improve personas</li> </ul> <p>External:</p> <ul> <li>Anthropic: Sub-agents : How parallel persona review works</li> <li>Anthropic: Skills : Building reusable document workflows</li> <li>Anthropic: Claude Code best practices : Official guidance on structuring work</li> </ul>"},{"location":"playbooks/data-and-decisions.html","title":"Data &amp; Decisions","text":"<p>Data-driven PM work is not about dashboards. It's about a continuous investigation where every step builds on the last, every finding is traceable, and every recommendation comes with the math to back it up. Claude Code turns you from \"the PM who makes charts\" into \"the PM who owns the analytical trail from question to running experiment.\"</p> <p>Quick Answer</p> <p>Use this when: Someone asks \"how's it going?\" and you need more than a dashboard screenshot.</p> <p>Avoid this when: You need market research or competitive positioning. That's Competitive Intelligence.</p> <p>What CC changes: Jupyter notebooks become your analysis medium. Prior work compounds across notebooks. Sub-agents run parallel analyses. One command triggers a full experiment check-in with contextual investigation.</p> <p>Default move: Start with Analyzing Data. Frame the question and build the notebook before touching any numbers.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/data-and-decisions.html#the-investigation-arc","title":"The Investigation Arc","text":"<p>Data work flows through four connected phases. Each one feeds the next.</p> <pre><code>flowchart LR\n    E[\"Evaluate\\n'How is it doing?'\"] --&gt; D[\"Diagnose\\n'Where is it breaking?'\"]\n    D --&gt; R[\"Recommend\\n'What should we do?'\"]\n    R --&gt; EX[\"Experiment\\n'Prove it.'\"]</code></pre> <p>This is not a checklist. It's how real analytical work actually moves. You evaluate a launch, discover something concerning, diagnose the root cause, model potential fixes, and design an experiment to validate. Each phase produces artifacts that feed the next.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/data-and-decisions.html#analyzing-data","title":"Analyzing Data","text":"<p>Evaluate launches and diagnose problems. Jupyter notebooks as the trust layer. Doc-as-context pattern to scope analysis from existing briefs. Cross-data-source joins, funnel construction, sub-agent parallel analysis, and qualitative triangulation when the quantitative data has gaps.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/data-and-decisions.html#building-a-data-driven-case","title":"Building a Data-Driven Case","text":"<p>Turn diagnosis into recommendation. Cross-notebook context so prior work compounds. Common metric pattern for apples-to-apples comparison. Interactive impact estimation with compound funnel math. Build recommendations with confidence markers and \"what would change your mind\" sections.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/data-and-decisions.html#experiment-design","title":"Experiment Design","text":"<p>Design experiments that monitor themselves. Experiment briefs as living documents. Power analysis to size your test. The document-as-interface pattern where the brief defines what data to pull, and contextual check-ins that go beyond dashboards to investigate support tickets, cancellation patterns, and segmentation alongside metrics.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/data-and-decisions.html#how-claude-code-changes-data-work","title":"How Claude Code Changes Data Work","text":"Traditional With Claude Code Open a spreadsheet and start making charts Point CC at your launch brief and data, get a structured notebook with traceable analysis Manually build funnels in a BI tool Describe the funnel in plain English, CC joins data sources and builds it Check a dashboard for experiment metrics One command triggers a full contextual check-in across metrics, support tickets, and cancellation patterns Copy numbers between spreadsheets for impact estimates Prior notebooks feed new analysis automatically via cross-notebook context Wait for an analyst to run a query Run the query yourself in a Jupyter notebook where every step is auditable <p>The speed matters, but the traceability matters more. Every chart has the code that made it right above it. Every recommendation traces back through notebooks to raw data. When your VP asks \"where'd you get that number?\" you open the notebook, not a Slack thread.</p> <p>CC Limitation</p> <p>Claude Code will find patterns in any data, whether they're real or not. Small samples, short timeframes, and confounding variables don't trigger warnings automatically. The framework (success metrics AND guardrails, confidence markers, sample size caveats) is what keeps you honest. Skip it and you'll just get faster at overstating.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/data-and-decisions.html#where-to-start","title":"Where to Start","text":"<p>Evaluating a launch or investigating a metric? Begin with Analyzing Data. It covers the full evaluate-and-diagnose cycle.</p> <p>Ready to recommend a course of action? Jump to Building a Data-Driven Case for impact estimation and recommendation building.</p> <p>Designing an experiment? Use Experiment Design for briefs, power analysis, and contextual check-ins.</p> <p>Need qualitative research instead? See User Research for interview and survey methodologies.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/data-and-decisions.html#plug-play","title":"Plug &amp; Play","text":"<p><code>/launch-review</code> Point at a launch brief and dataset. Gets a structured Jupyter notebook with success metrics, guardrail checks, and an executive summary.</p> <p><code>/diagnostic-funnel</code> Joins data sources, builds the conversion funnel, compares time periods, and flags tracking gaps.</p> <p><code>/impact-estimation</code> Interactive estimation session. You pick which funnel steps each option targets, estimate the lift, and CC runs compound math across the full funnel.</p> <p><code>/experiment-check</code> Reads an experiment brief and runs a full contextual check-in. Metrics, support tickets, cancellation patterns, proactive investigation.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/data-and-decisions.html#references","title":"References","text":"<p>Internal:</p> <ul> <li>Analyzing Data : Jupyter notebooks, doc-as-context, funnel construction, qualitative triangulation</li> <li>Building a Data-Driven Case : Cross-notebook context, compound funnel math, recommendations</li> <li>Experiment Design : Experiment briefs, power analysis, contextual check-ins</li> <li>User Research : Qualitative research methodologies</li> <li>Competitive Intelligence : Market research and positioning</li> </ul> <p>External:</p> <ul> <li>Anthropic: Sub-agents : How parallel analysis works under the hood</li> <li>Anthropic: Claude Code best practices : Official guidance on structuring work</li> </ul>"},{"location":"playbooks/documents-and-communication.html","title":"Documents &amp; Communication","text":"<p>The communication system that learns. Documents get better because your templates improve with every use. Presentations get better because brand guidelines persist. Meeting prep gets better because real meeting outcomes feed back into your persona files. It's a cycle: Think, Show, Loop.</p> <p>Quick Answer</p> <p>Use this when: You need to create a document, build a presentation, or process a meeting.</p> <p>Avoid this when: You need data analysis or research. That's Data &amp; Decisions or User Research.</p> <p>What CC changes: Templates become interactive interviews. Pattern extraction captures your team's implicit quality standards. Adversarial personas catch objections before the meeting. One command processes the entire post-meeting cascade. The system compounds with every cycle.</p> <p>Default move: Start with Creating Documents. The argument comes first. Visuals and meetings serve it.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/documents-and-communication.html#the-think-show-loop-arc","title":"The Think-Show-Loop Arc","text":"<p>Three phases, one continuous cycle. Each revolution makes the next one sharper.</p> <pre><code>flowchart LR\n    T[\"Think\\nCreating Documents\"] --&gt; S[\"Show\\nPresentations &amp; Visuals\"]\n    S --&gt; L[\"Loop\\nMeeting Processing\"]\n    L --&gt; T</code></pre>"},{"location":"playbooks/documents-and-communication.html#creating-documents","title":"Creating Documents","text":"<p>Build the argument. Pattern extraction from exemplars, AI-native template enrichment, template-driven interviews, reverse outlining, {{comment}} refinement, and adversarial persona review. Seven techniques, each building on the last.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/documents-and-communication.html#presentations-visuals","title":"Presentations &amp; Visuals","text":"<p>Make the argument visible. Mermaid diagrams embedded in documents, brand guidelines as persistent context, presentation outlines with actionable slide titles, and full deck generation from a single command.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/documents-and-communication.html#meeting-processing","title":"Meeting Processing","text":"<p>Close the loop. Process the transcript, compare persona predictions to reality, update people files, track action items, draft follow-ups, and write a status update. One command triggers the entire cascade. Every meeting makes the next cycle sharper.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/documents-and-communication.html#how-claude-code-changes-communication","title":"How Claude Code Changes Communication","text":"Traditional With Claude Code Start from a blank template every time Templates enriched with data-pull and judgment-call prompts from past successes Review the doc yourself, miss structural issues Reverse outline catches argument breaks before anyone else sees them Walk into the meeting hoping for the best Adversarial personas stress-test the document from specific stakeholder perspectives Process meeting notes manually, update docs one at a time One command triggers six sub-skills that process the full aftermath People files stay static Real meeting outcomes feed back into personas, making the next prep sharper <p>The compounding is the point. Each document you write improves your template. Each meeting you process improves your personas. Each cycle is faster and sharper than the last.</p> <p>CC Limitation</p> <p>CC accelerates the mechanics, but the thinking is yours. A beautifully formatted document with shallow thinking is still shallow. The system is designed to push your thinking harder (through enriched templates, reverse outlines, and adversarial review), not replace it.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/documents-and-communication.html#where-to-start","title":"Where to Start","text":"<p>Writing a document? Begin with Creating Documents. It covers the full pipeline from pattern extraction through adversarial review.</p> <p>Need visuals or a slide deck? Use Presentations &amp; Visuals once the argument is solid.</p> <p>Just had an important meeting? Run Meeting Processing to close the loop.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/documents-and-communication.html#plug-play","title":"Plug &amp; Play","text":"<p><code>/pattern-extraction</code> Analyze exemplar documents to extract what made them effective with your specific stakeholders.</p> <p><code>/review-comments</code> Find and resolve {{comment}} markers for targeted refinement.</p> <p><code>/frontend-slides</code> Full slide deck from an outline. Style discovery, brand guidelines, animation-rich output.</p> <p><code>/meeting-aftermath</code> Process the full meeting cascade in one command. Six sub-skills, one orchestrator.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/documents-and-communication.html#references","title":"References","text":"<p>Internal:</p> <ul> <li>Creating Documents : The full document creation pipeline</li> <li>Presentations &amp; Visuals : Mermaid diagrams, brand guidelines, slide decks</li> <li>Meeting Processing : Post-meeting cascade and the compounding loop</li> </ul> <p>External:</p> <ul> <li>Anthropic: Sub-agents : How parallel persona review works</li> <li>Anthropic: Skills : Building composable skill architectures</li> <li>Anthropic: Claude Code best practices : Official guidance on structuring work</li> </ul>"},{"location":"playbooks/meeting-processing.html","title":"Meeting Processing","text":"<p>Meeting processing turns the information that comes out of every meeting into structured updates across your system. The methodology: process the transcript, compare persona predictions to reality, update people files, track action items, draft follow-ups, and write a status update. One command triggers the entire cascade.</p> <p>Quick Answer</p> <p>Use this when: You've just had an important meeting and need to process the aftermath: notes, action items, people file updates, follow-up messages, status updates.</p> <p>Avoid this when: You need to prepare FOR a meeting. Use adversarial personas from Creating Documents for that.</p> <p>What CC changes: One command triggers six sub-skills in sequence. The transcript feeds the people updates, which feed the follow-up drafts. The whole cascade runs from a single prompt. And the system learns from every meeting.</p> <p>Default move: Run <code>/meeting-aftermath</code> on the transcript. Review the proposed updates. Apply what makes sense.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/meeting-processing.html#the-meeting-aftermath-cascade","title":"The Meeting Aftermath Cascade","text":"<p>Six operations, each feeding the next. One command.</p> <pre><code>flowchart TD\n    T[\"Meeting transcript\"] --&gt; PT[\"/process-transcript\\nDecisions, actions, quotes\"]\n    PT --&gt; RC[\"/reality-check\\nPredictions vs. actual\"]\n    RC --&gt; UP1[\"/update-people\\n(per stakeholder)\"]\n    UP1 --&gt; UA[\"/update-actions\\nNew + completed items\"]\n    UA --&gt; DF[\"/draft-followups\\nSlack/email drafts\"]\n    DF --&gt; SU[\"/status-update\\nBLUF meeting summary\"]\n    SU --&gt; PROP[\"PROPOSED UPDATES\\n(you approve what to write)\"]</code></pre> <pre><code>Run /meeting-aftermath on @stakeholder-meeting-notes.md\n</code></pre> <p>The key word: proposed. The aftermath cascade doesn't write anything automatically. It surfaces what changed and suggests updates. You decide which ones to apply. The system proposes. You bring the judgment.</p>  Bad  Good Process the transcript manually, update docs one at a time One command triggers the full cascade Forget to update people files after meetings Reality check automatically identifies what to update Draft follow-ups from memory two hours later Follow-up drafts generated while context is fresh Status update written the next day BLUF summary produced immediately"},{"location":"playbooks/meeting-processing.html#reality-calibration","title":"Reality Calibration","text":"<p>If you used adversarial personas to prepare for the meeting (from Creating Documents), the aftermath cascade compares what the personas predicted to what actually happened. The gaps are the signal.</p> <pre><code>flowchart LR\n    PRED[\"Persona predictions\\n'Lisa will ask\\nabout eng cost'\"] --&gt; CMP[\"Compare\"]\n    REAL[\"What actually happened\\n'Lisa asked about\\nQ3 headcount'\"] --&gt; CMP\n    CMP --&gt; GAP[\"Gap analysis\\n'Lisa's concern is\\nresource allocation,\\nnot just cost'\"]\n    GAP --&gt; UPD[\"Update people file\\nwith corrected pattern\"]</code></pre> Predicted Actually Said What to Update \"Lisa will push on engineering cost\" Lisa asked about Q3 headcount impact She thinks in resource allocation, not just cost \"James wants the 30-second version\" James dove deep on competitive questions He goes deep when competitive positioning is at stake \"Priya will flag edge cases\" Priya supported aggressive timeline when data was solid She's risk-tolerant when evidence is strong <p>Why compare instead of just processing the transcript? The transcript tells you what happened. The comparison tells you what your system DIDN'T know. Processing the transcript alone updates facts. The comparison updates understanding.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/meeting-processing.html#composable-skills","title":"Composable Skills","text":"<p>The aftermath cascade is built from composable skills. One orchestrator calls focused sub-skills in sequence. Each sub-skill works on its own AND as part of the orchestrator.</p> Sub-skill Standalone Use In the Cascade <code>/process-transcript</code> Quick meeting notes from any transcript Extracts decisions, actions, quotes for the cascade <code>/reality-check</code> Compare any prediction to an outcome Identifies gaps per stakeholder for people updates <code>/update-people</code> Update one person's file after a quick chat Updates all relevant people files from gap analysis <code>/update-actions</code> Track a new action item Reconciles new items with existing action log <code>/draft-followups</code> Draft a message to one person Drafts all follow-ups, matching tone per recipient <code>/status-update</code> Write a quick status update Produces BLUF summary from full cascade context <p>The architectural advantage: <code>/update-people</code> works on its own when you just need to update one person's file after a quick chat, but it also works inside <code>/meeting-aftermath</code> when you want to process an entire meeting. Same skill, two contexts.</p> <p>This pattern extends beyond meetings. Any multi-step workflow (daily standups, weekly reporting, sprint planning) follows the same architecture: one orchestrator, focused sub-skills, each pulling from your existing context.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/meeting-processing.html#the-compounding-loop","title":"The Compounding Loop","text":"<p>Every meeting you process makes the next meeting prep sharper.</p> <pre><code>flowchart LR\n    BUILD[\"Build document\\n+ personas\"] --&gt; PRESENT[\"Present\\n(the meeting)\"]\n    PRESENT --&gt; PROCESS[\"Process aftermath\\n+ reality check\"]\n    PROCESS --&gt; UPDATE[\"Update people files\\nwith real patterns\"]\n    UPDATE --&gt; BUILD</code></pre> <p>Three meetings in, your people files know exactly what each person cares about. Not because you told the system, but because the meetings told it. The adversarial personas get sharper. The meeting prep improves. The meetings go better. More signal flows back.</p>  Bad  Good People files based on your assumptions People files updated from actual meeting behavior Same generic persona predictions every time Predictions improve as files capture real patterns Meeting prep doesn't learn from past meetings Each meeting's aftermath feeds the next meeting's prep"},{"location":"playbooks/meeting-processing.html#action-tracking-and-follow-up-drafting","title":"Action Tracking and Follow-Up Drafting","text":"<p>The cascade doesn't just identify action items. It reconciles them against your existing action log (marking completed items, adding new ones with owners and deadlines) and drafts follow-up messages matched to each recipient's communication style.</p> <p>Follow-up drafts are exactly that: drafts. Review them, adjust the tone, then send. The value is having them ready immediately after the meeting while context is fresh, instead of drafting from memory later.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/meeting-processing.html#common-mistakes","title":"Common Mistakes","text":"Mistake Why It Happens What to Do Instead Process meetings manually \"It's only 10 minutes of notes\" One command processes the full aftermath. Those 10 minutes compound across every meeting. Skip reality calibration \"The meeting went fine\" The gaps between predictions and reality are how your system learns. Skip it and personas stay frozen. Auto-apply all proposed updates \"CC knows what to update\" Review every proposed update. The system proposes, you decide. Forget to update people files \"I'll remember what Lisa said\" You won't. The cascade captures it immediately. Draft follow-ups from memory hours later \"I'll do it after lunch\" Drafts generated while the meeting context is fresh are more accurate and specific."},{"location":"playbooks/meeting-processing.html#plug-play","title":"Plug &amp; Play","text":"<p><code>/meeting-aftermath</code> The full cascade. Process transcript, reality check, people updates, action tracking, follow-up drafts, status update. One command, six sub-skills.</p> <p><code>/process-transcript</code> Extract decisions, action items, and key quotes from a meeting transcript. Works standalone or as part of the cascade.</p> <p><code>/draft-followups</code> Draft follow-up Slack messages and emails from meeting outcomes. Matches tone to recipient using people files.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/meeting-processing.html#references","title":"References","text":"<p>Internal:</p> <ul> <li>Documents &amp; Communication : Hub page for the full Think-Show-Loop arc</li> <li>Creating Documents : Adversarial personas for meeting prep</li> <li>Presentations &amp; Visuals : Building the deck you present</li> </ul> <p>External:</p> <ul> <li>Anthropic: Skills : Building composable skill architectures</li> <li>Anthropic: Claude Code best practices : Official guidance on structuring workflows</li> </ul>"},{"location":"playbooks/presentations-and-visuals.html","title":"Presentations &amp; Visuals","text":"<p>Presentations and visuals with Claude Code are about making the argument visible. The thinking is already done. The document is stress-tested. Now you need diagrams that embed in your docs, brand consistency across everything you generate, and slide decks that tell a story with actionable titles. The methodology: Mermaid for structured diagrams, brand guidelines as persistent context, presentation outlines that state claims (not topics), and full deck generation from a single command.</p> <p>Quick Answer</p> <p>Use this when: You have a document or analysis that needs visual communication, whether embedded diagrams, a slide deck, or both.</p> <p>Avoid this when: You haven't done the thinking yet. Visuals serve arguments. Build the argument first with Creating Documents.</p> <p>What CC changes: Generate diagrams inline with a text description. Build full slide decks from a single command. Brand guidelines apply automatically once set up. Style discovery shows you options instead of asking you to describe your aesthetic in words.</p> <p>Default move: Mermaid for any structured diagram (architecture, timelines, flows). Brand guidelines first if this is your first visual project.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/presentations-and-visuals.html#mermaid-diagrams-visuals-inside-your-documents","title":"Mermaid Diagrams: Visuals Inside Your Documents","text":"<p>Mermaid is a text-based diagram language. Describe what you want, and it renders as a visual diagram right inside your markdown. GitHub renders it, VS Code renders it, Obsidian renders it. Anywhere you write markdown, Mermaid just works.</p> <pre><code>flowchart LR\n    D[\"Describe the\\ndiagram in words\"] --&gt; M[\"Mermaid code\\n(text-based)\"]\n    M --&gt; R[\"Rendered diagram\\n(embedded in doc)\"]</code></pre> <p>Why PMs should care: A PRD with a clean architecture diagram lands differently with everyone in the room, not just the engineers. Most PMs never add visuals to their documents because diagramming tools are slow and the output lives behind a link to an external tool. Mermaid diagrams live inside the document itself.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/presentations-and-visuals.html#what-mermaid-handles-well","title":"What Mermaid Handles Well","text":"Diagram Type Use For Example Flowcharts Process flows, decision trees, user journeys Upgrade funnel, approval process Sequence diagrams System interactions, API flows How the payment flow works end to end Timeline Milestones, experiment progress, roadmap Experiment timeline with current status Architecture System components, data flow Before/after comparison of a feature State diagrams Status transitions, lifecycle Ticket states, user account lifecycle <pre><code>Generate two Mermaid diagrams for the wizard PRD. A flow diagram\nshowing the team setup process, and an experiment timeline\nwith milestones and current status.\n</code></pre>  Bad  Good Open Lucidchart, drag boxes for 30 minutes, export as PNG, link from doc Describe the diagram in one sentence. Mermaid code renders inline. Diagram lives in an external tool behind a link Diagram IS the document. Text-based, versions with git, no external tool. Diagram gets out of date because updating it is a pain Update the text, the diagram updates. Same effort as editing a sentence. <p>CC Advantage</p> <p>Mermaid diagrams are text, which means they live inside your markdown documents, render in most editors and platforms, and version-control with git like any other file. A Lucidchart diagram is a link. A Mermaid diagram IS the document.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/presentations-and-visuals.html#brand-guidelines-as-persistent-context","title":"Brand Guidelines as Persistent Context","text":"<p>The biggest question PMs have about using AI for visuals: how do I make it look like MY company's stuff instead of generic AI output?</p> <p>The answer: set up brand guidelines once, reference them forever.</p> <pre><code>flowchart LR\n    BG[\"brand-guidelines.md\\n(set up once)\"] --&gt; V1[\"Slide deck\"]\n    BG --&gt; V2[\"Infographic\"]\n    BG --&gt; V3[\"Social graphic\"]\n    BG --&gt; V4[\"Any future visual\"]</code></pre>"},{"location":"playbooks/presentations-and-visuals.html#what-goes-in-brand-guidelines","title":"What Goes in Brand Guidelines","text":"Section Why It Matters What to Include Colors Consistency without specifying hex codes each time Primary, secondary, accent with hex values Typography Font choices carry brand identity more than almost anything else Heading fonts, body fonts, size hierarchy Layout rules The biggest difference for AI-generated output Content density, spacing, alignment, grid system Content hierarchy Gets the right weight in the right places How headings, subheadings, and body text relate <p>If your company already has brand guidelines, great. Point CC at them. If not, CC can extract visual rules from existing slides or documents:</p> <pre><code>Look at these 3 slides from our last board deck. Extract the\nvisual rules -- colors, fonts, spacing, layout density. Save\nas brand-guidelines.md.\n</code></pre> <p>Once the file exists, reference it on every visual task. You define the rules once, and everything you generate from here looks like it belongs in your company.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/presentations-and-visuals.html#presentation-outlines-claims-not-topics","title":"Presentation Outlines: Claims, Not Topics","text":"<p>A presentation outline is your argument restructured for a room. Before generating any slides, get the narrative right.</p> <p>The rule: Slide titles should state claims, not topics. If your VP reads just the slide titles top to bottom, they should follow the argument without opening a single slide.</p>  Bad (Topic Titles)  Good (Claim Titles) \"Results\" \"Invite completion jumped 33% in three weeks\" \"Recommendation\" \"Option B yields the highest impact at manageable eng cost\" \"Next Steps\" \"Ship the quiz to 100% with a 4-week evaluation window\" \"Background\" \"Adding a third tier broke the upgrade path\" <pre><code>Transform @team-wizard-prd.md into a presentation outline\nusing @presentation-outline-template.md. Pull additional data\nfrom the experiment results where it helps.\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"playbooks/presentations-and-visuals.html#outline-best-practices","title":"Outline Best Practices","text":"<ul> <li>One idea per slide. If a slide makes two points, it's two slides.</li> <li>Evidence before recommendation. Show the data, then tell them what to do.</li> <li>Explicit ask on the final slide. What do you need from this room?</li> <li>Preempt known objections. If your adversarial personas flagged concerns, build your slides to answer them before anyone asks.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"playbooks/presentations-and-visuals.html#slide-generation","title":"Slide Generation","text":"<p>Once the outline is solid, generate the full deck. CC can produce complete HTML slide decks from the outline, brand guidelines, and project data.</p> <pre><code>flowchart LR\n    O[\"Presentation\\noutline\"] --&gt; G[\"Slide\\ngeneration\"]\n    BG2[\"Brand\\nguidelines\"] --&gt; G\n    D2[\"Project data\\n(notebooks, analysis)\"] --&gt; G\n    G --&gt; DECK[\"Full slide deck\\n(HTML, self-contained)\"]</code></pre> <pre><code>Run /frontend-slides for the go/no-go presentation.\nUse @presentation-outline.md for content,\n@brand-guidelines.md for styling, and pull data\nfrom the experiment results.\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"playbooks/presentations-and-visuals.html#visual-style-discovery","title":"Visual Style Discovery","text":"<p>Instead of trying to describe your aesthetic in words (\"make it look professional but not boring\"), CC shows you options and you react to what you see.</p> <p>The flow:</p> <ol> <li>CC generates 3 style previews based on your brand guidelines and content</li> <li>You pick the one that feels right</li> <li>CC generates the full deck in that style</li> </ol> <p>This is \"show, don't tell\" applied to visual design. Reacting to something you can see is always easier than describing something that doesn't exist yet.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/presentations-and-visuals.html#other-approaches","title":"Other Approaches","text":"<p>Different situations call for different tools:</p> Approach Best For Trade-off Frontend-slides skill Full decks from a single command Fast, animation-rich, HTML output Puppeteer builder-validator Slide-by-slide with precise control Slower, more control per slide PowerPoint tools Organizations that need .pptx files Native format, less visual polish <p>The techniques (outline first, brand guidelines, style discovery) transfer to any of these tools. Pick based on your output format needs.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/presentations-and-visuals.html#ai-image-generation","title":"AI Image Generation","text":"<p>When you need visuals that go beyond structured diagrams. User journey illustrations, concept visuals, reference images, abstract diagrams.</p> <p>Mermaid handles structured information well. For everything else, AI image generation tools can produce visuals directly from descriptions. This is a capability that exists, not a core methodology. The course covers it in a dedicated bonus module.</p> <p>The mental model:</p> Visual Need Tool Architecture, flows, timelines, state machines Mermaid (text-based, embeds in docs) User journeys, concepts, illustrations AI image generation Data visualizations, charts Jupyter notebooks (matplotlib, seaborn) Full slide decks Frontend-slides, Puppeteer, or PowerPoint tools"},{"location":"playbooks/presentations-and-visuals.html#common-mistakes","title":"Common Mistakes","text":"Mistake Why It Happens What to Do Instead Build slides before the argument is ready \"I need to present Tuesday\" Build the document first. The argument is the hard part. Slides are just the medium. Topic titles on slides Convention Claim titles. If someone reads only your titles, they should follow the argument. No brand guidelines \"I'll just describe what I want\" Set them up once. 10 minutes. Every future visual is better. Diagrams in external tools \"That's how we've always done it\" Mermaid lives in the doc. Updates in seconds. Versions with git. Try to describe your aesthetic in words \"Make it professional but creative\" Style discovery. Look at 3 options and pick one. Skip the outline \"Let CC generate the slides directly\" Outline first. Claim titles, one idea per slide, evidence before recommendation."},{"location":"playbooks/presentations-and-visuals.html#plug-play","title":"Plug &amp; Play","text":"<p><code>/frontend-slides</code> Full HTML slide deck from an outline. Style discovery with visual previews. Brand guidelines integration. Animation-rich, self-contained output.</p> <p><code>/presentation-outline</code> Transform any document into a structured presentation outline with actionable slide titles.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/presentations-and-visuals.html#references","title":"References","text":"<p>Internal:</p> <ul> <li>Documents &amp; Communication : Hub page for the full Think-Show-Loop arc</li> <li>Creating Documents : Build the argument before making it visual</li> <li>Meeting Processing : Process the meeting after you present</li> </ul> <p>External:</p> <ul> <li>Mermaid Documentation : Full diagram syntax reference</li> <li>Anthropic: Claude Code best practices : Official guidance on structuring work</li> </ul>"},{"location":"playbooks/the-collaboration-layer.html","title":"The Collaboration Layer","text":"<p>Scaling Claude Code across your team -- shared configs, conventions, and multiplayer workflows.</p> <p>Quick Answer</p> <p>Use this when: You have a working personal OS and want to extend it to your team.</p> <p>Avoid this when: Your own setup isn't stable yet. Get your personal OS solid first, then share.</p> <p>What CC changes: Instead of sending Slack messages about processes, you encode them into shareable skills, rules, and templates that teammates install once and benefit from forever.</p> <p>Default move: Start with one shared skill that solves a pain point everyone has. Build the infrastructure around it.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/the-collaboration-layer.html#the-four-step-arc","title":"The Four-Step Arc","text":"<p>Collaboration in Claude Code follows a natural progression. Each step builds on the last.</p> <pre><code>flowchart LR\n    S[\"Sharing &amp;\\nDistribution\"] --&gt; T[\"Team\\nToolkit\"]\n    T --&gt; A[\"Driving\\nAdoption\"]\n    A --&gt; G[\"Governance\"]\n\n    style S fill:#f0f4ff,stroke:#4a6cf7\n    style T fill:#f0f4ff,stroke:#4a6cf7\n    style A fill:#f0f4ff,stroke:#4a6cf7\n    style G fill:#f0f4ff,stroke:#4a6cf7</code></pre> Step Question It Answers Page Sharing &amp; Distribution What can I share and how do I prepare it? Sharing &amp; Distribution Team Toolkit Where does the shared stuff live and how do people get it? Team Toolkit Driving Adoption How do I get people to actually use it? Driving Adoption Governance How do I keep the shared system healthy over time? Governance"},{"location":"playbooks/the-collaboration-layer.html#the-flywheel","title":"The Flywheel","text":"<p>The collaboration layer compounds. Each person who contributes makes the toolkit more valuable, which brings more contributors.</p> <pre><code>You share a skill\n  --&gt; teammate uses it, saves 2 hours\n    --&gt; they add their own skill\n      --&gt; new hire gets both on day one\n        --&gt; team's learning compounds instead of\n           staying trapped in individual heads\n</code></pre> <p>Most teams try to jump straight to governance (rolling out a full system to everyone). That kills adoption. Start small: prepare one asset, share it with one person, see what happens.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/the-collaboration-layer.html#sub-pages","title":"Sub-Pages","text":"<p>Sharing &amp; Distribution -- What can be shared (skills, rules, templates, agents), the shareability principles, and how to prepare personal assets for team use.</p> <p>Team Toolkit -- Building a shared GitHub repo with structure, catalog, contribution guidelines, and an install flow that takes under 3 minutes.</p> <p>Driving Adoption -- The champion model, engineering the before/after moment, handling objections, and planning your first real test case.</p> <p>Governance -- Ownership, review cadence, conflict resolution, deprecation, communicating changes, and measuring impact.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/the-collaboration-layer.html#references","title":"References","text":"<p>Internal:</p> <ul> <li>Your PM OS : Build your personal system before sharing it</li> <li>Skills: Building : How to build skills worth sharing</li> </ul> <p>External:</p> <ul> <li>Anthropic: Claude Code best practices : Foundation for effective Claude Code usage</li> <li>Anthropic: Skills : Official skills documentation</li> </ul>"},{"location":"playbooks/the-pm-builder.html","title":"The PM Builder","text":"<p>PMs don't touch code. That used to be true. Claude Code makes it false. Not because you become an engineer, but because the barrier between \"I know what to build\" and \"I can show what I mean\" disappears.</p> <p>Quick Answer</p> <p>Use this when: You need to explore a codebase, improve existing features, build prototypes, or ship contributions through git.</p> <p>Avoid this when: You're doing research or analysis. That's User Research.</p> <p>What CC changes: You go from \"ask engineering and wait\" to \"explore it yourself, prototype it yourself, ship it yourself.\" Read-only intelligence, targeted improvements, full feature builds, and real PRs. All through natural language.</p> <p>Default move: Start by exploring. Never change code you haven't mapped first.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/the-pm-builder.html#the-arc","title":"The Arc","text":"<p>Four phases, each one ratcheting up what you can do. Every phase builds on the last.</p> <pre><code>flowchart LR\n    O[\"Explore\\n(read-only)\"] --&gt; C[\"Modify\\n(targeted changes)\"]\n    C --&gt; B[\"Build\\n(new features)\"]\n    B --&gt; S[\"Ship\\n(git + PRs)\"]</code></pre>"},{"location":"playbooks/the-pm-builder.html#exploring-codebases","title":"Exploring Codebases","text":"<p>Map the system without touching anything. Architecture diagrams, flow traces, complexity estimates. The intelligence package that used to take a week of bugging engineers, generated in minutes. This is where you earn the context that makes everything else work.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/the-pm-builder.html#modifying-improving","title":"Modifying &amp; Improving","text":"<p>Cross from observer to contributor. Targeted improvements to existing features following the patterns the codebase already uses. The reference pattern: find how the app handles something before you change it. Consistency over creativity.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/the-pm-builder.html#adding-features","title":"Adding Features","text":"<p>Build something that doesn't exist yet. Spec-driven development with <code>/grill-me</code> catches wrong assumptions before a line of code is written. Design system context makes everything look native. Variant generation lets you build three options in the time it takes to debate one.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/the-pm-builder.html#shipping-code","title":"Shipping Code","text":"<p>Save your work, fix bugs, push PRs. Git through natural language. The Esc Esc safety mechanism means you can break things without consequences. The full cycle from change to reviewed PR, using the same workflow your engineering team uses every day.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/the-pm-builder.html#how-claude-code-changes-building","title":"How Claude Code Changes Building","text":"Traditional PM PM with Claude Code Ask engineering \"how hard would this be?\" and wait Generate a scoping brief grounded in the actual code Describe what you want in a PRD and hope Build three working prototypes and pick the winner File a vague bug report: \"Settings is broken\" Trace the bug to a one-character route mismatch and fix it Review mockups in Figma and give feedback Review working code in a browser and iterate in real-time Never see the PR process Author PRs with clear context that engineers actually want to review <p>The mindset shift: you are not becoming an engineer. You are becoming a PM who can see, touch, and contribute to the same system your engineers work in. That changes every conversation about scope, feasibility, and priority.</p> <p>CC Limitation</p> <p>Claude Code is a powerful building tool, but it does not replace engineering judgment on production systems. Use it for prototyping, exploration, and targeted contributions. Complex architectural decisions, performance optimization, and production deployment still need your engineering team. Knowing when to hand off is as important as knowing how to contribute.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/the-pm-builder.html#where-to-start","title":"Where to Start","text":"<p>Never worked in a codebase before? Start with Exploring Codebases. Map the system before you touch anything.</p> <p>Want to make improvements? Go to Modifying &amp; Improving. Three targeted changes following the reference pattern.</p> <p>Ready to build something new? See Adding Features. Spec-driven development with variant generation.</p> <p>Need to save and ship your work? Shipping Code covers git, safety, and the PR workflow.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/the-pm-builder.html#references","title":"References","text":"<p>Internal:</p> <ul> <li>Exploring Codebases : Architecture mapping, flow tracing, complexity estimation</li> <li>Modifying &amp; Improving : The reference pattern for targeted improvements</li> <li>Adding Features : Spec-driven development and variant generation</li> <li>Shipping Code : Git workflow, safety mechanisms, and PRs</li> </ul> <p>External:</p> <ul> <li>Anthropic: Sub-agents : How parallel codebase exploration works</li> <li>Anthropic: Claude Code best practices : Official guidance on building with Claude Code</li> </ul>"},{"location":"playbooks/user-research.html","title":"User Research","text":"<p>User research moves you from \"we think\" to \"we know.\" It starts with your hidden assumptions, works backward from what you'll do with the answers, and uses Claude Code to make the whole process faster without cutting corners on rigor.</p> <p>Quick Answer</p> <p>Use this when: You have a decision to make and not enough evidence about what your users actually need.</p> <p>Avoid this when: You're looking at market landscape or competitor positioning. That's Competitive Intelligence.</p> <p>What CC changes: Research that used to take weeks compresses to days. You can analyze 10 transcripts in parallel, code survey responses on the fly, and still maintain methodological rigor.</p> <p>Default move: Start with Research Design. Surface assumptions before collecting data.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/user-research.html#the-research-arc","title":"The Research Arc","text":"<p>Research flows through four connected phases. Each builds on the last.</p> <pre><code>flowchart LR\n    D[\"Research\\nDesign\"] --&gt; I[\"Interview\\nAnalysis\"]\n    I --&gt; S[\"Survey &amp;\\nFeedback\"]\n    S --&gt; SY[\"Research\\nSynthesis\"]</code></pre> <p>Claude Code compresses this from a multi-week process to days. Assumption surfacing takes minutes, transcript analysis runs in parallel, and synthesis happens same-day.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/user-research.html#research-design","title":"Research Design","text":"<p>Surface your hidden assumptions. Turn them into answerable questions. Design your interviews and surveys. Define what findings would change your mind before you collect any data.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/user-research.html#interview-analysis","title":"Interview Analysis","text":"<p>Extract insights from conversations. Code themes independently per participant. Verify quotes against source transcripts. Find contradictions between what people say and what they actually do.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/user-research.html#survey-feedback-analysis","title":"Survey &amp; Feedback Analysis","text":"<p>Quantify what interviews discovered. Code open-ended responses inductively. Calculate how common a pattern actually is. Spot gaps between stated needs and willingness to pay.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/user-research.html#research-synthesis","title":"Research Synthesis","text":"<p>Weave multiple streams of evidence into a single recommendation. Map findings to decisions. Surface contested claims. Build something you'd actually show leadership.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/user-research.html#how-claude-code-changes-research","title":"How Claude Code Changes Research","text":"Traditional With Claude Code Design questions, get feedback, iterate over days Design questions, iterate in minutes with <code>/assumption-surfacing</code> Analyze 5 interviews manually over weeks Analyze 10+ transcripts in parallel, same day Code survey responses by hand Code responses inductively as they come in Compile findings into slides over days Generate evidence matrices and briefs in hours <p>The speed doesn't change the rigor. It changes what you can afford to do. You can run more ambitious research, iterate faster, and actually change your mind when evidence demands it.</p> <p>CC Limitation</p> <p>Claude Code accelerates analysis but it can't replace your judgment. It will find patterns in any data, whether they're real or not. The research design (assumptions, decision framework, verification) is what keeps you honest. Skip it and you'll just get faster at being wrong.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/user-research.html#where-to-start","title":"Where to Start","text":"<p>New to research? Begin with Research Design. It covers assumption surfacing, question design, and decision frameworks.</p> <p>Already designed your study? Jump to Interview Analysis or Survey &amp; Feedback Analysis depending on what you're collecting.</p> <p>Ready to write up findings? Use Research Synthesis to turn multi-stream evidence into a stakeholder brief.</p> <p>Need market context instead? See Competitive Intelligence for web research, review mining, and competitive positioning.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/user-research.html#plug-play","title":"Plug &amp; Play","text":"<p><code>/assumption-surfacing</code> 10-minute structured interview to surface what you know vs. what you assume. The starting point for any research.</p> <p><code>/mom-test-filter</code> Scans interview guides and flags questions that get polite lies instead of truth.</p> <p><code>/research-design</code> Full end-to-end pipeline from vague question to stakeholder-ready research plan.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/user-research.html#references","title":"References","text":"<p>Internal:</p> <ul> <li>Research Design : Assumptions, questions, methods, decision frameworks</li> <li>Interview Analysis : Extraction, coding, verification</li> <li>Survey &amp; Feedback Analysis : Inductive coding, codebooks, intensity scoring</li> <li>Research Synthesis : Evidence matrix, contested findings, stakeholder briefs</li> <li>Competitive Intelligence : Market research, review mining, positioning</li> </ul> <p>External:</p> <ul> <li>Rob Fitzpatrick: How to Talk to Customers (The Mom Test) : Hour-long interview covering the core principles of getting honest feedback</li> <li>Teresa Torres: Continuous Discovery Habits : Talk on building weekly research into your product process</li> <li>The Product Manager's Guide to User Research : Practical tactical guide from Maze</li> <li>The Mom Test by Rob Fitzpatrick : The book on asking questions that get truth (short, practical, essential)</li> <li>ProductTalk: What Claude Code Is and How It's Different : Teresa Torres on using Claude Code for product discovery</li> </ul>"},{"location":"playbooks/your-pm-os.html","title":"Your PM OS","text":"<p>A personal OS is the workspace where Claude Code knows your context, your work is organized, and your recurring processes get easier over time instead of staying manual. Without it, CC is just a chatbot. You ask something, it answers, and next time you start from zero. With it, every session builds on the last.</p> <p>Quick Answer</p> <p>Use this when: You want to move from ad-hoc Claude Code usage to a system that compounds over time.</p> <p>Avoid this when: You're looking for a step-by-step tutorial. This page is the philosophy. The course module walks you through building yours.</p> <p>What CC changes: CLAUDE.md is how CC knows your context. Skills turn recurring work into reusable commands. MCPs connect to your real tools. The folder structure keeps your work organized. Together, they form a system that gets smarter the more you use it.</p> <p>Default move: Start with context (CLAUDE.md + a few reference files). Add structure as your work demands it. Automate only what hurts to do manually.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/your-pm-os.html#the-three-layers","title":"The Three Layers","text":"<p>Every effective OS, regardless of how it's organized, has the same three layers. The specific folder structure doesn't matter. The layers do.</p> <pre><code>flowchart TD\n    subgraph OS[\"YOUR OS\"]\n        C[\"CONTEXT\\nClaude knows who you are\\n\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\\nCLAUDE.md, reference files,\\nproject docs\"]\n        W[\"WORK\\nWhere things get done\\n\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\\nProject folders, drafts,\\noutputs\"]\n        A[\"AUTOMATION\\nWhat makes it compound\\n\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\\nSkills, rules, MCPs,\\nhooks, scripts\"]\n    end</code></pre> <p>Context means CC doesn't start from zero. You don't re-explain your role, your company, or your preferences every session. CLAUDE.md and reference files carry that forward.</p> <p>Work means your outputs have a home. Projects live in folders. Drafts are findable. Nothing disappears into conversation history.</p> <p>Automation means recurring things get easier over time. The fifth time you do something takes less effort than the first. Skills, rules, MCPs, hooks, and scripts are the mechanisms.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/your-pm-os.html#the-fractal-property","title":"The Fractal Property","text":"<p>The same three-layer pattern shows up at every scale. Not just your whole OS, but every area within it.</p> <pre><code>Your Whole OS                       One Area (e.g., Content Creation)\n\u250c\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2510             \u250c\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2510\n\u2502 Context             \u2502             \u2502 Context: voice files, brand     \u2502\n\u2502 Work                \u2502   same      \u2502   guidelines, audience docs     \u2502\n\u2502 Automation          \u2502  pattern    \u2502 Work: drafts, published pieces, \u2502\n\u2514\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2518     \u2192       \u2502   content calendar              \u2502\n                                    \u2502 Automation: dev centers,        \u2502\n                                    \u2502   publishing workflows          \u2502\n                                    \u2514\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2518\n</code></pre> <p>Zoom into any single area -- content creation, project management, research, data analysis, meetings -- and it has the same three layers at a smaller scale. Each area has its own context (the background info specific to that type of work), its own work artifacts (the outputs), and its own automation (skills and processes for that domain).</p> <p>Your OS is not one monolithic system. It's a collection of areas, each with its own version of the three layers, each at a different level of maturity. That's normal. That's how it's supposed to work.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/your-pm-os.html#the-five-level-progression","title":"The Five-Level Progression","text":"<p>The three layers describe what your OS is made of. The five levels describe how each part develops over time.</p> <pre><code>flowchart LR\n    L1[\"Level 1\\nManual\"] --&gt; L2[\"Level 2\\nDocumented\"]\n    L2 --&gt; L3[\"Level 3\\nSkilled\"]\n    L3 --&gt; L4[\"Level 4\\nConnected\"]\n    L4 --&gt; L5[\"Level 5\\nAutomated\"]</code></pre> Level What It Means Example (Meeting Summaries) 1. Manual You do it in a conversation every time \"Summarize this meeting for me\" with format instructions every time 2. Documented Context is written down so CC does it better CLAUDE.md says \"when summarizing meetings, pull out action items with owners and deadlines\" 3. Skilled It's a reusable command <code>/process-transcript</code> produces consistent output every time. See Skills reference. 4. Connected The skill pulls from real tools via MCPs Skill reads calendar to know which meetings happened, checks task manager for existing items 5. Automated It just runs Every evening at 5pm, summaries generated, actions filed, tomorrow's prep ready <p>The key insight: Different parts of the same system sit at different levels. Your content creation might be level 5 (full pipeline with publishing workflows), while your personal finance is level 1 (you just installed the budget tool last week). That's fine. That's expected.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/your-pm-os.html#real-examples-at-different-levels","title":"Real Examples at Different Levels","text":"Person Area at Level 4-5 Area at Level 1-2 Teresa Torres Daily planning (automated research digest, /today command pulls from Trello) File organization (structured folders, no automation for how files move) Arman Hezarkhani Document processing (skilled processing commands, connected to tools) Ongoing work management (system processes inputs, doesn't manage long-running work) Carl Vellotti Content creation (full pipeline, scheduled stats, publishing workflows, 70+ skills) Personal finance (just installed the budget MCP, barely started)"},{"location":"playbooks/your-pm-os.html#context-lives-where-its-useful","title":"Context Lives Where It's Useful","text":"<p>Context doesn't all live in one place. It lives wherever it makes sense.</p> <pre><code>Root level:      CLAUDE.md, reference files that apply to everything\n                 (company info, preferences, global rules)\n\nArea level:      Context shared across related work\n                 (brand guidelines in a content area, style guide\n                 in a writing folder, stakeholder notes in meetings)\n\nProject level:   Context specific to one piece of work\n                 (the client brief, the research, the requirements)\n</code></pre> <p>CC can read any of it. You don't need to centralize context. Put it where it's most useful.</p> <p>Some people have a dedicated <code>reference/</code> or <code>llm-context/</code> folder. Others scatter context files wherever they're relevant. Both work. The question is whether CC can find and read the right context when it needs to, and your CLAUDE.md can index those files so CC knows where to look.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/your-pm-os.html#what-makes-good-context","title":"What Makes Good Context","text":"Bad  Good A resume or bio (\"I'm a PM at Acme Corp with 8 years of experience\") Opinions about how work should be done (\"stakeholder updates should lead with decisions needed, not status\") \"I like Claude to be helpful\" \"Lead with the answer. Use bullet points. Always assign owners to action items.\" Everything in one massive CLAUDE.md Global rules in CLAUDE.md, area context in area folders, project context in project folders Static context written once Context that evolves. When you find yourself explaining the same thing twice, capture it."},{"location":"playbooks/your-pm-os.html#when-not-to-level-up","title":"When NOT to Level Up","text":"<p>Not everything should go to level 5. There is a real cost to moving up the progression. More to maintain. More to remember. More that can break. A level 5 automation that you built six months ago and forgot how it works is worse than a level 2 workflow you do manually but reliably.</p> <p>The question is not \"how do I get everything to level 5.\" The question is \"what's worth the investment?\"</p> <pre><code>flowchart TD\n    Q[\"'Should I automate this?'\"] --&gt; F{How often?}\n    F --&gt;|Rarely| STOP[\"Stay at Level 1-2\\nNot worth the investment\"]\n    F --&gt;|Regularly| P{How painful?}\n    P --&gt;|Manageable| STAY[\"Stay current level\\nFriction isn't high enough\"]\n    P --&gt;|Genuinely painful| COST{Maintenance cost?}\n    COST --&gt;|Low| UP[\"Promote one level\\nSkill or connection\"]\n    COST --&gt;|High| WAIT[\"Wait until the pain\\nclearly exceeds the cost\"]</code></pre> <p>The framework for deciding: only promote something when the pain of doing it manually genuinely exceeds the cost of building and maintaining the automation.</p> <p>Most things can live at level 1 or 2 forever and that's fine. A few level 4-5 workflows will handle most of your recurring work. The 80/20 rule applies hard here.</p> <p>The common failure mode: People try to automate everything on day one. They design the whole thing at once, get overwhelmed, and abandon it. The people who succeed build gradually. They try to do something, figure it out, and if they do it enough times, they formalize it. It's pull-based, not push-based.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/your-pm-os.html#the-system-grows-from-use-not-from-planning","title":"The System Grows From Use, Not From Planning","text":"<p>This is the most important principle. You don't sit down and design your OS. You discover it through friction.</p> <p>Teresa Torres didn't create all her context files one afternoon. She built them gradually. Every time she found herself explaining something to CC that she'd need to explain again, she stopped and said \"let's capture this in a context file.\" She'd tell CC to interview her about a topic and then write a file from what it learned. At the end of sessions, she asks \"what did you learn about me that we should add to a context file?\"</p> <p>That's the pattern:</p> <ol> <li>You do work in CC</li> <li>You notice friction (re-explaining context, doing something the same way every time, wishing CC knew something)</li> <li>You formalize what's worth keeping (context file, skill, rule)</li> <li>The next time is easier</li> <li>Repeat</li> </ol> <p>The system tells you what's worth formalizing. You don't have to guess upfront. The friction is the signal.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/your-pm-os.html#the-universal-cycle","title":"The Universal Cycle","text":"<p>Every area of work in an OS follows the same cycle:</p> <pre><code>flowchart LR\n    CTX[\"Context\\n(was there)\"] --&gt; AUTO[\"Automation\\n(did the work)\"]\n    AUTO --&gt; OUT[\"Output\\n(landed in project)\"]\n    OUT --&gt; LEARN[\"Learn\\n(what to formalize)\"]\n    LEARN --&gt; CTX</code></pre> <p>Context feeds the skill. The skill does the work. The output lives in the project. And you learn what's worth capturing for next time. This cycle applies to quarterly planning, meeting processing, data analysis, document creation, content production. The content changes. The cycle doesn't.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/your-pm-os.html#building-your-os-the-practical-path","title":"Building Your OS: The Practical Path","text":"<p>Week 1: Start with CLAUDE.md. Write your role, preferences, and current focus. Add one project folder with real files in it. Do real work.</p> <p>Week 2-3: Notice what you keep re-explaining. Capture it in context files. Notice what you keep doing the same way. Consider whether it's worth a skill.</p> <p>Month 2: You have 3-5 context files, a few project folders, maybe 1-2 skills. One area is at level 3. Most are at level 1-2. This is a working OS.</p> <p>Month 3+: Connect a tool via MCP if the manual input is genuinely painful. Build more skills as patterns emerge. Archive completed projects. Keep CLAUDE.md current.</p>  Bad  Good Design the perfect folder structure on day one Start with CLAUDE.md and one project folder. Add structure when work demands it. Build 20 skills before doing any real work Do real work first. Build skills when you notice repetition. Try to reach level 5 everywhere Let most things sit at level 1-2. Promote only when the pain justifies it. Copy someone else's OS structure Your OS reflects your work. Use others for inspiration, not blueprints."},{"location":"playbooks/your-pm-os.html#three-real-setups","title":"Three Real Setups","text":"<p>Different people, different structures, same principles.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/your-pm-os.html#the-obsidian-pm","title":"The Obsidian PM","text":"<pre><code>work/                          (Obsidian vault)\n\u251c\u2500\u2500 CLAUDE.md                  (global rules + context file index)\n\u251c\u2500\u2500 llm-context/               (focused reference files)\n\u2502   \u251c\u2500\u2500 business-profile.md\n\u2502   \u251c\u2500\u2500 target-audience.md\n\u2502   \u2514\u2500\u2500 personal-profile.md\n\u251c\u2500\u2500 tasks/                     (own CLAUDE.md, runs /today)\n\u2502   \u251c\u2500\u2500 CLAUDE.md\n\u2502   \u2514\u2500\u2500 tasks/, ideas/, inbox/\n\u251c\u2500\u2500 writing/                   (own CLAUDE.md, style guide)\n\u2502   \u251c\u2500\u2500 CLAUDE.md\n\u2502   \u2514\u2500\u2500 article-series/\n\u2514\u2500\u2500 research/\n</code></pre> <p>Context layer: llm-context/ with focused reference files, plus CLAUDE.md files in each subfolder. Work layer: tasks, writing, research. Automation layer: /today command that generates daily planning from Trello + academic research.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/your-pm-os.html#the-processing-queue","title":"The Processing Queue","text":"<pre><code>workspace/\n\u251c\u2500\u2500 CLAUDE.md                  (processing instructions)\n\u251c\u2500\u2500 inbox/                     (raw inputs land here)\n\u251c\u2500\u2500 processed/                 (handled items)\n\u251c\u2500\u2500 outputs/                   (finished artifacts)\n\u2502   \u251c\u2500\u2500 summaries/\n\u2502   \u251c\u2500\u2500 action-items/\n\u2502   \u2514\u2500\u2500 drafts/\n\u251c\u2500\u2500 reference/                 (read-only context)\n\u2514\u2500\u2500 .claude/skills/            (processing skills)\n</code></pre> <p>Context layer: reference/ folder (company info, team roles, style guide), never modified. Work layer: inbox-to-processed-to-outputs flow. Automation layer: processing skills for different input types.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/your-pm-os.html#the-business-runner","title":"The Business Runner","text":"<pre><code>life-os/\n\u251c\u2500\u2500 CLAUDE.md                  (global rules, initiative index)\n\u251c\u2500\u2500 Work Journal/              (planning context)\n\u2502   \u251c\u2500\u2500 Business Context.md\n\u2502   \u2514\u2500\u2500 SAO.md\n\u251c\u2500\u2500 Initiatives/               (per-initiative strategy)\n\u251c\u2500\u2500 Projects/                  (active deliverables)\n\u251c\u2500\u2500 Content Creation/          (full pipeline)\n\u251c\u2500\u2500 .claude/skills/            (70+ skills)\n\u2514\u2500\u2500 .mcp.json                  (8 tool connections)\n</code></pre> <p>Context layer: Business Context, SAO, Initiative files scattered wherever they're relevant. Work layer: Projects, Content Creation, Work Journal. Automation layer: 70+ skills, 8 MCPs, daily/weekly rituals.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/your-pm-os.html#the-maintenance-habits","title":"The Maintenance Habits","text":"<p>An OS that doesn't get maintained rots. But maintenance should be lightweight, not a chore.</p> <p>_temp/ folder: Pure scratch space. Throwaway outputs, files to copy-paste, quick looks. Delete the whole thing periodically.</p> <p>Archive completed projects. Don't delete old work. Move it to archive/. Still readable, not cluttering your active workspace.</p> <p>Keep CLAUDE.md current. Review it when your role changes, when you start a major new area of work, or when CC keeps making the same mistake. If it's working, don't touch it.</p> <p>End-of-session habit: Ask CC \"based on what we just did, is there anything we should update in CLAUDE.md or any cleanup you'd suggest?\" Takes ten seconds. It's how your OS learns from use.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/your-pm-os.html#common-mistakes","title":"Common Mistakes","text":"Mistake Why It Happens What to Do Instead Over-design upfront \"I need the perfect structure first\" Start with CLAUDE.md and one project. The structure reveals itself through use. Automate everything on day one Excitement about the possibilities Do real work manually first. Automate when friction tells you to. One massive CLAUDE.md \"Everything is important\" Global context in CLAUDE.md. Area context in area folders. Project context in projects. Copy someone else's OS \"Teresa's setup looks great\" Her OS reflects her work. Yours needs to reflect yours. Use others for principles, not structure. Never maintain it \"It's set up, I'm done\" End-of-session check, periodic CLAUDE.md review, archive old projects Treat all areas equally \"Everything should be level 4\" 80/20. A few high-maturity workflows. Most things at level 1-2."},{"location":"playbooks/your-pm-os.html#plug-play","title":"Plug &amp; Play","text":"<p><code>/quarterly-goals</code> Example skill: reads project context, asks three questions, writes a goals document. Demonstrates the full context-to-output cycle.</p> <p><code>/meeting-aftermath</code> Composable skill: six sub-skills chained together. Demonstrates the orchestrator pattern for multi-step workflows.</p> <p><code>/sync-github</code> Back up your OS to a private GitHub repo. Version history, backup, and cross-device access in one command.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/your-pm-os.html#references","title":"References","text":"<p>Internal:</p> <ul> <li>Creating Documents : Document system that compounds over time</li> <li>Meeting Processing : Composable skills architecture in practice</li> <li>Data &amp; Decisions : Analytical workflows with cross-notebook context</li> </ul> <p>External:</p> <ul> <li>Anthropic: Skills : Building reusable commands</li> <li>Anthropic: Sub-agents : Parallel processing patterns</li> <li>Anthropic: Claude Code best practices : Official guidance on workspace design</li> <li>ProductTalk: What Claude Code Is and How It's Different : Teresa Torres on building her OS</li> </ul>"},{"location":"playbooks/building/index.html","title":"The PM Builder","text":"<p>PMs don't touch code. That used to be true. Claude Code makes it false. Not because you become an engineer, but because the barrier between \"I know what to build\" and \"I can show what I mean\" disappears.</p> <p>Quick Answer</p> <p>Use this when: You need to explore a codebase, improve existing features, build prototypes, or ship contributions through git.</p> <p>Avoid this when: You're doing research or analysis. That's User Research.</p> <p>What CC changes: You go from \"ask engineering and wait\" to \"explore it yourself, prototype it yourself, ship it yourself.\" Read-only intelligence, targeted improvements, full feature builds, and real PRs. All through natural language.</p> <p>Default move: Start by exploring. Never change code you haven't mapped first.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/building/index.html#the-arc","title":"The Arc","text":"<p>Four phases, each one ratcheting up what you can do. Every phase builds on the last.</p> <pre><code>flowchart LR\n    O[\"Explore\\n(read-only)\"] --&gt; C[\"Modify\\n(targeted changes)\"]\n    C --&gt; B[\"Build\\n(new features)\"]\n    B --&gt; S[\"Ship\\n(git + PRs)\"]</code></pre>"},{"location":"playbooks/building/index.html#exploring-codebases","title":"Exploring Codebases","text":"<p>Map the system without touching anything. Architecture diagrams, flow traces, complexity estimates. The intelligence package that used to take a week of bugging engineers, generated in minutes. This is where you earn the context that makes everything else work.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/building/index.html#modifying-improving","title":"Modifying &amp; Improving","text":"<p>Cross from observer to contributor. Targeted improvements to existing features following the patterns the codebase already uses. The reference pattern: find how the app handles something before you change it. Consistency over creativity.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/building/index.html#adding-features","title":"Adding Features","text":"<p>Build something that doesn't exist yet. Spec-driven development with <code>/grill-me</code> catches wrong assumptions before a line of code is written. Design system context makes everything look native. Variant generation lets you build three options in the time it takes to debate one.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/building/index.html#shipping-code","title":"Shipping Code","text":"<p>Save your work, fix bugs, push PRs. Git through natural language. The Esc Esc safety mechanism means you can break things without consequences. The full cycle from change to reviewed PR, using the same workflow your engineering team uses every day.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/building/index.html#how-claude-code-changes-building","title":"How Claude Code Changes Building","text":"Traditional PM PM with Claude Code Ask engineering \"how hard would this be?\" and wait Generate a scoping brief grounded in the actual code Describe what you want in a PRD and hope Build three working prototypes and pick the winner File a vague bug report: \"Settings is broken\" Trace the bug to a one-character route mismatch and fix it Review mockups in Figma and give feedback Review working code in a browser and iterate in real-time Never see the PR process Author PRs with clear context that engineers actually want to review <p>The mindset shift: you are not becoming an engineer. You are becoming a PM who can see, touch, and contribute to the same system your engineers work in. That changes every conversation about scope, feasibility, and priority.</p> <p>CC Limitation</p> <p>Claude Code is a powerful building tool, but it does not replace engineering judgment on production systems. Use it for prototyping, exploration, and targeted contributions. Complex architectural decisions, performance optimization, and production deployment still need your engineering team. Knowing when to hand off is as important as knowing how to contribute.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/building/index.html#where-to-start","title":"Where to Start","text":"<p>Never worked in a codebase before? Start with Exploring Codebases. Map the system before you touch anything.</p> <p>Want to make improvements? Go to Modifying &amp; Improving. Three targeted changes following the reference pattern.</p> <p>Ready to build something new? See Adding Features. Spec-driven development with variant generation.</p> <p>Need to save and ship your work? Shipping Code covers git, safety, and the PR workflow.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/building/index.html#references","title":"References","text":"<p>Internal:</p> <ul> <li>Exploring Codebases : Architecture mapping, flow tracing, complexity estimation</li> <li>Modifying &amp; Improving : The reference pattern for targeted improvements</li> <li>Adding Features : Spec-driven development and variant generation</li> <li>Shipping Code : Git workflow, safety mechanisms, and PRs</li> </ul> <p>External:</p> <ul> <li>Anthropic: Sub-agents : How parallel codebase exploration works</li> <li>Anthropic: Claude Code best practices : Official guidance on building with Claude Code</li> </ul>"},{"location":"playbooks/building/adding-features.html","title":"Adding Features","text":"<p>Building a new feature with Claude Code follows a specific order: spec first, build second. The biggest risk is not bad code. It is wrong assumptions. You say \"dashboard\" and Claude pictures something. You picture something different. Twenty minutes later you are looking at a working feature that solves the wrong problem.</p> <p>Quick Answer</p> <p>Use this when: You need to build a new feature, prototype, or component that doesn't exist in the codebase yet.</p> <p>Avoid this when: You're improving existing features. That's Modifying &amp; Improving. If you haven't explored the codebase yet, start with Exploring Codebases.</p> <p>What CC changes: You can build three working prototypes in the time it takes to debate one approach in a meeting. Spec-driven development with <code>/grill-me</code> catches wrong assumptions before any code exists. Design system context makes everything look native.</p> <p>Default move: Write the spec (or let <code>/grill-me</code> extract it from you) before building anything. Define variant directions upfront. Build all of them.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/building/adding-features.html#the-spec-driven-build","title":"The Spec-Driven Build","text":"<p>Four things Claude needs from you before building. Skip any of them and the result drifts from what you actually want.</p> <pre><code>flowchart TD\n    V[\"Vision\\nWhat this does for users\"] --&gt; C[\"Constraints\\nWhat it must NOT do\"]\n    C --&gt; AC[\"Acceptance Criteria\\nHow you know it's done\"]\n    AC --&gt; TP[\"Test Plan\\nHow Claude self-verifies\"]\n    TP --&gt; VD[\"Variant Directions\\n2-3 interaction models\"]\n    VD --&gt; B[\"Build\"]</code></pre> Element What It Covers Why It Matters Vision What this feature does for users, not what it looks like Keeps the build anchored to a real problem Constraints What it must NOT do (scope boundaries, off-limits behavior) Prevents Claude from adding \"helpful\" extras that bloat the feature Acceptance criteria Specific conditions for \"done\" Gives you and Claude a shared definition of success Test plan How Claude self-verifies at each stage (puppeteer screenshots, not just a check at the end) Catches drift during the build, not after Variant directions 2-3 different interaction models to build Turns debate into evaluation of real options"},{"location":"playbooks/building/adding-features.html#let-grill-me-extract-the-spec","title":"Let <code>/grill-me</code> Extract the Spec","text":"<p>You could write the spec yourself. Or you could let Claude interrogate you until the spec writes itself.</p> <pre><code>/grill-me @docs/workload-dashboard-scoping.md\n- I want to explore 3 variants: expandable rows, slide-out panel,\n  and modal deep-dive.\n- Save the spec to docs/workload-dashboard-spec.md.\n</code></pre> <p>The <code>/grill-me</code> skill asks questions you haven't considered. What happens when a team member has zero tasks? How do overload thresholds work? What counts as \"at risk\" vs \"blocked\"? Your answers shape every part of the spec.</p> <p>The conversation matters more than the document. The questions surface assumptions you didn't know you were making. The spec document is the artifact. The process of creating it is the value.</p>  Bad  Good \"Build a workload dashboard\" \"Here's the spec: vision, constraints, acceptance criteria, test plan, and 3 variant directions. All informed by the scoping brief from exploration.\" Let Claude make assumptions about layout and behavior Let <code>/grill-me</code> surface those assumptions before building One take: build it and hope Define 2-3 variants upfront. Build all of them."},{"location":"playbooks/building/adding-features.html#design-system-context","title":"Design System Context","text":"<p>The difference between \"technically works but looks like a demo\" and \"looks like it belongs in this product\" is a design system file.</p> <p>A <code>design-system.md</code> tells Claude what your product looks like: brand tokens, component patterns, spacing rules, visual guidelines. The same brief you would give a designer, except Claude reads it every time it builds something.</p> <pre><code>## Brand Tokens\n- Primary: #2563EB\n- Surface: #F8FAFC\n- Border radius: 8px\n- Spacing scale: 4/8/12/16/24/32px\n\n## Component Patterns\n- Cards: subtle shadow, 1px border, 16px padding\n- Buttons: filled primary, outlined secondary, ghost tertiary\n- Tables: alternating row backgrounds, sticky headers\n\n## Visual Guidelines\n- Information hierarchy through size and weight, not color\n- Generous whitespace between sections\n- Icons from [library name] only\n</code></pre> <p>Without a design system, Claude produces generic-looking output. Safe colors, default padding, nothing distinctive. With one, every component matches your product's visual identity.</p> <p>CC Advantage</p> <p>If your team has a Figma design system, you can use the Figma MCP server to pull design context directly. Or build <code>design-system.md</code> by hand from your product's existing patterns. Either way, the file becomes the quality lever for every build.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/building/adding-features.html#why-variants","title":"Why Variants","text":"<p>Traditional product development: debate three layout options in a meeting, pick one, build it over a sprint, hope it was the right call.</p> <p>With Claude Code: build all three in the time it takes to have that meeting. Evaluate real working prototypes instead of imagining what they would feel like.</p> <pre><code>flowchart LR\n    subgraph Traditional\n        D[\"Debate\"] --&gt; P[\"Pick 1\"] --&gt; BT[\"Build it\\n(1 sprint)\"]\n    end\n\n    subgraph With CC\n        V2[\"Vision\"] --&gt; B3[\"Build 3\\nvariants\"]\n        B3 --&gt; E[\"Evaluate\\nreal prototypes\"]\n        E --&gt; W[\"Pick\\nwinner\"]\n    end</code></pre> <p>Variant directions go into the spec from the start. You define 2-3 different interaction models, and Claude builds all of them against the same acceptance criteria.</p> <p>Example variant set for a workload dashboard:</p> Variant Interaction Model Best For A: Expandable rows Click a row to expand detail inline Quick scanning without losing context B: Slide-out panel Click to open a side panel with deep detail Detail without losing the overview C: Modal deep-dive Click to open a full modal with all context Maximum information per person <p>All three serve the same user need. They just solve it differently. Building all three takes less time than arguing about which one to build.</p> <pre><code>Switch to plan mode: build all 3 variants from the spec.\nInclude the test plan verification after each one.\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"playbooks/building/adding-features.html#evaluating-variants","title":"Evaluating Variants","text":"<p>After all three are built, click through each one. Pay attention to how each feels when doing the actual task the feature serves, not how it looks in a screenshot.</p> <p>The judgment call is yours. Different teams, different workflows, different answers. The point is you had three real options to evaluate instead of one take-it-or-leave-it build.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/building/adding-features.html#the-build-workflow","title":"The Build Workflow","text":"<pre><code>flowchart TD\n    SC[\"Scoping brief\\n(from Exploring Codebases)\"] --&gt; SP[\"Spec\\n(from /grill-me)\"]\n    SP --&gt; DS[\"Design system\\ncontext\"]\n    DS --&gt; B2[\"Build variants\"]\n    B2 --&gt; EV[\"Evaluate +\\npick winner\"]\n    EV --&gt; IT[\"Iterate on\\nwinner\"]\n    IT --&gt; SH[\"Ship\\n(Shipping Code)\"]</code></pre> <p>The scoping brief from Exploring Codebases maps files, components, and patterns. The spec from <code>/grill-me</code> captures vision, constraints, and acceptance criteria. The design system ensures visual consistency. Build, evaluate, iterate, ship.</p> <p>For 90% of feature prototyping, high-fidelity takes the same effort as low-fidelity. The prototype IS the wireframe. You would never show a stakeholder a grey box when you can show them a working prototype.</p> <p>The exception: truly novel interaction patterns that don't have UI precedent. If you are inventing the interaction model itself, sketching on paper still has value. But for dashboards, forms, settings pages, CRUD features? Build the real thing.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/building/adding-features.html#common-mistakes","title":"Common Mistakes","text":"Mistake Why It Happens What to Do Instead Building without a spec \"I'll know it when I see it\" You won't. Or rather, you'll see it and realize it's wrong. Spec first. One variant only Feels faster Build 2-3. The time difference is minimal. The decision quality improvement is massive. No design system context Seems optional Claude produces generic-looking output without it. Even a minimal design system file transforms the result. Skipping <code>/grill-me</code> \"I already know what I want\" You know what you want at the surface level. <code>/grill-me</code> surfaces the edge cases and constraints you haven't considered. Iterating endlessly on variants Perfectionism Pick a winner, ship it, iterate based on real feedback. Three builds is enough to make a decision. No test plan in the spec Testing feels like a separate step Include it in the spec. Claude self-verifies at each stage with puppeteer screenshots, catching drift during the build, not after."},{"location":"playbooks/building/adding-features.html#plug-play","title":"Plug &amp; Play","text":"<p><code>/grill-me</code> Spec extraction through interrogation. Asks about vision, constraints, acceptance criteria, test plan, and variant directions. Saves a complete spec document. Works for any feature.</p> <p><code>/scope-feature</code> Generates a scoping brief from the codebase: files affected, patterns to reuse, new components needed. Use this as input to <code>/grill-me</code>.</p> <p><code>/explore-codebase</code> If you haven't mapped the codebase yet, start here. The architecture overview and UI pattern catalog inform every build decision.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/building/adding-features.html#references","title":"References","text":"<p>Internal:</p> <ul> <li>The PM Builder : Hub page for the full building arc</li> <li>Exploring Codebases : Generate the scoping brief that feeds spec creation</li> <li>Modifying &amp; Improving : The reference pattern that keeps new features consistent with existing code</li> <li>Shipping Code : Save and ship your built features</li> </ul> <p>External:</p> <ul> <li>Anthropic: Claude Code best practices : Official guidance on feature development workflows</li> </ul>"},{"location":"playbooks/building/exploring-codebases.html","title":"Exploring Codebases","text":"<p>Codebase exploration turns \"I have no idea what's in there\" into a complete technical intelligence package: architecture diagram, flow trace, complexity estimate. All read-only. All generated without writing a single line of code. The kind of context that normally takes a week of bugging engineers, produced in minutes.</p> <p>Quick Answer</p> <p>Use this when: You're joining a new team, evaluating an open-source project, scoping engineering work, or need to understand how a feature actually works before making product decisions.</p> <p>Avoid this when: You already know the codebase and want to make changes. That's Modifying &amp; Improving.</p> <p>What CC changes: Three parallel sub-agents explore architecture, tech stack, and UI patterns simultaneously. Fresh context per agent prevents cross-contamination. You get three independent analyses synthesized into one document.</p> <p>Default move: Run the parallel exploration first. Map the whole system before tracing any specific flow.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/building/exploring-codebases.html#three-artifacts-three-agents","title":"Three Artifacts, Three Agents","text":"<p>A useful codebase exploration produces three things:</p> <ol> <li>Architecture overview : how the pieces connect (components, layers, data flow)</li> <li>Tech stack summary : what you're working with (frameworks, libraries, conventions)</li> <li>UI pattern catalog : what's already built that you can reuse (components, design tokens, layouts)</li> </ol> <p>Each gets its own sub-agent with fresh context. No cross-contamination between analyses.</p> <pre><code>flowchart TD\n    Y[\"You\"] --&gt; A1[\"Agent 1\\nArchitecture\"]\n    Y --&gt; A2[\"Agent 2\\nTech Stack\"]\n    Y --&gt; A3[\"Agent 3\\nUI Patterns\"]\n\n    A1 --&gt; S[\"Synthesized into\\ndocs/architecture-overview.md\"]\n    A2 --&gt; S\n    A3 --&gt; S</code></pre> <p>Why three agents, not one long exploration? Same reason as parallel extraction in interview analysis. Each agent analyzes one dimension of the codebase without being influenced by what the others found. The architecture agent is not biased by the UI patterns agent's findings. Three independent perspectives, then synthesis. Different lenses on the same thing produce better results than one sequential pass.</p> <pre><code>/explore-codebase\n</code></pre> <p>Or describe what you want:</p> <pre><code>Explore this codebase with parallel agents. One for architecture\nand component relationships, one for tech stack and dependencies,\none for UI patterns and reusable components. Synthesize findings\ninto docs/architecture-overview.md.\n</code></pre> <p>CC Advantage</p> <p>Each sub-agent gets fresh context. The main conversation might be deep into a product discussion, but the exploration agents see only the codebase. This isolation produces cleaner analysis than reading files sequentially in one increasingly crowded context window.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/building/exploring-codebases.html#what-a-typical-architecture-overview-contains","title":"What a Typical Architecture Overview Contains","text":"<p>The synthesized document covers:</p> Section What It Shows Why PMs Care System diagram Major components and how they connect (Mermaid) Know which teams own which pieces. Understand dependencies before proposing changes. Data flow How information moves through the system Trace where bugs could live. Understand what a \"simple\" change actually touches. Tech stack Frameworks, libraries, key conventions Speak engineering's language in sprint planning. Know what's possible within the current stack. UI components Reusable pieces already built Don't propose features that require new components when existing ones would work. Know what your design system already supports. Test coverage Where tests exist and where they don't Flag risk areas before they become production incidents. <p>This document becomes your project's context library. Reference it in every future conversation about this codebase.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/building/exploring-codebases.html#flow-tracing","title":"Flow Tracing","text":"<p>After the broad overview, pick a specific feature and trace exactly how it works end to end. One user action, from the moment they click a button to the moment the result appears on screen.</p> <pre><code>Trace the \"create a task\" flow end to end. Show every component,\nAPI call, and validation step. Generate a Mermaid sequence diagram\nand save to docs/task-creation-flow.md.\n</code></pre> <p>What a flow trace reveals:</p> <pre><code>sequenceDiagram\n    participant U as User\n    participant F as Form Component\n    participant H as Hook (API call)\n    participant R as API Route\n    participant V as Validation\n    participant DB as Database\n\n    U-&gt;&gt;F: Clicks \"Create Task\"\n    F-&gt;&gt;F: Validates form fields\n    F-&gt;&gt;H: Calls createTask()\n    H-&gt;&gt;R: POST /api/tasks\n    R-&gt;&gt;V: Validates request body\n    V-&gt;&gt;DB: INSERT task\n    DB--&gt;&gt;R: Return new task\n    R--&gt;&gt;H: 201 Created\n    H--&gt;&gt;F: Update local state\n    F--&gt;&gt;U: Show new task in list</code></pre> <p>One button. Six files deep. Now you know why engineers sigh when you say \"can we just add a button?\" A form component, a hook, an API route, database logic, validation at multiple levels, response handling back up the chain.</p> <p>How this changes bug conversations:</p>  Bad  Good \"Task creation is broken\" \"Task creation fails silently. Based on the flow trace, the issue is likely between the API route and the database write because the form validation passes but the task doesn't appear.\" File a vague bug report and wait Pinpoint the layer and hand engineering a specific starting point <p>You went from filing a vague report to pinpointing the layer. That is a fundamentally different conversation with your engineering team.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/building/exploring-codebases.html#feature-scoping","title":"Feature Scoping","text":"<p>The third artifact: a complexity estimate for a proposed feature.</p> <pre><code>Scope a feature: Team Workload Dashboard with workload indicators\nper member, overload warnings, and flag-and-triage system.\nAnalyze the codebase for feasibility. Save to\ndocs/workload-dashboard-scoping.md.\n</code></pre> <p>A scoping brief covers:</p> <ul> <li>New components needed and their responsibilities</li> <li>Existing patterns to reuse (components, layouts, hooks)</li> <li>API additions required</li> <li>Database changes (new tables, modified schemas)</li> <li>Test gaps that the feature would expose</li> <li>Complexity estimate (directional, not exact hours)</li> </ul>  Bad  Good \"How hard would it be to add a workload dashboard?\" \"It depends.\" \"The scoping brief shows 3 new components, 2 API routes, reuse of the existing card layout and design tokens. Estimated medium complexity based on the codebase patterns.\" Walk into sprint planning with vibes Walk in with specific files, patterns, and dependencies <p>CC Limitation</p> <p>Complexity estimates from Claude Code are directional, not gospel. Claude maps which files are involved and what patterns exist, but it will not nail the exact hours. Use scoping briefs as a starting point for the conversation with engineering, not a replacement for it. The difference is you're walking in with specifics instead of vibes.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/building/exploring-codebases.html#real-world-applications","title":"Real-World Applications","text":"<p>This is not just a learning exercise. The exploration pattern works anywhere.</p> Scenario What to Run What You Get Onboarding to a new team Parallel exploration on the team's repo Architecture overview before your first sprint Evaluating a vendor's open-source project Architecture overview + critical flow trace Informed decision before committing Scoping engineering work for roadmap Feature scoping brief Complexity estimates grounded in actual code Verifying docs vs. reality Flow trace on a documented feature Find where docs are outdated or wrong Investigating a customer-reported bug Flow trace on the affected feature Pinpoint the layer before escalating to engineering"},{"location":"playbooks/building/exploring-codebases.html#common-mistakes","title":"Common Mistakes","text":"Mistake Why It Happens What to Do Instead One long exploration instead of parallel agents Feels simpler Three focused agents produce better results than one unfocused pass Tracing a flow before mapping the system Want to jump into specifics Broad overview first. You need context to interpret what the flow trace shows Taking complexity estimates as exact Numbers feel authoritative They're directional. Use them to start conversations, not end them Not saving artifacts to a docs folder Seems like extra work These become your context library. Every future conversation benefits from referencing them Exploring without a question Curiosity without purpose Start with what you need to know. \"How does task creation work?\" focuses the exploration"},{"location":"playbooks/building/exploring-codebases.html#plug-play","title":"Plug &amp; Play","text":"<p><code>/explore-codebase</code> Three parallel sub-agents: architecture, tech stack, UI patterns. Synthesizes into a single architecture overview document.</p> <p><code>/scope-feature</code> Takes a feature description and generates a full scoping brief: files affected, patterns to reuse, new components needed, test gaps, complexity estimate.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/building/exploring-codebases.html#references","title":"References","text":"<p>Internal:</p> <ul> <li>The PM Builder : Hub page for the full building arc</li> <li>Modifying &amp; Improving : What to do after you've mapped the codebase</li> <li>Adding Features : Using scoping briefs as build input</li> <li>Shipping Code : Saving and sharing your exploration artifacts</li> </ul> <p>External:</p> <ul> <li>Anthropic: Sub-agents : How parallel exploration works under the hood</li> <li>Anthropic: Claude Code best practices : Official guidance on exploration workflows</li> </ul>"},{"location":"playbooks/building/modifying-and-improving.html","title":"Modifying &amp; Improving","text":"<p>The jump from reading code to changing code is smaller than it feels. The rule is simple: before you change anything, find how the codebase already handles that exact thing. Match it. Consistency over creativity.</p> <p>Quick Answer</p> <p>Use this when: You've explored a codebase and want to make targeted improvements to existing features: copy fixes, form polish, visual enhancements.</p> <p>Avoid this when: You're building something new from scratch. That's Adding Features. Or if you haven't explored the codebase yet, start with Exploring Codebases.</p> <p>What CC changes: Claude can find patterns across the codebase and match them in seconds. But left to its own devices, it will import different libraries, invent naming conventions, and produce changes that look AI-generated. The reference pattern fixes this.</p> <p>Default move: Always find the existing pattern first. Then make your change within it.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/building/modifying-and-improving.html#the-reference-pattern","title":"The Reference Pattern","text":"<p>One idea runs through every modification you make: find how the codebase already handles this, then match it.</p> <pre><code>flowchart LR\n    Q[\"What do I want\\nto change?\"] --&gt; F[\"Find how the app\\nalready does it\"]\n    F --&gt; M[\"Match that\\npattern\"]\n    M --&gt; R[\"Result looks\\nnative\"]</code></pre> <p>This is different from the broad exploration in Exploring Codebases. Exploration maps the whole system. The reference pattern is a targeted lookup for one specific thing.</p> <ul> <li>Want to improve a form? Find how other forms in the app work.</li> <li>Want to add an icon? Find where icons are already used and how they're imported.</li> <li>Want to fix copy? Find the existing tone and conventions in similar text.</li> </ul>  Bad  Good \"Improve this form based on UX best practices\" \"Compare TaskForm and ProjectForm. What patterns does TaskForm use that ProjectForm is missing? Improve ProjectForm to match.\" Import a new icon library because you know a good one Find which icon library the app already uses. Use that. Write placeholder text that sounds good in isolation Find how other forms in the app handle placeholder text. Match that voice. <p>Why this matters for AI-assisted changes: When people complain about AI-generated code looking \"off,\" it is because Claude got creative when it should have been consistent. Claude will import a different icon library when the app already has one. It will invent new naming conventions when perfectly good ones exist two files away. The reference pattern fixes this by making the existing codebase the authority, not Claude's training data.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/building/modifying-and-improving.html#three-types-of-improvement","title":"Three Types of Improvement","text":""},{"location":"playbooks/building/modifying-and-improving.html#1-copy-fixes","title":"1. Copy Fixes","text":"<p>The smallest change with the biggest impact on product feel. Button labels, placeholder text, form labels, error messages.</p> <pre><code>Look at the forms and UI components in this app. Where could\nthe microcopy be better? Give me 3-5 specific suggestions for\nlabels, placeholder text, or button copy that could be clearer.\nFind how similar text is handled elsewhere so improvements\nmatch the existing style.\n</code></pre> <p>The PM judgment call: Not everything Claude suggests is worth changing. Some suggestions are real improvements. Some are fine as-is. Your call.</p> <p>Then scope before you change:</p> <pre><code>Enter plan mode. Scope the copy change I picked. What files does\nthis touch? What might break?\n</code></pre> <p>For a copy fix, the scope should be minimal: one or two files, no breaking risk. If plan mode shows more complexity than that, reconsider.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/building/modifying-and-improving.html#2-form-polish","title":"2. Form Polish","text":"<p>Every codebase has inconsistency. Different developers, different sprints, different levels of polish. One feature gets the full treatment. Another ships bare. As a PM, these inconsistencies erode user trust.</p> <p>The reference pattern is most powerful here. You are not redesigning from scratch. You are finding the best version of something in the codebase and pulling everything else up to that standard.</p> <pre><code>Enter plan mode. Compare TaskForm and ProjectForm. What patterns\ndoes TaskForm use that ProjectForm is missing? Improve ProjectForm\nto match the same level of quality.\n</code></pre> <p>What to look for when comparing:</p> <ul> <li>Placeholder text conventions</li> <li>Field layout and spacing</li> <li>Label styles</li> <li>Validation patterns</li> <li>Error messaging</li> <li>Empty state handling</li> </ul>"},{"location":"playbooks/building/modifying-and-improving.html#3-visual-polish","title":"3. Visual Polish","text":"<p>Design tokens are your reference file for visual changes. Most modern apps have a <code>tokens.css</code> or equivalent that defines the color palette, spacing scale, typography, and other visual constants.</p> <pre><code>Enter plan mode. Improve the stat cards with better spacing,\nicons, and visual weight. Reference the design tokens in\ntokens.css. Use puppeteer to screenshot before and after.\n</code></pre> <p>The before/after loop: Use puppeteer (or equivalent screenshot tools) to capture the current state before making changes, then capture after. This gives Claude the ability to actually see what it built. Without it, Claude is making visual changes blindfolded.</p> <pre><code>flowchart LR\n    B[\"Screenshot\\n(before)\"] --&gt; C[\"Make\\nchanges\"]\n    C --&gt; A[\"Screenshot\\n(after)\"]\n    A --&gt; V{\"Looks\\nright?\"}\n    V --&gt;|Yes| D[\"Done\"]\n    V --&gt;|No| C</code></pre>"},{"location":"playbooks/building/modifying-and-improving.html#plan-mode-as-pre-flight-check","title":"Plan Mode as Pre-flight Check","text":"<p>Always scope before you change. Plan mode shows you what files will be touched and what might break.</p>  Bad  Good \"Fix the copy on the project form\" (and hope for the best) \"Enter plan mode. Scope this copy change. What files does this touch? What might break?\" Then approve and execute. Jump straight into editing Understand the blast radius first <p>Plan mode does not catch everything. But it is the difference between \"I hope this works\" and \"I know what this touches.\"</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/building/modifying-and-improving.html#common-mistakes","title":"Common Mistakes","text":"Mistake Why It Happens What to Do Instead Getting creative instead of matching Feels like improvement should mean innovation Match first. Innovate in Adding Features, not here Skipping plan mode \"It's just a small change\" Small changes touch more files than you expect. Scope first Importing new libraries Claude's default when it doesn't look around Ask Claude to check what libraries the app already uses Visual changes without screenshots Assumes it looks right Use puppeteer or check in browser. Claude cannot see what it built without screenshots Changing everything at once Excitement after the first fix One change at a time. Verify each one before moving to the next"},{"location":"playbooks/building/modifying-and-improving.html#plug-play","title":"Plug &amp; Play","text":"<p><code>/explore-codebase</code> Run this first if you haven't mapped the codebase yet. The architecture overview and UI pattern catalog are your reference library for modifications.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/building/modifying-and-improving.html#references","title":"References","text":"<p>Internal:</p> <ul> <li>The PM Builder : Hub page for the full building arc</li> <li>Exploring Codebases : Map the system before you modify it</li> <li>Adding Features : When you need to build something new, not improve what exists</li> <li>Shipping Code : Save and share your improvements through git</li> </ul> <p>External:</p> <ul> <li>Anthropic: Claude Code best practices : Official guidance on making targeted improvements</li> </ul>"},{"location":"playbooks/building/shipping-code.html","title":"Shipping Code","text":"<p>Git is how your engineering team saves, shares, and reviews work. Understanding it is not just about keeping your work safe. It is about speaking their language, working in their workflow, and contributing alongside them. Claude Code handles all the syntax. You just describe what you want in plain English.</p> <p>Quick Answer</p> <p>Use this when: You have code changes (improvements, features, bug fixes) and need to save them permanently, back them up, or get them reviewed.</p> <p>Avoid this when: You haven't made any changes yet. Start with Exploring Codebases or Modifying &amp; Improving.</p> <p>What CC changes: Git through natural language. No memorized commands. \"Create a branch,\" \"commit this,\" \"push and make a PR.\" Plus the Esc Esc safety mechanism that eliminates the fear of breaking things.</p> <p>Default move: Branch, change, commit, push, PR. Same flow your engineering team uses every day.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/building/shipping-code.html#the-git-workflow","title":"The Git Workflow","text":"<p>Six stages. Every open-source project, every engineering team, every codebase on GitHub. Same flow.</p> <pre><code>flowchart LR\n    BR[\"Branch\"] --&gt; CH[\"Change\"]\n    CH --&gt; CO[\"Commit\"]\n    CO --&gt; PU[\"Push\"]\n    PU --&gt; PR[\"Pull\\nRequest\"]\n    PR --&gt; MG[\"Merge\"]</code></pre> Stage What It Does PM Analogy Branch Creates a named container for related changes Starting a new doc for a specific initiative Change The actual work (edits, additions, fixes) Writing the content Commit A permanent save point with a description Clicking save with a note about what changed Push Sends your branch to GitHub (cloud backup) Uploading to the shared drive Pull Request Tags a teammate: \"here's what I changed, can you review?\" Sending a doc for review before publishing Merge Accepts the changes into the official version Publishing the final version <p>You don't need to memorize commands. Natural language and Claude handles the syntax.</p> <pre><code>Create a new branch called feature/workload-dashboard\n</code></pre> <pre><code>Commit all our changes with a message about what we did\n</code></pre> <pre><code>Push this branch to GitHub\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"playbooks/building/shipping-code.html#the-safety-net-esc-esc","title":"The Safety Net: Esc Esc","text":"<p>The fear of breaking something is the #1 barrier to PMs touching code. Esc Esc eliminates it.</p> <p>What it does: Press Escape twice quickly to interrupt Claude. Then scroll up to the message before the bad change and revert the code changes. Instant undo. No commands, no syntax. Two keystrokes.</p> <pre><code>flowchart LR\n    B[\"Something\\nbreaks\"] --&gt; E[\"Press\\nEsc Esc\"]\n    E --&gt; R[\"Scroll up,\\nrevert changes\"]\n    R --&gt; S[\"Code restored\\nto last good state\"]</code></pre> <p>You can break things. Recover in seconds. The consequences of mistakes approach zero, which means you can experiment freely.</p> <p>CC Advantage</p> <p>Esc Esc also removes the bad change from Claude's context, so it is like it never happened. No lingering confusion from a failed attempt. Clean slate.</p> <p>When Esc Esc is not enough: For bigger recovery, git itself is the safety net underneath. Commits are save points. You can always go back to any commit at any time. That is why you commit regularly: each commit is a checkpoint you can return to.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/building/shipping-code.html#saving-your-work","title":"Saving Your Work","text":"<p>Three steps: branch, commit, push. Do this whenever you have working changes you don't want to lose.</p> <p>Step 1: Create a branch.</p> <pre><code>Create a new branch called p3/practice-app-work\n</code></pre> <p>A branch groups related changes together under a name. It is how you package a set of work. Main stays clean. Your changes live on the branch until they're reviewed and merged.</p> <p>Step 2: Commit.</p> <pre><code>Commit all our changes up to this point\n</code></pre> <p>A commit is a permanent save point. Once committed, you can always get back to this exact state, even if you break things later. Claude writes a descriptive commit message summarizing what changed.</p> <p>Step 3: Push.</p> <pre><code>Push this branch to GitHub\n</code></pre> <p>Now your work exists in two places: your machine and GitHub. Laptop could catch fire and your work is safe.</p> <p>Scoping branches in practice: One logical piece of work per branch. Copy fixes go in one branch, a new feature in another, a bug fix in a third. Each becomes its own PR, which makes review easier. Tight scope means faster, cleaner reviews.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/building/shipping-code.html#fixing-bugs-the-full-cycle","title":"Fixing Bugs: The Full Cycle","text":"<p>Bug fixing follows a consistent pattern: investigate, scope, fix, verify, commit.</p> <p>Step 1: Investigate with plan mode.</p> <pre><code>Enter plan mode. Why is the Settings page blank when I click\nit in the sidebar? Make a plan to fix it.\n</code></pre> <p>Plan mode diagnoses the root cause and shows you what files will change. For a routing bug, it might find a one-character path mismatch: <code>/setting</code> instead of <code>/settings</code>.</p> <p>Step 2: Review the plan and approve.</p> <p>Plan mode shows the diagnosis, the proposed fix, and the files affected. You review it like you would review a spec: does this make sense? Is the blast radius acceptable?</p> <p>Step 3: Execute and verify.</p> <pre><code>Run the plan. Then take a puppeteer screenshot to verify.\n</code></pre> <p>Check the fix in your browser. Does Settings load? Is everything else still working?</p> <p>Step 4: Commit.</p> <pre><code>Commit this fix\n</code></pre> <p>Lock in the fix as a permanent save point.</p> <p>Knowing when to hand off: Not every bug is a 5-minute fix. If plan mode reveals a fix that spans multiple files with unclear side effects, the PM judgment call is to flag it for engineering with your analysis rather than attempt the fix. The scoping skills from Exploring Codebases help you make that call. Knowing when to hand off is as important as knowing how to contribute.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/building/shipping-code.html#the-pull-request","title":"The Pull Request","text":"<p>A PR description is stakeholder communication applied to code. You have been writing stakeholder communication your entire career. A PR description is the same thing, just addressed to engineers instead of executives.</p> <pre><code>flowchart TD\n    CT[\"Context\\nWhat user problem\\ndoes this fix?\"] --&gt; CG[\"Change\\nWhat was\\nmodified?\"]\n    CG --&gt; TS[\"Testing\\nHow did you\\nverify it?\"]\n    TS --&gt; SC[\"Screenshots\\nBefore/after\\nvisual proof\"]</code></pre> <p>Four sections:</p> Section What It Covers Why Engineers Care Context What user problem does this fix? Engineers want to know WHY, not just what. Context makes review faster. Change What was modified? Quick summary of the scope. Helps reviewers know what to focus on. Testing How did you verify it? Proves you didn't just write code and hope. Builds trust. Screenshots Before/after visual proof (optional but nice) Worth a thousand words of description. Especially for UI changes. <pre><code>Push the latest commit and create a PR. Write a description with\ncontext for everything on this branch: the improvements, the\ndashboard, and the bug fix.\n</code></pre> <p>Claude generates the PR with <code>gh pr create</code> and gives you a link to view it on GitHub. That is what your engineering team sees when they review your contribution.</p>  Bad  Good \"Fixed some stuff\" \"Fixed Settings navigation (route mismatch: /setting -&gt; /settings). Added workload dashboard with expandable row interaction. Polished ProjectForm to match TaskForm quality bar.\" No testing section \"Verified Settings loads from sidebar. Verified dashboard renders with seed data. Checked ProjectForm field layout matches TaskForm conventions.\" No context \"The Settings page has been broken since launch. Users clicking Settings see a blank page. Root cause: NavLink path was /setting instead of /settings.\" <p>Engineers love PRs with clear context because most PRs do not have it. Yours will stand out.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/building/shipping-code.html#git-concepts-for-pms","title":"Git Concepts for PMs","text":"Concept What It Means When You'll See It Repository (repo) A project folder tracked by git Every codebase lives in one Branch A named container for related changes You create one per piece of work Commit A permanent save point with a description You create these whenever you have working changes Push Send your branch to GitHub After committing, to back up and share Pull request (PR) A request for someone to review your changes When your work is ready for review Merge Accept changes into the official version After review and approval Main/master The official branch everyone works from You branch off this and merge back into it <p>Things to not worry about yet: Merge conflicts, rebasing, detached HEAD states. If you see any of those messages, don't push through. Ask for help. That is not failure. That is knowing when the tool needs an expert.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/building/shipping-code.html#common-mistakes","title":"Common Mistakes","text":"Mistake Why It Happens What to Do Instead Not committing regularly Focused on the work Commit after every working change. Each commit is a checkpoint you can return to Huge branches with many unrelated changes Batching feels efficient One logical piece of work per branch. Tight scope means better reviews No PR description \"The code speaks for itself\" It doesn't. Engineers need context, testing notes, and screenshots Trying to fix complex bugs alone Confidence from fixing simple ones Use plan mode to scope complexity. If it spans many files with unclear side effects, hand off with your analysis Fear of breaking things Natural instinct Esc Esc exists. Commits exist. The safety net is real. Experiment freely"},{"location":"playbooks/building/shipping-code.html#plug-play","title":"Plug &amp; Play","text":"<p><code>/explore-codebase</code> Map the codebase before attempting bug fixes. Architecture overview and flow traces help you scope what a fix actually touches.</p> <p><code>/scope-feature</code> When a bug fix looks complex, generate a scoping brief before deciding whether to fix it yourself or hand it off.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/building/shipping-code.html#references","title":"References","text":"<p>Internal:</p> <ul> <li>The PM Builder : Hub page for the full building arc</li> <li>Exploring Codebases : Map the system before contributing to it</li> <li>Modifying &amp; Improving : Targeted improvements that follow the reference pattern</li> <li>Adding Features : Building new features from spec to prototype</li> </ul> <p>External:</p> <ul> <li>GitHub: About pull requests : Official docs on the PR workflow</li> <li>Anthropic: Claude Code best practices : Official guidance on shipping workflows</li> </ul>"},{"location":"playbooks/collaboration/index.html","title":"The Collaboration Layer","text":"<p>Scaling Claude Code across your team -- shared configs, conventions, and multiplayer workflows.</p> <p>Quick Answer</p> <p>Use this when: You have a working personal OS and want to extend it to your team.</p> <p>Avoid this when: Your own setup isn't stable yet. Get your personal OS solid first, then share.</p> <p>What CC changes: Instead of sending Slack messages about processes, you encode them into shareable skills, rules, and templates that teammates install once and benefit from forever.</p> <p>Default move: Start with one shared skill that solves a pain point everyone has. Build the infrastructure around it.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/collaboration/index.html#the-four-step-arc","title":"The Four-Step Arc","text":"<p>Collaboration in Claude Code follows a natural progression. Each step builds on the last.</p> <pre><code>flowchart LR\n    S[\"Sharing &amp;\\nDistribution\"] --&gt; T[\"Team\\nToolkit\"]\n    T --&gt; A[\"Driving\\nAdoption\"]\n    A --&gt; G[\"Governance\"]\n\n    style S fill:#f0f4ff,stroke:#4a6cf7\n    style T fill:#f0f4ff,stroke:#4a6cf7\n    style A fill:#f0f4ff,stroke:#4a6cf7\n    style G fill:#f0f4ff,stroke:#4a6cf7</code></pre> Step Question It Answers Page Sharing &amp; Distribution What can I share and how do I prepare it? Sharing &amp; Distribution Team Toolkit Where does the shared stuff live and how do people get it? Team Toolkit Driving Adoption How do I get people to actually use it? Driving Adoption Governance How do I keep the shared system healthy over time? Governance"},{"location":"playbooks/collaboration/index.html#the-flywheel","title":"The Flywheel","text":"<p>The collaboration layer compounds. Each person who contributes makes the toolkit more valuable, which brings more contributors.</p> <pre><code>You share a skill\n  --&gt; teammate uses it, saves 2 hours\n    --&gt; they add their own skill\n      --&gt; new hire gets both on day one\n        --&gt; team's learning compounds instead of\n           staying trapped in individual heads\n</code></pre> <p>Most teams try to jump straight to governance (rolling out a full system to everyone). That kills adoption. Start small: prepare one asset, share it with one person, see what happens.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/collaboration/index.html#sub-pages","title":"Sub-Pages","text":"<p>Sharing &amp; Distribution -- What can be shared (skills, rules, templates, agents), the shareability principles, and how to prepare personal assets for team use.</p> <p>Team Toolkit -- Building a shared GitHub repo with structure, catalog, contribution guidelines, and an install flow that takes under 3 minutes.</p> <p>Driving Adoption -- The champion model, engineering the before/after moment, handling objections, and planning your first real test case.</p> <p>Governance -- Ownership, review cadence, conflict resolution, deprecation, communicating changes, and measuring impact.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/collaboration/index.html#references","title":"References","text":"<p>Internal:</p> <ul> <li>Your PM OS : Build your personal system before sharing it</li> <li>Skills: Building : How to build skills worth sharing</li> </ul> <p>External:</p> <ul> <li>Anthropic: Claude Code best practices : Foundation for effective Claude Code usage</li> <li>Anthropic: Skills : Official skills documentation</li> </ul>"},{"location":"playbooks/collaboration/driving-adoption.html","title":"Driving Adoption","text":"<p>Getting your team to actually use the shared toolkit. The champion model, before/after demos, and handling objections.</p> <p>Quick Answer</p> <p>Use this when: You have a working team toolkit and need people to start using it.</p> <p>Avoid this when: The toolkit is not ready yet. Sharing broken or half-baked tools kills adoption permanently.</p> <p>What CC changes: The before/after moment is dramatically more convincing when someone sees 3 hours of work collapse into 20 minutes on their own real task. Claude Code makes the demo undeniable.</p> <p>Default move: Pick one curious teammate, pick one tedious shared task, sit with them and run the skill on their real work. That is the entire strategy.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/collaboration/driving-adoption.html#how-adoption-actually-works","title":"How Adoption Actually Works","text":"<p>Adoption does not happen through Slack messages, all-hands announcements, or mandatory training sessions. It spreads person to person, one moment at a time.</p> <pre><code>flowchart TD\n    S1[\"Step 1\\nOne person gets obsessed\\nGets real results on their own work\"]\n    S1 --&gt; S2[\"Step 2\\nThey create a BEFORE/AFTER MOMENT\\n'This took 3 hours, now it takes 20 min'\"]\n    S2 --&gt; S3[\"Step 3\\nThey get ONE colleague to try it\\nNot ten. One.\"]\n    S3 --&gt; S4[\"Step 4\\nThat colleague tells others\\nOrganic spread, not top-down mandate\"]\n    S4 --&gt; S5[\"Step 5\\nTeam formalizes\\nShared toolkit, contribution process\"]\n\n    style S2 fill:#fff4f0,stroke:#f74a4a</code></pre> <p>If you have the toolkit infrastructure from Team Toolkit, you are past Step 1 and have Step 5's infrastructure. The gap is Steps 2-4.</p> <p>The immediate goal is not a company-wide adoption campaign. It is smaller and more useful: get one person to use it and see what happens.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/collaboration/driving-adoption.html#the-beforeafter-moment","title":"The Before/After Moment","text":"<p>This is the single most powerful adoption tool you have. When someone on your team sees a task they know is painful get done in a fraction of the time, they pay attention.</p> <p>Anatomy of a good before/after:</p> Element What It Means PICK A task everyone does and everyone knows is tedious SHOW The \"before\" -- time, steps, friction, errors RUN The skill on THEIR real data, live RESULT Done. The gap should be dramatic  Bad Demo  Good Demo \"Watch me demo on fake data\" -- does not feel real Run the skill on their actual work, live \"It's slightly faster\" -- not dramatic enough to stick \"Status updates took 45 min, now done in 5\" \"Here's a presentation about AI tools\" -- death by slides Sit with them and run it together \"Everyone should try this\" -- no urgency, no proof \"Want me to show you? Takes 3 minutes to set up\" <p>Best candidates for a before/after:</p> <ul> <li>Status updates -- everyone writes them, everyone hates writing them</li> <li>Meeting prep -- pulling context from multiple places into one brief</li> <li>Document drafting -- PRDs, briefs, proposals from messy inputs</li> <li>Research synthesis -- summarizing lots of sources into something coherent</li> </ul>"},{"location":"playbooks/collaboration/driving-adoption.html#the-first-conversation","title":"The First Conversation","text":"<p>You do not schedule a training session. You have a conversation.</p> <p>The approach: \"Hey, I've been using Claude Code for [task] and it's dramatically faster. Want me to show you?\"</p> <p>Then sit with the person (or screen share) and run the skill on a real task that person cares about.</p> <p>Handling objections:</p> Objection Response \"I don't have time to learn a new tool\" \"3 minutes to set up. Let me show you.\" \"I'm not technical enough\" \"Plain English. You tell Claude what to do. Let me show you.\" \"AI output isn't good enough\" \"Shared skills with the team's quality standards built in. Let me show you.\" \"I already use ChatGPT\" \"This is connected to your files and your team's standards. Let me show you.\" <p>The pattern: every response ends with \"let me show you.\" Do not argue. Do not explain. Demo. The before/after moment does the convincing, not words.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/collaboration/driving-adoption.html#planning-your-test-case","title":"Planning Your Test Case","text":"<p>Before you approach anyone, answer these four questions:</p> <ol> <li>Who? -- The most curious person on your team. Not the most technical. Curious.</li> <li>What? -- The recurring task that would make the most dramatic before/after.</li> <li>Objections? -- What pushback will this specific person have? Prepare the response.</li> <li>What are you testing? -- \"Whether the skill works for someone with a different role.\" Not \"whether AI is useful.\"</li> </ol> <p>That is your champion playbook. One person, one moment, one test case.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/collaboration/driving-adoption.html#after-it-works","title":"After It Works","text":"<p>If your first person gets value from it, adoption tends to happen naturally:</p> <ol> <li>That person mentions it in a meeting (\"I used the shared template for this\")</li> <li>Someone asks about it</li> <li>They show that person</li> <li>Repeat</li> </ol> <p>Accelerators that help it along:</p> <ul> <li>Weekly show-and-tell (20 min) -- one person shares what they used that week. This is the number one driver of peer adoption.</li> <li>Post wins in Slack -- \"Just used <code>/think-it-through</code> to prep for the board review. Caught two blind spots.\" Real results, not promotion.</li> <li>Toolkit link in onboarding -- new person joins, they get the link day one.</li> </ul> <p>Things that kill adoption:</p> <ul> <li>Mandating it. Compliance without buy-in creates resentment.</li> <li>Training without follow-up. People forget 90% within a week if nobody checks in.</li> <li>Sharing too many things at once. Start with one skill, one pain point. Let them get value before piling on.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"playbooks/collaboration/driving-adoption.html#plug-play","title":"Plug &amp; Play","text":"<p>Components: Skills Pre-built skills that make good first demos.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/collaboration/driving-adoption.html#references","title":"References","text":"<p>Internal:</p> <ul> <li>The Collaboration Layer : Hub page for the full collaboration arc</li> <li>Team Toolkit : The infrastructure teammates install from</li> <li>Governance : Keeping the toolkit healthy as adoption grows</li> </ul> <p>External:</p> <ul> <li>Anthropic: Claude Code best practices : Foundation for effective Claude Code usage</li> </ul>"},{"location":"playbooks/collaboration/governance.html","title":"Governance","text":"<p>Ownership, review cadence, conflict resolution, deprecation, and measuring impact. Keeping the shared toolkit trustworthy.</p> <p>Quick Answer</p> <p>Use this when: Your team toolkit has active users and you want it to survive beyond the initial enthusiasm.</p> <p>Avoid this when: Nobody is using the toolkit yet. Get adoption first (see Driving Adoption), then formalize governance.</p> <p>What CC changes: Claude can automate the tedious parts of governance: reading the git log and drafting weekly change summaries, flagging skills that have not been used or updated, and running diagnostic checks on the toolkit.</p> <p>Default move: Assign a named owner to every piece in the toolkit. That single action predicts whether the system survives.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/collaboration/governance.html#the-one-thing-that-matters","title":"The One Thing That Matters","text":"<p>There is a diagnostic question that predicts whether your toolkit will be alive in six months:</p> <p>\"Does every piece in the toolkit have a named owner?\"</p> <p>Not \"the team.\" Not \"whoever built it.\" A specific person.</p> What an Owner Does Why It Matters Keeps it working -- fixes breakage from model changes Without this, broken things stay broken because everyone assumes someone else will fix it Answers questions -- \"how does this skill handle X?\" Without this, people guess wrong and stop trusting the tool Decides on changes -- reviews modification requests Without this, changes happen randomly with no quality bar Flags retirement -- says when something is no longer useful Without this, stale tools accumulate and erode trust in everything <p>This is lightweight. Owning a skill does not mean a weekly meeting. It means: if this breaks, someone specific knows it is their job to deal with it.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/collaboration/governance.html#review-cadence","title":"Review Cadence","text":"<p>Even with owners, things go stale. Models change. Team priorities shift.</p> <p>Monthly check-in (~15 minutes): Each owner confirms their stuff still works. Run the skill, check the output, verify rules still apply.</p> <p>Quarterly prune (~30 minutes): The team looks at everything and asks three questions.</p> <pre><code>flowchart TD\n    I[\"For each item\\nin the toolkit\"] --&gt; U{Still actively\\nused?}\n    U --&gt;|Yes| O{Owner still\\non team?}\n    U --&gt;|No| W{Why not?}\n    W --&gt;|Broken| FX[\"Fix or\\ndeprecate\"]\n    W --&gt;|Outdated| UP[\"Update or\\ndeprecate\"]\n    W --&gt;|Nobody needs it| DP[\"Deprecate\"]\n    O --&gt;|Yes| K[\"Keep\"]\n    O --&gt;|No| TR[\"Transfer ownership\\nor archive\"]\n    I --&gt; C{Contradicts\\nanything else?}\n    C --&gt;|Yes| RS[\"Resolve\"]\n    C --&gt;|No| K</code></pre> <p>The hardest part of the quarterly prune is actually deleting things. People resist removing tools because \"someone might need it someday.\" But a toolkit with 20 things where 8 are stale is worse than a toolkit with 12 that all work. The stale ones erode trust in everything.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/collaboration/governance.html#when-an-owner-leaves","title":"When an Owner Leaves","text":"<p>The most dangerous moment for any shared tool is when its owner gives notice.</p> Approach Verdict Ask them to document everything Good but incomplete. Documentation without a new owner means the docs sit there and the skill rots Transfer ownership to the heaviest user Gets you an owner fast, but without context transfer they are guessing at design decisions Transfer ownership AND knowledge-transfer handoff Usually the best move. New owner understands the intent, not just the mechanics Archive until someone volunteers Honest move if nobody steps up. An archived skill with a clear label is better than a broken skill people think is maintained <p>The key insight: documentation alone does not save a tool. A person saves a tool. Documentation helps that person do their job.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/collaboration/governance.html#conflict-resolution","title":"Conflict Resolution","text":"<p>As more people contribute, conflicts are inevitable. Two rules contradict. Two skills overlap. Someone's addition steps on something that already exists.</p> <p>For overlapping skills: Two similar things with no clear distinction is worse than one good thing. If nobody can articulate when to use one versus the other, they need to be merged or one needs to go.</p> <p>For conflicting rules: Newer and more specific wins. A rule about \"all documents use headers\" gets overridden by a later rule about \"proposals use numbered sections.\" Owners talk and resolve. The champion breaks ties if needed.</p>  Bad  Good Two skills that do almost the same thing, no guidance on which to use Clear documentation: \"Use <code>/write-proposal</code> for formal exec proposals, <code>/draft-brief</code> for early-stage exploration\" Conflicting rules sitting side by side, nobody notices Quarterly prune catches the conflict, owners resolve it Rejecting a contribution because of overlap, discouraging participation Working with the contributor to merge or differentiate"},{"location":"playbooks/collaboration/governance.html#deprecation","title":"Deprecation","text":"<p>There is a right way and a wrong way to remove things from a toolkit.</p> <p>Wrong way: Delete it. Teammates who relied on it discover it is gone when their workflow breaks.</p> <p>Right way: announce, grace period, remove.</p> Asset Type Deprecation Process Skills Mark deprecated in README. Note the replacement. Give a grace period (one sprint or one month). Remove after the grace period. Rules Update in place rather than creating a new rule alongside the old one. <code>prioritization.md</code> gets updated, not replaced by <code>prioritization-v2.md</code>. Replaced skills The new skill's README says \"Replaces <code>/old-skill</code>\" so people coming from the old one know where to go. <p>Nobody should be surprised when something disappears.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/collaboration/governance.html#communicating-changes","title":"Communicating Changes","text":"<p>People need to know when the toolkit changes. This is where most governance falls apart.</p> <p>Treat the toolkit like a product. It has users (the team), features (skills and rules), and releases (changes). Ship notes.</p> Channel When to Use Slack post Additions and meaningful changes. \"Added <code>/competitive-scan</code>. Use before strategy meetings.\" PR description Small changes. The contribution workflow creates a paper trail automatically. Show-and-tell Big additions. Someone demos at standup. Takes 2 minutes, drives adoption. <p>You can automate the communication: run a weekly prompt that reads the git log and drafts a Slack summary of what changed. Review it, paste it in the channel. Two minutes. The team always knows what is current.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/collaboration/governance.html#measuring-impact","title":"Measuring Impact","text":"<p>At some point, someone will ask: is this helping?</p> Signal What to Look For Why It Matters Usage Are people running the shared skills? A skill nobody uses should be pruned Contributions Are people adding to the toolkit, not just consuming? Signals the team sees it as theirs, not yours Time savings Before/after stories -- anecdotes are powerful \"Stakeholder emails used to take 30 min, now 5\" Consistency Are outputs more consistent across the team? Fewer \"wait, which template do we use?\" questions <p>The best signal is qualitative. Are people talking about the toolkit unprompted? Asking for new skills? Using it without being reminded? When someone says \"can we add a skill for X?\" -- that is the strongest signal. They trust the system enough to invest in it.</p> <p>Do not over-engineer measurement. If you find yourself building a dashboard to track toolkit usage, you have gone too far.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/collaboration/governance.html#plug-play","title":"Plug &amp; Play","text":"<p>Skill Maintenance Detailed guidance on keeping individual skills working over time.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/collaboration/governance.html#references","title":"References","text":"<p>Internal:</p> <ul> <li>The Collaboration Layer : Hub page for the full collaboration arc</li> <li>Team Toolkit : The infrastructure governance protects</li> <li>Driving Adoption : Get adoption before formalizing governance</li> <li>Sharing &amp; Distribution : The quality bar governance enforces</li> </ul> <p>External:</p> <ul> <li>Anthropic: Claude Code best practices : Foundation for effective Claude Code usage</li> </ul>"},{"location":"playbooks/collaboration/sharing-and-distribution.html","title":"Sharing &amp; Distribution","text":"<p>What can be shared in Claude Code, the principles that make shared assets succeed, and how to prepare personal tools for your team.</p> <p>Quick Answer</p> <p>Use this when: You have a skill, rule, or template that solves a real problem and a teammate could benefit from it.</p> <p>Avoid this when: The asset only works for you because it depends on your personal context, role, or preferences.</p> <p>What CC changes: Instead of writing a wiki article about a process, you encode the process into a skill that runs it. Sharing becomes distributing working software, not documentation people forget to read.</p> <p>Default move: Pick the skill your team would benefit from most. Run it through the shareability checklist. Fix what fails. Share it.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/collaboration/sharing-and-distribution.html#what-can-be-shared","title":"What Can Be Shared","text":"<p>There are four shareable things in Claude Code. Skills get the most attention because they carry the most value.</p> <pre><code>flowchart TD\n    TK[\"Team Toolkit\"] --&gt; SK[\"Skills\"]\n    TK --&gt; RU[\"Rules\"]\n    TK --&gt; TE[\"Templates\"]\n    TK --&gt; AG[\"Agents\"]\n\n    SK --&gt; |\"Reusable workflows\\n/write-status-update\\n/prep-for-meeting\"| SK2[\" \"]\n    RU --&gt; |\"Behavioral standards\\nin .claude/rules/\"| RU2[\" \"]\n    TE --&gt; |\"Document formats\\nfor consistent output\"| TE2[\" \"]\n    AG --&gt; |\"Custom agents with\\nown tools + model\"| AG2[\" \"]\n\n    style SK2 fill:none,stroke:none\n    style RU2 fill:none,stroke:none\n    style TE2 fill:none,stroke:none\n    style AG2 fill:none,stroke:none</code></pre> Type What It Is When to Share Example Skills Reusable workflows anyone can run When a process should be consistent across the team <code>/write-status-update</code>, <code>/prep-for-meeting</code> Rules Behavioral standards in <code>.claude/rules/</code> When inconsistency across the team causes real problems <code>prioritization-framework.md</code>, <code>data-privacy.md</code> Templates Document formats for when you have the info and need a shape When every person uses a different format for the same artifact PRD template, status update format Agents Custom agents with their own tool access and model When a workflow needs its own environment (rare) Deep research agent with web search <p>One thing you do NOT share: CLAUDE.md. It is personal -- your role, your preferences, your style. Shared context like product info and terminology lives in skill reference files and rules.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/collaboration/sharing-and-distribution.html#skills-vs-rules-vs-templates-vs-agents","title":"Skills vs. Rules vs. Templates vs. Agents","text":"<p>People confuse these. Here is the decision tree:</p> <pre><code>flowchart TD\n    Q[\"What do you want\\nto share?\"] --&gt; P{Involves a\\nprocess?}\n    P --&gt;|Yes| SK[\"Skill\\nInteractive workflow\"]\n    P --&gt;|No| F{Enforces a\\nstandard?}\n    F --&gt;|Yes| RU[\"Rule\\nBehavioral constraint\"]\n    F --&gt;|No| SH{Needs its own\\nenvironment?}\n    SH --&gt;|No| TE[\"Template\\nDocument format\"]\n    SH --&gt;|Yes| AG[\"Agent\\nIsolated subprocess\"]</code></pre> <p>The practical breakdown:</p> <pre><code>SKILL  --&gt; runs in your session, your tools, your model\n           \"Do this workflow step by step\"\n\nRULE   --&gt; passive constraint Claude always follows\n           \"Always use RICE for prioritization\"\n\nTEMPLATE --&gt; static format, no interactivity\n           \"Put my notes in this shape\"\n\nAGENT  --&gt; runs in its own session, its own tools, its own model\n           \"Deep research with its own web search access\"\n</code></pre> <p>Most teams use skills for 90% of what they share. Agents are for the rare case where you genuinely need isolated tool config or a different model.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/collaboration/sharing-and-distribution.html#the-shareability-principles","title":"The Shareability Principles","text":"<p>Every shared asset fails in one of five predictable ways. These principles are the checklist.</p> Principle What It Means What Failure Looks Like Described README in the skill folder: what it does, when to use it, what it needs Teammate finds the skill, has no idea what it does, never runs it No hardcoded personal context Works for anyone. If it needs role info, ASK, don't assume Skill references \"a Senior PM at a mid-stage B2B SaaS company\" and makes no sense for a teammate Dependencies documented If it needs web search or an MCP, say so Teammate runs the skill, gets degraded results, has no idea why No secrets in files API keys go in environment variables, never in shared files API key gets pushed to a shared repo and is exposed to everyone with access Testable Someone who isn't you can run this and succeed in a few minutes Asset sits in the repo because nobody can figure out how to use it"},{"location":"playbooks/collaboration/sharing-and-distribution.html#preparing-a-skill-for-sharing","title":"Preparing a Skill for Sharing","text":"<p>Here is the before/after of making a personal skill shareable.</p>  Bad (Personal)  Good (Shareable) \"Context About Me: I'm a Senior PM at a mid-stage B2B SaaS company. My team includes Alex (eng lead) and Sarah (designer).\" \"Ask the user two questions before starting: (1) What's your role and who are you presenting to? (2) Any specific areas where you want extra pushback?\" No README. Frontmatter description says \"thinking tool.\" README with: what it does, when to use it, dependencies, setup steps <code>TAVILY_API_KEY=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</code> sitting in a reference file \"Requires TAVILY_API_KEY environment variable. See README for setup.\" \"My Company's Numbers: NPS 42, trial-to-paid 23%\" in a \"My\" section \"Company Metrics\" section framed as shared team knowledge Vague frontmatter: <code>description: \"thinking tool\"</code> Clear frontmatter: <code>description: \"Strategic thinking partner. Stress-tests ideas and proposals before you present them.\"</code> <p>The key distinction: personal context gets removed. Shared context stays. Your role, your weaknesses, your preferences -- those get replaced with questions. Company metrics, industry benchmarks, team standards -- those stay, but reframed as team knowledge.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/collaboration/sharing-and-distribution.html#preparing-rules-for-sharing","title":"Preparing Rules for Sharing","text":"<p>Not every rule should be shared. Share a rule if it meets all three criteria:</p> <ol> <li>Reused by multiple people -- not just your personal preference</li> <li>Stable enough it will not change weekly</li> <li>Inconsistency across the team would cause real problems</li> </ol>  Bad (Don't Share)  Good (Share) \"I prefer concise responses, no more than 3 paragraphs\" (personal style) \"When discussing prioritization, always use the RICE framework\" (team standard) \"Use a friendly, casual tone\" (personal preference) \"Use 'TaskFlow' not 'Taskflow' or 'Task Flow'\" (terminology) \"Never use bullet points\" (idiosyncratic) \"Never include customer PII in outputs\" (guardrail) <p>One important constraint: Claude can reliably follow about 150 instructions. Every rule competes for attention. Share the 5-10 that actually matter, not 40.</p> <p>Best practice: one concern per file, named descriptively. <code>prioritization-framework.md</code>, not <code>rule-7.md</code>.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/collaboration/sharing-and-distribution.html#preparing-templates-for-sharing","title":"Preparing Templates for Sharing","text":"<p>Templates are the simplest thing to share. The rule: when you already have the information and just need it in a specific shape, use a template. If there is a guided process involved (questions, context-pulling, decisions), it should probably be a skill with the template embedded.</p> <p>Keep templates self-explanatory. Someone should look at it and know what goes where. Include a filled example if the structure is not obvious.</p>  Bad  Good Bare skeleton with section headers and nothing else Section headers with brief guidance on what goes in each section Template that requires tribal knowledge to fill correctly Template with an example entry in each section Template embedded in a Confluence page nobody can find Template in the shared repo, listed in the catalog"},{"location":"playbooks/collaboration/sharing-and-distribution.html#what-teams-typically-share","title":"What Teams Typically Share","text":"<p>Skills:</p> <ul> <li>Decision-making and thinking tools (<code>/think-it-through</code>, <code>/reality-check</code>)</li> <li>Document creation (<code>/write-proposal</code>, <code>/draft-brief</code>)</li> <li>Review and feedback (<code>/review-doc</code>, <code>/prep-for-meeting</code>)</li> <li>Research and analysis (<code>/competitive-scan</code>, <code>/summarize-research</code>)</li> <li>Communication (<code>/write-status-update</code>, <code>/draft-announcement</code>)</li> </ul> <p>Rules:</p> <ul> <li>Quality standards (\"Always include success metrics in proposals\")</li> <li>Terminology (\"Use 'TaskFlow' not 'Taskflow' or 'Task Flow'\")</li> <li>Formatting conventions (\"Dates in YYYY-MM-DD format\")</li> <li>Guardrails (\"Never include customer PII in outputs\")</li> <li>Process standards (\"All PRDs must address scalability\")</li> </ul> <p>Templates:</p> <ul> <li>Status update formats</li> <li>Meeting notes structures</li> <li>Brief and proposal formats</li> <li>Handoff documents</li> <li>Retrospective formats</li> </ul>"},{"location":"playbooks/collaboration/sharing-and-distribution.html#plug-play","title":"Plug &amp; Play","text":"<p>Skill Maintenance Guidance on keeping skills working over time -- relevant for any shared skill.</p> <p>Components: Skills Ready-made skills you can adapt and share with your team.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/collaboration/sharing-and-distribution.html#references","title":"References","text":"<p>Internal:</p> <ul> <li>The Collaboration Layer : Hub page for the full collaboration arc</li> <li>Team Toolkit : Where shared assets live and how people get them</li> <li>Building Skills : How to build skills worth sharing</li> <li>Skill Types : Understanding different skill architectures</li> </ul> <p>External:</p> <ul> <li>Anthropic: Skills : Official skills documentation</li> <li>Anthropic: Claude Code best practices : Foundation for effective Claude Code usage</li> </ul>"},{"location":"playbooks/collaboration/team-toolkit.html","title":"Team Toolkit","text":"<p>Building the shared GitHub repo that distributes skills, rules, and templates to your team.</p> <p>Quick Answer</p> <p>Use this when: You have shareable assets and need a place for the team to grab them.</p> <p>Avoid this when: You have nothing ready to share yet. Prepare assets first (see Sharing &amp; Distribution).</p> <p>What CC changes: The repo is not just a human-readable catalog. Claude reads the README to understand what is available, so a teammate can say \"install the team toolkit\" and Claude handles the rest.</p> <p>Default move: Create a private GitHub repo, add one skill, write the README catalog, and test the install flow with one person.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/collaboration/team-toolkit.html#why-a-repo","title":"Why a Repo","text":"<p>The team toolkit is a GitHub repo. Not a shared folder. Not a Google Drive. Not a Slack thread.</p> <p>A repo gives you four things nothing else does:</p> Capability What It Means Version history See what changed, when, and why. Roll back if something breaks Contribution workflow Anyone can propose additions through pull requests Single source of truth One place, always current. No version confusion Easy install <code>git clone</code> or tell Claude to install it -- done in minutes <p>The toolkit is NOT a workspace. Nobody does their work inside this repo. It is a distribution point, like an app store for your team's Claude setup. People grab what they need and put it in their own OS.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/collaboration/team-toolkit.html#repo-structure","title":"Repo Structure","text":"<pre><code>team-toolkit/\n\u251c\u2500\u2500 skills/                    \u2190 shared skills (each skill is a folder)\n\u2502   \u2514\u2500\u2500 think-it-through/\n\u2502       \u251c\u2500\u2500 SKILL.md           \u2190 the skill itself\n\u2502       \u2514\u2500\u2500 README.md          \u2190 what it does, dependencies, setup\n\u251c\u2500\u2500 rules/                     \u2190 shared rules (.md files)\n\u2502   \u251c\u2500\u2500 prioritization.md\n\u2502   \u2514\u2500\u2500 file-naming.md\n\u251c\u2500\u2500 templates/                 \u2190 document formats\n\u2502   \u2514\u2500\u2500 prd-template.md\n\u251c\u2500\u2500 agents/                    \u2190 custom agents (rare)\n\u251c\u2500\u2500 README.md                  \u2190 catalog of everything + install instructions\n\u2514\u2500\u2500 CONTRIBUTING.md            \u2190 how to add to the toolkit\n</code></pre> <p>The folder structure mirrors Claude Code's own organization. When a teammate grabs a skill folder and drops it into their <code>.claude/skills/</code>, it just works. Same with rules into <code>.claude/rules/</code>. That is the whole point.</p> <pre><code>flowchart LR\n    TK[\"team-toolkit/\\nskills/think-it-through/\"] --&gt;|copy| OS[\"your-os/\\n.claude/skills/think-it-through/\"]\n    TK2[\"team-toolkit/\\nrules/prioritization.md\"] --&gt;|copy| OS2[\"your-os/\\n.claude/rules/prioritization.md\"]</code></pre>"},{"location":"playbooks/collaboration/team-toolkit.html#the-readme-catalog","title":"The README Catalog","text":"<p>The README is the front door. It serves two audiences: humans browsing the repo, and Claude reading it to understand what is available.</p> <pre><code># [Team Name] Toolkit\n\nShared skills, rules, and templates for [team]'s Claude Code setup.\n\n## Skills\n\n| Skill | Description | Dependencies |\n|-------|-------------|-------------|\n| `/think-it-through` | Strategic thinking partner | None |\n| `/write-status-update` | Weekly status from project context | None |\n\n## Rules\n\n| Rule | What It Enforces |\n|------|-----------------|\n| `prioritization.md` | Always use RICE framework |\n| `file-naming.md` | kebab-case for all files |\n\n## Templates\n\n| Template | What It's For |\n|----------|--------------|\n| `prd-template.md` | Product requirements document |\n\n## How to Install\n\nTell Claude: \"Add the skills and rules from [repo URL] to my setup.\" (Claude reads the README, clones the repo, and copies files into the right `.claude/` directories on your machine.)\n\nOr manually:\n1. Clone this repo: `git clone [url]`\n2. Copy skill folders into your `.claude/skills/`\n3. Copy rule files into your `.claude/rules/`\n4. Grab templates as needed\n</code></pre> <p>The install instructions are the most important part. Realistically, a teammate opens Claude Code and says \"add the skills and rules from [repo URL] to my setup.\" Claude reads the README, understands the structure, and copies everything into the right places. The teammate never touches git.</p> <p>The 3-minute test: send a teammate the repo link, they tell Claude to install it, done. If it takes longer than that, fix the README.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/collaboration/team-toolkit.html#contribution-workflow","title":"Contribution Workflow","text":"<p>Without a contribution process, either you become the bottleneck (\"hey can you add this for me?\") or people throw stuff in with no quality bar.</p> <pre><code>flowchart TD\n    A[\"Create a branch\"] --&gt; B[\"Add your skill,\\nrule, or template\"]\n    B --&gt; C[\"Open a pull request\\nwith description\"]\n    C --&gt; D[\"Reviewer checks\\nquality bar\"]\n    D --&gt; E{\"Approved?\"}\n    E --&gt;|Yes| F[\"Merge into\\nmain branch\"]\n    E --&gt;|No| G[\"Feedback +\\nrevisions\"]\n    G --&gt; C\n    F --&gt; H[\"Post in Slack\\nso team knows\"]</code></pre> <p>The CONTRIBUTING.md file encodes this:</p> <pre><code># Contributing to the Toolkit\n\n## How to Add Something New\n\n1. Create a branch: `git checkout -b add-[thing-name]`\n2. Add your skill folder, rule file, or template\n3. Commit: `git commit -m \"Add [thing] to toolkit\"`\n4. Push and open a PR: `git push -u origin add-[thing-name]`\n5. Reviewer reviews and merges\n\n## Quality Bar\n\nBefore submitting:\n- Skills must have a README (what it does, dependencies, setup)\n- Must be useful to more than one person\n- No hardcoded personal context\n- No API keys or secrets in files\n- Dependencies documented\n</code></pre> <p>For a small team, the process is simple: make a PR, someone reviews it, merge, post in Slack. Do not overthink it.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/collaboration/team-toolkit.html#the-pr-workflow","title":"The PR Workflow","text":"<p>A pull request is a proposal to change the toolkit. It creates a review step between \"someone wants to add something\" and \"it goes live for everyone.\"</p> Step Command What Happens Branch <code>git checkout -b add-market-risk-question</code> Creates a working copy Edit Make changes to the skill/rule/template Changes happen on your branch Commit <code>git commit -m \"Add market risk question\"</code> Saves a snapshot with description Push <code>git push -u origin add-market-risk-question</code> Sends changes to GitHub PR <code>gh pr create --title \"Add market risk question\"</code> Creates the proposal for review Review Teammate reviews the diff Quality check before it goes live Merge <code>gh pr merge</code> Change goes live in the toolkit <p>Why bother with PRs instead of changing files directly?</p>  Bad (Direct Edits)  Good (Pull Requests) Nobody knows what changed or when Every change has a description and timestamp A broken change goes live immediately Someone reviews before it affects the team \"Who changed the prioritization rule?\" becomes a mystery Full history of who changed what and why Rolling back means guessing what was there before Clean revert to any previous version"},{"location":"playbooks/collaboration/team-toolkit.html#the-full-lifecycle","title":"The Full Lifecycle","text":"<pre><code>flowchart TD\n    GH[\"Team Toolkit\\n(GitHub)\"] --&gt;|clone| LC[\"Your\\nComputer\"]\n    LC --&gt;|make changes| CM[\"Commit\\n(snapshot)\"]\n    CM --&gt;|push| PR[\"Pull Request\\n(proposal)\"]\n    PR --&gt;|review + approve| MG[\"Merge\"]\n    MG --&gt;|update| GH\n\n    style GH fill:#f0f4ff,stroke:#4a6cf7\n    style PR fill:#fff4f0,stroke:#f74a4a</code></pre> <p>That is the entire cycle. Someone has an insight, they branch off, make the change, open a PR, it gets reviewed, merged, and now everyone benefits.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/collaboration/team-toolkit.html#plug-play","title":"Plug &amp; Play","text":"<p>Components: Skills Pre-built skills you can drop into your team toolkit immediately.</p> <p>Components: Rules &amp; Config Starter rules for common team standards.</p> <p>Git &amp; GitHub for PMs If any of the git concepts are unfamiliar, start here.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/collaboration/team-toolkit.html#references","title":"References","text":"<p>Internal:</p> <ul> <li>The Collaboration Layer : Hub page for the full collaboration arc</li> <li>Sharing &amp; Distribution : How to prepare assets before adding them to the toolkit</li> <li>Driving Adoption : Getting your team to actually use the toolkit</li> <li>Governance : Keeping the toolkit healthy over time</li> </ul> <p>External:</p> <ul> <li>Anthropic: Skills : Official skills documentation</li> <li>GitHub: About pull requests : PR workflow reference</li> </ul>"},{"location":"playbooks/data-analysis/index.html","title":"Data &amp; Decisions","text":"<p>Data-driven PM work is not about dashboards. It's about a continuous investigation where every step builds on the last, every finding is traceable, and every recommendation comes with the math to back it up. Claude Code turns you from \"the PM who makes charts\" into \"the PM who owns the analytical trail from question to running experiment.\"</p> <p>Quick Answer</p> <p>Use this when: Someone asks \"how's it going?\" and you need more than a dashboard screenshot.</p> <p>Avoid this when: You need market research or competitive positioning. That's Competitive Intelligence.</p> <p>What CC changes: Jupyter notebooks become your analysis medium. Prior work compounds across notebooks. Sub-agents run parallel analyses. One command triggers a full experiment check-in with contextual investigation.</p> <p>Default move: Start with Analyzing Data. Frame the question and build the notebook before touching any numbers.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/data-analysis/index.html#the-investigation-arc","title":"The Investigation Arc","text":"<p>Data work flows through four connected phases. Each one feeds the next.</p> <pre><code>flowchart LR\n    E[\"Evaluate\\n'How is it doing?'\"] --&gt; D[\"Diagnose\\n'Where is it breaking?'\"]\n    D --&gt; R[\"Recommend\\n'What should we do?'\"]\n    R --&gt; EX[\"Experiment\\n'Prove it.'\"]</code></pre> <p>This is not a checklist. It's how real analytical work actually moves. You evaluate a launch, discover something concerning, diagnose the root cause, model potential fixes, and design an experiment to validate. Each phase produces artifacts that feed the next.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/data-analysis/index.html#analyzing-data","title":"Analyzing Data","text":"<p>Evaluate launches and diagnose problems. Jupyter notebooks as the trust layer. Doc-as-context pattern to scope analysis from existing briefs. Cross-data-source joins, funnel construction, sub-agent parallel analysis, and qualitative triangulation when the quantitative data has gaps.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/data-analysis/index.html#building-a-data-driven-case","title":"Building a Data-Driven Case","text":"<p>Turn diagnosis into recommendation. Cross-notebook context so prior work compounds. Common metric pattern for apples-to-apples comparison. Interactive impact estimation with compound funnel math. Build recommendations with confidence markers and \"what would change your mind\" sections.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/data-analysis/index.html#experiment-design","title":"Experiment Design","text":"<p>Design experiments that monitor themselves. Experiment briefs as living documents. Power analysis to size your test. The document-as-interface pattern where the brief defines what data to pull, and contextual check-ins that go beyond dashboards to investigate support tickets, cancellation patterns, and segmentation alongside metrics.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/data-analysis/index.html#how-claude-code-changes-data-work","title":"How Claude Code Changes Data Work","text":"Traditional With Claude Code Open a spreadsheet and start making charts Point CC at your launch brief and data, get a structured notebook with traceable analysis Manually build funnels in a BI tool Describe the funnel in plain English, CC joins data sources and builds it Check a dashboard for experiment metrics One command triggers a full contextual check-in across metrics, support tickets, and cancellation patterns Copy numbers between spreadsheets for impact estimates Prior notebooks feed new analysis automatically via cross-notebook context Wait for an analyst to run a query Run the query yourself in a Jupyter notebook where every step is auditable <p>The speed matters, but the traceability matters more. Every chart has the code that made it right above it. Every recommendation traces back through notebooks to raw data. When your VP asks \"where'd you get that number?\" you open the notebook, not a Slack thread.</p> <p>CC Limitation</p> <p>Claude Code will find patterns in any data, whether they're real or not. Small samples, short timeframes, and confounding variables don't trigger warnings automatically. The framework (success metrics AND guardrails, confidence markers, sample size caveats) is what keeps you honest. Skip it and you'll just get faster at overstating.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/data-analysis/index.html#where-to-start","title":"Where to Start","text":"<p>Evaluating a launch or investigating a metric? Begin with Analyzing Data. It covers the full evaluate-and-diagnose cycle.</p> <p>Ready to recommend a course of action? Jump to Building a Data-Driven Case for impact estimation and recommendation building.</p> <p>Designing an experiment? Use Experiment Design for briefs, power analysis, and contextual check-ins.</p> <p>Need qualitative research instead? See User Research for interview and survey methodologies.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/data-analysis/index.html#plug-play","title":"Plug &amp; Play","text":"<p><code>/launch-review</code> Point at a launch brief and dataset. Gets a structured Jupyter notebook with success metrics, guardrail checks, and an executive summary.</p> <p><code>/diagnostic-funnel</code> Joins data sources, builds the conversion funnel, compares time periods, and flags tracking gaps.</p> <p><code>/impact-estimation</code> Interactive estimation session. You pick which funnel steps each option targets, estimate the lift, and CC runs compound math across the full funnel.</p> <p><code>/experiment-check</code> Reads an experiment brief and runs a full contextual check-in. Metrics, support tickets, cancellation patterns, proactive investigation.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/data-analysis/index.html#references","title":"References","text":"<p>Internal:</p> <ul> <li>Analyzing Data : Jupyter notebooks, doc-as-context, funnel construction, qualitative triangulation</li> <li>Building a Data-Driven Case : Cross-notebook context, compound funnel math, recommendations</li> <li>Experiment Design : Experiment briefs, power analysis, contextual check-ins</li> <li>User Research : Qualitative research methodologies</li> <li>Competitive Intelligence : Market research and positioning</li> </ul> <p>External:</p> <ul> <li>Anthropic: Sub-agents : How parallel analysis works under the hood</li> <li>Anthropic: Claude Code best practices : Official guidance on structuring work</li> </ul>"},{"location":"playbooks/data-analysis/analyzing-data.html","title":"Analyzing Data","text":"<p>Analyzing data means turning \"how's it going?\" into a traceable, auditable answer that stakeholders can follow from question to conclusion. The methodology: frame the question with existing documents, run the analysis in Jupyter notebooks where every number has the code that produced it, and triangulate with qualitative sources when quantitative data has gaps.</p> <p>Quick Answer</p> <p>Use this when: You need to evaluate a launch, diagnose a metric change, investigate a funnel, or answer a stakeholder's data question with evidence.</p> <p>Avoid this when: You already know the diagnosis and need to recommend a fix. That's Building a Data-Driven Case.</p> <p>What CC changes: Jupyter notebooks become your analysis medium. The doc-as-context pattern turns existing briefs into structured analysis plans. Sub-agents (separate Claude instances that work in parallel) run qualitative scans. You file instrumentation tickets while the analysis context is fresh.</p> <p>Default move: Frame first, analyze second. Point CC at an existing brief or doc to scope the analysis before touching any data.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/data-analysis/analyzing-data.html#jupyter-notebooks-are-the-trust-layer","title":"Jupyter Notebooks Are the Trust Layer","text":"<p>The biggest question PMs have about doing analysis with an LLM: how can you trust it? If your VP asks where you got those numbers, you can't say \"Claude did the analysis.\"</p> <p>Jupyter notebooks solve this. Every chart has the code that made it right above it. Your analysts can audit it. Stakeholders can trace any number. You're not asking people to trust the AI. You're showing them the work.</p> <p>A good notebook has three layers:</p> <pre><code>flowchart TD\n    M[\"Markdown cells\\nThe narrative: what question you're\\nanswering and why\"] --&gt; C[\"Code cells\\nThe proof: exactly how\\nyou got the number\"]\n    C --&gt; O[\"Output cells\\nThe result: charts, tables,\\nthe evidence itself\"]</code></pre>  Bad  Good A Slack message saying \"conversion dropped 3%\" A notebook with the query, the chart, and the executive summary all in one document \"Claude analyzed the data and found...\" \"Here's the notebook. Section 3 has the funnel. The code is right above each chart.\" Separate spreadsheet, slide deck, and data export One notebook that IS the analysis, the evidence, and the narrative"},{"location":"playbooks/data-analysis/analyzing-data.html#what-a-good-notebook-structure-looks-like","title":"What a Good Notebook Structure Looks Like","text":"<pre><code>launch-review.ipynb\n\u251c\u2500\u2500 Executive Summary        (markdown: the answer, up front)\n\u251c\u2500\u2500 Setup &amp; Data Loading     (code: imports, file loading, date ranges)\n\u251c\u2500\u2500 Success Metrics\n\u2502   \u251c\u2500\u2500 Adoption             (markdown context \u2192 code \u2192 chart)\n\u2502   \u251c\u2500\u2500 Retention            (markdown context \u2192 code \u2192 chart)\n\u2502   \u251c\u2500\u2500 Engagement           (markdown context \u2192 code \u2192 chart)\n\u2502   \u2514\u2500\u2500 Revenue              (markdown context \u2192 code \u2192 chart)\n\u251c\u2500\u2500 Guardrail Metrics\n\u2502   \u251c\u2500\u2500 Overall Conversion   (markdown context \u2192 code \u2192 chart)\n\u2502   \u251c\u2500\u2500 Support Volume       (markdown context \u2192 code \u2192 chart)\n\u2502   \u2514\u2500\u2500 Starter Churn        (markdown context \u2192 code \u2192 chart)\n\u2514\u2500\u2500 Executive Summary        (markdown: findings, caveats, next steps)\n</code></pre> <p>Every section follows the same pattern: markdown explains what you're measuring and why, code does the computation, output shows the result. Anyone can follow the trail from question to conclusion.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/data-analysis/analyzing-data.html#frame-the-analysis-before-touching-data","title":"Frame the Analysis Before Touching Data","text":"<p>Most PMs open a spreadsheet and start making charts. That's backward. Before you touch a single number, figure out what \"good\" looks like.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/data-analysis/analyzing-data.html#the-doc-as-context-pattern","title":"The Doc-as-Context Pattern","text":"<p>You've already written documents that define what success means. Launch briefs, strategy docs, OKRs. Point CC at one of those plus your data, and it turns the existing document into a structured analysis plan.</p> <pre><code>flowchart LR\n    B[\"Existing brief\\n(success metrics,\\nguardrails, baselines)\"] --&gt; CC[\"Claude Code\"]\n    D[\"Data files\\n(CSVs, exports)\"] --&gt; CC\n    CC --&gt; N[\"Structured notebook\\nalready scoped to\\nyour metrics\"]</code></pre> <pre><code>Load @usage-data.csv and create a launch review notebook based\non the analysis plan from @growth-launch-brief.md\n</code></pre> <p>The brief already defined your success metrics, baselines, and guardrail metrics. CC reads it, knows what to measure, and structures the notebook accordingly. You didn't rewrite anything or build a framework from scratch.</p>  Bad  Good \"Analyze this data\" (no scope, no definition of success) \"Create a launch review based on @launch-brief.md and @data.csv\" Define metrics from scratch every time Reuse the metrics you already defined in the brief Success metrics only Success metrics AND guardrail metrics (things that should NOT get worse) <p>This works for any document. Launch briefs, strategy docs, OKR definitions, experiment plans. If you've already written down what matters, you don't need to explain it again.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/data-analysis/analyzing-data.html#success-metrics-and-guardrails","title":"Success Metrics AND Guardrails","text":"<p>The most important thing most PMs skip: checking the metrics that should NOT have gotten worse.</p> <p>Success metrics tell you if the thing you shipped is working. Guardrail metrics tell you if shipping it broke something else. You need both.</p> <pre><code>SUCCESS METRICS           GUARDRAILS\n(did it work?)            (did it break something?)\n\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500          \u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\n\u2713 Adoption                \u2713 Support volume\n\u2713 Retention               \u2713 Adjacent product churn\n\u2713 Engagement              \u2717 Overall conversion\n\u2713 Revenue                      \u2191\n                          This is where the story changes\n</code></pre> <p>The success metrics might all look great. Growth users who converted are thriving. Strong engagement, strong retention. Looks like a win. Until you check the guardrails and discover that overall Free-to-Paid conversion dropped since launch. More ways to pay, fewer people paying.</p> <p>The rule: Never declare success without checking guardrails. Build them into your analysis plan from the start.</p> <p>CC Limitation</p> <p>CC will not automatically check guardrails unless you tell it to. If your brief doesn't include them, neither will the notebook. The doc-as-context pattern is only as good as the document you point it at.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/data-analysis/analyzing-data.html#cross-data-source-joins","title":"Cross-Data-Source Joins","text":"<p>Real analysis almost never lives in one dataset. User data tells you who people are. Event data tells you what they did. Support tickets tell you what they complained about. You need to combine them.</p> <p>The join concept is simple: find a common identifier between two datasets and connect them.</p> <pre><code>flowchart LR\n    U[\"usage-data.csv\\nuser_id, plan,\\nsignup_date\"] --&gt; J[\"Join on\\nuser_id\"]\n    E[\"events.csv\\nuser_id, event_type,\\ntimestamp\"] --&gt; J\n    J --&gt; F[\"Combined dataset\\nwho did what, when,\\non which plan\"]</code></pre> <pre><code>Can we combine @usage-data.csv and @events.csv?\nCheck if there's a common field to join on.\n</code></pre> <p>You described it in plain English. No SQL, no merge syntax. CC checks both schemas, finds the common identifier, and explains what the join lets you do.</p> <p>This works for any combination of data sources. User data + event data. CRM records + support tickets. Survey responses + product usage. The pattern is always the same: find the common field, join, and now you can see what specific types of people actually did.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/data-analysis/analyzing-data.html#funnel-construction","title":"Funnel Construction","text":"<p>Once you've joined your data sources, build the funnel. Show every step from the first trigger through the final conversion, with conversion rates at each step.</p> <pre><code>Join these datasets on user_id and build an upgrade funnel.\nShow each step from hitting a free limit through to paid\nconversion. Compare pre-launch vs. post-launch.\n</code></pre> <p>The key analytical move: compare time periods. A funnel in isolation tells you where people drop off. A funnel compared across periods tells you what changed and where.</p>  Bad  Good \"Our conversion rate is 6%\" \"Conversion dropped from 18% to 6% after the Growth launch. Every step degraded.\" Look at overall conversion only Build step-by-step conversion and compare each step across periods \"The funnel is broken\" \"Step 2 dropped 13pp, Step 4 dropped 16pp. Compounding leaks, not one catastrophic break.\""},{"location":"playbooks/data-analysis/analyzing-data.html#when-you-hit-a-tracking-gap","title":"When You Hit a Tracking Gap","text":"<p>You'll narrow down to the exact question and discover the data isn't being tracked. This happens constantly. New UI components ship without detailed event instrumentation.</p> <pre><code>LIMIT \u2192 PRICING \u2192 [BLACK BOX - no data] \u2192 TRIAL \u2192 PAID\n         HIT       PAGE                    START\n</code></pre> <p>When you find a gap, do two things:</p> <ol> <li>File the instrumentation ticket immediately. The analysis context is fresh. You know exactly what events are missing and why you need them. CC can draft the ticket while you're still in the notebook.</li> <li>Look for qualitative signal to fill the gap. You can't see what's happening in the data, but you can look at what people are saying.</li> </ol> <pre><code>Draft an instrumentation ticket for the missing funnel events.\nInclude specific event names, properties, and rationale\nreferencing the funnel analysis. Save to tickets/.\n</code></pre> <p>CC Advantage</p> <p>Discovery to action with zero context switching. The ticket gets drafted while every detail is fresh. Every event spec, every property, every justification pulled directly from the diagnosis. In real work, if you have Linear or Jira connected via MCP, you could file this directly to the backlog.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/data-analysis/analyzing-data.html#qualitative-triangulation","title":"Qualitative Triangulation","text":"<p>When quantitative data has gaps, check what people are saying. Support tickets, cancellation reasons, NPS comments, forum posts. This isn't deep qualitative research. It's a targeted signal check: is there anything in these sources that confirms or contradicts what you're seeing in the funnel?</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/data-analysis/analyzing-data.html#sub-agent-parallel-analysis","title":"Sub-Agent Parallel Analysis","text":"<p>Run multiple qualitative scans simultaneously. Each sub-agent gets one data source and the same focused question.</p> <pre><code>flowchart TD\n    Q[\"Focused question:\\n'What are people saying about\\nthe upgrade experience?'\"] --&gt; A1[\"Agent 1\\nSupport tickets\"]\n    Q --&gt; A2[\"Agent 2\\nCancellation reasons\"]\n    A1 --&gt; S[\"Synthesized signal:\\nConfusion about plan choice,\\nonboarding overwhelm,\\nno mid-trial switching\"]\n    A2 --&gt; S</code></pre> <pre><code>Scan @support-tickets.csv for patterns related to the upgrade\nexperience. Use sub-agents: one on support tickets, one on\ncancellation reasons from @usage-data.csv. Both should focus\non upgrade-related signals.\n</code></pre> <p>Two datasets, two analyses, simultaneously. The qualitative signal either confirms or contradicts the quantitative pattern.</p> <p>Important framing: This is a signal check, not a research study. You have a specific question from the funnel analysis. If you find something, great. If not, you wait for the instrumentation.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/data-analysis/analyzing-data.html#confidence-markers","title":"Confidence Markers","text":"<p>Every finding should carry a confidence level. This is how you build trust with leadership. You're not overstating or hedging everything equally. You're being specific about what you know, what you think, and what you still need.</p> Level Marker Example HIGH Quantitative data, clear pattern \"Every funnel step degraded post-launch\" MEDIUM Qualitative signal, not instrumented \"Choice confusion and onboarding overwhelm (from support tickets)\" LOW Directional, awaiting validation \"Which specific step breaks most (awaiting tracking)\" <pre><code>KNOW  \u2713  funnel degraded at every step\nKNOW  \u2713  Growth trials convert worse than Starter\nTHINK \u25d0  choice confusion + onboarding mismatch\nNEED  \u25cb  which specific step breaks most\n</code></pre> <p>The rule for early data: 45 users and two weeks is a directional signal, not a validated success. Either caveat alone should make you hedge. Together, they mean you frame it as \"promising early signal,\" not \"validated success.\" That distinction is the difference between a PM who builds trust and a PM who gets caught overstating.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/data-analysis/analyzing-data.html#common-mistakes","title":"Common Mistakes","text":"Mistake Why It Happens What to Do Instead Jump straight to charts \"The VP asked for data\" Frame the question first. What does \"good\" look like? Success metrics only Guardrails feel like looking for trouble Build guardrails into the analysis plan from the start One data source \"The CSV has what I need\" Join sources. User data + event data + qualitative signal Declare conclusions from small samples The numbers look clean Caveat sample size and timeframe explicitly Skip the executive summary \"The charts speak for themselves\" Charts don't speak. Write the narrative. What's working, what's concerning, what needs follow-up Wait for perfect data \"We can't analyze until tracking ships\" Use qualitative sources to fill gaps. Signal beats silence"},{"location":"playbooks/data-analysis/analyzing-data.html#plug-play","title":"Plug &amp; Play","text":"<p><code>/launch-review</code> Point at a launch brief and dataset. Gets a structured Jupyter notebook with success metrics, guardrail checks, and an executive summary. Uses the doc-as-context pattern.</p> <p><code>/diagnostic-funnel</code> Joins data sources, builds the conversion funnel, compares time periods, and flags tracking gaps. Drafts instrumentation tickets for missing events.</p> <p><code>/experiment-check</code> Reads an experiment brief and runs a contextual check-in. Goes beyond metrics to investigate qualitative signals.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/data-analysis/analyzing-data.html#references","title":"References","text":"<p>Internal:</p> <ul> <li>Data &amp; Decisions : Hub page and the full investigation arc</li> <li>Building a Data-Driven Case : Cross-notebook context, compound funnel math, recommendations</li> <li>Experiment Design : Experiment briefs, power analysis, contextual check-ins</li> <li>Research Synthesis : Evidence matrix and stakeholder briefs</li> </ul> <p>External:</p> <ul> <li>Anthropic: Sub-agents : How parallel qualitative analysis works</li> <li>Anthropic: Claude Code best practices : Official guidance on structuring work</li> <li>Jupyter Documentation : The notebook format and ecosystem</li> </ul>"},{"location":"playbooks/data-analysis/building-a-data-driven-case.html","title":"Building a Data-Driven Case","text":"<p>Building a data-driven case means turning diagnosis into a recommendation that leadership can actually act on. The methodology: connect prior analyses so work compounds, establish a common metric for apples-to-apples comparison, estimate impact interactively with compound funnel math, and package everything with confidence markers and clear decision criteria.</p> <p>Quick Answer</p> <p>Use this when: You've diagnosed a problem and need to recommend a course of action with numbers to back it up.</p> <p>Avoid this when: You're still investigating what's wrong. That's Analyzing Data. Or you need to validate the fix with an experiment. That's Experiment Design.</p> <p>What CC changes: Cross-notebook context means prior work feeds new analysis without re-doing anything. Interactive estimation sessions let you apply PM judgment to funnel math. Compound calculations that would take hours in a spreadsheet happen in seconds.</p> <p>Default move: Pull baselines from prior notebooks, agree on a common metric, then estimate impact per option.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/data-analysis/building-a-data-driven-case.html#cross-notebook-context","title":"Cross-Notebook Context","text":"<p>Your prior work should compound, not reset. When you've already run a launch review (L1) and a diagnostic funnel (L2), the recommendation notebook (L3) should pull directly from both without re-analysis.</p> <pre><code>flowchart LR\n    L1[\"Launch Review\\nnotebook\\n(baselines)\"] --&gt; L3[\"Recommendation\\nnotebook\"]\n    L2[\"Diagnostic Funnel\\nnotebook\\n(current rates)\"] --&gt; L3\n    L3 --&gt; OUT[\"Side-by-side\\ncomparison +\\nrevenue estimate\"]</code></pre> <pre><code>Create recommendation.ipynb. Pull pre-launch baseline conversion\nrates from @launch-review.ipynb and current rates from\n@funnel-diagnosis.ipynb. Show the full funnel with current rates\nat each step.\n</code></pre> <p>CC reads two prior notebooks and pulls the relevant data into a third. No copy-pasting, no re-running queries, no \"can you remind me what the baseline was?\"</p>  Bad  Good Re-analyze raw data for every new question Pull from prior notebooks. Prior work compounds. Copy-paste numbers between spreadsheets CC reads the source notebooks directly \"I think the baseline was around 18%\" \"The baseline is 18.2%, from launch-review.ipynb, section 3\" <p>Why this matters: Each notebook in your analytical trail serves a purpose. The launch review established baselines. The diagnostic funnel mapped the current state. The recommendation notebook compares options against both. If someone questions a number, you trace it back through the chain.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/data-analysis/building-a-data-driven-case.html#the-common-metric-pattern","title":"The Common Metric Pattern","text":"<p>Before comparing anything, agree on what you're comparing. If three options each fix different parts of a funnel, you need one number that captures the end-to-end impact.</p> <p>The rule: Pick the metric that every estimate flows through.</p> <p>For funnel problems, that's almost always end-to-end conversion. Every per-step improvement compounds through the funnel to this one number. And translating to revenue is just multiplication.</p> <pre><code>flowchart TD\n    S1[\"Step 1\\nimprovement\"] --&gt; E2E[\"End-to-end\\nconversion\"]\n    S2[\"Step 2\\nimprovement\"] --&gt; E2E\n    S3[\"Step 3\\nimprovement\"] --&gt; E2E\n    E2E --&gt; R[\"Revenue impact\\n= conversion lift x\\nARPU x volume\"]</code></pre>  Bad  Good Compare options on different metrics (one on trial rate, another on retention) One common metric. End-to-end conversion. \"Option A improves step 2 by 7pp\" (isolated step) \"Option A improves end-to-end conversion from 6.1% to 8.4%\" (full funnel) Skip the revenue translation Conversion lift x average revenue per user x total free users hitting limits <p>Agreeing on the common metric upfront prevents the most common recommendation failure: comparing options on metrics that favor whatever you already prefer.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/data-analysis/building-a-data-driven-case.html#interactive-impact-estimation","title":"Interactive Impact Estimation","text":"<p>Impact estimation is not something CC does alone. It's a conversation where your PM judgment drives the numbers and CC does the math.</p> <p>For each option:</p> <ol> <li>Identify which funnel steps it targets. A smart upgrade prompt targets steps 1-2. A recommendation quiz targets steps 2-4. Each option has a theory about where the funnel breaks.</li> <li>Estimate the lift per step. This is the judgment call. You're the PM. You know your users, your product, and your market. CC presents options, you pick what seems realistic.</li> <li>CC runs the compound math. Your per-step estimates flow through the full funnel to the common metric.</li> </ol> <pre><code>flowchart LR\n    ID[\"Identify\\ntargeted steps\"] --&gt; EST[\"Estimate\\nper-step lift\"]\n    EST --&gt; MATH[\"Compound through\\nfull funnel\"]\n    MATH --&gt; CMP[\"Compare on\\ncommon metric\"]\n    CMP --&gt; REV[\"Translate\\nto revenue\"]</code></pre>"},{"location":"playbooks/data-analysis/building-a-data-driven-case.html#what-compound-funnel-math-looks-like","title":"What Compound Funnel Math Looks Like","text":"<p>This is the core analytical technique. Per-step lifts compound multiplicatively through the funnel.</p> <p>Suppose your current funnel looks like this:</p> Step Current Rate Limit Hit to Pricing Page 60% Pricing Page to Trial Start 45% Trial Start to Onboarding 70% Onboarding to Active Trial 62% Active Trial to Conversion 52% <p>End-to-end conversion: 0.60 x 0.45 x 0.70 x 0.62 x 0.52 = 6.1%</p> <p>Now suppose Option A (smart prompts + simplified pricing) improves step 1 to 66% and step 2 to 52%:</p> <p>Option A end-to-end: 0.66 x 0.52 x 0.70 x 0.62 x 0.52 = 9.7%</p> <p>And Option B (recommendation quiz + tailored onboarding) improves step 2 to 52%, step 3 to 80%, and step 4 to 72%:</p> <p>Option B end-to-end: 0.60 x 0.52 x 0.80 x 0.72 x 0.52 = 9.3%</p> <p>The key insight: where you intervene matters as much as how much you move the number. Early funnel changes compound more than late funnel changes, even if the per-step improvement looks smaller. A 6pp lift in step 1 can beat a 10pp lift in step 4 because every downstream step multiplies the gain.</p> <pre><code>Run the impact estimate for all options. Apply our estimates\nto the targeted steps and flow through the full funnel to\nend-to-end conversion. Show them side by side. Include revenue\ntranslation.\n</code></pre>  Bad  Good \"Option A is better because it targets more steps\" \"Option A yields 9.7% e2e vs Option B at 9.3%. Early-funnel compounding is why.\" Present per-step improvements in isolation Show the full compound math so stakeholders can see exactly how the numbers flow Skip revenue \"That's a 3.6pp lift on a base of 1,200 limit-hits/month at $29 ARPU = $X/month\""},{"location":"playbooks/data-analysis/building-a-data-driven-case.html#building-the-recommendation","title":"Building the Recommendation","text":"<p>A recommendation is not \"here are three options, you pick.\" A recommendation is \"here's what we should do, here's the math, and here's what would change my mind.\"</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/data-analysis/building-a-data-driven-case.html#the-template-structure","title":"The Template Structure","text":"<pre><code>1. Context          - What happened, what we investigated, what we found\n2. Options          - What we considered (with estimated impact for each)\n3. Recommendation   - Which option and why\n4. Assumptions      - What we're betting on being true\n5. What Would       - Specific findings that would make us reconsider\n   Change My Mind\n</code></pre> <p>The \"what would change my mind\" section is the power move. It shows you've thought about the limits of your analysis. It gives leadership clear criteria for revisiting the decision. And it's honest. These are estimates.</p> <pre><code>Fill @recommendation-template.md using the analysis from\n@recommendation.ipynb. Save as recommendation.md.\n</code></pre>  Bad  Good \"We recommend Option B\" \"We recommend Option B. It yields the highest e2e lift at 9.3%, targets the steps where qualitative data confirms the most friction, and has the most manageable eng scope.\" No assumptions listed \"Assumes quiz completion rate &gt;60%, onboarding improvements apply equally to Starter and Growth trials, current traffic volume holds\" No reversibility criteria \"Reconsider if: quiz completion &lt;40%, Growth trials don't improve within 2 weeks of launch, support tickets about 'wrong plan' don't decrease\""},{"location":"playbooks/data-analysis/building-a-data-driven-case.html#connecting-recommendation-to-evidence","title":"Connecting Recommendation to Evidence","text":"<p>Every claim in the recommendation should trace back to a notebook. The VP should be able to follow the thread:</p> <pre><code>flowchart TD\n    REC[\"recommendation.md\\n'Option B, 9.3% e2e'\"] --&gt; N3[\"recommendation.ipynb\\nCompound math,\\nside-by-side comparison\"]\n    N3 --&gt; N2[\"funnel-diagnosis.ipynb\\nCurrent funnel rates,\\nqualitative signal\"]\n    N2 --&gt; N1[\"launch-review.ipynb\\nPre-launch baselines,\\nguardrail discovery\"]\n    N1 --&gt; RAW[\"Raw data files\\nCSVs, exports\"]</code></pre> <p>The whole analytical trail is traceable. The recommendation document cites the notebook. The notebook references prior notebooks. Every number points back to data.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/data-analysis/building-a-data-driven-case.html#common-mistakes","title":"Common Mistakes","text":"Mistake Why It Happens What to Do Instead Compare options on different metrics Each option's strength shows on a different metric Pick one common metric. Make everything comparable. Present analysis without a recommendation \"I don't want to be wrong\" Take a position. Include the \"what would change my mind\" section so you're covered. Let CC estimate impact alone CC can generate plausible numbers for anything You estimate. CC does the math. Your judgment drives the numbers. Skip the compound math \"A 7pp lift sounds good\" Show the full funnel multiplication. Stakeholders need to see how per-step lifts become end-to-end impact. Forget revenue translation \"Conversion improvement\" feels sufficient The VP cares about revenue. One more multiplication. Do it. Re-do prior analysis \"I need the baseline again\" Pull from prior notebooks. Cross-notebook context is the whole point."},{"location":"playbooks/data-analysis/building-a-data-driven-case.html#plug-play","title":"Plug &amp; Play","text":"<p><code>/impact-estimation</code> Interactive estimation session. Walks through each option's targeted steps, collects your per-step estimates, runs compound funnel math, and shows side-by-side comparison with revenue translation.</p> <p><code>/recommendation-builder</code> Fills a recommendation template from notebook analysis. Pulls context, options, math, assumptions, and decision criteria into a stakeholder-ready document.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/data-analysis/building-a-data-driven-case.html#references","title":"References","text":"<p>Internal:</p> <ul> <li>Data &amp; Decisions : Hub page and the full investigation arc</li> <li>Analyzing Data : Jupyter notebooks, funnel construction, qualitative triangulation</li> <li>Experiment Design : Validating the recommended option with a controlled test</li> </ul> <p>External:</p> <ul> <li>Anthropic: Claude Code best practices : Official guidance on structuring analytical work</li> </ul>"},{"location":"playbooks/data-analysis/experiment-design.html","title":"Experiment Design","text":"<p>Experiment design is about building a living document that defines the experiment AND tells Claude Code where to look when you want a check-in. The brief is not just documentation. It's the interface between you and ongoing analysis. Write it once, and every check-in from that point forward pulls metrics, support tickets, cancellation patterns, and segmentation automatically.</p> <p>Quick Answer</p> <p>Use this when: You've recommended a course of action and need to validate it with a controlled experiment.</p> <p>Avoid this when: You're still diagnosing the problem. That's Analyzing Data. Or you're still choosing between options. That's Building a Data-Driven Case.</p> <p>What CC changes: The experiment brief IS the interface. CC reads it and knows what metrics to check, what data sources to scan, and what qualitative signals to investigate. One command triggers a full contextual check-in that goes far beyond what any dashboard shows.</p> <p>Default move: Fill the experiment brief from your recommendation, then run contextual check-ins against it.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/data-analysis/experiment-design.html#the-experiment-brief-as-a-living-document","title":"The Experiment Brief as a Living Document","text":"<p>Most experiment briefs get written, filed, and never touched again. A dashboard gets set up, someone checks it occasionally, and the experiment runs on autopilot until someone remembers to look at it.</p> <p>The CC approach is different. The experiment brief is a structured document that defines everything CC needs to run a full contextual check-in:</p> <pre><code>flowchart TD\n    B[\"experiment-brief.md\"] --&gt; H[\"Hypothesis\\nWhat you expect to happen\"]\n    B --&gt; M[\"Metrics\\nPrimary, secondary, guardrails\"]\n    B --&gt; D[\"Data Sources\\nWhere to look\"]\n    B --&gt; S[\"Sample Size\\nHow many, how long\"]\n    B --&gt; I[\"Instrumentation\\nWhat events to track\"]\n    B --&gt; MP[\"Monitoring Plan\\nWhat to check and where\"]\n    B --&gt; SC[\"Success Criteria\\nShip / extend / kill thresholds\"]</code></pre>"},{"location":"playbooks/data-analysis/experiment-design.html#what-goes-in-each-section","title":"What Goes in Each Section","text":"Section Purpose Example Hypothesis What you expect and why \"Adding a recommendation quiz will increase targeted funnel step conversion by 5pp because it reduces choice confusion\" Primary metric The one number that determines success Targeted funnel step conversion rate Secondary metrics Supporting signals End-to-end conversion, time-to-trial-start Guardrail metrics Things that should NOT get worse Support ticket volume, other funnel steps, adjacent product metrics Sample size + duration How many users, how long ~380 per variant, ~3-4 weeks at current traffic Instrumentation Events specific to THIS experiment quiz_started, quiz_completed, plan_recommended, recommendation_accepted Monitoring plan Data sources for check-ins Experiment metrics + support tickets + cancellation reasons + plan segmentation Success criteria Ship / extend / kill thresholds Ship if &gt;3pp lift at p&lt;0.05. Extend if directional but not significant. Kill if guardrails trigger. <pre><code>Fill @experiment-brief-template.md using @recommendation.md\nand @recommendation.ipynb. Save as experiment-brief.md.\n</code></pre> <p>The brief pulls directly from the recommendation. The hypothesis was already in the recommendation. The metrics were already defined. The instrumentation requirements come from the specific option you're testing. CC connects the dots.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/data-analysis/experiment-design.html#the-document-as-interface-pattern","title":"The Document-as-Interface Pattern","text":"<p>This is the key concept. The experiment brief is not just documentation. It's the interface between you and the analysis.</p> <p>When you ask CC to run a check-in, it reads the brief first. The brief's structure tells CC:</p> <ul> <li>What to measure (the metrics section)</li> <li>Where to look (the data sources in the monitoring plan)</li> <li>What not to break (the guardrail metrics)</li> <li>When to escalate (the success criteria)</li> </ul> <pre><code>flowchart LR\n    BRIEF[\"experiment-brief.md\\n\\nmetrics \u2192 what to measure\\ndata sources \u2192 where to look\\nguardrails \u2192 what not to break\\ncriteria \u2192 when to escalate\"] --&gt; CC[\"Claude Code\\nreads the brief,\\nknows the full context\"]\n    CC --&gt; CHECK[\"Contextual check-in\\nMetrics + qualitative\\n+ proactive investigation\"]</code></pre> <p>One prompt, full context. You don't re-explain the experiment every time.</p>  Bad  Good \"Check how the experiment is doing\" (no context about what to check) \"Run a full check-in on the experiment using @experiment-brief.md and @latest-data.csv\" Open a dashboard, look at one graph CC checks metrics, scans support tickets, reviews cancellation patterns, and investigates interesting signals Remember which metrics to check each time The brief defines everything. CC reads it and knows."},{"location":"playbooks/data-analysis/experiment-design.html#power-analysis-sizing-your-experiment","title":"Power Analysis: Sizing Your Experiment","text":"<p>Power analysis is the math that tells you how many users you need and how long to run the experiment. Smaller expected effect means more users means longer experiment.</p> <pre><code>Expected lift:    +5pp\nSignificance:     95%\nPower:            80%\n\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\nNeed:  ~380 users per variant\nAt current traffic:  ~3-4 weeks\n</code></pre> <p>CC runs this calculation directly. You provide the expected lift (from your impact estimation), the significance level you want, and the power. CC returns the sample size and estimated duration.</p> <p>Why this matters for PMs: You need to tell leadership how long the experiment will run before you can call it. \"Two weeks\" based on gut feel vs. \"three to four weeks\" based on power analysis are very different conversations.</p> <p>CC Advantage</p> <p>CC can run any statistical analysis. Power analysis, significance testing, confidence intervals. You describe what you want in plain English. The notebook captures the methodology. Your data science team can audit the approach.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/data-analysis/experiment-design.html#contextual-check-ins","title":"Contextual Check-Ins","text":"<p>This is where the document-as-interface pattern pays off. A contextual check-in is not a dashboard refresh. It's CC reading the experiment brief, pulling data from multiple sources, and investigating interesting signals proactively.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/data-analysis/experiment-design.html#what-a-check-in-produces","title":"What a Check-In Produces","text":"<pre><code>flowchart TD\n    CMD[\"'Run a full check-in on the\\nexperiment using @experiment-brief.md\\nand @week2-data.csv'\"] --&gt; S1[\"Standard metrics\\nProgress toward sample size,\\nprimary + secondary metrics,\\nguardrail check\"]\n    S1 --&gt; S2[\"Qualitative scan\\nSupport tickets from experiment period,\\ncancellation reasons,\\ntreatment vs control comparison\"]\n    S2 --&gt; S3[\"Proactive investigation\\nCC notices something interesting\\nand digs deeper without being asked\"]\n    S3 --&gt; SUM[\"Summary\\nWhat the numbers say,\\nwhat qualitative confirms,\\nwhat's interesting,\\nwhat you'd want to see before calling it\"]</code></pre> <p>A typical week-2 check-in might produce:</p> <ol> <li>Standard metrics: 63% enrolled toward target. Primary metric shows directional improvement, not yet significant at p &gt; 0.05. Guardrails clean.</li> <li>Qualitative scan: Confusion-related support tickets are down in the treatment group. \"Chose wrong plan\" cancellations also down.</li> <li>Proactive investigation: CC noticed the confusion ticket drop, segmented by plan type unprompted, and found the improvement is stronger for Growth trials than Starter trials.</li> <li>Summary: Directional positive signal across quantitative and qualitative. Not yet significant. Interesting Growth-specific pattern worth watching. Need ~2 more weeks for statistical power.</li> </ol>  Bad (Dashboard)  Good (Contextual Check-In) \"Here's your graph\" \"Here's your graph. Confusion tickets are down in treatment. Stronger for Growth trials. The mechanism appears to be working.\" Shows what you asked to see Shows what you actually want to know One data source Metrics + support tickets + cancellation patterns + segmentation Static Investigates interesting signals proactively"},{"location":"playbooks/data-analysis/experiment-design.html#the-difference-is-context","title":"The Difference Is Context","text":"<p>A dashboard shows you what you configured it to show. A contextual check-in reads the experiment brief, understands what you're trying to learn, and follows threads when something looks interesting. It's the difference between a graph and an analyst who knows your experiment.</p> <p>The brief is what makes this possible. Without it, CC is just pulling numbers. With it, CC knows the hypothesis, the metrics, the data sources, the guardrails, and the success criteria. That context turns a data pull into an investigation.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/data-analysis/experiment-design.html#experiment-instrumentation-vs-general-tracking","title":"Experiment Instrumentation vs. General Tracking","text":"<p>There's an important distinction between the instrumentation you filed in the diagnostic phase and the instrumentation for your experiment.</p> General Tracking Experiment-Specific Events for the whole funnel (pricing_plan_compared, plan_selection_clicked) Events for the specific feature being tested (quiz_started, quiz_completed, recommendation_accepted) Shipped to understand the product Shipped to measure the experiment Lives forever May be removed after the experiment concludes <p>The experiment brief defines what experiment-specific events you need implemented. This is another example of the brief as a working document. It tells engineering exactly what to build.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/data-analysis/experiment-design.html#from-check-ins-to-automation","title":"From Check-Ins to Automation","text":"<p>The trajectory: from \"I check on my experiment\" to \"my experiment checks in with me.\"</p> <p>Once you have the check-in working manually, the same pattern can run on a schedule. A GitHub Action triggers CC to read the brief, pull fresh data, run the analysis, and post a summary to Slack every morning.</p> <pre><code>7:00 AM\n\nSlack:\n\"Experiment check-in (auto):\n Treatment +2.1pp, not yet sig.\n Confusion tickets still trending\n down. No guardrails triggered.\n Nothing needs your attention.\"\n\nYou haven't opened your laptop yet.\n</code></pre> <p>You don't need to build this on day one. The manual check-in teaches you the pattern. The automation comes when you're ready.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/data-analysis/experiment-design.html#common-mistakes","title":"Common Mistakes","text":"Mistake Why It Happens What to Do Instead No power analysis \"We'll just run it for two weeks\" Calculate sample size. Know how long you actually need. Dashboard-only monitoring \"We set up the graphs\" Use contextual check-ins that pull multiple data sources and investigate signals Brief written and forgotten \"It's in Confluence somewhere\" The brief IS the interface. Point CC at it for every check-in. No guardrail metrics \"We're just watching the primary metric\" Define what should NOT get worse. Check it every time. Calling it too early Directional signal feels conclusive Wait for statistical significance. \"Not yet significant\" is the most important phrase in experiment monitoring. Separate instrumentation for experiment and general tracking \"We'll figure it out\" Define experiment-specific events in the brief. Keep them distinct from the general tracking you filed earlier."},{"location":"playbooks/data-analysis/experiment-design.html#plug-play","title":"Plug &amp; Play","text":"<p><code>/experiment-brief</code> Fills an experiment brief template from a recommendation document. Includes hypothesis, metrics, power analysis, instrumentation requirements, and monitoring plan.</p> <p><code>/experiment-check</code> Reads an experiment brief and runs a full contextual check-in. Standard metrics, qualitative scan, proactive investigation, and summary. The document-as-interface pattern in action.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/data-analysis/experiment-design.html#references","title":"References","text":"<p>Internal:</p> <ul> <li>Data &amp; Decisions : Hub page and the full investigation arc</li> <li>Analyzing Data : The diagnostic work that precedes experiment design</li> <li>Building a Data-Driven Case : The recommendation that the experiment validates</li> </ul> <p>External:</p> <ul> <li>Anthropic: Sub-agents : How parallel qualitative analysis works in check-ins</li> <li>Anthropic: Claude Code best practices : Official guidance on structuring work</li> <li>Evan Miller: Sample Size Calculator : Quick reference for experiment sizing</li> </ul>"},{"location":"playbooks/user-research/index.html","title":"User Research","text":"<p>User research moves you from \"we think\" to \"we know.\" It starts with your hidden assumptions, works backward from what you'll do with the answers, and uses Claude Code to make the whole process faster without cutting corners on rigor.</p> <p>Quick Answer</p> <p>Use this when: You have a decision to make and not enough evidence about what your users actually need.</p> <p>Avoid this when: You're looking at market landscape or competitor positioning. That's Competitive Intelligence.</p> <p>What CC changes: Research that used to take weeks compresses to days. You can analyze 10 transcripts in parallel, code survey responses on the fly, and still maintain methodological rigor.</p> <p>Default move: Start with Research Design. Surface assumptions before collecting data.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/user-research/index.html#the-research-arc","title":"The Research Arc","text":"<p>Research flows through four connected phases. Each builds on the last.</p> <pre><code>flowchart LR\n    D[\"Research\\nDesign\"] --&gt; I[\"Interview\\nAnalysis\"]\n    I --&gt; S[\"Survey &amp;\\nFeedback\"]\n    S --&gt; SY[\"Research\\nSynthesis\"]</code></pre> <p>Claude Code compresses this from a multi-week process to days. Assumption surfacing takes minutes, transcript analysis runs in parallel, and synthesis happens same-day.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/user-research/index.html#research-design","title":"Research Design","text":"<p>Surface your hidden assumptions. Turn them into answerable questions. Design your interviews and surveys. Define what findings would change your mind before you collect any data.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/user-research/index.html#interview-analysis","title":"Interview Analysis","text":"<p>Extract insights from conversations. Code themes independently per participant. Verify quotes against source transcripts. Find contradictions between what people say and what they actually do.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/user-research/index.html#survey-feedback-analysis","title":"Survey &amp; Feedback Analysis","text":"<p>Quantify what interviews discovered. Code open-ended responses inductively. Calculate how common a pattern actually is. Spot gaps between stated needs and willingness to pay.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/user-research/index.html#research-synthesis","title":"Research Synthesis","text":"<p>Weave multiple streams of evidence into a single recommendation. Map findings to decisions. Surface contested claims. Build something you'd actually show leadership.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/user-research/index.html#how-claude-code-changes-research","title":"How Claude Code Changes Research","text":"Traditional With Claude Code Design questions, get feedback, iterate over days Design questions, iterate in minutes with <code>/assumption-surfacing</code> Analyze 5 interviews manually over weeks Analyze 10+ transcripts in parallel, same day Code survey responses by hand Code responses inductively as they come in Compile findings into slides over days Generate evidence matrices and briefs in hours <p>The speed doesn't change the rigor. It changes what you can afford to do. You can run more ambitious research, iterate faster, and actually change your mind when evidence demands it.</p> <p>CC Limitation</p> <p>Claude Code accelerates analysis but it can't replace your judgment. It will find patterns in any data, whether they're real or not. The research design (assumptions, decision framework, verification) is what keeps you honest. Skip it and you'll just get faster at being wrong.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/user-research/index.html#where-to-start","title":"Where to Start","text":"<p>New to research? Begin with Research Design. It covers assumption surfacing, question design, and decision frameworks.</p> <p>Already designed your study? Jump to Interview Analysis or Survey &amp; Feedback Analysis depending on what you're collecting.</p> <p>Ready to write up findings? Use Research Synthesis to turn multi-stream evidence into a stakeholder brief.</p> <p>Need market context instead? See Competitive Intelligence for web research, review mining, and competitive positioning.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/user-research/index.html#plug-play","title":"Plug &amp; Play","text":"<p><code>/assumption-surfacing</code> 10-minute structured interview to surface what you know vs. what you assume. The starting point for any research.</p> <p><code>/mom-test-filter</code> Scans interview guides and flags questions that get polite lies instead of truth.</p> <p><code>/research-design</code> Full end-to-end pipeline from vague question to stakeholder-ready research plan.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/user-research/index.html#references","title":"References","text":"<p>Internal:</p> <ul> <li>Research Design : Assumptions, questions, methods, decision frameworks</li> <li>Interview Analysis : Extraction, coding, verification</li> <li>Survey &amp; Feedback Analysis : Inductive coding, codebooks, intensity scoring</li> <li>Research Synthesis : Evidence matrix, contested findings, stakeholder briefs</li> <li>Competitive Intelligence : Market research, review mining, positioning</li> </ul> <p>External:</p> <ul> <li>Rob Fitzpatrick: How to Talk to Customers (The Mom Test) : Hour-long interview covering the core principles of getting honest feedback</li> <li>Teresa Torres: Continuous Discovery Habits : Talk on building weekly research into your product process</li> <li>The Product Manager's Guide to User Research : Practical tactical guide from Maze</li> <li>The Mom Test by Rob Fitzpatrick : The book on asking questions that get truth (short, practical, essential)</li> <li>ProductTalk: What Claude Code Is and How It's Different : Teresa Torres on using Claude Code for product discovery</li> </ul>"},{"location":"playbooks/user-research/interview-analysis.html","title":"Interview Analysis","text":"<p>Interview analysis turns recorded conversations into traceable, verified findings. The process is simple: extract per-person, verify the evidence, synthesize across participants. Every step exists because of a specific way LLMs fail at research.</p> <p>Quick Answer</p> <p>Use this when: You have 3+ interview transcripts and need structured findings you can defend to stakeholders.</p> <p>Avoid this when: You have survey data or quantitative feedback. That's Survey &amp; Feedback Analysis.</p> <p>What CC changes: Parallel sub-agents analyze each transcript in isolation. Fresh context per transcript prevents cross-contamination. A separate validator checks every quote against source material.</p> <p>Default move: One agent per transcript. Verify before you synthesize. Never dump all transcripts into one prompt.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/user-research/interview-analysis.html#why-dump-and-summarize-fails","title":"Why \"Dump and Summarize\" Fails","text":"<p>The instinct is to paste all your transcripts into Claude and ask for themes. The output reads well. It's also dangerous.</p> <p>Four failure modes compound on each other:</p> <ol> <li>Voices get averaged. Five people with different roles and contexts become \"participants.\" You lose who said what and why.</li> <li>Gaps get smoothed. Someone says \"I need SSO\" then describes a workflow that never touches authentication. That gap between stated needs and described behavior is the most valuable finding in the interview, and it vanishes when you summarize across people.</li> <li>Clean stories get told. LLMs prefer coherence over contradiction. Claude picks quotes that fit a tidy narrative and quietly drops the messy ones. The messy data is where insight lives.</li> <li>Quotes get fabricated. Claude will invent quotes that sound right but were never said. Without verification, fabricated evidence looks identical to real evidence.</li> </ol>  Bad  Good Paste 5 transcripts into one prompt, ask for themes One agent per transcript, same extraction criteria, isolated context \"Participants expressed strong interest in enterprise features\" \"Chen stated 'we need SSO' but her described workflow centers on team permissions. Park mentioned 'missing enterprise features' but described 12-team workspace management.\" Trust the output because it reads well Run a validator agent to check every quote against source transcripts"},{"location":"playbooks/user-research/interview-analysis.html#the-process","title":"The Process","text":"<p>Four steps. Each builds on the last. Skipping verification is how research goes sideways.</p> <pre><code>flowchart LR\n    S[\"Setup\\n(extraction guide)\"] --&gt; E[\"Extract\\n(parallel agents)\"]\n    E --&gt; V[\"Verify\\n(fresh validator)\"]\n    V --&gt; SY[\"Synthesize\\n(cross-participant)\"]</code></pre>"},{"location":"playbooks/user-research/interview-analysis.html#1-set-up-extraction-criteria","title":"1. Set Up Extraction Criteria","text":"<p>Before running any agents, define what they should look for. An extraction guide ensures every agent applies the same criteria consistently.</p> <p>What each agent tracks:</p> Criterion Why It Matters Key claims with timestamps Traceability. Every finding points back to a moment in the conversation. Without timestamps, stakeholders just have to trust you. Stated preferences What the person says they want, in their words. \"We need SSO.\" This is the surface layer. Described behaviors What the person actually does. Workflows they walk through, workarounds they've built. This is the deeper layer. Gaps between stated and described The most valuable finding type. When someone says one thing and describes another, that contradiction is usually the real insight. Confidence indicators Hedging (\"I think,\" \"probably\") vs. definitive (\"absolutely,\" \"that's the line\"). Tells you how much weight a claim deserves. Open questions Things that came up but weren't fully explored, or where the data is thin. <p>Save this as <code>extraction-guide.md</code> in your research project folder. Every agent gets a copy.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/user-research/interview-analysis.html#2-run-parallel-extraction","title":"2. Run Parallel Extraction","text":"<p>One sub-agent per transcript. Each agent gets fresh context with only its assigned transcript plus the extraction guide and participant overview. Agents cannot see each other's work.</p> <pre><code>flowchart TD\n    P[\"You\"] --&gt; A1[\"Agent 1\\nTranscript: Chen\"]\n    P --&gt; A2[\"Agent 2\\nTranscript: Park\"]\n    P --&gt; A3[\"Agent 3\\nTranscript: Kim\"]\n    P --&gt; A4[\"Agent 4\\nTranscript: Rodriguez\"]\n    P --&gt; A5[\"Agent 5\\nTranscript: Okafor\"]\n\n    A1 --&gt; E1[\"extraction-chen.md\"]\n    A2 --&gt; E2[\"extraction-park.md\"]\n    A3 --&gt; E3[\"extraction-kim.md\"]\n    A4 --&gt; E4[\"extraction-rodriguez.md\"]\n    A5 --&gt; E5[\"extraction-okafor.md\"]</code></pre> <p>The prompt:</p> <pre><code>Spawn a sub-agent for each transcript in [folder].\nGive each agent extraction-guide.md, participant-overview.md,\nand their one transcript.\nSave each extraction to the same folder as extraction-[name].md.\n</code></pre> <p>Why isolation matters: A sub-agent that only sees one person's transcript cannot blend voices or let one participant's strong opinion influence findings from another. This is the same reason juries deliberate after hearing all testimony, not during. Cross-contamination is the enemy of honest extraction.</p> <p>Batch size: Five transcripts at a time is reliable. Beyond five, batch them in groups of five.</p> <p>CC Advantage</p> <p>Each sub-agent gets fresh context, meaning it starts with zero preconceptions. The main conversation might be deep into analysis mode, but the extraction agents see only raw transcript. This isolation is why parallel extraction produces better findings than sequential analysis in one context window.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/user-research/interview-analysis.html#3-verify-quotes","title":"3. Verify Quotes","text":"<p>This is the builder-validator pattern applied to research. A fresh agent with zero investment in the original analysis checks every quoted or paraphrased claim against the source transcripts.</p> <p>The validator classifies each item into three tiers:</p> Tier Definition Action VERIFIED Exact or near-exact match found in transcript at the stated timestamp Use as-is in synthesis PARAPHRASE Meaning preserved but wording changed significantly Flag the wording shift, use with caveat NOT FOUND Cannot locate in the transcript at all Remove from analysis entirely <pre><code>Spawn a fresh validator agent. Give it all original transcripts\nand all extraction files. Check every quote and classify as\nVERIFIED, PARAPHRASE, or NOT FOUND.\nSave to verification-report.md.\n</code></pre> <p>Why fresh context matters: A validator that shares context with the extractor will unconsciously defend the extractor's work. The validator has zero investment in the original analysis. It is just comparing claims against source material.</p>  Bad  Good Trust extraction output because it reads well Run a separate validator against source transcripts \"Chen mentioned needing better permissions\" (did she?) \"VERIFIED: Chen said 'I've literally been maintaining a spreadsheet of who has access to what' at 12:34\" Skip verification because it takes extra time Catch a NOT FOUND quote before it ends up in your stakeholder brief"},{"location":"playbooks/user-research/interview-analysis.html#4-synthesize-across-participants","title":"4. Synthesize Across Participants","text":"<p>Only after extraction is complete and verification confirms the evidence is real do you synthesize. This step runs in the main conversation because extraction files are already distilled summaries, not raw transcripts.</p> <p>The key principle: Group by described need, not stated label.</p> <p>\"We need SSO\" and \"we need team permissions\" may point to the same underlying theme if the described behaviors match. The stated label is what people reach for. The described behavior is what they actually experience.</p> <pre><code>Synthesize the verified extractions using synthesis-template.md.\nGroup findings by actual underlying need, not stated labels.\nMap each theme to the participants who contributed evidence.\nSave to interview-synthesis.md.\n</code></pre> <p>A good synthesis:</p> <ul> <li>Groups themes by described need, not stated preference</li> <li>Maps each theme to the participants who contributed evidence</li> <li>Cites specific evidence with pointers back to extraction files</li> <li>Notes segments and variations by company size, role, or other factors</li> <li>Surfaces aggregate open questions</li> </ul> <pre><code>flowchart TD\n    E1[\"extraction-chen.md\"] --&gt; S[\"Synthesis\"]\n    E2[\"extraction-park.md\"] --&gt; S\n    E3[\"extraction-kim.md\"] --&gt; S\n    E4[\"extraction-rodriguez.md\"] --&gt; S\n    E5[\"extraction-okafor.md\"] --&gt; S\n    VR[\"verification-report.md\"] --&gt; S\n\n    S --&gt; T1[\"Theme 1: Team Scaling\\nChen, Park, Kim\"]\n    S --&gt; T2[\"Theme 2: Access Control\\nChen, Rodriguez, Okafor\"]\n    S --&gt; T3[\"Theme 3: Pricing Flexibility\\nRodriguez, Okafor\"]</code></pre>"},{"location":"playbooks/user-research/interview-analysis.html#stated-vs-described-the-gap-that-matters","title":"Stated vs. Described: The Gap That Matters","text":"<p>The single most important analytical move in interview analysis is tracking both what people say they need and what their described workflows reveal, then noting the gap.</p> Participant Stated Need Described Behavior The Gap Chen \"We need SSO\" Described workflow never touches authentication. Keeps returning to who can see what across teams. Real need is team permissions, not SSO Park \"Missing enterprise features\" Story centers on managing 12 teams in a flat workspace with no separation Real need is workspace organization Rodriguez \"Need better security\" Built 3 workarounds for team structure within existing tool Real need is team hierarchy support <p>These gaps only surface when you track both sides per person. A cross-participant summary would have averaged these into \"participants want enterprise features\" and buried the insight.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/user-research/interview-analysis.html#the-transcript-preparation-step","title":"The Transcript Preparation Step","text":"<p>Raw transcripts waste agent context on small talk and tangents. Before running extraction:</p> <ul> <li>Strip filler words and conversational noise</li> <li>Organize by topic where possible</li> <li>Keep timestamps intact (the traceability chain depends on them)</li> <li>One file per participant, named consistently</li> </ul>"},{"location":"playbooks/user-research/interview-analysis.html#common-mistakes","title":"Common Mistakes","text":"Mistake Why It Happens What to Do Instead All transcripts in one prompt Feels efficient One agent per transcript. Isolation prevents cross-contamination Skipping verification \"The extraction looks right\" It always looks right. That's the problem. Run the validator Grouping by stated label Labels feel concrete Group by described behavior. \"We need SSO\" might mean three different things Synthesizing from raw transcripts Seems faster Synthesize from verified extractions. Raw transcripts reintroduce noise Not tracking confidence indicators Focused on content over conviction Hedging vs. definitive language changes how much weight a claim deserves"},{"location":"playbooks/user-research/interview-analysis.html#plug-play","title":"Plug &amp; Play","text":"<p><code>/interview-extraction</code> Parallel per-transcript extraction. One sub-agent per transcript, same criteria, isolated context. Works for any batch of conversations: customer interviews, user testing, sales calls, meeting notes.</p> <p><code>/quote-verification</code> Builder-validator for research. A fresh agent checks every claim against source material. Classifies as VERIFIED, PARAPHRASE, or NOT FOUND.</p> <p><code>/interview-synthesis</code> Cross-participant theme identification grouped by described need. Maps themes to participants with specific evidence citations.</p> <p><code>/interview-analysis</code> Full pipeline coordinator. Runs extraction, verification, and synthesis end to end. Reach for this when starting from scratch with a new batch of transcripts.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/user-research/interview-analysis.html#references","title":"References","text":"<p>Internal:</p> <ul> <li>Research Design : Surface assumptions and design your interview guide before collecting data</li> <li>Survey &amp; Feedback Analysis : The quantitative complement to interview analysis</li> <li>Research Synthesis : Combining interview findings with other evidence streams</li> <li>User Research : The hub page connecting all research methods</li> </ul> <p>External:</p> <ul> <li>Anthropic: Sub-agents : How parallel extraction works under the hood</li> <li>Anthropic: Claude Code best practices : Official guidance on structuring work with Claude Code</li> <li>The Mom Test by Rob Fitzpatrick : The book on conducting interviews that get truth</li> </ul>"},{"location":"playbooks/user-research/research-design.html","title":"Research Design","text":"<p>Research design turns \"we should talk to users\" into a plan that will actually change a decision. The best research starts with your hidden assumptions, works backward from what you'll do with the answers, and uses Claude Code to make the whole process radically faster without cutting corners on rigor.</p> <p>Quick Answer</p> <p>Use this when: You have a decision to make and not enough evidence.</p> <p>Avoid this when: You've already decided and want validation (that's a different problem).</p> <p>What CC changes: Assumption surfacing becomes a conversation. Interview and survey design iterates in minutes. Skills like <code>/mom-test-filter</code> check your interview guides automatically.</p> <p>Default move: Surface assumptions first, then design your interviews/surveys, then define your decision framework.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/user-research/research-design.html#surface-your-assumptions-first","title":"Surface Your Assumptions First","text":"<p>Before you write a single interview question, figure out what you actually need to learn. Most research fails because the PM jumped straight to questions without understanding what they were assuming.</p> <p>Have Claude Code interview you. It asks about your target definition, key requirements, business model, competitive context, feasibility, and timing. CC is genuinely good at this because it asks questions without ego or politics. It will surface blind spots you didn't know you had.</p> <p>Skill: <code>/assumption-surfacing</code> A 10-minute structured interview that maps what you KNOW vs. what you ASSUME. Works for any decision, not just research. Run it before scoping a feature, planning a roadmap, or designing a GTM strategy.</p> <p>Or do it manually with a prompt:</p> <pre><code>I'm working on [brief description]. Interview me to surface my hidden\nassumptions. Ask about:\n- Who exactly is the target and how I'm defining them\n- What I believe they need and why\n- Business model implications I might not be considering\n- What competitors are doing that I might be wrong about\n- Internal feasibility risks\n- Timing and urgency assumptions\n\nAfter each round of questions, update a KNOW vs ASSUME table with\nconfidence levels (high/medium/low) and the source for each belief.\n</code></pre> <p>The output is a KNOW vs. ASSUME table with confidence scoring:</p>  Bad  Good SSO \"Enterprise buyers need SSO\" / Assume \"Enterprise buyers need SSO before evaluating\" / Low confidence / Source: one prospect mentioned it Onboarding \"Onboarding is slow\" / Assume \"Onboarding takes &gt;2 weeks for teams of 50+\" / Medium confidence / Source: support tickets suggest this Competition \"We're better than competitors\" / Know \"Competitors don't offer self-serve provisioning\" / High confidence / Source: verified across top 5 last month <p>The good version has specificity, confidence levels, and sources. The bad version is binary and vague. You can't design research from vague assumptions.</p> <p>CC Limitation</p> <p>Claude Code can surface assumptions you didn't know you had, but it can't tell you which ones matter most for your business. That's your judgment. Rank by: \"If I'm wrong about this, does it change my decision?\"</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/user-research/research-design.html#turn-assumptions-into-research-questions","title":"Turn Assumptions Into Research Questions","text":"<p>Each high-risk assumption maps directly to a research question. You're not inventing questions from scratch. You're taking your riskiest assumptions and asking \"how do I find out if this is true?\"</p>  Bad  Good \"Do enterprises care about security?\" \"What percentage of enterprise evaluations stall at the security review stage?\" \"Is our onboarding good?\" \"How do teams of 50+ actually onboard collaboration tools today?\" \"Why would someone switch to us?\" \"What triggers a team lead to start evaluating alternatives to their current tool?\" <p>Good research questions are specific enough that you could imagine a concrete answer. Bad ones invite vague, useless responses.</p> <p>Ask CC to help generate the questions:</p> <pre><code>Here are my highest-risk assumptions (the ones that would change my\ndecision if wrong):\n\n[paste your KNOW vs ASSUME table]\n\nFor each assumption, write a specific, answerable research question.\nThe question should be concrete enough that I could imagine what a\nuseful answer looks like.\n</code></pre> <p>The scoping rule: 3-5 research questions max per study. More than that and you get shallow answers to everything. If you have 12 questions, you have 3 studies.</p> <pre><code>flowchart LR\n    A[High-risk assumptions] --&gt; B[Research questions]\n    B --&gt; C[Choose methods]\n    C --&gt; D[Define decision framework]\n    D --&gt; E[Execute]\n    E --&gt; F[Decide]</code></pre>"},{"location":"playbooks/user-research/research-design.html#structure-your-research-project-in-claude-code","title":"Structure Your Research Project in Claude Code","text":"<p>Set up your workspace so CC can help at every stage without mixing up your analysis.</p> <pre><code>research-project/\n  CLAUDE.md              # Research context, goals, constraints, segments\n  assumptions.md         # KNOW vs ASSUME table\n  research-plan.md       # Compiled plan with decision framework\n  interviews/\n    interview-guide.md   # Questions, probes, warm-up script\n    survey-draft.md      # Full survey with scales and logic\n  transcripts/           # Raw interview transcripts (one per file)\n  extractions/           # Per-participant structured findings\n  synthesis/\n    themes.md            # Cross-participant patterns\n    evidence-matrix.md   # Claims mapped to evidence\n    stakeholder-brief.md # Final deliverable\n</code></pre> <p>Your research CLAUDE.md should include the research questions, target segments, key assumptions, decision framework, and analysis ground rules. Here's a starter:</p> <pre><code># Research: [Project Name]\n\n## Research Questions\n1. [question]\n2. [question]\n3. [question]\n\n## Target Segments\n- [segment 1]: [definition and recruitment criteria]\n- [segment 2]: [definition and recruitment criteria]\n\n## Decision Framework\n- If we learn [X], we will [Y]\n- If we learn [A], we will [B]\n\n## Analysis Rules\n- Extract from each transcript independently before comparing\n- One extraction file per participant\n- Synthesis happens LAST, from structured extractions only\n</code></pre> <p>Why separation matters: If all your transcripts are in one file, CC will blend voices and find patterns that aren't there. One transcript per file, one extraction per file. Synthesis happens last, from structured extractions, not raw transcripts.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/user-research/research-design.html#design-questions-that-get-truth","title":"Design Questions That Get Truth","text":"<p>Interviews and surveys fail in completely different ways. You need different quality checks for each.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/user-research/research-design.html#for-interviews-the-mom-test","title":"For Interviews: The Mom Test","text":"<p>Three principles for questions that get truth instead of polite agreement:</p> <ol> <li>Past behavior over future hypotheticals. Ask what they did, not what they would do.</li> <li>Their life over your idea. Explore their world before introducing yours.</li> <li>Specifics over generics. Get the story, not the summary.</li> </ol> Scenario  Bad  Good Pricing \"Would you pay $50/month for this?\" \"Walk me through how your team decided to buy [current tool]. What was the budget conversation like?\" Feature validation \"Would a dashboard help you?\" \"Last time you needed to check project status, what did you actually do?\" Churn \"What would make you stay?\" \"Tell me about the last time you almost cancelled a tool subscription. What happened?\" Adoption \"Would your team use this?\" \"When your team adopted [last tool], how did that actually roll out? Who resisted?\" <p>Skill: <code>/mom-test-filter</code> Scans your interview guide against all three Mom Test principles. Flags violations with specific explanations and rewrites them. Run it on any interview guide before going live.</p> <p>After writing your guide, run the filter:</p> <pre><code>Read interview-guide.md and run /mom-test-filter on it. Flag any\nquestions that ask about future behavior, lead with our product\nidea, or ask for generics instead of specifics.\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"playbooks/user-research/research-design.html#for-surveys-different-failure-modes","title":"For Surveys: Different Failure Modes","text":"<p>The Mom Test applies to conversations. Surveys have their own problems:</p> Bias Type  Example  Fix Leading preamble \"Given that AI is transforming work, how important is...\" Drop the preamble entirely Double-barreled \"How satisfied are you with speed and reliability?\" Split into two questions Hypothetical pricing \"Would you pay $X for this?\" Ask about current spending instead Social desirability \"Do you value work-life balance?\" Ask about last week's actual hours Anchoring First option biases all subsequent answers Randomize option order <p>Scale design matters. Use Likert (1-5 agreement) for attitudes, NPS for loyalty benchmarking, forced-rank when you need priorities not just ratings, and open-ended when you don't know the answer space yet.</p> <p>CC is great at spotting double-barreled questions and generating scale options. Ask it directly:</p> <pre><code>Review this survey draft for bias. Check specifically for:\n- Leading preambles that prime a response\n- Double-barreled questions (asking two things at once)\n- Hypothetical pricing questions\n- Questions where social desirability would skew answers\n- Anchoring from option order\n\nFor each issue found, explain why it's a problem and rewrite it.\n</code></pre> <p>CC Limitation</p> <p>CC can catch structural problems (double-barreled, leading) but it can't detect social desirability bias in your specific audience. That requires your domain knowledge of what your participants are likely to overstate or understate.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/user-research/research-design.html#choose-your-methods","title":"Choose Your Methods","text":"Signal You Need Best Method Why CC Helps With \"What's really going on?\" Interviews Uncovers unknown unknowns, context, stories Guide design, transcript analysis \"How common is this?\" Surveys Quantifies across your population Question generation, response analysis \"What do they actually do?\" Behavioral data / logs Removes self-report bias entirely CSV analysis, funnel construction \"How do they talk about it?\" Review mining / forums Natural, unprompted language Scraping, coding, pattern extraction \"What's the landscape?\" Competitive research Positioning, gaps, market shape Web research, battlecard building <p>For review mining, see Competitive Intelligence. For behavioral data analysis, see Analyzing Data.</p> <p>Almost always combine methods. Interviews first to discover, surveys to quantify. The interview tells you what's happening; the survey tells you how common it is.</p> <p>Sample sizes:</p> <ul> <li>Interviews: 5-8 per segment. After about 6 interviews in a segment, you'll hear the same themes repeated. That's your signal to stop.</li> <li>Surveys: 100+ for statistical confidence, more if you're segmenting. The number depends on how many sub-groups you need to compare.</li> </ul> <p>CC makes methods that used to require a research team practical for a solo PM. You can analyze 10 interview transcripts in parallel, code survey responses on the fly, and mine thousands of app reviews in an afternoon. See Interview Analysis and Survey &amp; Feedback Analysis for how to run each one.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/user-research/research-design.html#define-your-decision-framework-before-collecting-data","title":"Define Your Decision Framework Before Collecting Data","text":"<p>This is the most important part of research design and the most often skipped.</p> <p>The rule: Define what you will DO with the answers before you collect them.</p> <p>Use this pattern:</p> <pre><code>If we learn [finding], we will [action].\n</code></pre>  Bad  Good \"We'll analyze the results and decide what to do.\" This isn't a framework. This is a blank check for confirmation bias. Research question: Do enterprise evaluations stall at security review?  Strong signal (&gt;60% stall): Build SSO before Q3. Reprioritize roadmap.  Moderate (30-60%): Ship SSO docs and security whitepaper first. Reassess after.  Weak (&lt;30%): SSO is not the blocker. Investigate other stall points.  Ambiguous: Run 5 targeted interviews with recently churned enterprise prospects. <p>Get stakeholder alignment on the decision framework BEFORE research starts. This prevents the most common failure mode: moving the goalposts after the data comes in.</p> <p>Ask CC to pressure-test your framework:</p> <pre><code>Here's my decision framework for this research:\n\n[paste framework]\n\nChallenge it. Are there findings that wouldn't fit any of these\nbranches? Are the action thresholds specific enough that two people\nwould reach the same conclusion from the same data? What branch\nam I most likely to rationalize my way into?\n</code></pre> <pre><code>flowchart TD\n    F[Research Findings] --&gt; S{Signal Strength}\n    S --&gt;|Strong positive| A1[Proceed with Option A]\n    S --&gt;|Mixed| A2[Narrow scope, targeted follow-up]\n    S --&gt;|Negative| A3[Pivot or kill]\n    S --&gt;|Ambiguous| A4[Define what additional data would clarify]</code></pre> <p>CC Limitation</p> <p>Claude Code will happily help you build a decision framework that lets you justify whatever you already wanted to do. It has no skin in the game. You have to be honest with yourself about what findings would actually change your mind.</p> <p>How much data is \"enough\"? When your decision framework branches are resolving clearly. If every interview points the same direction and your survey confirms it, you're done. Research becomes procrastination when you keep collecting data to avoid making the call.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/user-research/research-design.html#when-research-doesnt-go-as-planned","title":"When Research Doesn't Go as Planned","text":"<p>Real research rarely follows the plan.</p> <p>Early interviews surface something unexpected. You planned to study onboarding friction but every participant keeps talking about billing confusion. Don't ignore it. Add 1-2 questions to your remaining interviews, but don't redesign mid-stream. Note it as a finding and flag it for a follow-up study.</p> <p>Your assumptions turn out to be unanswerable. The data you expected doesn't exist, or participants can't answer the question meaningfully. Reframe the research question, not the whole study. CC makes this cheap:</p> <pre><code>The original research question was: [question]\n\nParticipants can't answer this meaningfully because [reason].\n\nBased on what we've heard so far, reframe this into a question we\nCAN answer with the remaining interviews. Keep the same underlying\ndecision we're trying to make.\n</code></pre> <p>Not enough participants. You got 3 interviews instead of 8. You can still learn from them, you just can't generalize. Be explicit about confidence levels in your synthesis: \"Based on 3 interviews, we observed X. This is directional, not conclusive.\"</p> <pre><code>flowchart LR\n    D[Design] --&gt; E[Execute]\n    E --&gt; N{New assumptions?}\n    N --&gt;|Yes| R[Refine design]\n    R --&gt; E\n    N --&gt;|No| S[Synthesize]\n    S --&gt; DE[Decide]</code></pre> <p>CC Advantage</p> <p>Pivoting is cheap when Claude Code is your research partner. Redesigning an interview guide takes minutes, not days. Reprocessing transcripts with new extraction criteria takes seconds. This changes the cost of getting your initial research design wrong. You can afford to start, learn, and adjust.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/user-research/research-design.html#common-mistakes","title":"Common Mistakes","text":"Mistake Why It Happens What to Do Instead Researching to confirm You already have a preferred answer Write down what finding would make you change your mind. If nothing would, you don't need research No decision framework \"We'll figure it out after\" feels easier Define branches before collecting data. Get stakeholders to sign off Skipping assumption surfacing \"I already know what we need to learn\" You don't. Run <code>/assumption-surfacing</code> for 10 minutes. You'll be surprised Only doing interviews Interviews feel sufficient Interviews tell you what's happening. Surveys tell you how common it is. You usually need both Not defining segments \"Users\" treated as one group Enterprise and SMB have different problems. Segment or your findings will average out to nothing Researching too long Perfectionism disguised as rigor Set a timebox. If your decision framework branches are resolving, stop"},{"location":"playbooks/user-research/research-design.html#plug-play","title":"Plug &amp; Play","text":"<p>These skills ship with the course and work in any research project:</p> <p><code>/assumption-surfacing</code> 10-minute structured interview that surfaces what you're assuming vs. what you know. Works for any decision, not just research.</p> <p><code>/mom-test-filter</code> Scans your interview guide and flags questions that will get polite lies instead of truth. Checks against all three Mom Test principles and rewrites them.</p> <p><code>/research-plan</code> Compiles assumptions, interview/survey designs, and decision criteria into a stakeholder-ready research plan.</p> <p><code>/research-design</code> Full end-to-end pipeline from scratch. Takes a vague prompt and walks you through assumption surfacing, question design, and plan compilation in one session.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/user-research/research-design.html#references","title":"References","text":"<p>Internal:</p> <ul> <li>Interview Analysis :How to extract, code, and verify findings from transcripts</li> <li>Survey &amp; Feedback Analysis :Inductive coding, codebooks, intensity scoring</li> <li>Competitive Intelligence :Web research, review mining, segmentation</li> <li>Research Synthesis :Evidence matrix, contested findings, stakeholder briefs</li> <li>Sub-agents :How parallel extraction works under the hood</li> </ul> <p>External:</p> <ul> <li>Rob Fitzpatrick: How to Talk to Customers (The Mom Test) : Hour-long interview on the core principles</li> <li>The 3 Rules to Customer Interviews from The Mom Test : Quick summary of the framework with examples</li> <li>Teresa Torres: Continuous Discovery Habits : Talk on building research into weekly product cadence</li> <li>The Mom Test by Rob Fitzpatrick : The book (short, practical, essential)</li> <li>Anthropic: Sub-agents : How parallel extraction works under the hood</li> <li>Anthropic: Claude Code best practices : Official guidance on structuring work</li> </ul>"},{"location":"playbooks/user-research/research-synthesis.html","title":"Research Synthesis","text":"<p>Research synthesis is where multiple evidence streams become one recommendation. It is not summarizing your findings. It is forcing them to argue with each other, watching where they agree, and paying close attention to where they fight. The contradictions are the insight.</p> <p>Quick Answer</p> <p>Use this when: You have findings from 2+ research methods (interviews, surveys, competitive intel) and need to produce a recommendation or stakeholder brief.</p> <p>Avoid this when: You only have one data source. Analyze it first with Interview Analysis, Survey &amp; Feedback Analysis, or Competitive Intelligence, then come here.</p> <p>What CC changes: Claude can hold multiple analysis documents in context simultaneously and map them against each other. The evidence matrix, contradiction surfacing, and stakeholder brief generation happen in one session instead of days of slide-building.</p> <p>Default move: Build the evidence matrix first. Map each research question against what each source found. Contradictions become visible immediately.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/user-research/research-synthesis.html#the-arc","title":"The Arc","text":"<p>Research synthesis is the culmination. It ties together everything from the research arc.</p> <pre><code>flowchart LR\n    RD[\"Research\\nDesign\"] --&gt; IA[\"Interview\\nAnalysis\"]\n    IA --&gt; SA[\"Survey &amp;\\nFeedback\"]\n    SA --&gt; CI[\"Competitive\\nIntelligence\"]\n    CI --&gt; RS[\"Research\\nSynthesis\"]\n\n    style RS stroke-width:3px</code></pre> <p>Each upstream method produces a focused analysis document. Synthesis reads all of them and asks: where do these sources converge, and where do they contradict?</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/user-research/research-synthesis.html#the-evidence-matrix","title":"The Evidence Matrix","text":"<p>The evidence matrix is the core artifact. Each row is a research question from your Research Design. Each column is what a specific source found. The final column is a confidence tag.</p> <pre><code>Build an evidence matrix using @evidence-matrix-template.md.\nMap our research questions against what interviews, surveys,\nand competitive data each found. Tag convergence as HIGH\nconfidence and divergence as CONTESTED.\n</code></pre> <p>What it looks like:</p> Research Question Interviews Surveys Competitive Confidence Is there real enterprise demand? \"Need SSO\" but real need is team scaling 68% stated interest Graduation gap exists in market HIGH (all 3 agree demand is real) Would they pay significantly more? Described workarounds (real pain) Only 12% high-intensity Enterprise tools charge 3-5x CONTESTED What features matter most? Permissions, workspace management Security ranked #1 but low intensity SSO is procurement checkbox, not differentiator CONTESTED Competitive positioning? Power users hitting limits N/A Mid-market gap is real HIGH <p>The HIGH-confidence rows are nice. All sources agree. Note them and move on.</p> <p>The CONTESTED rows are where the real insight lives. They are not errors in your research. They are where each method revealed a different facet of the same truth.</p> <pre><code>flowchart TD\n    EM[\"Evidence Matrix\"] --&gt; H{Confidence?}\n    H --&gt;|HIGH| C[\"Convergence\\nAll sources agree\"]\n    H --&gt;|CONTESTED| D[\"Contradiction\\nSources disagree\"]\n    D --&gt; R[\"Resolution:\\nWhy do they disagree?\\nWhat does each method\\nreveal that others miss?\"]\n    R --&gt; I[\"Insight\"]</code></pre>"},{"location":"playbooks/user-research/research-synthesis.html#resolving-contradictions","title":"Resolving Contradictions","text":"<p>Contested findings are not problems to fix. They are puzzles to solve. Each contradiction tells you something a single method could not.</p> <p>Contradiction 1: Interest vs. willingness to pay. 68% say they want enterprise features, but only 12% would actually pay for them. The survey captured stated interest. The intensity analysis revealed that most \"interested\" respondents wouldn't change behavior. Different questions, different answers, both true.</p> <p>Contradiction 2: Stated needs vs. described behaviors. People say \"we need SSO\" but their day-to-day problems are about team permissions and workspace management. Interviews caught the gap between the label people reach for and the problem they actually experience.</p> <p>Contradiction 3: Anti-enterprise users building enterprise workarounds. Power users who say \"don't make this enterprise\" have already built workarounds for enterprise-scale problems. They need the capabilities. They reject the packaging and pricing model.</p> <p>Each contradiction resolves when you ask: what does each method uniquely reveal?</p> Method What It Uniquely Reveals Interviews Gaps between stated needs and described behaviors. The \"why\" behind the \"what.\" Surveys How common a pattern is, and how intensely people feel about it. The scale of the signal. Competitive intel Market structure, pricing norms, and gaps nobody is filling. The landscape context."},{"location":"playbooks/user-research/research-synthesis.html#the-reframing-technique","title":"The Reframing Technique","text":"<p>The most powerful synthesis outcome is when research doesn't answer the original question. It changes the question.</p> <pre><code>flowchart TD\n    Q[\"Original Question:\\nShould we go enterprise?\"] --&gt; SA2[\"Surface Answer:\\nYes, 68% want it\"]\n    SA2 --&gt; RA[\"Real Answer:\\nThe enterprise TIER is wrong.\\nThe enterprise NEED is real\\nbut narrow.\"]\n    RA --&gt; REC[\"Recommendation:\\nBuild team-scaling features\\npriced as a Growth plan\"]</code></pre> <p>The reframing emerges from contradictions:</p> <ul> <li>68% stated interest, but only 12% high-intensity willingness to pay</li> <li>\"Enterprise features\" is not one need; it is four distinct capabilities</li> <li>The signal concentrates in mid-market (50-200 employees), not large enterprise</li> <li>Competitors gate basic team-scaling features behind 3-5x price jumps</li> </ul> <p>The answer is not \"yes, go enterprise\" or \"no, don't.\" It is: build team-scaling features at a growth-plan price point for mid-market companies. Three dimensions (what they need, how real the demand is, who needs it), three sources, one recommendation nobody walked in expecting.</p>  Bad  Good \"Based on our research, 68% of users want enterprise features. We recommend building an enterprise tier.\" \"The enterprise tier is wrong, but the enterprise need is real. 12% of users would pay for team-scaling features (permissions, workspace management, flexible access). Signal concentrates in mid-market (50-200 employees). Recommend a Growth plan at $15-20/seat, not a $50K enterprise contract.\" Answer the original question as asked Reframe the question when evidence demands it Summarize findings from each source Force sources to argue and resolve the contradictions"},{"location":"playbooks/user-research/research-synthesis.html#the-stakeholder-brief","title":"The Stakeholder Brief","text":"<p>The synthesis culminates in a brief you could hand to leadership. Structure it for decision-makers who will read the first paragraph and maybe skim the rest.</p> <p>Lead with the recommendation. Not the process, not the background. The very first thing a busy exec reads is what you think they should do.</p> <pre><code>## Recommendation\n[One paragraph. What to do and why.]\n\n## Evidence Summary\n### Interviews (5 enterprise prospects)\n[2-3 bullet key findings with participant citations]\n\n### Survey (212 responses)\n[2-3 bullet key findings with intensity breakdown]\n\n### Competitive Landscape\n[2-3 bullet key findings with confidence tags]\n\n## Contested Findings\n[What the evidence disagrees on and how you resolved it]\n\n## Financial Implication\n[Revenue estimate, pricing recommendation, sizing]\n\n## What Would Change Our Mind\n[Conditions under which you'd reverse this recommendation]\n</code></pre> <p>The highest-leverage section is \"What Would Change Our Mind.\" It tells leadership you are confident but not dogmatic. You have thought about the conditions under which you would reverse course. That is how you build credibility. You are not selling a conclusion. You are showing that your thinking survives scrutiny.</p> <pre><code>Draft the stakeholder brief using @stakeholder-brief-template.md.\nLead with the recommendation. Pull evidence from\n@interview-analysis.md, @survey-analysis.md,\n@competitive-analysis.md, and @evidence-matrix.md.\nSave to exec-brief.md.\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"playbooks/user-research/research-synthesis.html#the-traceability-chain","title":"The Traceability Chain","text":"<p>Every claim in the stakeholder brief should trace backward through the full research chain.</p> <pre><code>flowchart RL\n    EB[\"Exec Brief\\n(recommendation)\"] --&gt; EM2[\"Evidence Matrix\\n(cross-source mapping)\"]\n    EM2 --&gt; IA2[\"Interview Analysis\\n(per-participant extractions)\"]\n    EM2 --&gt; SA3[\"Survey Analysis\\n(codebook + intensity)\"]\n    EM2 --&gt; CI2[\"Competitive Intel\\n(sourced claims)\"]\n    IA2 --&gt; TR[\"Raw Transcripts\"]\n    SA3 --&gt; CSV[\"Raw Survey Data\"]\n    CI2 --&gt; SRC[\"Primary Sources\"]</code></pre> <p>If your CEO pushes back on any claim, you can walk it back through the evidence matrix, through the per-source analysis, through the raw data. You didn't just get an answer. You built an argument that survives scrutiny.</p> <p>This traceability is why the upstream methods matter. Dump-and-summarize produces a recommendation with no audit trail. The structured process produces one where every decision can be defended.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/user-research/research-synthesis.html#when-you-have-fewer-sources","title":"When You Have Fewer Sources","text":"<p>You don't always have three evidence streams. The methodology scales down.</p> Sources Available What Changes 2 sources (e.g., interviews + surveys) Evidence matrix still works. Fewer columns, fewer contradiction opportunities. Be explicit about confidence levels. 1 source + competitive context You can identify gaps but not validate demand. Frame findings as directional, not conclusive. 1 source only This is analysis, not synthesis. Use Interview Analysis or Survey &amp; Feedback Analysis. Synthesis requires 2+ independent sources. <p>The rule: One source is a hypothesis. Two sources pointing the same direction is a signal. Three sources converging is evidence.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/user-research/research-synthesis.html#common-mistakes","title":"Common Mistakes","text":"Mistake Why It Happens What to Do Instead Summarizing instead of synthesizing Summary is easier than forcing contradictions Build the evidence matrix. Contradictions become visible immediately Burying the recommendation Process-oriented thinking Lead with what you think they should do. Evidence comes second Ignoring contested findings Contradictions feel like failures Contested findings are the insight. Resolve them, don't hide them No \"what would change our mind\" Feels like showing weakness It builds credibility. Dogmatic recommendations get less trust, not more Synthesizing from raw data Feels more thorough Synthesize from per-source analysis documents. Raw data reintroduces noise and risks cross-contamination Moving goalposts after data Uncomfortable findings Lock the decision framework before research starts (see Research Design)"},{"location":"playbooks/user-research/research-synthesis.html#plug-play","title":"Plug &amp; Play","text":"<p><code>/research-synthesis</code> Full synthesis pipeline: evidence matrix construction, contradiction resolution, reframing, and stakeholder brief generation. Takes per-source analysis documents as input.</p> <p><code>/interview-analysis</code> Upstream skill for interview data. Produces the per-participant extractions that feed synthesis.</p> <p><code>/survey-analysis</code> Upstream skill for survey data. Produces the codebook-anchored, intensity-scored analysis that feeds synthesis.</p> <p><code>/competitive-intel</code> Upstream skill for competitive data. Produces sourced, confidence-tagged findings that feed synthesis.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/user-research/research-synthesis.html#references","title":"References","text":"<p>Internal:</p> <ul> <li>Research Design : Where synthesis starts: assumptions, questions, and the decision framework</li> <li>Interview Analysis : Upstream qualitative analysis</li> <li>Survey &amp; Feedback Analysis : Upstream quantitative analysis</li> <li>Competitive Intelligence : Upstream market analysis</li> <li>User Research : Hub page connecting the full research arc</li> </ul> <p>External:</p> <ul> <li>Anthropic: Claude Code best practices : Guidance on structuring complex analytical work</li> <li>Triangulation in Research : Academic primer on combining multiple data sources</li> <li>How to Write an Executive Summary : HBR guidance on writing for decision-makers</li> </ul>"},{"location":"playbooks/user-research/survey-and-feedback-analysis.html","title":"Survey &amp; Feedback Analysis","text":"<p>Survey analysis is about separating signal from noise in quantitative data. The surface numbers always look clean. The real story lives in what people wrote, how strongly they felt about it, and whether their stated interest matches any real willingness to act.</p> <p>Quick Answer</p> <p>Use this when: You have survey responses, NPS open-ends, support tickets, app store reviews, or any volume of structured + open-ended feedback to analyze.</p> <p>Avoid this when: You have interview transcripts or long-form conversations. That's Interview Analysis.</p> <p>What CC changes: Claude can code responses on the fly without bringing preconceptions. Inductive coding, codebook application, and intensity scoring run in minutes instead of days. But without explicit methodology, Claude will give you confident summaries that hide the most important findings.</p> <p>Default move: Never start with \"give me the key takeaways.\" Start with inductive coding on the open-ended responses. Let categories emerge from the data.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/user-research/survey-and-feedback-analysis.html#three-ways-llms-fail-at-survey-data","title":"Three Ways LLMs Fail at Survey Data","text":"<p>Every technique in this playbook exists to patch a specific failure mode. Know the failures first.</p> <pre><code>flowchart TD\n    S[\"Survey Data\"] --&gt; F1[\"Failure 1:\\nAverages hide\\ndistributions\"]\n    S --&gt; F2[\"Failure 2:\\nPreset categories\\nmiss what's there\"]\n    S --&gt; F3[\"Failure 3:\\nCheckbox = commitment\\n(it doesn't)\"]\n\n    F1 --&gt; P1[\"Fix: Distribution\\nanalysis\"]\n    F2 --&gt; P2[\"Fix: Inductive\\ncoding\"]\n    F3 --&gt; P3[\"Fix: Intensity\\nscoring\"]</code></pre> <p>1. Averages hide distributions. \"3.8/5 satisfaction\" could mean everyone is lukewarm, or half love it and half hate it. Very different problems, very different actions. Claude loves averages. Averages love hiding things.</p> <p>2. Preset categories miss what's actually there. If you designed a question with 6 options, you get 6 results back. The need you didn't think to ask about? Invisible. Claude will sort into your categories without questioning whether they're the right ones.</p> <p>3. Checking a box is not the same as willingness to act. Someone ticking \"interested\" between meetings and someone writing three paragraphs about restructuring their workflow look identical in a top-line summary. But one might pay 3x for the feature, and the other won't remember they checked the box.</p>  Bad  Good \"68% of respondents expressed interest in enterprise features\" \"68% stated interest. 12% described specific workflow impacts and willingness to pay. The other 56% checked a box.\" \"Average satisfaction is 3.8 out of 5\" \"Satisfaction is bimodal: 40% rate 4-5, 35% rate 1-2. The 3.8 average masks a polarized user base.\" \"Top requested feature: team management\" \"Team management ranked #1, but inductive coding reveals 4 distinct needs hiding under that label: workspace organization, permissions, portfolio visibility, and flexible pricing\""},{"location":"playbooks/user-research/survey-and-feedback-analysis.html#the-process","title":"The Process","text":"<p>Four phases. Each one patches a specific failure mode.</p> <pre><code>flowchart LR\n    IC[\"Inductive\\nCoding\"] --&gt; CB[\"Codebook\\nConstruction\"]\n    CB --&gt; IS[\"Intensity\\nScoring\"]\n    IS --&gt; CA[\"Cross-tab\\nAnalysis\"]</code></pre>"},{"location":"playbooks/user-research/survey-and-feedback-analysis.html#phase-1-inductive-coding","title":"Phase 1: Inductive Coding","text":"<p>Let the data tell you the categories. Read the open-ended responses first and tag themes as you find them. No preset buckets.</p> <p>This is the opposite of the default approach, where you start with your categories and count how many responses land in each one. Inductive coding starts from the raw text and lets patterns emerge.</p> <p>Two passes:</p> <ol> <li>Discovery pass: Read responses, tag themes as they appear. Don't merge yet.</li> <li>Consolidation pass: Merge overlapping codes, sharpen definitions, resolve boundary cases.</li> </ol> <p>Two passes prevent you from jumping to categories too early.</p> <pre><code>Run an inductive coding pass on the open-ended responses in\n@survey-responses.csv using @inductive-coding-guide.md.\nNo preset categories. Read what people wrote and propose the\ncodes you find. For each code: name, one-line definition,\nand 2-3 example quotes. Save results to inductive-coding-results.md.\n</code></pre> <p>What emerges: Codes the survey didn't have categories for. In enterprise research, \"enterprise features\" might split into Security &amp; Compliance, Team Permissions, Reporting &amp; Visibility, and Flexible Pricing. Plus unexpected codes like Migration Fear (too costly to switch) or Champion Frustration (loves the product, can't justify it internally).</p>  Bad  Good Sort responses into the survey's existing categories Let codes emerge from what people actually wrote \"Enterprise features\" as one bucket 4 distinct needs hiding under the enterprise label, plus 2 codes the survey never anticipated Skip the open-ended fields, focus on Likert scores Open-ended fields contain the signal Likert scores flatten <p>CC Advantage</p> <p>Claude approaches each response without the preconceptions a human coder brings after the first 20 responses. It will not unconsciously steer toward the categories it \"expects\" to find. That said, give it an inductive coding guide as methodology reference, or it will default to generic categories from its training data.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/user-research/survey-and-feedback-analysis.html#phase-2-codebook-construction","title":"Phase 2: Codebook Construction","text":"<p>Codes need definitions precise enough that two people (or two Claude sessions) would categorize the same response the same way. A codebook formalizes: definition, inclusion criteria, exclusion criteria, and boundary examples.</p> <p>What a codebook entry looks like:</p> <pre><code>## Security &amp; Compliance\n\n**Definition:** Responses describing security requirements, compliance needs,\nor procurement blockers related to security review processes.\n\n**Include when:**\n- Response mentions SOC2, SCIM, SAML, audit logs, session management\n- Response describes security review as a blocker to expansion or purchase\n- SSO mentioned in context of IT/procurement requirements\n\n**Exclude when:**\n- SSO mentioned in context of managing team access (\u2192 Team Permissions)\n- General mention of \"security\" without specific requirements\n\n**Boundary example:**\n\"Our IT team needs SSO before they'll approve expanding licenses\"\n\u2192 Security &amp; Compliance (it's a procurement blocker)\n\n\"Managing who has access to what project through SSO\"\n\u2192 Team Permissions (it's a workspace management need)\n</code></pre> <p>Same three letters (SSO), completely different problems. Without boundary definitions, both responses land in the same bucket. And Claude is the worst offender. Ask it to code today, it puts SSO under Security. Ask tomorrow, it might put it under Team Permissions. The codebook fixes that.</p> <p>Why codebooks matter for CC: Claude's categorization drifts between sessions. A codebook anchors it. Same definitions, same boundaries, every session. Run it once or run it a hundred times, the categorization stays consistent because the reference file travels with the prompt.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/user-research/survey-and-feedback-analysis.html#phase-3-intensity-scoring","title":"Phase 3: Intensity Scoring","text":"<p>This is the technique that turns \"68% interested\" into something useful. Three levels, based on whether someone described specific, concrete impacts on their work.</p> Level Definition Signal HIGH Specific details, described workflow impact, numbers or timelines, willingness to pay or switch This person would change behavior MEDIUM Some detail, general interest expressed, but no urgency or concrete impact described This person has an opinion, not a plan LOW Checkbox only, blank or minimal open-end, no specifics, no described behavior This person was filling out a survey <p>The key distinction: HIGH-intensity responses describe what would actually change. Not \"this would be nice\" but \"here's specifically how this would affect my team's workflow, and here's what I'd pay for it.\" Specifics and described impact. That is the signal.</p> <p>Contrasting examples from real data:</p> HIGH Intensity LOW Intensity Response \"Security review is the single reason we haven't expanded from 15 seats to the full 120-person engineering org. Our IT team needs SCIM provisioning, session management controls, and SOC2 Type II. I've literally been maintaining a spreadsheet of who has access to what because your permission model is too basic.\" \"Better permissions would be useful for managing contractors.\" Likert score 5 (Very interested) 4 (Interested) What it means Would restructure team and pay more tomorrow General interest, no specifics, no behavior change signal <p>Both people checked \"interested.\" A top-line summary makes them look identical. Intensity scoring separates them.</p> <p>Build an <code>intensity-calibration.md</code> reference with worked examples for each level, so the scoring stays consistent across sessions. Same principle as the codebook: definitions with examples beat vibes.</p> <pre><code>Apply intensity scoring to all enterprise-interest responses using\n@intensity-calibration.md. Cross-reference Likert scores with\nopen-ended response quality. Classify each respondent as\nHIGH, MEDIUM, or LOW intensity. Save to survey-analysis.md.\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"playbooks/user-research/survey-and-feedback-analysis.html#phase-4-cross-tab-analysis","title":"Phase 4: Cross-tab Analysis","text":"<p>Now segment. Intensity tells you how real the signal is. Demographics tell you who it's coming from.</p> <pre><code>Segment the HIGH-intensity respondents by company size.\nShow me where the signal is coming from.\n</code></pre> <p>The reveal: When you cross-tab intensity with company size, the picture changes completely. The \"68% want enterprise\" headline might become:</p> <pre><code>HIGH-INTENSITY BY COMPANY SIZE\n\n1-50 employees      \u2588\u2588               8%\n51-200 employees    \u2588\u2588\u2588\u2588\u2588\u2588\u2588\u2588\u2588\u2588\u2588\u2588\u2588\u2588  58%\n201-500 employees   \u2588\u2588\u2588\u2588\u2588\u2588          25%\n500+ employees      \u2588\u2588               9%\n</code></pre> <p>The signal comes from mid-market, not large enterprise. That changes what you build, what you charge, and who you sell to.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/user-research/survey-and-feedback-analysis.html#stated-vs-revealed-the-pattern","title":"Stated vs. Revealed: The Pattern","text":"<p>This is the same pattern that appears in Interview Analysis, just in quantitative data.</p> Qualitative (Interviews) Quantitative (Surveys) Stated \"We need SSO\" \"Interested in enterprise\" (68%) Revealed Workflow never touched authentication No specifics, no described behavior change (56%) Surface answer hid The real need The intensity gap <p>What people SAY and what they'd actually DO are different questions. Each requires different analytical techniques to separate.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/user-research/survey-and-feedback-analysis.html#beyond-surveys-where-this-applies","title":"Beyond Surveys: Where This Applies","text":"<p>The inductive coding + codebook + intensity framework works on any open-ended data at volume:</p> <ul> <li>NPS open-ends : Why detractors detract, why promoters promote</li> <li>Support tickets : Recurring pain points, emerging issues</li> <li>App store reviews : What users praise and complain about in their own words</li> <li>Sales call notes : Objections, feature requests, competitive mentions</li> <li>Feature request logs : What people ask for vs. what they describe needing</li> </ul> <p>The pattern is always the same: let codes emerge from the data, anchor them with a codebook, score intensity, separate what people said from what they'd actually do.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/user-research/survey-and-feedback-analysis.html#common-mistakes","title":"Common Mistakes","text":"Mistake Why It Happens What to Do Instead Leading with top-line percentages Feels like real analysis Lead with intensity breakdown. Top-line numbers hide the story Preset categories for open-ended data Survey already has categories Let codes emerge inductively. The survey's categories are what YOU thought to ask about Skipping the codebook \"The codes are obvious\" They drift between sessions. Codebook anchors categorization Treating Likert scores as intensity Scale position feels like strength Someone rating 5 who wrote nothing is LOW intensity. Score on behavioral specificity, not scale position Analyzing without segmentation \"Users\" treated as one group Company size, role, plan type all change the picture. Segment before concluding No calibration reference for intensity \"I'll know HIGH when I see it\" You won't be consistent. Build a reference with worked examples"},{"location":"playbooks/user-research/survey-and-feedback-analysis.html#plug-play","title":"Plug &amp; Play","text":"<p><code>/survey-analysis</code> Full pipeline: inductive coding, codebook application, intensity scoring, cross-tab analysis, stated-vs-revealed gap analysis. Point it at a CSV and it runs the whole process.</p> <p><code>/interview-extraction</code> If your \"survey\" includes long-form responses that read more like interview transcripts, use parallel extraction instead. One agent per response.</p>"},{"location":"playbooks/user-research/survey-and-feedback-analysis.html#references","title":"References","text":"<p>Internal:</p> <ul> <li>Interview Analysis : Qualitative analysis of conversations (the complement to survey analysis)</li> <li>Research Design : Designing surveys that produce analyzable data</li> <li>Research Synthesis : Combining survey findings with other evidence streams</li> <li>Competitive Intelligence : Inductive coding applied to competitor review data</li> </ul> <p>External:</p> <ul> <li>Anthropic: Claude Code best practices : Official guidance on structuring analytical work</li> <li>UX Research Methods: A Practical Guide : Covers survey design and analysis fundamentals</li> <li>How to Analyze Open-Ended Survey Questions : Practical guide to coding open-ended responses</li> </ul>"},{"location":"reference/index.html","title":"Reference","text":"<p>Opinionated guides to Claude Code's core concepts, framed for product managers.</p> <p>The Reference section breaks down every major Claude Code capability into standalone guides. Each one explains what the feature is, why it matters for PM work, and how to use it effectively. These are not generic docs. They're written through the lens of how PMs actually work.</p>"},{"location":"reference/index.html#whats-here","title":"What's here","text":"<ul> <li> <p> CLAUDE.md</p> <p>The configuration file that tells Claude who you are, what you're working on, and how to behave. Your most important file.</p> </li> <li> <p> Context Management</p> <p>How Claude's context window works and how to keep it clean. The skill that separates casual users from power users.</p> </li> <li> <p> Sub-agents</p> <p>Spawn separate Claude sessions for heavy lifting. Keep your main context lean while delegating research, analysis, and validation.</p> </li> <li> <p> Plan Mode</p> <p>Make Claude think before it acts. Plan mode forces deliberate reasoning on complex, multi-step tasks.</p> </li> <li> <p> Skills</p> <p>Teach Claude repeatable workflows with slash commands. Five skill types, building techniques, maintenance patterns.</p> </li> <li> <p> Connections</p> <p>Connect Claude to external tools: CLIs, MCP servers, and APIs. Stop being the middleman between your tools.</p> </li> <li> <p> Customization</p> <p>Hooks, settings, permissions, and visual tweaks. Make Claude Code work the way you think.</p> </li> </ul>"},{"location":"reference/ask-user-question.html","title":"AskUserQuestion","text":"<p>Interactive workflows \u2014 how Claude Code can ask you questions mid-task to get better results.</p> <p>Coming Soon</p> <p>This guide is under development. Check back soon.</p>"},{"location":"reference/claude-md.html","title":"CLAUDE.md","text":"<p>Your AI teammate has amnesia. Every session, it forgets everything: your role, the project, the constraints, how you like things done. CLAUDE.md fixes that. It's an onboarding document that loads automatically before you type a single word, so Claude shows up already knowing who you are and what you're working on.</p> <p>Quick answer</p> <p>Use this when: You want Claude Code to remember your project context, rules, and preferences across sessions</p> <p>Avoid this when: You need task-specific context for a single session (use <code>@file</code> or Skills instead)</p> <p>What CC changes: Without CLAUDE.md, you re-explain everything every session. With it, Claude shows up already briefed on your project, your standards, and your workflow</p> <p>Default move: Start with 10-20 lines (project name, stack, validation commands). Grow it from friction, not imagination</p> <p>Here's what a minimal one looks like:</p> <pre><code># Acme Dashboard\n\nB2B analytics dashboard for mid-market SaaS companies.\nReact 18 + TypeScript frontend, Python FastAPI backend, PostgreSQL.\n\n## Key directories\n- `src/components/` \u2014 shared UI components\n- `src/features/` \u2014 feature-specific modules\n- `api/` \u2014 FastAPI routes and services\n- `tests/` \u2014 pytest suite\n\n## Validation\n- Tests: `pytest tests/ -v`\n- Lint: `npm run lint`\n- Build: `npm run build`\n\n## Rules\n- Always create a git branch before making changes\n- Run tests before committing\n- Use existing component patterns \u2014 check src/components/ first\n</code></pre> <p>That's 20 lines. It takes Claude from \"what project is this?\" to \"I know what this is, how it's built, and how to verify my work.\" Every single session, automatically.</p> <p>This guide covers how to write a good one, what to put in it, what to leave out, and the PM-specific patterns that make it actually useful.</p>"},{"location":"reference/claude-md.html#the-mental-model","title":"The mental model","text":"<p>CLAUDE.md is not a configuration file. It's not a prompt. It's onboarding documentation for an AI teammate that starts fresh every day.</p> <p>Think about it this way: every morning, a brilliant contractor shows up at your desk. They can do anything you ask. But they have no memory of yesterday. No memory of your codebase, your team, your product, your preferences, your users. You have to re-explain everything, every time.</p> <p>CLAUDE.md is the briefing packet you hand them when they walk in. The better the packet, the faster they're productive. A bad one (or none at all) means you spend the first 10 minutes of every session re-explaining context that should be automatic.</p> <p>For PMs, this is the lever. More powerful than any individual prompt you'll ever write. A good CLAUDE.md means Claude already knows your personas, your quality standards, your preferred document formats, and your product's architecture before you ask it anything.</p> <p>The core promise</p> <p>Write it once, Claude knows it forever. Every session. Automatically.</p>"},{"location":"reference/claude-md.html#the-thinking-room-trade-off","title":"The thinking room trade-off","text":"<p>Here's the catch: CLAUDE.md loads into Claude's context window with every message. Every line you add is a line Claude has to process, and a line less available for actual reasoning.</p> <p>Hannah Stulberg nailed this: \"More context loaded = less room to think = lower quality output.\"</p> <p>The numbers:</p> <ul> <li>CLAUDE.md loads with every single API call, including the warmup when you start a session</li> <li>If your CLAUDE.md eats 10-15% of the context window before you type anything, it's too big</li> <li>Anthropic recommends keeping it under ~500 lines</li> <li>Boris Cherny targets ~2,500 tokens</li> <li>HumanLayer's research found a hard ceiling: frontier LLMs follow roughly 150-200 instructions with consistency. Claude Code's system prompt already uses ~50 of those. Your actual budget is about 100 instructions. Smaller models degrade exponentially; larger ones degrade linearly, but the ceiling exists either way</li> <li>One user discovered a single word \"thanks\" at the end of a session cost 7% of their quota because the entire context (including CLAUDE.md) gets reprocessed</li> </ul> <p>There's another wrinkle. Claude Code injects a system message that literally says: \"this context may or may not be relevant to your tasks.\" Claude is told to actively discount CLAUDE.md content that doesn't seem universally applicable. So task-specific guidance buried in CLAUDE.md gets deprioritized by design. Another reason to keep it general and move the specifics to Skills.</p> <p>You want Claude to know everything. But everything has a cost. That's the tension.</p> <p>The rule: Include what Claude needs for the current session's work. Move everything else to Skills (which load on-demand) or reference files (which load only when called with <code>@</code>).</p> <p>Think of it as the difference between what goes on your desk vs what goes in your filing cabinet. CLAUDE.md is the desk. Keep it clean.</p>"},{"location":"reference/claude-md.html#the-memory-hierarchy","title":"The memory hierarchy","text":"<p>CLAUDE.md isn't one file. It's a stack of files that load in order, from broadest to most specific:</p> <pre><code>flowchart TD\n    A[\"\ud83c\udfe2 Enterprise / System&lt;br/&gt;&lt;code&gt;/etc/claude-code/CLAUDE.md&lt;/code&gt;\"] --&gt; B\n    B[\"\ud83d\udc64 User / Global&lt;br/&gt;&lt;code&gt;~/.claude/CLAUDE.md&lt;/code&gt;\"] --&gt; C\n    C[\"\ud83d\udc64 User Rules&lt;br/&gt;&lt;code&gt;~/.claude/rules/*.md&lt;/code&gt;\"] --&gt; D\n    D[\"\ud83d\udcc1 Project&lt;br/&gt;&lt;code&gt;./CLAUDE.md&lt;/code&gt;\"] --&gt; E\n    E[\"\ud83d\udcc1 Project Rules&lt;br/&gt;&lt;code&gt;.claude/rules/*.md&lt;/code&gt;\"] --&gt; F\n    F[\"\ud83d\udcc2 Directory&lt;br/&gt;&lt;code&gt;subfolder/CLAUDE.md&lt;/code&gt;\"] --&gt; G\n    G[\"\ud83d\udd12 Local Override&lt;br/&gt;&lt;code&gt;CLAUDE.local.md&lt;/code&gt;\"] --&gt; H\n    H[\"\ud83e\udde0 Auto Memory&lt;br/&gt;&lt;code&gt;~/.claude/projects/.../MEMORY.md&lt;/code&gt;\"]\n\n    style A fill:#1e293b,color:#f8fafc,stroke:#374151\n    style B fill:#1e293b,color:#f8fafc,stroke:#374151\n    style C fill:#1e293b,color:#f8fafc,stroke:#374151\n    style D fill:#e63f02,color:#fff,stroke:#b43200\n    style E fill:#e63f02,color:#fff,stroke:#b43200\n    style F fill:#374151,color:#f8fafc,stroke:#4b5563\n    style G fill:#374151,color:#f8fafc,stroke:#4b5563\n    style H fill:#374151,color:#f8fafc,stroke:#4b5563</code></pre> <p>More specific always wins. A rule in your project's <code>.claude/rules/testing.md</code> overrides a conflicting rule in your user-level <code>~/.claude/CLAUDE.md</code>. A directory-level CLAUDE.md in <code>src/api/</code> overrides the root CLAUDE.md for files in that directory.</p>"},{"location":"reference/claude-md.html#what-pms-actually-need-to-know","title":"What PMs actually need to know","text":"<p>Most PMs will use three of these:</p> Level File What goes here User-level <code>~/.claude/CLAUDE.md</code> Your personal preferences: communication style, formatting, role context. Travels with you across projects. Project-level <code>./CLAUDE.md</code> The main one. Project context, tech stack, validation commands, team rules. Version controlled in git. Local override <code>CLAUDE.local.md</code> Your personal project preferences that shouldn't be in git. Things like \"I'm the PM on this team\" or API keys for your local dev environment. Gitignored by default. <p>The enterprise level matters if your company deploys org-wide standards. Directory-level matters for large monorepos. But for most PM work, project-level CLAUDE.md is where 90% of the value lives.</p>"},{"location":"reference/claude-md.html#what-goes-in","title":"What goes in","text":"<p>The three-section framework that works for any project:</p>"},{"location":"reference/claude-md.html#1-the-what-project-context","title":"1. The \"What\": project context","text":"<p>What this project is, how it's built, where things live. Claude needs this to navigate your codebase and make appropriate decisions.</p> <pre><code># TaskFlow\n\nB2B SaaS for team task management. 3,200 paying customers,\nprimarily 10-50 person teams in tech and professional services.\n\n## Tech stack\n- Frontend: React 18 + TypeScript, Tailwind CSS\n- Backend: Python FastAPI, SQLAlchemy ORM\n- Database: PostgreSQL 15\n- Infra: AWS (ECS, RDS, S3), deployed via Terraform\n\n## Key directories\n- `app/api/` \u2014 API routes (one file per resource)\n- `app/models/` \u2014 SQLAlchemy models\n- `app/services/` \u2014 business logic (never in routes)\n- `web/src/features/` \u2014 React feature modules\n- `web/src/components/` \u2014 shared UI components\n</code></pre> <p>Keep this section factual and scannable. Bullet points and tables over paragraphs. Claude doesn't need a narrative about your company history. It needs to know what's in <code>app/services/</code> and why.</p>"},{"location":"reference/claude-md.html#2-the-domain-what-makes-your-product-unique","title":"2. The \"Domain\": what makes your product unique","text":"<p>The context that shapes how Claude thinks about your product. This is where PMs add the most value. Nobody else on the team is going to write this.</p> <pre><code>## Users\n- **Team Leads** \u2014 power users, manage task workflows, care about visibility\n- **Individual Contributors** \u2014 daily active, care about speed and simplicity\n- **Admins** \u2014 configure integrations, manage permissions, care about control\n\n## Product principles\n- Speed over features \u2014 if it's slow, it doesn't matter what it does\n- Progressive disclosure \u2014 simple by default, powerful when needed\n- Team-first \u2014 every feature should make the team better, not just individuals\n\n## Current focus\n- Q1: Enterprise permissions overhaul (SOC2 compliance driver)\n- Active experiment: simplified invite flow (31% \u2192 target 50% completion)\n</code></pre> <p>This section is the PM's home turf. Nobody else on the team writes this stuff. And when Claude knows your personas, your principles, and your current focus, the output quality changes completely. Compare a PRD written with this context to one without. You'll never go back.</p>"},{"location":"reference/claude-md.html#3-the-validation-how-to-verify-work","title":"3. The \"Validation\": how to verify work","text":"<p>The single most impactful thing you can put in CLAUDE.md. Give Claude a way to check its own work, and quality jumps 2-3x.</p> <pre><code>## Validation\nBefore completing any task, verify:\n- Tests pass: `pytest tests/ -v`\n- Lint clean: `npm run lint`\n- Build succeeds: `npm run build`\n- If UI change: take a screenshot and describe what changed\n</code></pre> <p>John Kim said it best: \"If there's one tip that matters more than the other 49, it's this: give Claude a way to verify its own work.\"</p> <p>Even for non-code PM work, validation rules matter:</p> <pre><code>## Validation (PM workspace)\nBefore completing any document:\n- Does it have measurable success criteria? (not just \"improve X\")\n- Are assumptions explicitly stated?\n- Is there a \"what would change my mind\" section?\n- Run through anti-AI writing checklist\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"reference/claude-md.html#pm-specific-additions","title":"PM-specific additions","text":"<p>Beyond the three sections, PMs should consider:</p> Content Why it matters Example Decision frameworks Claude applies YOUR prioritization logic \"Use RICE scoring. Default weights: Reach 30%, Impact 30%, Confidence 20%, Effort 20%\" Output format preferences Consistent document style \"PRDs follow this structure: Problem \u2192 Users \u2192 Goals \u2192 Non-goals \u2192 Solution \u2192 Success Metrics \u2192 Risks\" Quality standards Calibrates \"done\" \"Success criteria must be measurable. 'Improve retention' is not acceptable. '85% 30-day retention for Growth plan' is.\" Team context Better stakeholder awareness \"VP of Eng (Sarah) cares about technical debt. CEO (Marcus) wants everything quantified.\" Anti-patterns Prevent bad habits \"Never present a single recommendation. Always model 3 options with tradeoffs.\""},{"location":"reference/claude-md.html#what-stays-out","title":"What stays out","text":"<p>Everything that doesn't need to load every session should live somewhere else.</p>"},{"location":"reference/claude-md.html#move-to-skills-load-on-demand","title":"Move to Skills (load on-demand)","text":"<p>Skills are markdown files in <code>.claude/skills/</code> that Claude reads only when triggered. They're the filing cabinet: detailed reference material that would bloat your CLAUDE.md but is invaluable when needed.</p> CLAUDE.md says Skill handles \"We do user research using the Mom Test framework\" The full research methodology: question templates, analysis rubrics, synthesis framework \"PRDs follow our standard format\" The complete PRD template with examples, anti-patterns, and review checklist \"Use RICE for prioritization\" The full RICE scoring system with worked examples and edge cases <p>The migration path is simple: when a section of your CLAUDE.md grows past 20-30 lines on a single topic, move it to a Skill. CLAUDE.md keeps the one-liner reference (\"We use RICE\"), the Skill has the details.</p>"},{"location":"reference/claude-md.html#move-to-reference-files-load-with","title":"Move to reference files (load with @)","text":"<p>Any file Claude can read with <code>@path/to/file.md</code> doesn't need to be in CLAUDE.md. Use <code>@</code> for:</p> <ul> <li>Detailed specs or requirements docs</li> <li>Meeting notes or research transcripts</li> <li>Data files or analysis results</li> <li>Anything that's relevant to one task but not every task</li> </ul>"},{"location":"reference/claude-md.html#the-official-includeexclude-list","title":"The official include/exclude list","text":"<p>Anthropic's own guidance on what belongs and what doesn't:</p> Include Exclude Bash commands Claude can't guess Anything Claude can figure out by reading code Code style rules that differ from defaults Standard language conventions Claude already knows Testing instructions and preferred test runners Detailed API documentation (link to docs instead) Repository etiquette (branch naming, PR conventions) Information that changes frequently Architectural decisions specific to your project Long explanations or tutorials Developer environment quirks (required env vars) File-by-file descriptions of the codebase Common gotchas or non-obvious behaviors Self-evident practices like \"write clean code\" <p>The pattern: include what Claude can't infer from the code itself. Exclude what it can.</p>"},{"location":"reference/claude-md.html#the-bloat-warning-signs","title":"The bloat warning signs","text":"<p>Your CLAUDE.md is too big if:</p> <ul> <li><code>/context</code> shows it consuming more than 10-15% before you type</li> <li>You're scrolling to find things in it</li> <li>It contains full templates instead of references to templates</li> <li>There's narrative explaining why decisions were made (Claude needs the decision, not the history)</li> <li>You have paragraphs where bullet points would work</li> </ul> <p>Shrivu Shankar put it well: \"Keeping your CLAUDE.md as short as possible is a fantastic forcing function for simplifying your codebase and internal tooling.\"</p>"},{"location":"reference/claude-md.html#the-5-section-structure-for-pms","title":"The 5-section structure for PMs","text":"<p>If you're building a PM workspace (not just working in a codebase), this structure works. It's designed so Claude can orient from CLAUDE.md alone, without you explaining anything.</p> <pre><code># [Your Name] \u2014 [Role] at [Company]\n\n## Who I am\nSenior PM on the Growth team at TaskFlow. I own the self-serve\nfunnel (signup \u2192 activation \u2192 expansion) and the Growth plan tier.\nDirect report to VP Product (Sarah Chen).\n\n## What I own\n- **Growth plan** \u2014 $1.2M ARR, 3,200 customers, 98% retention\n- **Self-serve funnel** \u2014 signup, onboarding, invite flow, activation\n- **Active experiment** \u2014 simplified invite flow (target: 31% \u2192 50% completion)\n- **Quarterly goal** \u2014 15% expansion revenue increase by Q2 end\n\n## How this workspace works\n- `Projects/` \u2014 one folder per active project, each with a brief.md\n- `Knowledge/` \u2014 company context, product docs, People/ profiles\n- `Tasks/` \u2014 active.md (current), backlog.md (future)\n- `Templates/` \u2014 reusable document templates\n- `.claude/skills/` \u2014 PM skills (standup, meeting-prep, prd, status-update)\n\n## Available skills\n- `/standup` \u2014 morning briefing from GOALS.md + Tasks/ + project activity\n- `/meeting-prep [person]` \u2014 pre-meeting brief from People/ profiles\n- `/prd` \u2014 guided PRD creation (interviews you first, then generates)\n- `/status-update` \u2014 weekly update from project context\n\n## Current focus\n- **This week:** Finalize invite flow experiment design, prep board deck\n- **Blocked on:** Waiting for Data team to instrument invite_accepted event\n- **Key risk:** Growth plan retention (98%) is based on n=9 \u2014 not enough signal\n</code></pre> <p>The test: Start a fresh Claude session in this workspace and ask \"what am I working on?\" If Claude answers correctly from CLAUDE.md alone, you're done. If it can't, your CLAUDE.md is missing something.</p>"},{"location":"reference/claude-md.html#modular-organization","title":"Modular organization","text":"<p>As your CLAUDE.md grows, break it apart. You have two tools for this.</p>"},{"location":"reference/claude-md.html#imports","title":"@imports","text":"<p>Pull content from other files into CLAUDE.md:</p> <pre><code># TaskFlow PM Workspace\n\n@Knowledge/company.md\n@Knowledge/product.md\n@.claude/rules/writing-standards.md\n\n## Current focus\n...\n</code></pre> <p>Claude reads the imported files as if they were part of CLAUDE.md. This keeps your root file clean: a table of contents, not a wall of text.</p>"},{"location":"reference/claude-md.html#clauderules","title":".claude/rules/","text":"<p>Modular rule files that auto-load alongside CLAUDE.md:</p> <pre><code>.claude/rules/\n\u251c\u2500\u2500 writing-standards.md    # Anti-AI rules, voice guidelines\n\u251c\u2500\u2500 document-format.md      # PRD structure, one-pager format\n\u251c\u2500\u2500 product-principles.md   # Decision frameworks, quality standards\n\u2514\u2500\u2500 testing.md              # Validation requirements\n</code></pre> <p>Each file can be scoped to specific file types using YAML frontmatter:</p> <pre><code>---\ndescription: TypeScript component conventions\nglobs: [\"*.tsx\", \"*.ts\"]\nalwaysApply: true\n---\n\nUse functional components with hooks. No class components.\nImport shared components from @/components before creating new ones.\n</code></pre> <p>Rules scoped with <code>globs</code> only load when Claude is working with matching files. This saves context for everything else.</p>"},{"location":"reference/claude-md.html#when-to-split-vs-keep-together","title":"When to split vs keep together","text":"<p>Keep in root CLAUDE.md:</p> <ul> <li>Project overview (5-10 lines)</li> <li>Directory structure</li> <li>Validation commands</li> <li>Current focus / active work</li> </ul> <p>Move to .claude/rules/:</p> <ul> <li>Style guides and conventions</li> <li>Document format requirements</li> <li>Domain-specific rules (one file per domain)</li> <li>Team-specific guidelines (PM rules vs engineering rules)</li> </ul> <p>Move to @imports:</p> <ul> <li>Persona documents</li> <li>Product specs</li> <li>Company context that rarely changes</li> </ul>"},{"location":"reference/claude-md.html#creating-your-first-claudemd","title":"Creating your first CLAUDE.md","text":"<p>Pick whichever fits where you are right now.</p>"},{"location":"reference/claude-md.html#method-1-let-claude-scan-the-project","title":"Method 1: Let Claude scan the project","text":"<p>Already have a codebase? Run <code>/init</code>. Claude reads your project structure, package files, README, and existing docs, then generates a starting CLAUDE.md.</p> <p>It's a solid starting point. But it only captures what's in the code, not what's in your head. Always review and add the PM context (personas, principles, quality standards) that Claude can't infer.</p>"},{"location":"reference/claude-md.html#method-2-have-claude-interview-you","title":"Method 2: Have Claude interview you","text":"<p>Start a session and say:</p> <p>\"Ask me 5 questions that would help you have a complete understanding of this project and how I work.\"</p> <p>Claude asks about your role, your goals, what \"done\" looks like, what mistakes to avoid. Your answers become the CLAUDE.md. This works especially well for new workspaces where there's no existing code to scan.</p> <p>Allie K. Miller's version is even broader: \"Have Claude interview you, NOT about the project at hand, but who YOU are.\" Your role, your communication style, how you think about quality. This goes in your user-level <code>~/.claude/CLAUDE.md</code> and travels with you across every project.</p>"},{"location":"reference/claude-md.html#method-3-start-from-scratch-and-grow","title":"Method 3: Start from scratch and grow","text":"<p>Write the minimum viable CLAUDE.md: project name, tech stack, validation commands. Maybe 10 lines. Start working. When Claude does something wrong, add a rule. When you repeat yourself, capture it. When you explain context for the third time, write it down.</p> <p>Boris Cherny (core Claude Code team) does this: \"My setup might be surprisingly vanilla. Claude Code works great out of the box, so I personally don't customize it much.\"</p> <p>The best CLAUDE.md files aren't designed. They're grown from real friction. Start small. Add when you feel pain.</p>"},{"location":"reference/claude-md.html#the-quick-add-shortcut","title":"The quick-add shortcut","text":"<p>Mid-conversation, type <code>#</code> followed by a rule:</p> <pre><code># When creating React components, always add a Storybook story\n</code></pre> <p>Claude asks where to save it, updates your CLAUDE.md or rules, and you keep working. No context switching to edit files.</p>"},{"location":"reference/claude-md.html#keeping-it-alive","title":"Keeping it alive","text":"<p>A CLAUDE.md is a living document. The moment you write it, it starts going stale.</p>"},{"location":"reference/claude-md.html#the-self-correcting-loop","title":"The self-correcting loop","text":"<p>This is the most powerful maintenance pattern. When Claude does something wrong:</p> <ol> <li>Correct it in conversation</li> <li>Say: \"Update the CLAUDE.md so you don't make that mistake again\"</li> <li>Claude writes a rule for itself</li> </ol> <p>Boris Cherny calls this out specifically: \"Claude is eerily good at writing rules for itself.\" Every correction becomes a permanent improvement. Over weeks, your CLAUDE.md evolves from a basic briefing into a comprehensive set of guardrails shaped by real work.</p>"},{"location":"reference/claude-md.html#doc-rot","title":"Doc rot","text":"<p>Matt Pocock coined this term for the slow decay of CLAUDE.md accuracy. Your project changes (new packages, new conventions, restructured directories) but CLAUDE.md still describes the old version.</p> <p>Outdated context is worse than no context. Claude confidently follows instructions that no longer apply, and the bugs compound.</p> <p>The fix: Build maintenance into your workflow.</p> <ul> <li>After major changes: Update CLAUDE.md when you restructure the project, add dependencies, or change conventions</li> <li>Weekly audit: Ask Claude \"Are any of my CLAUDE.md files too long, redundant, or out of date?\"</li> <li>The 10-15% check: Run <code>/context</code> periodically. If CLAUDE.md consumes too much, prune it</li> <li>Run <code>/insights</code> weekly: It analyzes your recent sessions and surfaces patterns: what's working, what's failing, where you're spending time. When it flags something useful, add a rule or trim one that isn't pulling its weight</li> </ul>"},{"location":"reference/claude-md.html#when-claude-ignores-your-rules","title":"When Claude ignores your rules","text":"<p>This happens. It's a known issue. The community describes it as working with \"a genius who has dementia.\"</p> <p>Workarounds:</p> <ol> <li>Keep rules short and actionable. \"Always run tests before committing\" works. A three-paragraph explanation of your testing philosophy doesn't.</li> <li>Use Hooks for critical rules. Hooks run deterministic scripts that can't be ignored. If a rule absolutely must be followed (like \"never push to main\"), make it a Hook, not a CLAUDE.md rule. See Hooks.</li> <li>Reinforce in conversation. Type <code># remember: always run tests</code> mid-session to bump a rule's priority.</li> <li>The two-failed-corrections rule. If you correct Claude twice on the same thing and it still doesn't stick, run <code>/clear</code> and start a fresh session. The context is polluted. Adding more instructions to a confused session makes it worse, not better.</li> </ol>"},{"location":"reference/claude-md.html#advanced-patterns","title":"Advanced patterns","text":"<p>Once you're comfortable with the basics, these are worth knowing about.</p>"},{"location":"reference/claude-md.html#design-context-for-visual-work","title":"Design context for visual work","text":"<p>If you're building UIs or reviewing designs, add a design section to your project CLAUDE.md:</p> <pre><code>## Design context\n- Style: clean, modern, generous whitespace\n- Colors: primary #e63f02, secondary #f4d35e, dark #0f172a\n- Components: use shadcn/ui, don't create custom components\n- Reference: see screenshots in docs/design/ for visual baseline\n</code></pre> <p>Four lines of design context. That's it. But Claude's visual output with this vs without it looks like two different tools.</p>"},{"location":"reference/claude-md.html#scoped-claudemd-for-workflows","title":"Scoped CLAUDE.md for workflows","text":"<p>For complex, repeatable workflows (like a weekly status update), create a workflow folder with its own CLAUDE.md:</p> <pre><code>Workflows/weekly-update/\n\u251c\u2500\u2500 CLAUDE.md           # Scoped instructions for this workflow\n\u251c\u2500\u2500 template.md         # Status update template\n\u2514\u2500\u2500 anti-ai-rules.md    # Writing voice guardrails\n</code></pre> <p>The scoped CLAUDE.md tells Claude how to run this specific workflow. You <code>cd</code> into the folder, and Claude picks up the workflow context automatically.</p>"},{"location":"reference/claude-md.html#hierarchical-claudemd-for-large-projects","title":"Hierarchical CLAUDE.md for large projects","text":"<p>In a monorepo or large project, subdirectory CLAUDE.md files specialize the root one:</p> <ul> <li>Root CLAUDE.md: Architecture overview, shared patterns, validation commands</li> <li><code>api/CLAUDE.md</code>: API conventions, endpoint patterns, auth requirements</li> <li><code>web/CLAUDE.md</code>: Frontend conventions, component patterns, accessibility rules</li> </ul> <p>Claude loads both the root and the relevant subdirectory file. The subdirectory one overrides conflicting rules from the root.</p> <p>Brandon Casci's take: \"Think of them as executable specifications, not just guidelines.\"</p>"},{"location":"reference/claude-md.html#plug-play","title":"Plug &amp; Play","text":"<ul> <li>Resources: Rules &amp; Config : copy-paste CLAUDE.md examples, .claude/rules/ files, and starter templates</li> <li>The 5-section PM workspace structure above is ready to copy into any new project</li> </ul>"},{"location":"reference/claude-md.html#references","title":"References","text":"<p>Internal</p> <ul> <li>Skills : on-demand context that keeps CLAUDE.md lean</li> <li>Customization : hooks, settings, and personalization</li> <li>Context Management : understanding the context window trade-off</li> </ul> <p>External</p> <ul> <li>Anthropic: CLAUDE.md : official docs on CLAUDE.md configuration, hierarchy, and best practices</li> <li>Anthropic: Memory and CLAUDE.md : how Claude Code persists context across sessions</li> <li>Hannah Stulberg's 4-level PM framework : the definitive guide to folder-based context management</li> <li>Boris Cherny's \"Effective Claude Code\" : pragmatic, minimalist approach from the core team</li> <li>Brandon Casci's hierarchical CLAUDE.md patterns : executable specifications for complex projects</li> <li>Aakash Gupta's PM Operating System : CLAUDE.md + Skills + Sub-agents as a complete PM system</li> </ul>"},{"location":"reference/context-management.html","title":"Context Management","text":"<p>The single most important skill in Claude Code. Everything else builds on this.</p> <p>Quick Answer</p> <p>Use this when: Every session. Context management is not a technique you switch on. It is the foundation under everything Claude Code does.</p> <p>Avoid this when: Never. Even \"just a quick question\" has a context cost.</p> <p>What CC changes: You stop thinking about prompts and start thinking about what Claude knows, when it knows it, and how much room it has left to think. This is the shift from prompt engineering to context engineering.</p> <p>Default move: Start every session fresh. Keep your CLAUDE.md lean. Monitor with <code>/context</code>. Compact or clear before quality degrades.</p>"},{"location":"reference/context-management.html#the-mental-model-shift","title":"The mental model shift","text":"<p>You are not writing prompts. You are managing a scarce resource.</p> <p>Claude Code is not a chatbot. It is a context engineering tool with a smart agentic loop powering it. The gap between casual users and power users is not about writing better messages. It is about controlling what Claude knows, when it knows it, and how much of its attention budget you have left.</p> <p>PMs already practice this skill daily. You scope requirements, curate information for stakeholders, and decide what context a teammate needs before a meeting. The difference is applying that same discipline to an AI collaborator.</p> <p>\"If you're still typing instructions into Claude Code like you're asking ChatGPT for help, you're missing the entire point.\" -- Diamant AI</p>"},{"location":"reference/context-management.html#the-context-window-is-working-memory-not-storage","title":"The context window is working memory, not storage","text":"<p>The 200k token context window is not a hard drive. It is working memory. And it is smaller than you think.</p> <p>The real capacity:</p> What eats it Typical cost System prompts and reserved allocation ~22.5% from the start MCP tool definitions 15k-70k+ tokens depending on how many you have enabled Your CLAUDE.md (loads every request) Varies, but loads on every single API call Conversation history Grows with every message <p>Practitioners report roughly 120k usable tokens in practice. That is your whiteboard, and everything you put on it competes for the same attention.</p> <p>Think of it like a product's UX budget. You have limited real estate, and every element you add competes for attention. Overloading it degrades the entire experience.</p>"},{"location":"reference/context-management.html#the-smart-zone-and-the-dumb-zone","title":"The smart zone and the dumb zone","text":"<p>LLMs do not maintain consistent intelligence across their context window. Matt Pocock popularized this concept, and multiple practitioners have validated it: as the context fills up, Claude gets measurably worse.</p> <pre><code>%%{init: {'theme': 'dark'}}%%\nflowchart LR\n    A[\"0-40%\\nSmart Zone\"] --&gt; B[\"40-60%\\nCaution Zone\"]\n    B --&gt; C[\"60-80%\\nDegradation\"]\n    C --&gt; D[\"80%+\\nDanger Zone\"]\n\n    style A fill:#16a34a,color:#fff,stroke:#15803d\n    style B fill:#ca8a04,color:#fff,stroke:#a16207\n    style C fill:#ea580c,color:#fff,stroke:#c2410c\n    style D fill:#dc2626,color:#fff,stroke:#b91c1c</code></pre> Context usage What happens What to do 0-40% (Smart Zone) Sharp reasoning, follows instructions, catches nuance Work normally 40-60% (Caution Zone) Occasional lapses, may miss instructions Monitor closely, consider compacting 60-80% (Degradation Zone) Repetitive responses, forgets earlier context, generic output Compact immediately or start fresh 80%+ (Danger Zone) Hallucinations, contradicts itself, ignores instructions Stop. Clear. Start over. <p>Why does this happen? HyperDev's analysis provides the explanation: that \"free\" context space is not wasted. It is where reasoning happens. The less thinking room Claude has, the lower the quality of its output. Claude Code's auto-compact trigger was moved from 90% to roughly 75% for exactly this reason.</p> <p>The counter-intuitive insight: stopping earlier actually extends productive session length.</p>"},{"location":"reference/context-management.html#the-three-types-of-context-poison","title":"The three types of context poison","text":"<p>When context degrades, it does not simply get \"less good.\" It actively poisons future outputs.</p> Poison type What it looks like Example Failed attempt residue Previous wrong approaches linger and bias future attempts You asked Claude to fix a bug three different ways. All three failed. Now Claude keeps circling back to those failed approaches instead of trying something new Stale context Outdated information in CLAUDE.md or docs contradicts the current state Your CLAUDE.md still says \"we use REST\" but you migrated to GraphQL two months ago. Claude keeps generating REST endpoints Noise accumulation Verbose tool outputs, long debugging logs, and conversational cruft dilute signal A test suite dumped 500 lines of output into context. Now Claude is referencing error messages from passing tests"},{"location":"reference/context-management.html#the-core-commands","title":"The core commands","text":"<p>Three commands form the foundation. Use them constantly.</p>"},{"location":"reference/context-management.html#clear-the-nuclear-reset","title":"/clear -- the nuclear reset","text":"<p>Completely resets the conversation. Only your CLAUDE.md persists.</p> <p>Use it: between unrelated tasks, after a plan is accepted, when Claude produces confused output, after two failed corrections on the same issue.</p> <p>Do not use it: mid-task when you need to preserve conversation context.</p> <p>\"Every time you're doing something new, clear. You don't need all that chat history in your tokens every time.\" -- Steve, Builder.io</p>"},{"location":"reference/context-management.html#compact-the-smart-summarizer","title":"/compact -- the smart summarizer","text":"<p>Summarizes conversation history to free tokens while preserving key information. You can customize it with specific instructions:</p> <pre><code>/compact Focus on the API design decisions and the test results\n</code></pre> <p>Use it: mid-task when context is getting heavy (50-60% usage), before switching phases within the same task.</p> <p>Do not use it: when switching to an unrelated task (use /clear instead), when Claude is producing confused output (compacting confusion does not fix confusion).</p> <p>Compaction loses nuance</p> <p>Multiple practitioners report that auto-compaction drops important details. \"Auto compact has a habit of nuking nuance.\" Power users disable auto-compact and manage it manually. For most users, the default is fine, but if you are doing sensitive work, run <code>/compact</code> yourself with specific instructions about what to preserve.</p>"},{"location":"reference/context-management.html#context-the-x-ray","title":"/context -- the x-ray","text":"<p>Shows exactly what is consuming your token budget. Run it when you suspect bloat, and run it at the start of sessions to understand your baseline.</p>"},{"location":"reference/context-management.html#the-decision-matrix","title":"The decision matrix","text":"Situation /clear /compact Switching to an unrelated task Yes No Mid-task, context getting heavy No Yes After accepting a plan Yes No Claude producing confused output Yes No Two failed corrections on the same issue Yes No"},{"location":"reference/context-management.html#the-two-failed-corrections-rule","title":"The two failed corrections rule","text":"<p>This heuristic comes directly from Anthropic's official best practices:</p> <p>If you have corrected Claude more than twice on the same issue in one session, the context is cluttered with failed approaches. Run /clear and start fresh with a more specific prompt that incorporates what you learned.</p> <p>\"A clean session with a better prompt almost always outperforms a long session with accumulated corrections.\" -- Anthropic</p> <p>This is the AI equivalent of \"fail fast.\" Do not sink more time into a broken session. Fire the contractor, get a new one, and give them better instructions from the start.</p>"},{"location":"reference/context-management.html#the-session-lifecycle","title":"The session lifecycle","text":"<p>Every session has three phases. Managing the transitions between them is where most people lose quality.</p> <pre><code>%%{init: {'theme': 'dark'}}%%\nflowchart LR\n    A[\"Phase 1\\nClean Start\"] --&gt; B[\"Phase 2\\nActive Monitoring\"]\n    B --&gt; C[\"Phase 3\\nStructured Handoff\"]\n    C --&gt;|\"new task\"| A\n\n    style A fill:#16a34a,color:#fff,stroke:#15803d\n    style B fill:#ca8a04,color:#fff,stroke:#a16207\n    style C fill:#6366f1,color:#fff,stroke:#4f46e5</code></pre>"},{"location":"reference/context-management.html#phase-1-clean-start","title":"Phase 1: Clean start","text":"<p>Start fresh rather than continuing bloated sessions. Selectively load only the context you need. A clean session with focused context always outperforms a stale one with \"everything from yesterday.\"</p>"},{"location":"reference/context-management.html#phase-2-active-monitoring","title":"Phase 2: Active monitoring","text":"<p>Monitor context usage passively through the status line. Run <code>/context</code> when you suspect bloat. Proactively compact at 50-60% usage. Do not wait for auto-compact.</p>"},{"location":"reference/context-management.html#phase-3-structured-handoff","title":"Phase 3: Structured handoff","text":"<p>Before ending a session or switching contexts, capture state externally:</p> <ul> <li>Run <code>/compact</code> with specific focus instructions</li> <li>Have Claude write a summary to a progress file or handoff document</li> <li>For long-running tasks, create a handoff document: what is done, what is next, key decisions made</li> </ul> <p>\"AI context is like milk; it's best served fresh and condensed.\" -- YK</p>"},{"location":"reference/context-management.html#the-context-loading-hierarchy","title":"The context loading hierarchy","text":"<p>Not all context loads the same way or at the same time. Understanding this hierarchy is how you control what Claude knows and when.</p> Mechanism When it loads Token cost Best for CLAUDE.md Every request Full content, always Universal project context (keep it lean) MCP tool definitions Session start Full definitions, always Use sparingly, disable unused MCPs Skills On invocation ~30-50 tokens at start; full on use On-demand workflows and knowledge Sub-agents On spawn Separate context window entirely Heavy-lifting tasks, verbose output @-referenced files On mention Full content, that request only One-time context loading Subdirectory CLAUDE.md When reading files in that folder Full content, on-demand Area-specific rules and context <p>The pattern: move things down this list as far as possible. What must Claude know every session? That goes in CLAUDE.md. What does Claude need only for specific tasks? That goes in skills or reference files. What produces verbose output? That gets delegated to a sub-agent.</p>"},{"location":"reference/context-management.html#what-belongs-where","title":"What belongs where","text":"<p>The fundamental question is not \"what goes in my CLAUDE.md?\" It is \"what goes WHERE?\"</p>  Bad  Good 500-line CLAUDE.md with everything you have ever told Claude 60-80 line CLAUDE.md with universal context, reference files for details Task-specific instructions in the root CLAUDE.md (\"use RICE for prioritization\") Task-specific instructions in a subdirectory CLAUDE.md or skill Full documents pasted inline Short summaries inline, full docs on demand via <code>@reference</code> or file reads Code conventions in a PM workspace root CLAUDE.md Code conventions in <code>.claude/rules/</code> or subdirectory CLAUDE.md 15 MCP servers enabled at all times Only the MCPs you actually use for this project enabled"},{"location":"reference/context-management.html#the-filtering-question","title":"The filtering question","text":"<p>For every piece of context, ask: \"Is this relevant to EVERYTHING I do in this workspace?\"</p> <ul> <li>Yes: root CLAUDE.md</li> <li>Yes, but it is a tool instruction, not project context: <code>.claude/rules/</code></li> <li>Only for specific types of work: subdirectory CLAUDE.md or skill</li> <li>Only needed when I explicitly ask for it: reference file, loaded on demand</li> </ul>"},{"location":"reference/context-management.html#the-pm-specific-challenge","title":"The PM-specific challenge","text":"<p>PM work is fundamentally different from developer work when it comes to context management. A developer's CLAUDE.md serves one type of work. A PM's workspace serves ten.</p>  Dev pattern (one type of work)  PM pattern (ten types of work) \"Use TypeScript strict\" Role and team context \"Run tests before commit\" Product summary \"Kebab-case filenames\" Key preferences \"ESLint rules\" Pointers to detailed docs One set of rules covers everything Rules change by task type <p>Monday morning you are doing competitive research. Monday afternoon you are writing a PRD. Tuesday you are analyzing data. Wednesday you are drafting a stakeholder update. Each of these tasks needs different context, and loading all of it all the time is a waste of whiteboard space.</p> <p>The PM CLAUDE.md playbook:</p> <ol> <li>Your role -- who you are, who you report to</li> <li>Product summary -- 2-3 sentences on what you are building and for whom</li> <li>Team overview -- one line per person</li> <li>Universal preferences -- tone, style, things Claude gets wrong without being told</li> <li>Key paths -- where things live in your workspace</li> </ol> <p>Everything else goes in subdirectory CLAUDE.md files, skills, or reference documents.</p>"},{"location":"reference/context-management.html#claudemd-vs-clauderules","title":"CLAUDE.md vs .claude/rules/","text":"<p>These two are often confused. The distinction is simple:</p> <p>CLAUDE.md = briefing about YOUR WORLD. \"We target mid-market teams of 50-500.\" \"Sarah prefers detailed specs.\" A human teammate needs to know this.</p> <p>.claude/rules/ = operating instructions for CLAUDE. \"Use kebab-case for file names.\" \"Delegate research to sub-agents.\" Only an AI tool needs to be told this.</p> <p>Rules files in <code>.claude/rules/</code> can also be scoped to specific file patterns, so they only activate when Claude is working with matching files. This is powerful for project-specific conventions.</p>"},{"location":"reference/context-management.html#keeping-it-alive","title":"Keeping it alive","text":"<p>CLAUDE.md files go stale. Old instructions can confuse newer versions of Claude. Stale workarounds become liabilities.</p> <p>The maintenance loop:</p> <ol> <li>Start small (you just did this)</li> <li>When Claude repeats a mistake, add one line</li> <li>End of session: \"What should change in my CLAUDE.md based on what we did today?\"</li> <li>Prune regularly. If an instruction is not earning its space, cut it</li> </ol> <p>Anthropic's own teams use this exact pattern. Your CLAUDE.md evolves from actual usage, not guesswork.</p>"},{"location":"reference/context-management.html#advanced-progressive-disclosure-through-skills","title":"Advanced: progressive disclosure through skills","text":"<p>When your CLAUDE.md grows past ~500 lines, the answer is not \"try to trim harder.\" It is skills.</p> <p>Skills load on-demand. A skill description costs ~30-50 tokens at session start. The full instructions only load when the skill is invoked. A project with 20 skills and a lean CLAUDE.md will outperform one with a 2,000-line CLAUDE.md every time.</p> Approach Context cost 500 lines in CLAUDE.md 500 lines loaded every request Same content as 10 skills ~300-500 tokens of descriptions loaded, full content only on invocation <p>The migration path is clear: anything in CLAUDE.md that is not universally relevant to every session becomes a skill.</p>"},{"location":"reference/context-management.html#advanced-sub-agents-for-context-isolation","title":"Advanced: sub-agents for context isolation","text":"<p>The primary purpose of sub-agents is not parallelism. It is context isolation.</p> <p>When you spawn a sub-agent, that agent gets its own fresh 200k-token context window. It does the heavy lifting, sends back a summary, and your main session barely moves. This is covered in depth on the Sub-agents page.</p> <p>The decision: Do you need the journey (follow-up questions, iteration, building on it) or just the answer (summary, output, result)? If you just need the answer, delegate it.</p>"},{"location":"reference/context-management.html#common-mistakes","title":"Common mistakes","text":"Mistake What to do instead Never checking <code>/context</code> Check it at session start and whenever context feels heavy Letting auto-compact handle everything Run manual <code>/compact</code> with specific instructions at 50-60% Continuing a session after two failed corrections <code>/clear</code> and start fresh with a better prompt Loading 15 MCP servers Disable unused MCPs. Use <code>/context</code> to see the cost Putting everything in root CLAUDE.md Use subdirectory CLAUDE.md files and skills for task-specific context Never pruning CLAUDE.md Run the maintenance loop. Cut what is not earning its space Saying \"thanks\" at the end of a session Every message reprocesses the entire context. Just close the session"},{"location":"reference/context-management.html#plug-play","title":"Plug &amp; Play","text":"<p><code>/humanizer</code> Behavioral skill that changes how Claude writes. Example of on-demand context loading -- 400+ lines of rules that only load when invoked, not every session.</p> <p><code>/feature-brief</code> Generate skill with progressive disclosure. Instructions in SKILL.md, template and examples in the folder. Full reference material loads only when the skill runs.</p>"},{"location":"reference/context-management.html#references","title":"References","text":"<p>Internal:</p> <ul> <li>CLAUDE.md : Deep dive on writing and structuring CLAUDE.md files</li> <li>Sub-agents : Context isolation through delegation</li> <li>Skills Overview : On-demand context loading through skills</li> <li>Plan Mode : Using Plan Mode as a context management strategy</li> </ul> <p>External:</p> <ul> <li>Anthropic: Claude Code best practices : Official guidance on context management and project structure</li> <li>Anthropic: Common workflows : Session management patterns and the /clear vs /compact decision</li> <li>Anthropic: Skills documentation : Progressive disclosure through skills</li> </ul>"},{"location":"reference/customization.html","title":"Customization","text":"<p>Claude Code ships with sensible defaults. But \"sensible defaults\" means \"designed for the average user,\" and you're not average. This page covers every knob you can turn: hooks for automation, settings.json for behavior, spinner verbs for personality, the status line for visibility, and the permissions system for safety.</p> <p>The goal isn't to configure everything. It's to know what's configurable so you can make Claude Code work the way you think.</p> <p>Quick Answer</p> <p>Use this when: You want Claude to behave consistently, enforce rules automatically, or feel less like a generic tool.</p> <p>Avoid this when: You're still learning the basics. Get comfortable with CLAUDE.md and skills first. Customization amplifies an existing workflow; it doesn't create one.</p> <p>What CC changes: You go from asking Claude to do things right to making it impossible to do things wrong. Hooks enforce standards. Settings control behavior. The status line keeps you oriented.</p> <p>Default move: Start with three things: permission rules that match your comfort level, a status line showing context usage and git branch, and one safety hook.</p>"},{"location":"reference/customization.html#the-configuration-landscape","title":"The configuration landscape","text":"<pre><code>flowchart TD\n    A[\"What do you want to control?\"] --&gt; B{\"Behavior &amp;&lt;br/&gt;permissions?\"}\n    A --&gt; C{\"Automated&lt;br/&gt;enforcement?\"}\n    A --&gt; D{\"Visual&lt;br/&gt;experience?\"}\n    A --&gt; E{\"AI instructions&lt;br/&gt;&amp; context?\"}\n\n    B --&gt; F[\"&lt;b&gt;settings.json&lt;/b&gt;&lt;br/&gt;Permissions, env vars,&lt;br/&gt;model selection\"]\n    C --&gt; G[\"&lt;b&gt;Hooks&lt;/b&gt;&lt;br/&gt;Run scripts on events.&lt;br/&gt;Block, automate, notify.\"]\n    D --&gt; H[\"&lt;b&gt;Status line + Spinners&lt;/b&gt;&lt;br/&gt;Dashboard, theme,&lt;br/&gt;personality\"]\n    E --&gt; I[\"&lt;b&gt;CLAUDE.md + Rules&lt;/b&gt;&lt;br/&gt;See: Reference &gt; CLAUDE.md\"]\n\n    style A fill:#e63f02,color:#fff,stroke:#b43200\n    style F fill:#1e293b,color:#f8fafc,stroke:#374151\n    style G fill:#1e293b,color:#f8fafc,stroke:#374151\n    style H fill:#1e293b,color:#f8fafc,stroke:#374151\n    style I fill:#374151,color:#f8fafc,stroke:#4b5563</code></pre>"},{"location":"reference/customization.html#settingsjson","title":"settings.json","text":"<p>This is the master configuration file. It controls permissions, environment variables, hooks, model selection, and everything behavioral. CLAUDE.md tells Claude what to know. settings.json tells Claude what it's allowed to do.</p>"},{"location":"reference/customization.html#where-settings-live","title":"Where settings live","text":"<p>Settings use a layered system. More specific scopes override broader ones.</p> Scope File Purpose User <code>~/.claude/settings.json</code> Your personal defaults across all projects Project <code>.claude/settings.json</code> Team standards, committed to git Local <code>.claude/settings.local.json</code> Your personal overrides for this project. Gitignored. Managed System-level path IT-enforced policies. Cannot be overridden. <p>Precedence: Managed &gt; Local &gt; Project &gt; User. A deny rule at any level cannot be overridden by a lower level.</p>"},{"location":"reference/customization.html#permission-rules","title":"Permission rules","text":"<p>Permissions are the most important thing in settings.json. They define what Claude can and cannot do without asking.</p> <pre><code>{\n  \"permissions\": {\n    \"allow\": [\n      \"Bash(ls *)\", \"Bash(cat *)\", \"Bash(grep *)\",\n      \"Bash(git diff *)\", \"Bash(git log *)\", \"Bash(git status *)\",\n      \"Read\", \"Glob\", \"Grep\"\n    ],\n    \"ask\": [\n      \"Bash(git push *)\", \"Bash(git commit *)\",\n      \"Write\", \"Edit\"\n    ],\n    \"deny\": [\n      \"Bash(rm -rf *)\",\n      \"Bash(git reset --hard *)\",\n      \"Bash(git push --force *)\"\n    ]\n  }\n}\n</code></pre> <p>Rules evaluate in order: deny &gt; ask &gt; allow. First match wins.</p>  Bad  Good Leave defaults and click \"approve\" 50 times a session Define allow rules for safe reads, ask rules for writes Use <code>--dangerously-skip-permissions</code> on a real project Use <code>acceptEdits</code> mode and allow known-safe bash patterns Deny <code>Read(.env)</code> and think you're safe Also deny <code>Bash(cat .env)</code> since bash bypasses file-level denials Allow <code>Bash(rm *)</code> Deny destructive commands explicitly. Always. <p>Gotcha</p> <p>Denying <code>Read(.env)</code> does NOT block <code>Bash(cat .env)</code>. Denying <code>Edit(file.txt)</code> blocks <code>Write(file.txt)</code>, but denying <code>Write(file.txt)</code> does NOT block <code>Edit(file.txt)</code>. Test your assumptions.</p>"},{"location":"reference/customization.html#environment-variables","title":"Environment variables","text":"<p>Set persistent environment variables in settings.json under the <code>env</code> key:</p> <pre><code>{\n  \"env\": {\n    \"ANTHROPIC_MODEL\": \"claude-sonnet-4-20250514\",\n    \"ENABLE_TOOL_SEARCH\": \"true\",\n    \"CLAUDE_CODE_DISABLE_TERMINAL_TITLE\": \"1\"\n  }\n}\n</code></pre> <p>Key variables for PMs:</p> Variable What it does <code>ANTHROPIC_MODEL</code> Override the default model <code>ENABLE_TOOL_SEARCH</code> Lazy-load MCP tools to save context <code>MAX_THINKING_TOKENS</code> Cap extended thinking cost <code>DISABLE_TELEMETRY</code> Turn off anonymous usage data <code>CLAUDE_CODE_DISABLE_TERMINAL_TITLE</code> Stop Claude from changing your terminal tab title"},{"location":"reference/customization.html#the-config-shortcut","title":"The /config shortcut","text":"<p>Don't want to edit JSON manually? Run <code>/config</code> inside Claude Code for an interactive settings menu. Run <code>/permissions</code> to inspect the active permission ruleset.</p>"},{"location":"reference/customization.html#hooks","title":"Hooks","text":"<p>Hooks are scripts that run automatically when Claude does something. Before it writes a file, after it runs a command, when a session starts, when it finishes a task. They add deterministic guardrails to a probabilistic AI.</p> <p>The core idea: Claude might remember to run your linter. It might follow your commit conventions. Hooks make sure it happens every time.</p>"},{"location":"reference/customization.html#the-hook-model","title":"The hook model","text":"<p>A hook binds three things together:</p> <ol> <li>Event - When to fire (before an edit, after a bash command, when Claude stops)</li> <li>Matcher - What to filter on (which tool, which file pattern)</li> <li>Handler - What to execute (a shell script, a prompt, a sub-agent)</li> </ol> <pre><code>flowchart LR\n    Event[\"Event&lt;br/&gt;&lt;i&gt;When does it fire?&lt;/i&gt;\"] --&gt; Matcher[\"Matcher&lt;br/&gt;&lt;i&gt;Which tool/context?&lt;/i&gt;\"]\n    Matcher --&gt; Handler[\"Handler&lt;br/&gt;&lt;i&gt;What runs?&lt;/i&gt;\"]\n    Handler --&gt; Result{\"Exit code\"}\n    Result --&gt;|\"0\"| Proceed[\"Proceed normally\"]\n    Result --&gt;|\"2\"| Block[\"Block the action.&lt;br/&gt;Error sent to Claude.\"]\n\n    style Event fill:#1e293b,color:#f8fafc,stroke:#374151\n    style Matcher fill:#1e293b,color:#f8fafc,stroke:#374151\n    style Handler fill:#1e293b,color:#f8fafc,stroke:#374151\n    style Proceed fill:#22c55e,color:#fff,stroke:#16a34a\n    style Block fill:#ef4444,color:#fff,stroke:#dc2626</code></pre>"},{"location":"reference/customization.html#key-events","title":"Key events","text":"Event When it fires PM use case <code>PreToolUse</code> Before a tool executes Block dangerous commands, protect files <code>PostToolUse</code> After a tool succeeds Auto-format, lint, log changes <code>Stop</code> Claude finishes responding Run test suite, send notification <code>SessionStart</code> Session begins (or after compaction) Load project context, set env vars <code>UserPromptSubmit</code> Before Claude processes your prompt Validate input, inject context, activate skills <code>PreCompact</code> Before context compaction Archive full transcript <code>Notification</code> When Claude sends a notification Desktop/mobile alerts, Slack messages"},{"location":"reference/customization.html#three-handler-types","title":"Three handler types","text":"Type What it does When to use <code>command</code> Runs a shell script Deterministic rules (linting, blocking, formatting) <code>prompt</code> Asks a lightweight LLM Fuzzy decisions that aren't purely rule-based <code>agent</code> Spawns a full sub-agent Complex verification (run test suite, review against spec) <p>Start with command hooks. Graduate to prompt hooks when you need judgment. Use agent hooks sparingly for critical quality gates.</p>"},{"location":"reference/customization.html#the-three-hooks-every-pm-should-install","title":"The three hooks every PM should install","text":"<p>1. The Safety Net - Block destructive commands before they execute.</p> <pre><code>{\n  \"hooks\": {\n    \"PreToolUse\": [\n      {\n        \"matcher\": \"Bash\",\n        \"handler\": {\n          \"type\": \"command\",\n          \"command\": \"echo '{\\\"tool_input\\\":{\\\"command\\\":\\\"\\\"}}' | jq -r '.tool_input.command' | grep -qE 'rm -rf|git reset --hard|git push --force' &amp;&amp; echo 'BLOCKED: Destructive command detected. Use a safer alternative.' &gt;&amp;2 &amp;&amp; exit 2 || exit 0\"\n        }\n      }\n    ]\n  }\n}\n</code></pre> <p>In practice, store this as a script in <code>.claude/hooks/safety-net.sh</code> and reference the path.</p> <p>2. The Done Bell - Get notified when Claude finishes a task.</p> <pre><code>{\n  \"hooks\": {\n    \"Stop\": [\n      {\n        \"handler\": {\n          \"type\": \"command\",\n          \"command\": \"osascript -e 'display notification \\\"Claude is done\\\" with title \\\"Claude Code\\\"'\"\n        }\n      }\n    ]\n  }\n}\n</code></pre> <p>(macOS example. Adapt for your OS.)</p> <p>3. The Context Reloader - Re-inject critical context after compaction.</p> <pre><code>{\n  \"hooks\": {\n    \"SessionStart\": [\n      {\n        \"matcher\": \"compact\",\n        \"handler\": {\n          \"type\": \"command\",\n          \"command\": \"echo 'Context was compacted. Re-read CLAUDE.md and the current task list before continuing.'\"\n        }\n      }\n    ]\n  }\n}\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"reference/customization.html#hook-configuration-scope","title":"Hook configuration scope","text":"<p>Like settings, hooks live at different levels:</p> Scope File Who it affects User <code>~/.claude/settings.json</code> All your projects Project <code>.claude/settings.json</code> Everyone on the team Local <code>.claude/settings.local.json</code> Just you, on this project"},{"location":"reference/customization.html#setting-up-hooks","title":"Setting up hooks","text":"<p>Two paths:</p> <ul> <li>Interactive: Type <code>/hooks</code> in Claude Code for a visual menu</li> <li>Manual: Edit the <code>hooks</code> key in <code>settings.json</code> directly</li> <li>Quick add: Press <code>Ctrl+O</code> during a session</li> </ul>"},{"location":"reference/customization.html#hook-scripts-best-practice","title":"Hook scripts best practice","text":"<p>Store hook scripts in <code>.claude/hooks/</code> within your project:</p> <pre><code>.claude/hooks/\n  safety-net.sh\n  post-edit-lint.sh\n  done-notification.sh\n</code></pre> <p>Reference them in settings.json with <code>$CLAUDE_PROJECT_DIR</code>:</p> <pre><code>{\n  \"handler\": {\n    \"type\": \"command\",\n    \"command\": \"$CLAUDE_PROJECT_DIR/.claude/hooks/safety-net.sh\"\n  }\n}\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"reference/customization.html#the-anti-pattern-file-modifying-hooks","title":"The anti-pattern: file-modifying hooks","text":"<p>Running Prettier or any formatter as a <code>PostToolUse</code> hook seems smart. It's actually a trap. File modifications trigger system-reminder notifications with full diffs, which consume massive amounts of context tokens.</p>  Bad  Good Run Prettier on every file edit via <code>PostToolUse</code> Run Prettier on the <code>Stop</code> event, or as part of a commit hook Auto-format triggers bloating context silently Use <code>/context</code> to monitor token usage after adding hooks <p>Run formatters on <code>Stop</code> events or as part of git commit workflows, not on every individual edit.</p>"},{"location":"reference/customization.html#status-line","title":"Status line","text":"<p>The status line is a persistent bar at the bottom of the terminal that shows whatever you want. It's the PM's dashboard.</p>"},{"location":"reference/customization.html#why-it-matters","title":"Why it matters","text":"<p>Without the status line, you're flying blind on two things PMs care about: how much context you've used (your budget) and which git branch you're on (your location). One user accidentally committed to main because there was no persistent branch indicator. The status line prevents that.</p>"},{"location":"reference/customization.html#quick-setup","title":"Quick setup","text":"<p>The fastest path:</p> <pre><code>/statusline show model name, context percentage, and git branch\n</code></pre> <p>Claude auto-generates the script and settings configuration. Done.</p>"},{"location":"reference/customization.html#manual-setup","title":"Manual setup","text":"<p>The status line is a shell script configured in <code>~/.claude/settings.json</code>:</p> <pre><code>{\n  \"statusLine\": \"~/.claude/statusline.sh\"\n}\n</code></pre> <p>The script receives session data as JSON on stdin and prints output:</p> <pre><code>#!/bin/bash\nread -r JSON\nMODEL=$(echo \"$JSON\" | jq -r '.model.display_name // \"unknown\"')\nCTX=$(echo \"$JSON\" | jq -r '.context_window.used_percentage // 0' | cut -d. -f1)\nBRANCH=$(git -C \"$(echo \"$JSON\" | jq -r '.cwd')\" branch --show-current 2&gt;/dev/null || echo \"no git\")\nCOST=$(echo \"$JSON\" | jq -r '.cost.total_cost_usd // 0')\n\necho \"$MODEL | ctx: ${CTX}% | $BRANCH | \\$${COST}\"\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"reference/customization.html#the-pm-dashboard-formula","title":"The PM dashboard formula","text":"<p>Three things, in priority order:</p> <ol> <li>Context usage with color coding (your budget)</li> <li>Current git branch (your location)</li> <li>Session cost in USD (your spend)</li> </ol> <p>Everything else (model name, weather, Bitcoin price) is optional personality.</p> <p>CLI only</p> <p>The status line does not exist in the Desktop app, VS Code extension, or web interface. It's one of the main reasons power users prefer the terminal.</p>"},{"location":"reference/customization.html#spinner-verbs","title":"Spinner verbs","text":"<p>When Claude is thinking, you see loading text like \"Thinking...\" or \"Analyzing...\" You can customize these.</p> <pre><code>{\n  \"spinner_verbs\": [\n    \"Strategizing\",\n    \"Prioritizing\",\n    \"Stakeholder managing\",\n    \"Aligning\",\n    \"Synergizing\"\n  ],\n  \"spinner_verbs_mode\": \"replace\"\n}\n</code></pre> <p>Set <code>spinner_verbs_mode</code> to <code>\"replace\"</code> to fully swap the defaults, or <code>\"append\"</code> to add yours to the existing set.</p> <p>This lives in <code>settings.json</code> and can be committed to <code>.claude/settings.json</code> in your repo for shared team culture. It's a small thing, but personalization creates ownership. When rolling out Claude Code to a team, having people customize their spinners as a first exercise breaks the ice.</p>"},{"location":"reference/customization.html#model-selection","title":"Model selection","text":"<p>You can override which model Claude uses:</p> Method How Per-session Press <code>Alt+M</code> or run <code>/model</code> to switch mid-session Permanent Set <code>ANTHROPIC_MODEL</code> in <code>settings.json</code> &gt; <code>env</code> Per-skill Add <code>model: claude-sonnet-4-20250514</code> to a skill's YAML frontmatter <p>Use the most capable model for complex reasoning. Use faster models for repetitive tasks. Skills let you set this per-workflow so you don't have to think about it.</p>"},{"location":"reference/customization.html#the-customization-sequence","title":"The customization sequence","text":"<p>If you're starting from scratch, do it in this order:</p> <pre><code>flowchart TD\n    A[\"1. Permission rules&lt;br/&gt;Allow safe reads, deny destructive commands\"] --&gt; B[\"2. Status line&lt;br/&gt;Context %, git branch, cost\"]\n    B --&gt; C[\"3. One safety hook&lt;br/&gt;PreToolUse bash firewall\"]\n    C --&gt; D[\"4. Done notification&lt;br/&gt;Stop event notification\"]\n    D --&gt; E[\"5. Spinner verbs&lt;br/&gt;Make it yours\"]\n    E --&gt; F[\"6. Advanced hooks&lt;br/&gt;As your workflow demands\"]\n\n    style A fill:#e63f02,color:#fff,stroke:#b43200\n    style B fill:#e63f02,color:#fff,stroke:#b43200\n    style C fill:#e63f02,color:#fff,stroke:#b43200\n    style D fill:#1e293b,color:#f8fafc,stroke:#374151\n    style E fill:#1e293b,color:#f8fafc,stroke:#374151\n    style F fill:#1e293b,color:#f8fafc,stroke:#374151</code></pre> <p>The first three are high-impact, low-effort. Start there. Add the rest as your workflow matures.</p>"},{"location":"reference/customization.html#plug-play","title":"Plug &amp; Play","text":"<p>Relevant components:</p> <ul> <li>Ready-made hook scripts: Hooks Library</li> <li>Configuration templates: Rules &amp; Config</li> </ul>"},{"location":"reference/customization.html#references","title":"References","text":"<p>Internal</p> <ul> <li>Reference: CLAUDE.md : Context and instructions (complements settings.json)</li> <li>Reference: Connections : MCPs : MCP configuration in <code>.mcp.json</code></li> <li>Reference: Skills : Building : Per-skill model selection</li> </ul> <p>External</p> <ul> <li>Anthropic: Hooks Guide</li> <li>Anthropic: Hooks Reference</li> <li>Anthropic: Claude Code Best Practices</li> </ul>"},{"location":"reference/hooks.html","title":"Hooks","text":"<p>Event-driven automation \u2014 run scripts automatically when Claude Code does things.</p> <p>Coming Soon</p> <p>This guide is under development. Check back soon.</p>"},{"location":"reference/integrations.html","title":"Integrations &amp; Connections","text":"<p>Connecting Claude Code to external tools \u2014 MCPs, APIs, and the broader ecosystem.</p> <p>Coming Soon</p> <p>This guide is under development. Check back soon.</p>"},{"location":"reference/plan-mode.html","title":"Plan Mode","text":"<p>Make Claude think before it acts. Five minutes of planning saves an hour of rework.</p> <p>Quick Answer</p> <p>Use this when: The task is non-trivial and has more than one reasonable approach. PRDs, architecture decisions, multi-file changes, research synthesis, document generation from examples.</p> <p>Avoid this when: The task is simple and obvious. Renaming a file, fixing a typo, generating a quick summary. Planning these is overhead.</p> <p>What CC changes: You stop hoping Claude picks the right approach and start reviewing the approach before it executes. The plan becomes a communication artifact, a documentation record, and a handoff document all at once.</p> <p>Default move: Shift+Tab twice to enter Plan Mode. Review the plan. Iterate until you are satisfied. Then Shift+Tab to auto-accept and let Claude execute.</p>"},{"location":"reference/plan-mode.html#what-plan-mode-is","title":"What Plan Mode is","text":"<p>Plan Mode constrains Claude to read-only operations. It can read files, explore the codebase, and analyze dependencies, but it cannot write or modify anything. The output is a plan for you to review before anything changes.</p> <p>Activation: Shift+Tab (cycles through modes), <code>claude --permission-mode plan</code>, or the <code>/plan</code> command.</p> <p>Plan Mode sits within a three-mode system:</p> <pre><code>%%{init: {'theme': 'dark'}}%%\nflowchart LR\n    P[\"Plan Mode\\n(read-only, propose)\"] --&gt;|\"Shift+Tab\"| D[\"Default Mode\\n(ask permission)\"]\n    D --&gt;|\"Shift+Tab\"| A[\"Auto-Accept\\n(execute freely)\"]\n    A --&gt;|\"Shift+Tab\"| P\n\n    style P fill:#6366f1,color:#fff,stroke:#4f46e5\n    style D fill:#ca8a04,color:#fff,stroke:#a16207\n    style A fill:#16a34a,color:#fff,stroke:#15803d</code></pre> <p>Think of it as a trust gradient. Plan Mode is maximum oversight. Auto-accept is full delegation. You adjust based on how much you trust what is about to happen.</p>"},{"location":"reference/plan-mode.html#why-planning-first-matters","title":"Why planning first matters","text":"<p>This is the single strongest point of agreement across the entire Claude Code community. Every practitioner, official doc, and community thread converges on the same principle: planning before execution is the most impactful workflow change you can make.</p> <p>Boris Cherny, the creator of Claude Code, starts most sessions in Plan Mode. He goes back and forth with Claude until he likes the plan, then switches to auto-accept and lets Claude execute.</p> <p>\"Make AI write a plan first, let AI critique it: eliminates 80% of 'AI got confused' moments.\" -- r/ClaudeAI (1,462 upvotes)</p> <p>\"Planning five minutes saves fixing broken implementations for an hour. Every single time.\" -- Diamant AI</p> <p>The cost of skipping is concrete: rapid initial progress followed by a painful debugging phase. The community calls this the \"AI coding death spiral.\" It happens because Claude picked the wrong approach and you did not catch it before it wrote 500 lines.</p>"},{"location":"reference/plan-mode.html#the-workflow","title":"The workflow","text":""},{"location":"reference/plan-mode.html#1-explore","title":"1. Explore","text":"<p>Have Claude analyze the relevant files, understand the current state, and build context. This is the most important phase and the one most often skipped.</p>"},{"location":"reference/plan-mode.html#2-plan","title":"2. Plan","text":"<p>Claude proposes an approach. Review it. Push back. Ask \"what about...\" and \"how would you handle...\" The plan is not a formality. It is the work.</p>"},{"location":"reference/plan-mode.html#3-execute","title":"3. Execute","text":"<p>When the plan is solid, Shift+Tab to auto-accept mode. Claude executes what you agreed on with a clean, focused approach.</p> <p>The plan-and-clear pattern</p> <p>After accepting a plan, Claude Code offers to clear the context. Choose \"Clear\" over \"Compact.\" A fresh start with only the plan as context leads to more reliable implementation than a compacted session carrying old exploration baggage.</p>"},{"location":"reference/plan-mode.html#when-to-use-which-mode","title":"When to use which mode","text":"<p>Boris Cherny provides the canonical difficulty framework:</p> Task difficulty Mode Example Easy Skip planning. Fire and forget Fix a typo, rename a variable, add a log line Medium Plan Mode. Align on approach before execution Write a PRD, build a feature, restructure a module Hard You drive. Claude provides research and prototyping Architecture decisions, system design, strategic direction <p>Most PM work falls in the \"medium\" category. That is Plan Mode's sweet spot.</p>"},{"location":"reference/plan-mode.html#plan-mode-beyond-code","title":"Plan Mode beyond code","text":"<p>Plan Mode is not only for code. It is for any task where the approach matters as much as the output.</p> PM use case What Plan Mode does Document generation Proposes structure and sections before writing Research synthesis Outlines themes and analysis framework before diving in Competitive analysis Proposes comparison dimensions before collecting data Meeting prep Identifies key topics and questions before building the agenda Hiring documents Plans the JD structure, interview rubric, and evaluation criteria before drafting <p>\"The biggest unlock from Boris's workflow is the realization that the setup for coding is the setup for everything else.\" -- Hannah Stulberg</p>"},{"location":"reference/plan-mode.html#reviewing-plans","title":"Reviewing plans","text":"<p>A plan you did not read is worse than no plan at all. It gives you false confidence that you are aligned when you are not.</p>  Bad plan review  Good plan review Glance at it, hit accept Read every section, question the approach Assume it covered your edge cases Ask \"what about [specific scenario]?\" Accept the first version Iterate: \"What if we took a different approach to section 3?\" Let Claude decide the architecture Specify the architecture, let Claude plan the implementation <p>Advanced technique: After Claude generates a plan, try: \"Knowing everything you know now, scrap this and propose the elegant solution.\" This forces Claude to rethink from scratch rather than incrementally polishing a mediocre first attempt.</p>"},{"location":"reference/plan-mode.html#common-pitfalls","title":"Common pitfalls","text":"Pitfall What to do instead Over-planning simple tasks Skip Plan Mode for easy tasks. Planning \"rename this file\" is overhead Plan bloat (Claude repeats previous plans inside new plans) Add to your CLAUDE.md: \"Generate concise plans. Do not repeat previous plan content\" Accepting plans without reading them Read the plan. Push back. Ask questions. The plan IS the work Using Plan Mode for architecture when you should be driving For hard tasks, you define the architecture. Claude plans the implementation Never using Plan Mode Start every non-trivial task in Plan Mode. Build the habit"},{"location":"reference/plan-mode.html#plug-play","title":"Plug &amp; Play","text":"<p><code>/feature-brief</code> Multi-step generate skill that benefits from Plan Mode to scope the brief structure before drafting.</p>"},{"location":"reference/plan-mode.html#references","title":"References","text":"<p>Internal:</p> <ul> <li>Context Management : How Plan Mode fits into the session lifecycle</li> <li>Sub-agents : Using sub-agents to review plans from a different perspective</li> </ul> <p>External:</p> <ul> <li>Anthropic: Common workflows : Official Plan Mode documentation and mode cycling</li> <li>Anthropic: Claude Code best practices : Planning patterns and the explore-plan-execute workflow</li> </ul>"},{"location":"reference/sub-agents.html","title":"Sub-agents","text":"<p>Stop doing all the work yourself. Sub-agents keep your context clean and your output sharp.</p> <p>Quick Answer</p> <p>Use this when: A task produces verbose output, involves reading many files, or does not need iterative follow-up. Research, summarization, analysis, and validation are all natural delegations.</p> <p>Avoid this when: You need the journey, not just the answer. If you will say \"great, now what about...\" or \"actually, change the framing on...\" the work needs to stay in your main session.</p> <p>What CC changes: You stop thinking of Claude as a single assistant and start thinking of it as a team. Your main session becomes the coordinator. Sub-agents do the heavy lifting in their own context windows and report back.</p> <p>Default move: Ask yourself, \"Do I need the journey or the answer?\" If the answer, delegate it.</p>"},{"location":"reference/sub-agents.html#why-sub-agents-exist","title":"Why sub-agents exist","text":"<p>Sub-agents exist to solve the context window problem.</p> <p>Every file Claude reads, every tool output, every back-and-forth exchange takes up space in your main context window. That space is your thinking room. When it fills up, quality degrades (see Context Management). Sub-agents give you a way out.</p> <p>When you spawn a sub-agent, it gets its own fresh 200k-token context window. It reads the files, does the analysis, and sends back a concise summary. Your main session barely moves.</p> <p>\"The absolutely bonkers part is that your main context window stays at 30-40% even after deep research or thousands of lines of code getting written. All heavy lifting happens consistently in fresh 200k subagent contexts.\" -- u/officialtaches</p> <p>Think of your main context window as your desk. If you pile every document from every meeting on it, you cannot work. Sub-agents are filing cabinets. They hold the detail and hand you back a one-page summary.</p>"},{"location":"reference/sub-agents.html#the-journey-or-answer-framework","title":"The journey-or-answer framework","text":"<p>This is the only framework you need for delegation decisions.</p> <pre><code>%%{init: {'theme': 'dark'}}%%\nflowchart TD\n    Q[\"Do you need the journey\\nor the answer?\"]\n    Q --&gt;|\"Journey\\n(follow-ups, iteration,\\nbuilding on context)\"| K[\"Keep in session\"]\n    Q --&gt;|\"Answer\\n(summary, output,\\nresult)\"| D[\"Delegate to sub-agent\"]\n\n    style Q fill:#6366f1,color:#fff,stroke:#4f46e5\n    style K fill:#ca8a04,color:#fff,stroke:#a16207\n    style D fill:#16a34a,color:#fff,stroke:#15803d</code></pre> <p>The journey: You will iterate on the output. You will ask follow-up questions. You need Claude to remember all the details because you are building on them. Keep this in session.</p> <p>The answer: You need the output and will use it somewhere else. The details of how it got there do not matter. Delegate this.</p>  Keep in session (need the journey)  Delegate (need the answer) \"Help me figure out how to frame this roadmap delay\" \"Summarize the last 3 sprint retro notes into key themes\" \"Iterate on this meeting agenda with me\" \"Read the user research folder and count feature requests by category\" \"Draft this PRD, then I want to refine the scope\" \"Analyze these 5 competitor profiles and summarize pricing differences\" \"Walk me through options for the API rate limiting approach\" \"Generate a stakeholder update from these meeting notes\" <p>Think of it like delegating to a junior PM. You would not hand them your quarterly strategy and say \"figure it out.\" But \"pull the key metrics from last quarter's reports\" is a perfect delegation.</p>"},{"location":"reference/sub-agents.html#how-sub-agents-work","title":"How sub-agents work","text":"<p>There are two ways Claude creates sub-agents:</p>"},{"location":"reference/sub-agents.html#automatic-claude-decides","title":"Automatic (Claude decides)","text":"<p>Claude can spawn sub-agents on its own when it determines the task is parallelizable or would benefit from isolation. You do not always control this. Sometimes Claude reads all five files inline when a sub-agent would have been smarter. Sometimes it delegates something you wanted in your main context.</p> <p>That is why knowing how to explicitly ask matters.</p>"},{"location":"reference/sub-agents.html#explicit-you-decide","title":"Explicit (you decide)","text":"<p>Tell Claude to use a sub-agent:</p> <ul> <li>\"Use a sub-agent to analyze the competitor files\"</li> <li>\"Delegate this to a sub-agent and give me the summary\"</li> <li>\"Spin up agents to research each competitor in parallel\"</li> </ul> <p>Being explicit is more reliable than hoping Claude makes the right call.</p>"},{"location":"reference/sub-agents.html#background-agents","title":"Background agents","text":"<p>Background agents let you keep working while a task runs. There are two ways to use them:</p> <p>Launch in the background from the start: \"Run this in the background: analyze the competitor files from a customer success lens.\"</p> <p>Background a running agent: Press Ctrl+B while an agent is running in the foreground to send it to the background. You get your prompt back immediately. When the agent finishes, the result appears in the chat.</p> <p>This is the PM equivalent of saying \"go do that research and ping me when it's done.\" You keep your conversation going while the heavy work happens elsewhere.</p>"},{"location":"reference/sub-agents.html#two-flavors-of-sub-agents","title":"Two flavors of sub-agents","text":"<pre><code>%%{init: {'theme': 'dark'}}%%\nflowchart TD\n    S[\"Sub-agent needed\"]\n    S --&gt; A[\"Ad-hoc\\n(describe the task)\"]\n    S --&gt; D[\"Dedicated\\n(pre-built persona)\"]\n    A --&gt; R1[\"You define the lens\\nevery time\"]\n    D --&gt; R2[\"Lens is baked in\\nreusable across tasks\"]\n\n    style S fill:#6366f1,color:#fff,stroke:#4f46e5\n    style A fill:#ca8a04,color:#fff,stroke:#a16207\n    style D fill:#16a34a,color:#fff,stroke:#15803d\n    style R1 fill:#374151,color:#f8fafc,stroke:#4b5563\n    style R2 fill:#374151,color:#f8fafc,stroke:#4b5563</code></pre>"},{"location":"reference/sub-agents.html#ad-hoc-sub-agents","title":"Ad-hoc sub-agents","text":"<p>Created fresh each time for a specific task. You describe exactly what you want, the lens to use, and the output format. They disappear when done.</p> <p>\"Analyze this positioning brief as if you were a VP of Sales. Flag anything you could not use in a real customer call.\"</p>"},{"location":"reference/sub-agents.html#dedicated-sub-agents","title":"Dedicated sub-agents","text":"<p>Pre-built agents stored as markdown files in <code>.claude/agents/</code>. They have a persona, a communication style, and specific expertise baked in. When you invoke them, they already know their role.</p> <pre><code># .claude/agents/eng-reviewer.md\n---\nname: eng-reviewer\ndescription: Reviews specs and briefs for technical feasibility,\n  flagging complexity, dependencies, and missing edge cases\ntools:\n  - Read\n  - Grep\n  - Glob\nmodel: sonnet\n---\n\nYou are a senior engineer reviewing PM deliverables.\nFlag: technical risks, missing edge cases, underestimated complexity,\nunclear acceptance criteria. Be direct. Skip the praise.\n</code></pre> <p>When to use which:</p> Ad-hoc Dedicated One-off tasks Recurring review patterns You know the lens and can describe it The lens is complex enough to codify Quick and disposable Worth maintaining over time"},{"location":"reference/sub-agents.html#the-builder-validator-pattern","title":"The builder-validator pattern","text":"<p>This is the single most powerful sub-agent pattern. One agent builds. A separate agent validates with fresh eyes.</p> <pre><code>%%{init: {'theme': 'dark'}}%%\nflowchart LR\n    B[\"Builder\\n(drafts the output)\"] --&gt;|\"output\"| V[\"Validator\\n(reviews as stakeholder)\"]\n    V --&gt;|\"gaps found\"| B\n\n    style B fill:#ca8a04,color:#fff,stroke:#a16207\n    style V fill:#16a34a,color:#fff,stroke:#15803d</code></pre> <p>When Claude writes something, it cannot truly reflect on what it produced. It just keeps generating tokens. But a separate agent with fresh context and no memory of the trade-offs sees only the output. That is why it catches things the builder misses.</p> <p>The key: give the validator a specific stakeholder lens. \"Review as a VP of Sales\" hits differently than \"please review.\" \"I can't use slide 3 in a customer call\" is actionable. \"This could be more specific\" is not.</p>  Weak validation  Strong validation \"Review this brief\" \"Review this brief as the VP of Sales. Flag anything you could not use in a customer call\" \"Check this PRD\" \"Review this PRD as the lead engineer. Flag anything that is ambiguous, underspecified, or will cause questions during sprint planning\" \"Is this good?\" \"Review this stakeholder update as the CEO. Flag anything that buries the lead or lacks clear next steps\" <p>The validation levels:</p> Level Approach When to use Level 1: Quick self-review \"Review what you just wrote and flag weak spots\" (same context) Quick passes, low-stakes work Level 2: Builder-validator Separate agent, fresh eyes, stakeholder lens Important deliverables, anything going to a real audience Level 3: Baked into a skill Validation is part of the workflow, happens automatically every run Repeatable processes where you never want to skip review"},{"location":"reference/sub-agents.html#parallel-execution","title":"Parallel execution","text":"<p>Sub-agents can run in parallel. \"Analyze these 5 competitors\" might become 5 parallel agents, each researching one competitor simultaneously. You do not need to orchestrate this manually. Claude often does it on its own when the task is naturally parallelizable.</p> <p>You can request it explicitly: \"Research each of these competitors in parallel using separate sub-agents.\"</p> <p>The result: research that would take 15 minutes sequentially finishes in the time it takes one agent to complete.</p> <p>Cost awareness</p> <p>Parallel agents multiply token usage. Five parallel agents use roughly five times the tokens of one sequential agent. This is fine when speed matters and the budget supports it. Be aware of the trade-off.</p>"},{"location":"reference/sub-agents.html#context-isolation-is-the-point","title":"Context isolation is the point","text":"<p>The primary purpose of sub-agents is not speed. It is context isolation.</p> Without sub-agents With sub-agents Reading 5 competitor files dumps their full content into your main context A sub-agent reads them, sends you a 200-word summary Test suite output consumes 500 lines of context A sub-agent runs tests, reports only failures Research clutter builds up over the session Research stays in the sub-agent's window. Your main session stays clean <p>The orchestrator model: Your main session acts as a lightweight conductor. It stays at low context (30-40%) while sub-agents handle the heavy lifting in fresh context windows. This keeps Claude in the smart zone for the decisions that matter -- the ones you are making together in the main session.</p>"},{"location":"reference/sub-agents.html#when-not-to-use-sub-agents","title":"When NOT to use sub-agents","text":"<p>Sub-agents are not always the right call.</p>  Do not delegate Why Tasks that need the rich context already built in your session The sub-agent starts fresh and loses everything you have built up Work requiring deep iteration and follow-up You will lose the thread. Keep it in session Simple tasks that take fewer tokens than the delegation overhead Spinning up a sub-agent has a cost. If the task is \"rename this file,\" just do it Tasks needing deep understanding of a complex codebase Sub-agents work best for isolated tasks, not ones requiring nuanced codebase knowledge built over a session <p>\"If the main agent already possesses the necessary context to perform a task, creating a sub-agent for it is an unnecessary consumption of tokens.\" -- Matt Pocock</p>"},{"location":"reference/sub-agents.html#common-mistakes","title":"Common mistakes","text":"Mistake What to do instead Doing all research in the main session Delegate research to sub-agents. You need the answer, not the journey Asking Claude to review its own work in the same context Use the builder-validator pattern. Fresh eyes find what tired eyes miss Never using sub-agents Start with one delegation per session. Build the habit Using sub-agents for everything, including simple tasks Apply the journey-or-answer framework. Some things belong in your main session Giving validators a generic \"review this\" instruction Give a stakeholder lens. \"Review as a VP of Sales\" produces actionable feedback Not being explicit about delegation Say \"use a sub-agent\" or \"delegate this.\" Do not assume Claude will decide correctly on its own"},{"location":"reference/sub-agents.html#plug-play","title":"Plug &amp; Play","text":"<p><code>/feature-brief</code> Generate skill that spawns reviewer sub-agents with specific stakeholder lenses. The builder-validator pattern in a single command.</p> <p><code>/meeting-aftermath</code> Composition skill that orchestrates 6 sub-skills in sequence. Each step can delegate to sub-agents for heavy processing while the main skill coordinates.</p>"},{"location":"reference/sub-agents.html#references","title":"References","text":"<p>Internal:</p> <ul> <li>Context Management : The smart zone/dumb zone framework and why delegation matters</li> <li>Skills Overview : Building skills that use sub-agents for validation and research</li> <li>Plan Mode : Planning as a complement to delegation</li> </ul> <p>External:</p> <ul> <li>Anthropic: Sub-agents documentation : Official reference for sub-agent configuration and patterns</li> <li>Anthropic: Claude Code best practices : The writer/reviewer pattern and context isolation guidance</li> <li>Anthropic: Common workflows : Parallel execution and background agent patterns</li> </ul>"},{"location":"reference/connections/index.html","title":"Connections","text":"<p>Claude Code is powerful on its own. But it's isolated. It can read your files, write code, run shell commands. What it can't do out of the box is check your Jira tickets, search Reddit, pull analytics data, or post a Slack message. Connections fix that.</p> <p>There are three ways to connect Claude to the outside world. Each one has a different job.</p> <p>Quick Answer</p> <p>Use this when: You want Claude to interact with external tools, services, or data sources.</p> <p>Avoid this when: Everything you need is already in local files. Don't add connections for the sake of it.</p> <p>What CC changes: Instead of copy-pasting between tools, Claude pulls data and takes actions directly. You stop being the middleman.</p> <p>Default move: CLI first. MCP if there's one available. API for custom integrations.</p>"},{"location":"reference/connections/index.html#the-three-connection-types","title":"The three connection types","text":"<pre><code>flowchart LR\n    You[\"You\"] --&gt; Claude[\"Claude Code\"]\n    Claude --&gt;|\"Runs commands&lt;br/&gt;in terminal\"| CLI[\"CLI Tools&lt;br/&gt;&lt;code&gt;gh, pandoc, jira&lt;/code&gt;\"]\n    Claude --&gt;|\"Calls pre-built&lt;br/&gt;integrations\"| MCP[\"MCP Servers&lt;br/&gt;&lt;code&gt;Slack, Reddit, Figma&lt;/code&gt;\"]\n    Claude --&gt;|\"Sends HTTP&lt;br/&gt;requests directly\"| API[\"APIs&lt;br/&gt;&lt;code&gt;curl, webhooks, REST&lt;/code&gt;\"]\n\n    style You fill:#1e293b,color:#f8fafc,stroke:#374151\n    style Claude fill:#e63f02,color:#fff,stroke:#b43200\n    style CLI fill:#1e293b,color:#f8fafc,stroke:#374151\n    style MCP fill:#1e293b,color:#f8fafc,stroke:#374151\n    style API fill:#1e293b,color:#f8fafc,stroke:#374151</code></pre> <p>Think of them as three tools in a toolbox. You wouldn't use a wrench for every job. Same idea.</p>"},{"location":"reference/connections/index.html#decision-framework","title":"Decision framework","text":"Question Answer Does the tool have a CLI? Use the CLI. Zero config, zero context cost. Claude discovers capabilities on its own. No CLI, but an MCP exists? Use the MCP. Someone already did the API work. Install and go. Neither CLI nor MCP? Use the API. You're building the integration yourself, or embedding it in a skill. <p>The order matters: CLI first, then MCP, then API. This isn't a preference. It's a decision rule based on reliability, context cost, and setup effort.</p>"},{"location":"reference/connections/index.html#how-they-compare","title":"How they compare","text":"CLI MCP API Context cost Zero Low (deferred via Tool Search) Zero Reliability Highest High High Setup effort Install the tool Add to <code>.mcp.json</code>, restart Write the request yourself Best for Tools with mature CLIs (<code>gh</code>, <code>pandoc</code>, <code>jira</code>) Daily-use tools where someone packaged the integration (Slack, Reddit, Figma) Custom integrations, webhooks, embedding in skills How Claude learns it Runs <code>--help</code> and figures it out Discovers tools via Tool Search You tell it the endpoint and parameters"},{"location":"reference/connections/index.html#where-to-go-from-here","title":"Where to go from here","text":"<p>CLIs - The most reliable option. Zero config, zero context cost. Start here.</p> <p>MCPs - Pre-packaged integrations. Someone already did the API work for you.</p> <p>APIs - The foundation layer. Full control, full responsibility.</p>"},{"location":"reference/connections/index.html#plug-play","title":"Plug &amp; Play","text":"<p>Relevant skills:</p> <ul> <li>Tooling &amp; integration configs: Tooling &amp; Integrations</li> </ul>"},{"location":"reference/connections/index.html#references","title":"References","text":"<p>Internal</p> <ul> <li>Lesson: L4 : Connect Claude to Everything</li> <li>Reference: CLAUDE.md : Where to document your connections</li> </ul> <p>External</p> <ul> <li>Anthropic: MCP Overview</li> <li>Anthropic: Claude Code Best Practices</li> </ul>"},{"location":"reference/connections/apis.html","title":"APIs","text":"<p>An API is a website that returns raw data instead of a visual page. When you visit reddit.com in your browser, you see images, buttons, formatting. When you hit Reddit's API, you get back structured data. Claude can request data from these URLs, read what comes back, and work with it.</p> <p>APIs are the bedrock. Everything else (MCPs, CLIs, even most web apps) is built on top of them. Understanding how they work gives you the foundation for everything in this section.</p> <p>Quick Answer</p> <p>Use this when: No CLI or MCP exists, you need custom integrations, or you're embedding external data into a skill.</p> <p>Avoid this when: A CLI or MCP already covers the use case. Don't rebuild what's already packaged.</p> <p>What CC changes: Claude can make API calls on your behalf using <code>curl</code> or scripts. You describe what you want, it writes the request, reads the response, and works with the data.</p> <p>Default move: Check for a CLI or MCP first. Use APIs for custom integrations or when you need surgical precision over exactly what data you pull.</p>"},{"location":"reference/connections/apis.html#how-api-calls-work","title":"How API calls work","text":"<pre><code>sequenceDiagram\n    participant You\n    participant Claude as Claude Code\n    participant API as External API\n\n    You-&gt;&gt;Claude: \"Get me a random dad joke\"\n    Claude-&gt;&gt;API: curl -s https://icanhazdadjoke.com/\n    API--&gt;&gt;Claude: {\"joke\": \"Why did the coffee...\"}\n    Claude--&gt;&gt;You: Here's the joke + explanation\n\n    Note over Claude,API: Context cost: ZERO&lt;br/&gt;The request runs in bash,&lt;br/&gt;not in Claude's context window</code></pre> <p>The flow is always the same:</p> <ol> <li>You tell Claude what you want</li> <li>Claude constructs a request (usually <code>curl</code>)</li> <li>The API returns data</li> <li>Claude processes and presents it</li> </ol> <p>Every API in the world works on this principle. A URL, a request, a response. Some need authentication, some are more complex, but the foundation is always this simple.</p>"},{"location":"reference/connections/apis.html#a-real-example","title":"A real example","text":"<p>Here's Claude making a live API call to get a dad joke:</p> <pre><code>curl -s -H \"Accept: application/json\" https://icanhazdadjoke.com/\n</code></pre> <p>Response: <pre><code>{\n  \"id\": \"R7UfaahVfFd\",\n  \"joke\": \"My dog used to chase people on a bike a lot. It got so bad I had to take his bike away.\",\n  \"status\": 200\n}\n</code></pre></p> <p>That's it. One command, structured data back. Claude reads the JSON, extracts the joke, and presents it.</p>"},{"location":"reference/connections/apis.html#when-apis-need-authentication","title":"When APIs need authentication","text":"<p>Most useful tools (Jira, Slack, your analytics platform) require you to prove you have access. An API key is the equivalent of a login.</p> <pre><code># Authenticated API call example\ncurl -s -H \"Authorization: Bearer YOUR_API_KEY\" \\\n     -H \"Content-Type: application/json\" \\\n     https://api.example.com/v1/data\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"reference/connections/apis.html#where-to-store-api-keys","title":"Where to store API keys","text":"Bad  Good Hardcoded in CLAUDE.md Stored in a <code>.env</code> file Pasted into the chat Referenced via environment variable Committed to git Loaded through <code>settings.json</code> &gt; <code>env</code> <p>Never put API keys in CLAUDE.md or commit them to version control. Use a <code>.env</code> file or the <code>env</code> object in <code>settings.json</code>.</p>"},{"location":"reference/connections/apis.html#common-api-patterns-for-pms","title":"Common API patterns for PMs","text":""},{"location":"reference/connections/apis.html#webhook-post-sending-data-out","title":"Webhook POST (sending data out)","text":"<p>When something happens in your workflow and you want to notify another system:</p> <pre><code>curl -X POST https://hooks.slack.com/services/YOUR/WEBHOOK/URL \\\n     -H \"Content-Type: application/json\" \\\n     -d '{\"text\": \"Feature brief for Q3 prioritization is ready for review\"}'\n</code></pre> <p>This pattern is how you'd trigger notifications, update external trackers, or push data to dashboards.</p>"},{"location":"reference/connections/apis.html#get-request-pulling-data-in","title":"GET request (pulling data in)","text":"<p>When you need data from an external source:</p> <pre><code>curl -s \"https://api.github.com/repos/owner/repo/issues?state=open&amp;labels=bug\" \\\n     -H \"Accept: application/vnd.github+json\"\n</code></pre> <p>Claude reads the response, filters what matters, and summarizes it for you.</p>"},{"location":"reference/connections/apis.html#embedding-api-calls-in-skills","title":"Embedding API calls in skills","text":"<p>The real power move is putting API calls inside skills so they run automatically as part of a workflow:</p> <pre><code>## Instructions\n\n1. Fetch the latest open bugs from GitHub:\n   Run: curl -s \"https://api.github.com/repos/acme/dashboard/issues?state=open&amp;labels=bug\"\n2. Categorize by severity using the labels\n3. Draft a bug triage summary with recommended priorities\n</code></pre> <p>This turns a manual \"check GitHub, read the bugs, write a summary\" workflow into a single command.</p>"},{"location":"reference/connections/apis.html#apis-vs-mcps-when-to-choose-which","title":"APIs vs MCPs: when to choose which","text":"Scenario Use API Use MCP You need one specific data point from a service You'll interact with the service constantly No MCP exists for the service You're embedding the call in a skill Someone already packaged the integration You need full control over the request <p>The mental model: MCPs are like installing an app. APIs are like running just the parts of an app you need and getting the raw data.</p>"},{"location":"reference/connections/apis.html#common-gotchas","title":"Common gotchas","text":"<p>Rate limits. Most APIs limit how many requests you can make per minute/hour. Claude doesn't inherently know about these. If calls start failing, rate limits are usually the reason.</p> <p>Authentication expiration. API keys and tokens expire. If a previously working API call suddenly fails, check your credentials first.</p> <p>Response size. Some APIs return massive payloads. If you're pulling data from an analytics API, filter the request (date ranges, specific fields) rather than downloading everything and parsing it.</p> <p>CORS doesn't apply. Claude runs <code>curl</code> in your terminal, not in a browser. Cross-origin restrictions don't exist here. If you've been told \"you can't call that API directly\" and the advice was for browser JavaScript, ignore it. Claude can hit it directly.</p>"},{"location":"reference/connections/apis.html#plug-play","title":"Plug &amp; Play","text":"<p>Relevant skills:</p> <ul> <li>API integration patterns: Skills Library</li> <li>External tool configs: Tooling &amp; Integrations</li> </ul>"},{"location":"reference/connections/apis.html#references","title":"References","text":"<p>Internal</p> <ul> <li>Lesson: L4 : Connect Claude to Everything</li> <li>Reference: Connections Overview : Decision framework for choosing APIs vs MCPs vs CLIs</li> <li>Reference: MCPs : Pre-packaged API integrations</li> <li>Reference: Skills : Building : Embedding API calls in skills</li> </ul> <p>External</p> <ul> <li>Anthropic: Claude Code Best Practices</li> </ul>"},{"location":"reference/connections/clis.html","title":"CLIs","text":"<p>CLI tools are command-line programs that Claude can just run in the terminal. No MCP server, no config file, no context cost. Install the tool, and Claude figures out how to use it by reading <code>--help</code> or the documentation.</p> <p>CLIs are the most reliable connection method. They've been around for years, they're battle-tested, and Claude is remarkably good at discovering their capabilities on its own.</p> <p>Quick Answer</p> <p>Use this when: The tool you want to connect has a CLI available. This should be your first check.</p> <p>Avoid this when: The tool has no CLI, or you need persistent connections with managed auth (that's MCP territory).</p> <p>What CC changes: Claude runs CLI commands directly in bash. You don't need to teach it the tool. It reads <code>--help</code>, discovers what's possible, and figures out the right command.</p> <p>Default move: Always check for a CLI first. Install it, tell Claude what you want, and let it handle the rest.</p>"},{"location":"reference/connections/clis.html#how-clis-work-with-claude","title":"How CLIs work with Claude","text":"<pre><code>sequenceDiagram\n    participant You\n    participant Claude as Claude Code\n    participant CLI as CLI Tool\n\n    You-&gt;&gt;Claude: \"Convert this markdown to HTML\"\n    Claude-&gt;&gt;CLI: pandoc --help (discovers usage)\n    CLI--&gt;&gt;Claude: Usage documentation\n    Claude-&gt;&gt;CLI: pandoc CLAUDE.md -o output.html\n    CLI--&gt;&gt;Claude: File created successfully\n    Claude--&gt;&gt;You: Done. Here's what I generated.\n\n    Note over Claude,CLI: Context cost: ZERO&lt;br/&gt;CLI runs in bash, not in context</code></pre> <p>The key difference from MCPs: there's nothing to configure. No JSON file, no server process, no authentication flow. Claude runs the command in bash, gets the output, and keeps working.</p>"},{"location":"reference/connections/clis.html#installing-cli-tools","title":"Installing CLI tools","text":"<p>Claude can install tools for you. Just ask:</p> <pre><code>Install pandoc\n</code></pre> <p>Claude adapts to your operating system:</p> OS Command macOS <code>brew install pandoc</code> Ubuntu/Debian <code>apt install pandoc</code> Windows <code>choco install pandoc</code> or <code>winget install pandoc</code> <p>Once installed, the tool is available immediately. No restart needed.</p>"},{"location":"reference/connections/clis.html#claude-using-a-cli-vs-you-using-it-directly","title":"Claude using a CLI vs you using it directly","text":"<p>Here's the difference. You don't need to know the command syntax. Claude does.</p> <p>You using pandoc directly: <pre><code>pandoc --from=markdown --to=html --standalone \\\n  --metadata title=\"Feature Brief\" \\\n  --css=style.css \\\n  -o feature-brief.html feature-brief.md\n</code></pre></p> <p>You with Claude Code: <pre><code>Convert feature-brief.md to a styled HTML page with a table of contents\n</code></pre></p> <p>Claude runs <code>pandoc --help</code>, discovers the flags it needs, constructs the command, and executes it. If you asked for something fancier (PDF output, custom fonts, numbered sections), Claude would figure out those flags too.</p> <p>This is why CLIs are so powerful with Claude. Tools that used to require memorizing flags and reading man pages become natural language interfaces.</p>"},{"location":"reference/connections/clis.html#cli-tools-that-matter-for-pms","title":"CLI tools that matter for PMs","text":""},{"location":"reference/connections/clis.html#essentials","title":"Essentials","text":"Tool What it does PM use case <code>gh</code> (GitHub CLI) Full GitHub access from the terminal Create issues, review PRs, check CI status, manage releases <code>pandoc</code> Convert documents between any format Markdown to PDF, HTML, Word. Share documents in the format your stakeholders want. <code>jq</code> Process and filter JSON data Parse API responses, filter data exports, reshape structured data"},{"location":"reference/connections/clis.html#development","title":"Development","text":"Tool What it does PM use case <code>git</code> Version control Already installed. Claude uses it constantly for branching, committing, diffing. <code>npm</code> / <code>pip</code> Package managers Install dependencies, run project scripts, manage toolchains <code>docker</code> Container management Run databases, test environments, preview builds"},{"location":"reference/connections/clis.html#productivity","title":"Productivity","text":"Tool What it does PM use case <code>jira</code> (Jira CLI) Jira access from terminal Create tickets, update statuses, query backlogs <code>linear</code> (Linear CLI) Linear access from terminal Same as Jira CLI but for Linear users <code>slack</code> (Slack CLI) Slack operations Post messages, search channels, manage workflows <code>ffmpeg</code> Video/audio processing Extract clips from recordings, convert formats, create thumbnails"},{"location":"reference/connections/clis.html#a-real-workflow-github-cli","title":"A real workflow: GitHub CLI","text":"<p>The GitHub CLI (<code>gh</code>) is the poster child for CLI-over-MCP. Here's why:</p> <p>Task: \"Create a bug ticket for the dashboard loading issue\"</p> <p>With <code>gh</code>, Claude runs: <pre><code>gh issue create --title \"Dashboard takes 12s to load on first visit\" \\\n  --body \"## Problem\\nFirst-time visitors see a blank screen for 12 seconds...\\n\\n## Expected\\nDashboard loads in under 3 seconds...\" \\\n  --label \"bug,performance\" \\\n  --assignee \"@me\"\n</code></pre></p> <p>Zero context cost. No MCP server running. No tool definitions loaded. Just a command, a result, done.</p> <p>Compare:</p> <code>gh</code> CLI GitHub MCP Context cost Zero Low (tool definitions loaded) Setup <code>brew install gh</code> + <code>gh auth login</code> Add to <code>.mcp.json</code>, configure auth, restart Reliability Extremely high High (but depends on MCP server process) Capabilities Full GitHub API access Whatever the MCP author exposed <p>For GitHub operations, the CLI wins on every dimension. This pattern holds for most tools that have mature CLIs.</p>"},{"location":"reference/connections/clis.html#when-clis-fall-short","title":"When CLIs fall short","text":"<p>CLIs are the default choice, but they're not always the answer.</p>  CLI is wrong  CLI is right The tool has no CLI (Figma, most analytics platforms) The tool has a well-documented CLI (<code>gh</code>, <code>jira</code>, <code>pandoc</code>) You need persistent auth that refreshes automatically Auth is a one-time <code>login</code> command You need Claude to proactively discover capabilities across many tools You know which tool you want Claude to use The integration requires complex multi-step API flows The operation maps cleanly to a single command <p>The honest truth: CLIs cover maybe 30% of the tools PMs use day to day. But that 30% includes the highest-frequency operations (git, GitHub, document conversion, data processing). Start there.</p>"},{"location":"reference/connections/clis.html#how-claude-self-discovers-cli-tools","title":"How Claude self-discovers CLI tools","text":"<p>This is the part that surprises people. You don't need to teach Claude how to use a CLI tool. It teaches itself.</p> <pre><code>flowchart TD\n    A[\"You: 'Use pandoc to convert&lt;br/&gt;this to a PDF with a TOC'\"] --&gt; B[\"Claude runs:&lt;br/&gt;&lt;code&gt;pandoc --help&lt;/code&gt;\"]\n    B --&gt; C[\"Claude reads the&lt;br/&gt;usage documentation\"]\n    C --&gt; D[\"Claude constructs&lt;br/&gt;the right command\"]\n    D --&gt; E[\"Claude runs:&lt;br/&gt;&lt;code&gt;pandoc input.md -o output.pdf --toc&lt;/code&gt;\"]\n    E --&gt; F[\"Done. Zero teaching&lt;br/&gt;required from you.\"]\n\n    style A fill:#1e293b,color:#f8fafc,stroke:#374151\n    style B fill:#374151,color:#f8fafc,stroke:#4b5563\n    style C fill:#374151,color:#f8fafc,stroke:#4b5563\n    style D fill:#374151,color:#f8fafc,stroke:#4b5563\n    style E fill:#e63f02,color:#fff,stroke:#b43200\n    style F fill:#22c55e,color:#fff,stroke:#16a34a</code></pre> <p>Claude reads <code>--help</code> output, man pages, and documentation. It understands flag syntax, subcommands, piping, and output formatting. For well-documented tools, Claude's usage is often more correct than what a human would type from memory.</p> <p>This self-discovery is a huge advantage over MCPs, where you're limited to whatever the MCP author chose to expose.</p>"},{"location":"reference/connections/clis.html#tips","title":"Tips","text":"<p>Install tools globally, not per-project. CLI tools should be available everywhere. Use your system package manager (<code>brew</code>, <code>apt</code>).</p> <p>Let Claude chain commands. Claude is good at piping output from one tool to another: <pre><code>gh issue list --label \"bug\" --json title,labels | jq '.[] | .title'\n</code></pre></p> <p>Check if a CLI exists before reaching for an MCP. Many services that have MCPs also have CLIs. The CLI is almost always the better choice when both exist.</p> <p>Don't pre-teach. Your instinct might be to explain the tool to Claude. Don't. Just say what you want done and let Claude figure out the tool. It's faster and often more accurate than your instructions would be.</p>"},{"location":"reference/connections/clis.html#plug-play","title":"Plug &amp; Play","text":"<p>Relevant skills:</p> <ul> <li>Tool installation patterns: Tooling &amp; Integrations</li> <li>Skills that use CLIs: Skills Library</li> </ul>"},{"location":"reference/connections/clis.html#references","title":"References","text":"<p>Internal</p> <ul> <li>Lesson: L4 : Connect Claude to Everything</li> <li>Reference: Connections Overview : Decision framework for choosing connection types</li> <li>Reference: MCPs : When a CLI doesn't exist and you need an MCP</li> <li>Reference: APIs : When neither CLI nor MCP covers the use case</li> </ul> <p>External</p> <ul> <li>GitHub CLI documentation</li> <li>Pandoc User's Guide</li> <li>Anthropic: Claude Code Best Practices</li> </ul>"},{"location":"reference/connections/mcps.html","title":"MCPs","text":"<p>MCP stands for Model Context Protocol. It's a standardized way for Claude Code to connect to external tools and services. Think of it as \"USB-C for AI.\" One protocol, hundreds of connections.</p> <p>The pitch is simple: someone already wrote the API requests, handled the authentication, figured out the edge cases, and packaged it all up. You install it, and Claude gets new capabilities without you writing any code.</p> <p>Quick Answer</p> <p>Use this when: A tool you use regularly has an MCP available. Slack, Figma, Google Drive, Reddit, Notion, GitHub, databases.</p> <p>Avoid this when: A CLI covers the use case (CLIs are more reliable and cheaper on context). Or when you only need one specific data point (use a direct API call).</p> <p>What CC changes: Claude can interact with your tools directly. Search Reddit, read Notion pages, post to Slack, pull Figma designs. No copy-pasting between apps.</p> <p>Default move: Check if a CLI exists first. If not, check for an MCP. If neither, build it yourself with an API.</p>"},{"location":"reference/connections/mcps.html#how-mcps-work","title":"How MCPs work","text":"<pre><code>flowchart LR\n    You[\"You\"] --&gt;|\"Search Reddit for&lt;br/&gt;PM task management\"| Claude[\"Claude Code\"]\n    Claude --&gt;|\"Tool Search finds&lt;br/&gt;the right MCP tool\"| MCP[\"MCP Server&lt;br/&gt;(running locally)\"]\n    MCP --&gt;|\"Handles auth,&lt;br/&gt;API calls, formatting\"| Service[\"External Service&lt;br/&gt;(Reddit, Slack, etc.)\"]\n    Service --&gt;|\"Raw data\"| MCP\n    MCP --&gt;|\"Structured results\"| Claude\n    Claude --&gt;|\"Summary +&lt;br/&gt;analysis\"| You\n\n    style You fill:#1e293b,color:#f8fafc,stroke:#374151\n    style Claude fill:#e63f02,color:#fff,stroke:#b43200\n    style MCP fill:#374151,color:#f8fafc,stroke:#4b5563\n    style Service fill:#1e293b,color:#f8fafc,stroke:#374151</code></pre> <p>The MCP server runs on your machine. It registers tools that Claude can discover and use. When you ask Claude to do something that matches an MCP's capabilities, Claude finds the right tool via Tool Search and calls it. The MCP handles the messy parts (authentication, API formatting, error handling) and returns clean data.</p> <p>You describe what you want in plain language. Claude picks the right tool. The MCP does the work.</p>"},{"location":"reference/connections/mcps.html#configuration","title":"Configuration","text":"<p>All MCP configuration lives in JSON files. There are two scopes:</p> Scope File Use case Project <code>.mcp.json</code> in your project root Travels with the project. Anyone who clones it gets the same tools. User <code>~/.claude/.mcp.json</code> Applies to all your projects. Good for tools you always want (Slack, calendar)."},{"location":"reference/connections/mcps.html#a-real-configuration","title":"A real configuration","text":"<p>Here's what a <code>.mcp.json</code> file looks like with a Reddit MCP:</p> <pre><code>{\n  \"mcpServers\": {\n    \"reddit\": {\n      \"command\": \"npx\",\n      \"args\": [\"-y\", \"@modelcontextprotocol/server-reddit\"]\n    }\n  }\n}\n</code></pre> <p>That's the whole thing. A command to run the server and its arguments. Add it to your project, restart Claude, and the tools appear.</p>"},{"location":"reference/connections/mcps.html#adding-an-mcp-with-authentication","title":"Adding an MCP with authentication","text":"<p>Some MCPs need API keys. Use environment variables to keep secrets out of version control:</p> <pre><code>{\n  \"mcpServers\": {\n    \"slack\": {\n      \"command\": \"npx\",\n      \"args\": [\"-y\", \"@anthropic/mcp-server-slack\"],\n      \"env\": {\n        \"SLACK_BOT_TOKEN\": \"${SLACK_BOT_TOKEN}\"\n      }\n    }\n  }\n}\n</code></pre> <p>The <code>${SLACK_BOT_TOKEN}</code> pulls from your shell environment. The actual token never touches version control.</p>"},{"location":"reference/connections/mcps.html#adding-via-cli","title":"Adding via CLI","text":"<p>You can also add MCPs from the command line:</p> <pre><code>claude mcp add reddit -- npx -y @modelcontextprotocol/server-reddit\n</code></pre> <p>Or import your existing Claude Desktop configuration:</p> <pre><code>claude mcp add-from-claude-desktop\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"reference/connections/mcps.html#checking-your-mcps","title":"Checking your MCPs","text":"<p>Type <code>/mcp</code> inside Claude Code to see which servers are connected and their status.</p>"},{"location":"reference/connections/mcps.html#the-mcp-toolkit-for-pms","title":"The MCP toolkit for PMs","text":"<p>Here are the MCPs that matter most for product management work, organized by what they let you do:</p>"},{"location":"reference/connections/mcps.html#research-and-discovery","title":"Research and Discovery","text":"MCP What it does Why PMs care Reddit Search and read Reddit posts and comments Unfiltered user feedback, competitive intel, feature requests from real users Exa AI-native web search with semantic understanding Research that understands meaning, not just keywords Apify Web scraping and data extraction at scale Competitive analysis, pricing research, review mining Firecrawl Web crawling and page extraction Pull content from competitor sites, documentation, blogs"},{"location":"reference/connections/mcps.html#collaboration","title":"Collaboration","text":"MCP What it does Why PMs care Slack Read channels, post messages, search threads Zero context-switching. Paste a bug thread and say \"fix.\" Notion Read/write pages, sync documents Bridge between Claude's drafts and team collaboration Google Drive Read and edit Docs, Sheets, Slides Work on shared documents without leaving Claude"},{"location":"reference/connections/mcps.html#design-and-development","title":"Design and Development","text":"MCP What it does Why PMs care Figma Analyze designs, extract specs, generate code Design-to-spec without long annotated handoffs GitHub Issues, PRs, repos, code search Track what shipped, create tickets, review changes Playwright Browser automation, screenshots, testing Automated QA, UX testing, visual verification"},{"location":"reference/connections/mcps.html#data","title":"Data","text":"MCP What it does Why PMs care Google Analytics Run reports, check real-time data Pull metrics without switching to GA4 SQLite / PostgreSQL Query databases directly Build dashboards, validate hypotheses, pull user data Context7 Fetch version-aware documentation Ensures Claude has current library/framework knowledge"},{"location":"reference/connections/mcps.html#the-context-cost-problem","title":"The context cost problem","text":"<p>This is the thing most MCP guides skip. Every MCP server you enable consumes tokens from your context window even before you use it, because tool definitions load into context.</p> <p>One user discovered their MCPs consumed over 70,000 tokens just by being enabled:</p> <p>\"Yeah, I got a shock finding out that all my MCPs took &gt;70k tokens, that's insane.\"</p> <p>Your 200k context window can shrink to 130k before you type a word. That's not a theoretical concern. It directly impacts Claude's reasoning quality.</p>"},{"location":"reference/connections/mcps.html#how-to-manage-context-cost","title":"How to manage context cost","text":"Strategy How Impact Enable Tool Search Set <code>ENABLE_TOOL_SEARCH: \"true\"</code> in <code>~/.claude/settings.json</code> (see below) Tools load on-demand instead of all at once. Major savings. Disable unused MCPs Add to <code>disabledMcpServers</code> in your project config MCPs you don't need for this project stop eating context Prefer CLIs over MCPs Use <code>gh</code> instead of GitHub MCP for common operations Zero context cost vs. low context cost Monitor with /context Run <code>/context</code> regularly See exactly how much space MCPs are consuming Fewer than 10 per project Configure many globally, enable selectively per project Keep the active set small <p>To enable Tool Search, add this to your <code>~/.claude/settings.json</code>:</p> <pre><code>{\n  \"env\": {\n    \"ENABLE_TOOL_SEARCH\": \"true\"\n  }\n}\n</code></pre> <pre><code>flowchart TD\n    A[\"200k context window\"] --&gt; B[\"System prompt&lt;br/&gt;~15k tokens\"]\n    B --&gt; C[\"CLAUDE.md&lt;br/&gt;~5k tokens\"]\n    C --&gt; D{\"How many MCPs&lt;br/&gt;enabled?\"}\n    D --&gt;|\"2-3 MCPs\"| E[\"~10k tokens&lt;br/&gt;170k remaining\"]\n    D --&gt;|\"8-10 MCPs\"| F[\"~40k tokens&lt;br/&gt;140k remaining\"]\n    D --&gt;|\"15+ MCPs\"| G[\"~70k+ tokens&lt;br/&gt;115k remaining\"]\n\n    style A fill:#1e293b,color:#f8fafc,stroke:#374151\n    style E fill:#22c55e,color:#fff,stroke:#16a34a\n    style F fill:#eab308,color:#1e293b,stroke:#ca8a04\n    style G fill:#ef4444,color:#fff,stroke:#dc2626</code></pre> <p>The rule: Be intentional about which MCPs are active. More connections does not mean more power if they're eating the space Claude needs to think.</p>"},{"location":"reference/connections/mcps.html#mcp-skills-the-symbiotic-pair","title":"MCP + Skills: the symbiotic pair","text":"<p>A common source of confusion: MCPs and skills are different things that work together.</p> MCP (Connectivity) Skill (Expertise) Connects to your Jira instance Teaches Claude how to write good tickets Connects to Reddit Teaches Claude your competitive analysis framework Connects to Google Analytics Teaches Claude which metrics matter for your product Connects to Figma Teaches Claude how to extract design specs your way <p>MCP provides the pipes. Skills provide the expertise. When you build a workflow, ask two questions:</p> <ol> <li>What data or actions does Claude need access to? (Answer: MCP)</li> <li>What domain knowledge does Claude need to use that data well? (Answer: Skill)</li> </ol>"},{"location":"reference/connections/mcps.html#good-vs-bad-mcp-usage","title":"Good vs bad MCP usage","text":"Bad  Good Enable every MCP you can find \"just in case\" Enable only what you need for the current project Use the GitHub MCP for operations <code>gh</code> handles fine Use <code>gh</code> CLI for GitHub, save the MCP for services without CLIs Never check <code>/context</code> after adding MCPs Run <code>/context</code> after adding a new MCP to see the cost Store API keys directly in <code>.mcp.json</code> Use <code>${ENV_VAR}</code> references so secrets stay out of git Add MCPs at user scope when they're project-specific Use project-level <code>.mcp.json</code> for project tools, user-level for universal tools"},{"location":"reference/connections/mcps.html#security","title":"Security","text":"<p>Every MCP server runs code on your machine and can execute actions on your behalf. Take this seriously.</p> <ul> <li>Read the docs first. If you don't understand what an MCP does, don't enable it.</li> <li>Use the permission system. Claude asks for approval before MCP tool calls. Don't auto-approve tools you haven't vetted.</li> <li>Review team configs. If <code>.mcp.json</code> is in your repo, review it like any other code change.</li> <li>Principle of least privilege. Only enable what you actively need.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"reference/connections/mcps.html#plug-play","title":"Plug &amp; Play","text":"<p>Relevant skills:</p> <ul> <li>MCP configuration templates: Tooling &amp; Integrations</li> <li>Skills that pair with MCPs: Skills Library</li> </ul>"},{"location":"reference/connections/mcps.html#references","title":"References","text":"<p>Internal</p> <ul> <li>Lesson: L4 : Connect Claude to Everything</li> <li>Reference: Connections Overview : Decision framework for choosing connection types</li> <li>Reference: APIs : Building custom integrations when no MCP exists</li> <li>Reference: CLIs : When a CLI is the better choice</li> <li>Reference: Skills : Building : Pairing skills with MCP connections</li> </ul> <p>External</p> <ul> <li>Anthropic: MCP in Claude Code</li> <li>Anthropic: Claude Code Best Practices</li> </ul>"},{"location":"reference/skills/index.html","title":"Skills","text":"<p>Teach Claude Code repeatable workflows with slash commands.</p> <p>Skills are reusable markdown instructions that turn complex workflows into single commands. Type <code>/feature-brief</code> and Claude reads the template, gathers your input, drafts the brief, spins up reviewers, and saves everything to files. Type <code>/humanizer</code> and Claude rewrites your draft against 24 AI-writing patterns. One command, consistent output, every time.</p> <p>Without skills, you rebuild context from scratch every session. With skills, your best workflows are codified and ready to run.</p> <pre><code>%%{init: {'theme': 'dark'}}%%\nflowchart TD\n    A[\"CLAUDE.md\\n(always loaded)\"] --&gt; B[\"Skills\\n(loaded on demand)\"]\n    B --&gt; C[\"MCPs\\n(external tools)\"]\n    B --&gt; D[\"Sub-agents\\n(isolated execution)\"]\n\n    style A fill:#e63f02,color:#fff,stroke:#b43200\n    style B fill:#6366f1,color:#fff,stroke:#4f46e5\n    style C fill:#16a34a,color:#fff,stroke:#15803d\n    style D fill:#ca8a04,color:#fff,stroke:#a16207</code></pre> <p>CLAUDE.md gives Claude persistent context. Skills give Claude on-demand expertise. MCPs connect Claude to external tools. Sub-agents let skills delegate heavy work. Skills sit at the center, orchestrating all of it.</p>"},{"location":"reference/skills/index.html#what-is-in-this-section","title":"What is in this section","text":"<ul> <li> <p> Skill Types</p> <p>The five types of skills (generate, review, research, workflow, behavioral) and when to use each.</p> </li> <li> <p> Building Skills</p> <p>How to write a SKILL.md, structure the folder, write good descriptions, and handle activation.</p> </li> <li> <p> Advanced Techniques</p> <p>Progressive disclosure, AUQ, self-improvement, and composition. The techniques that make skills powerful.</p> </li> <li> <p> Skill Maintenance</p> <p>When to build a skill, when not to, the twice rule, lifecycle, and keeping skills healthy.</p> </li> <li> <p> The Skill Ecosystem</p> <p>Finding skills, sharing with your team, the plugin marketplace, and community sources.</p> </li> </ul>"},{"location":"reference/skills/index.html#references","title":"References","text":"<p>External:</p> <ul> <li>Anthropic: Skills documentation : Official reference for all frontmatter fields and behavior</li> <li>Anthropic: Claude Code best practices : Official guidance on structuring projects and skills</li> </ul>"},{"location":"reference/skills/advanced-techniques.html","title":"Advanced Techniques","text":"<p>The five ideas that take skills from \"convenient\" to \"this changes how I work.\"</p> <p>Quick Answer</p> <p>Use this when: You have built basic skills and want to make them dramatically more capable. These techniques layer on top of each other.</p> <p>Avoid this when: You are building your first skill. Start simple. Add techniques when the simple version is not enough.</p> <p>What CC changes: Skills stop being saved prompts and become systems. They ask you questions, load reference material on demand, learn from your feedback, and chain together into pipelines.</p> <p>Default move: Start with a text-only skill. Add progressive disclosure when you need reference files. Add AUQ when you need user input. Add composition when you need a pipeline.</p>"},{"location":"reference/skills/advanced-techniques.html#big-idea-1-progressive-disclosure-the-folder-architecture","title":"Big Idea 1: Progressive disclosure (the folder architecture)","text":"<p>Most simple skills are a single SKILL.md file. The moment a skill needs reference material (a template, examples, a style guide), you do not want to shove all of that into the SKILL.md.</p> <p>The SKILL.md should be the orchestration. Everything else lives in the folder.</p> <pre><code>Basic skill                     Skill with progressive disclosure\n-----------                     --------------------------------\nwrite-proposal/                 write-proposal/\n  SKILL.md                        SKILL.md           &lt;-- orchestrator\n  (everything                     template.md        &lt;-- reference doc\n   lives here)                    examples/\n                                    past-work.md     &lt;-- sample output\n</code></pre> <p>When Claude runs the skill, it reads the SKILL.md first for instructions, then pulls in the template and checks examples only when needed. A 20-page style guide in the folder costs zero tokens until Claude actually reads it.</p> <pre><code>%%{init: {'theme': 'dark'}}%%\nflowchart TD\n    S[\"/write-proposal\"] --&gt; SK[\"SKILL.md loads\\n(instructions only)\"]\n    SK --&gt; I[\"Read instructions\"]\n    I --&gt; N{\"Need reference?\"}\n    N --&gt;|\"Yes\"| R[\"Load template.md\\n(on demand)\"]\n    N --&gt;|\"No\"| W[\"Start working\"]\n    R --&gt; W\n\n    style S fill:#6366f1,color:#fff,stroke:#4f46e5\n    style SK fill:#374151,color:#f8fafc,stroke:#4b5563\n    style R fill:#16a34a,color:#fff,stroke:#15803d\n    style W fill:#ca8a04,color:#fff,stroke:#a16207</code></pre> <p>This is what makes skills better than CLAUDE.md. Your CLAUDE.md loads every session regardless of what you are doing. Skills load only when invoked. A project with 20 skills and a lean CLAUDE.md will outperform one with a 2,000-line CLAUDE.md every time.</p> <p>The test for when to use a folder:</p> Single file is fine Folder architecture is needed Everything is instruction logic: \"do this, then this, check for that\" You are embedding reference data: examples, templates, style guides, large rule sets Instructions are under 200 lines Instructions plus reference material would exceed 500 lines No supporting documents The skill needs a template, checklist, or example to produce good output <p>The rule: If you could remove a chunk from the SKILL.md and the logic still makes sense, that chunk is reference material and belongs in its own file.</p>"},{"location":"reference/skills/advanced-techniques.html#big-idea-2-skills-that-use-tools","title":"Big Idea 2: Skills that use tools","text":"<p>Skills can do more than generate text. They can use external tools: CLIs, scripts, APIs, anything installed on your system.</p> <p>MCPs and tools give Claude the ability to do things. Skills tell Claude how to do them well.</p> Tool gives ability Skill says how to use it pandoc converts documents <code>/convert-doc</code> converts with THIS template, THESE margins, THIS font git does version control <code>/sync-github</code> runs in THIS sequence with THIS commit message format Stripe CLI does billing <code>/stripe-invoice</code> creates invoices with THESE defaults web search finds information <code>/web-research</code> follows THIS research methodology and outputs in THIS format <p>Without the skill, if you said \"convert this to PDF,\" Claude would run pandoc with generic defaults. The skill says \"run pandoc with THIS template, THESE margins, THIS font.\" Consistent, polished output every time.</p> <p>The pattern: Skills that use tools have a <code>references/</code> or <code>scripts/</code> folder with the supporting files (CSS templates, Python scripts, configuration). The SKILL.md orchestrates when and how to use them.</p> <pre><code>convert-doc/\n  SKILL.md                  &lt;-- instructions: use pandoc with these options\n  templates/\n    clean-report.css        &lt;-- professional style\n    fun.css                 &lt;-- playful style\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"reference/skills/advanced-techniques.html#big-idea-3-skills-that-ask-auq","title":"Big Idea 3: Skills that ask (AUQ)","text":"<p>AskUserQuestion is a tool that lets Claude ask you structured questions in the terminal. Multiple-choice, single-select, multi-select. Embedding it inside a skill unlocks two very different patterns.</p>"},{"location":"reference/skills/advanced-techniques.html#pattern-1-mid-task-judgment-calls","title":"Pattern 1: Mid-task judgment calls","text":"<p>The skill asks you follow-up questions during its work, getting your judgment at exactly the right moment instead of guessing.</p> <p>Example: A meeting processing skill hits a gray area. Someone said \"we should probably look into that.\" Is that a real action item or just musing? Instead of guessing, the skill collects borderline items and asks you.</p> <pre><code>Processing meeting transcripts...\n\n3 clear action items found.\n2 borderline items need your judgment:\n\n&gt; \"We should probably look into the Salesforce integration timeline\"\n  Is this an action item?\n  (a) Yes, assign to someone\n  (b) No, just discussion\n  (c) Flag for next meeting\n</code></pre> <p>Your answer shapes the output. The result is better because the skill involved your judgment at the right moment.</p> <p>Other places this pattern works:</p> <ul> <li>A research skill asks which angle you care about before diving in</li> <li>A generate skill asks who the audience is before drafting</li> <li>A workflow skill confirms parameters before executing something irreversible</li> </ul>"},{"location":"reference/skills/advanced-techniques.html#pattern-2-first-run-setup","title":"Pattern 2: First-run setup","text":"<p>The skill checks if there is a config file in its folder. If there is not one (meaning it is the first time you are running it), it asks setup questions. It saves your answers to a config file. Next time it runs, it reads the config and skips straight to work.</p> <pre><code>First run:                      Second run:\n-----------                     -----------\nstandup/                        standup/\n  SKILL.md                        SKILL.md\n  (no config yet)                 config.json  &lt;-- YOUR answers\n\n\"What format?\"                  (no questions)\n\"What sections?\"                (reads config, generates immediately)\n\"How long?\"\n</code></pre> <p>AUQ just built the progressive disclosure layer for you. The skill asked questions, and those answers became a reference file in the folder. This is how skills learn what they need to know. The folder is how they remember it.</p>"},{"location":"reference/skills/advanced-techniques.html#auq-timing-matters","title":"AUQ timing matters","text":"When Pattern Example Before a task Setup questions, config First-run preferences, audience selection During a task Judgment calls Borderline items, ambiguous inputs After a task Confirmation \"Does this look right?\" before saving"},{"location":"reference/skills/advanced-techniques.html#big-idea-4-skills-that-grow-self-improvement","title":"Big Idea 4: Skills that grow (self-improvement)","text":"<p>Most skills produce the same output every time. A self-improving skill stores data in its folder and reads it on the next run. The folder becomes its memory.</p> <p>Example: <code>/writing-voice</code></p> <pre><code>Run 1:                          Run 5:\n------                          ------\nwriting-voice/                  writing-voice/\n  SKILL.md                        SKILL.md\n  corrections/                    corrections/\n    too-formal.md                   too-formal.md\n    avoid-lists.md                  avoid-lists.md\n                                    no-rhetorical-qs.md\n                                    more-contractions.md\n\nOutput: mostly generic          Output: sounds like YOU\n</code></pre> <p>Every time you run the skill and give feedback (\"too many rhetorical questions,\" \"not punchy enough\"), Claude saves a new correction to the <code>corrections/</code> folder. Next run, it reads all corrections and adjusts. The skill gets better without you rewriting the SKILL.md.</p> <p>The simpler version: a gotchas file. Instead of automatic correction logging, maintain a <code>gotchas.md</code> in the skill folder manually. Every time the skill makes a specific mistake, add a line. Claude reads it and avoids those mistakes. Less automated, more controlled.</p>  Static skill  Self-improving skill Same output regardless of how many times you run it Output improves based on accumulated corrections You rewrite the SKILL.md when the output is wrong You give feedback, and a correction file captures it Your preferences are guessed Your preferences are learned from real usage <p>What makes this possible: The folder architecture. Without the folder, the skill has no memory. The corrections folder is progressive disclosure that accumulates over time.</p>"},{"location":"reference/skills/advanced-techniques.html#big-idea-5-skills-that-chain-composition","title":"Big Idea 5: Skills that chain (composition)","text":"<p>Everything so far makes a single skill more powerful. Composition connects skills into pipelines. One skill calls other skills.</p> <p>Example: <code>/draft-and-humanize</code></p> <pre><code>%%{init: {'theme': 'dark'}}%%\nflowchart LR\n    D[\"/draft-and-humanize\"] --&gt; F[\"/draft-followups\\n(generates messages)\"]\n    F --&gt; H[\"/humanizer\\n(cleans AI patterns)\"]\n    H --&gt; R[\"Polished messages\\none command\"]\n\n    style D fill:#6366f1,color:#fff,stroke:#4f46e5\n    style F fill:#16a34a,color:#fff,stroke:#15803d\n    style H fill:#ca8a04,color:#fff,stroke:#a16207\n    style R fill:#374151,color:#f8fafc,stroke:#4b5563</code></pre> <p>Each piece is still usable on its own. But the composition skill connects them so you do not run them manually in sequence.</p> <p>Common composition patterns:</p> Pattern How it works Research + Generate Gather information, then produce a document Generate + Review Draft something, then critique it (builder-validator) Workflow + Generate Complete a process, then summarize what happened Generate + Review + Workflow Draft, validate, then save/send/publish <p>Composition does not use the folder architecture. It is purely orchestration. The SKILL.md coordinates other skills. No reference files needed.</p> <p>The limitation: No formal dependency management yet. If a referenced skill is not installed, the composition fails. Keep this in mind when sharing composition skills.</p>"},{"location":"reference/skills/advanced-techniques.html#how-the-techniques-layer","title":"How the techniques layer","text":"<p>These five ideas build on each other. You do not need all of them. Start simple and add layers as the simple version proves insufficient.</p> <pre><code>%%{init: {'theme': 'dark'}}%%\nflowchart TD\n    T[\"Text-only SKILL.md\\n(start here)\"]\n    T --&gt;|\"Need reference files?\"| PD[\"Add progressive disclosure\\n(folder architecture)\"]\n    T --&gt;|\"Need user input?\"| AUQ[\"Add AUQ\\n(questions + config)\"]\n    PD --&gt;|\"Need external tools?\"| TOOLS[\"Add tool integration\\n(scripts, CLIs, APIs)\"]\n    AUQ --&gt;|\"Need to learn over time?\"| SI[\"Add self-improvement\\n(corrections folder)\"]\n    T --&gt;|\"Need a pipeline?\"| COMP[\"Add composition\\n(chain skills together)\"]\n\n    style T fill:#374151,color:#f8fafc,stroke:#4b5563\n    style PD fill:#16a34a,color:#fff,stroke:#15803d\n    style AUQ fill:#ca8a04,color:#fff,stroke:#a16207\n    style TOOLS fill:#6366f1,color:#fff,stroke:#4f46e5\n    style SI fill:#9333ea,color:#fff,stroke:#7e22ce\n    style COMP fill:#0891b2,color:#fff,stroke:#0e7490</code></pre>"},{"location":"reference/skills/advanced-techniques.html#plug-play","title":"Plug &amp; Play","text":"<p><code>/write-proposal</code> Progressive disclosure in action. SKILL.md orchestrates, template and examples live in the folder.</p> <p><code>/humanizer</code> Self-improving review skill. 400+ lines of rules, correction accumulation over time.</p> <p><code>/meeting-aftermath</code> Full composition. Orchestrates 6 sub-skills: process transcript, reality-check, update people, update actions, draft follow-ups, status update.</p> <p><code>/standup</code> AUQ first-run setup. Asks preferences on first run, saves config, skips to work on subsequent runs.</p>"},{"location":"reference/skills/advanced-techniques.html#references","title":"References","text":"<p>Internal:</p> <ul> <li>Building Skills : The fundamentals of SKILL.md structure before adding advanced techniques</li> <li>Skill Types : The five types that these techniques enhance</li> <li>Skill Maintenance : When to add complexity and when to keep it simple</li> <li>Sub-agents : How skills use sub-agents for validation and parallel work</li> </ul> <p>External:</p> <ul> <li>Anthropic: Skills documentation : Official reference for frontmatter fields including allowed-tools and context</li> <li>Anthropic: Hooks reference : For building activation hooks that improve skill triggering</li> <li>Anthropic: Claude Code best practices : Structuring complex workflows</li> </ul>"},{"location":"reference/skills/building.html","title":"Building Skills","text":"<p>Skills are markdown files that give Claude Code expertise on demand. Instead of cramming everything into CLAUDE.md, you write focused skills that load only when needed. A skill is a YAML header plus instructions in a <code>SKILL.md</code> file inside <code>.claude/skills/</code>.</p> <p>Quick Answer</p> <p>Use this when: You find yourself rebuilding the same context or repeating the same instructions across sessions.</p> <p>Avoid this when: You only need something once. Just prompt it. Build the skill the second time.</p> <p>What CC changes: Skills turn tribal knowledge into reusable, shareable tools. What used to live in your head (or a Google Doc nobody reads) becomes something Claude can execute consistently.</p> <p>Default move: Start with a text-only skill. Add references, tools, and code only when the simple version isn't enough.</p>"},{"location":"reference/skills/building.html#the-anatomy-of-a-skill","title":"The Anatomy of a Skill","text":"<p>Every skill is a <code>SKILL.md</code> file inside a named folder in <code>.claude/skills/</code>:</p> <pre><code>.claude/skills/\n  feature-brief/\n    SKILL.md        \u2190 this is the skill\n</code></pre> <p>The file has two parts: YAML frontmatter and markdown instructions.</p> <pre><code>---\nname: feature-brief\ndescription: \"This skill should be used when the user wants to draft\n  a feature brief from product notes or meeting transcripts.\"\n---\n\n## Instructions\n\nRead the product notes in the current directory. Draft a feature brief\ncovering: problem statement, proposed solution, success metrics, risks,\nand open questions.\n\nUse bullet points for risks and open questions. Keep the brief under\n2 pages.\n</code></pre> <p>That's a working skill. You can run it right now with <code>/feature-brief</code>.</p>"},{"location":"reference/skills/building.html#frontmatter-fields","title":"Frontmatter Fields","text":"<p>The YAML header controls how your skill behaves. Only <code>description</code> really matters. Everything else is optional.</p> Field What It Does When You Need It <code>name</code> Display name (lowercase, hyphens, max 64 chars) Always include for clarity <code>description</code> Tells Claude what this skill does and when to use it Always. This is the most important field <code>allowed-tools</code> Restricts which tools Claude can use When the skill should only read, or only write, or never run code <code>disable-model-invocation</code> Forces manual <code>/name</code> invocation only Sensitive operations you don't want auto-triggered <code>user-invocable</code> Set to <code>false</code> to hide from the <code>/</code> menu Reference files that other skills read, not standalone commands <code>argument-hint</code> Shows hint text during autocomplete When the skill takes an argument like a file path or topic <code>model</code> Force a specific model When you need Opus for quality or Haiku for speed <code>context</code> Set to <code>fork</code> to run in an isolated subagent When the skill shouldn't see or pollute conversation history"},{"location":"reference/skills/building.html#the-description-field-matters-more-than-you-think","title":"The Description Field Matters More Than You Think","text":"<p>The description controls whether Claude auto-triggers your skill when a user says something relevant. A vague description means Claude won't know when to suggest it. A specific one means it works like magic.</p>  Bad  Good \"Process documents\" \"This skill should be used when the user wants to process meeting transcripts and extract action items, decisions, and follow-ups with owners and deadlines\" \"Help with research\" \"This skill should be used when the user wants to design a user research study, including assumption surfacing, interview guide design, and research plan compilation\" \"Writing tool\" \"This skill should be used when the user wants to rewrite AI-generated text to sound more human, removing filler words, cliches, and generic phrasing\" <p>Write descriptions in third person: \"This skill should be used when...\" Include the specific keywords a user would naturally say.</p> <p>CC Limitation</p> <p>Even with a perfect description, auto-triggering is unreliable (about 20% of the time by default). For important skills, use manual <code>/skill-name</code> invocation. If you need higher auto-trigger rates, look into forced evaluation hooks.</p>"},{"location":"reference/skills/building.html#file-structure-patterns","title":"File Structure Patterns","text":"<p>A simple skill is just a <code>SKILL.md</code>. As skills get more complex, you add reference files that load on demand.</p>"},{"location":"reference/skills/building.html#simple-skill-most-skills-start-here","title":"Simple skill (most skills start here)","text":"<pre><code>feature-brief/\n  SKILL.md\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"reference/skills/building.html#skill-with-references","title":"Skill with references","text":"<pre><code>feature-brief/\n  SKILL.md              \u2190 orchestrates everything\n  references/\n    template.md         \u2190 loads only when skill runs\n    examples.md         \u2190 good/bad examples for Claude to follow\n    style-guide.md      \u2190 voice and formatting rules\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"reference/skills/building.html#skill-with-code","title":"Skill with code","text":"<pre><code>data-check/\n  SKILL.md\n  scripts/\n    validate.py         \u2190 Claude can run this\n  references/\n    thresholds.md       \u2190 acceptable ranges, rules\n</code></pre> <p>The key pattern: SKILL.md tells Claude what to do and where to find supporting files. Claude only loads those files when it needs them. This keeps your context window clean. A skill with 5 reference files doesn't cost anything until you actually run it.</p> <pre><code>flowchart TD\n    S[\"/feature-brief\"] --&gt; SK[SKILL.md loads]\n    SK --&gt; I[Read instructions]\n    I --&gt; N{Need reference?}\n    N --&gt;|Yes| R[Load references/template.md]\n    N --&gt;|No| W[Start working]\n    R --&gt; W</code></pre> <p>CC Advantage</p> <p>Progressive loading is what makes skills better than putting everything in CLAUDE.md. Your CLAUDE.md loads every session regardless of what you're doing. Skills load only when invoked. A project with 20 skills and a lean CLAUDE.md will outperform one with a 2,000-line CLAUDE.md every time.</p>"},{"location":"reference/skills/building.html#writing-good-instructions","title":"Writing Good Instructions","text":"<p>The markdown body of SKILL.md is where you tell Claude what to do. Write it like you're giving instructions to a smart colleague who's never done this specific task.</p>  Bad  Good \"Write a good feature brief\" \"Read the product notes in the current directory. Draft a feature brief with these sections: Problem Statement, Proposed Solution, Success Metrics, Risks, Open Questions. Use bullet points for risks. Keep it under 2 pages.\" \"Analyze the data and make charts\" \"Read the CSV files in data/. For each metric, create a Jupyter notebook cell with a chart. Use line charts for trends, bar charts for comparisons. Include a markdown cell above each chart explaining what it shows.\" \"Help me write better\" \"Read the draft the user provides. Flag: filler words (just, very, really, actually), passive voice, sentences over 25 words, cliches, and jargon. For each issue, show the original and a rewrite.\" <p>The pattern: be specific about inputs (what to read), outputs (what to produce), and format (how to structure it).</p>"},{"location":"reference/skills/building.html#variables-for-dynamic-input","title":"Variables for Dynamic Input","text":"<p>Skills support variable substitution:</p> <pre><code>---\nname: scope-feature\nargument-hint: \"&lt;feature-name&gt;\"\n---\n\nThe user wants to scope the feature: $ARGUMENTS\n\nRead the codebase and produce a scoping brief covering:\n- Affected files and modules\n- New components needed\n- Existing patterns to reuse\n- Estimated complexity\n</code></pre> <p>Now <code>/scope-feature dark mode toggle</code> passes \"dark mode toggle\" as the argument.</p>"},{"location":"reference/skills/building.html#inject-live-data-with-shell-commands","title":"Inject Live Data with Shell Commands","text":"<p>Use <code>!command</code> syntax to pull in live context before Claude sees the skill. The commands go in the markdown body of your SKILL.md:</p> <pre><code>---\nname: pr-summary\ndescription: \"This skill should be used when the user wants a summary of recent changes.\"\n---\n\n## Current State\n\n!git status --short\n\n## Recent Changes\n\n!git log --oneline -10\n\n## Instructions\n\nSummarize the recent changes above into a brief status update...\n</code></pre> <p>Claude sees the output of these commands as part of the skill. This is how you build skills that react to the current state of your project, like a PR summary skill that reads the actual diff.</p>"},{"location":"reference/skills/building.html#restricting-tool-access","title":"Restricting Tool Access","text":"<p>By default, a skill can use any tool Claude has access to. Use <code>allowed-tools</code> to limit what it can do.</p> <pre><code>---\nname: code-review\nallowed-tools: Read, Grep, Glob\n---\n</code></pre> <p>This skill can read and search files but can't edit anything.</p> Scenario Allowed Tools Why Review/audit <code>Read, Grep, Glob</code> Analyze without modifying Document generation <code>Read, Write</code> Create files, don't edit existing ones Research <code>Read, WebSearch, WebFetch</code> Gather info, don't touch the codebase Full workflow (don't set this field) Let Claude use whatever it needs <p>CC Limitation</p> <p>Listing a tool in <code>allowed-tools</code> gives Claude access without asking for user permission. If your skill lists <code>Bash</code>, Claude can run shell commands without confirmation. Be intentional about what you grant.</p>"},{"location":"reference/skills/building.html#activation-why-skills-dont-always-trigger","title":"Activation: Why Skills Don't Always Trigger","text":"<p>By default, Claude decides whether to suggest a skill based on the description matching what the user said. This works about 20% of the time. That's not a bug, it's just how LLM-based matching works with many skills competing for attention.</p> <p>Your options, from least to most reliable:</p> Approach Reliability How It Works Auto-trigger (default) ~20% Claude matches description to user input Manual <code>/skill-name</code> 100% User types the command directly Forced evaluation hook ~84% A hook forces Claude to evaluate each skill YES/NO before responding <p>Forced evaluation hooks use Claude Code's hooks system to intercept every prompt and check it against your skill descriptions. See the Anthropic hooks guide for setup.</p> <p>For most PM workflows, just use manual invocation. Type <code>/feature-brief</code> instead of hoping Claude suggests it. Save hook-based activation for teams with dozens of skills where discovery matters.</p>"},{"location":"reference/skills/building.html#the-graduation-path","title":"The Graduation Path","text":"<p>Not everything needs to be a skill. Here's when to move context from one level to the next:</p> <pre><code>flowchart TD\n    A[\"One-time prompt\"] --&gt;|\"Doing it again?\"| B[\"Skill\"]\n    B --&gt;|\"Need external data?\"| C[\"Skill + MCP\"]\n    B --&gt;|\"Need isolation?\"| D[\"Skill + Subagent\"]\n    A --&gt;|\"Always needed?\"| E[\"CLAUDE.md\"]\n    E --&gt;|\"Over 500 lines?\"| B</code></pre> <p>The rule: If you're rebuilding the same context more than once, make it a skill. If your CLAUDE.md is over 500 lines, move reference sections into skills. Skills are cheaper on context and easier to maintain.</p>"},{"location":"reference/skills/building.html#skill-scoping","title":"Skill Scoping","text":"<p>Skills can live at different levels depending on who needs them:</p> Scope Location Who Sees It Use Case Personal <code>~/.claude/skills/</code> All your projects Cross-project workflows (your writing voice, daily standup) Project <code>.claude/skills/</code> in repo Everyone who clones the repo Codebase-specific tools (PR template, deploy checklist) Plugin Installed via plugin system Where plugin is installed Distributed skill packs <p>Project-level skills committed to git mean everyone on your team gets the same tools automatically when they clone the repo.</p>"},{"location":"reference/skills/building.html#common-mistakes","title":"Common Mistakes","text":"Mistake Why It Happens What to Do Instead Monolithic SKILL.md Trying to handle everything in one file Keep SKILL.md under 500 lines. Move reference material to <code>references/</code> Vague description \"Helps with tasks\" Be specific: what it does, when to use it, in third person One big skill instead of several focused ones Feels simpler to maintain Chunk it. <code>/voice-linkedin</code> and <code>/voice-newsletter</code> beat one generic <code>/voice</code> Everything in CLAUDE.md Doesn't know about skills yet Move on-demand knowledge to skills. CLAUDE.md is for always-on context only Over-broad tool access Didn't think about it Set <code>allowed-tools</code> to the minimum the skill needs Fighting auto-trigger It \"should just work\" It won't, reliably. Use manual <code>/skill-name</code> for important workflows"},{"location":"reference/skills/building.html#plug-play","title":"Plug &amp; Play","text":"<p>Example skills from the course you can study and adapt:</p> <p><code>/feature-brief</code> Simple generate skill. Takes product notes, outputs a structured brief. Good starting template.</p> <p><code>/mom-test-filter</code> Review skill with specific criteria. Scans interview guides against three principles and rewrites violations.</p> <p><code>/meeting-aftermath</code> Composition skill. Orchestrates 6 sub-skills in sequence (process transcript, reality-check, update people, update actions, draft follow-ups, status update).</p> <p><code>/humanizer</code> Behavioral skill. Changes how Claude writes by loading specific rules about what to avoid and what to do instead.</p>"},{"location":"reference/skills/building.html#references","title":"References","text":"<p>Internal:</p> <ul> <li>Skill Types : The five types (generate, review, research, workflow, behavioral) and when to use each</li> <li>Advanced Techniques : Progressive disclosure, AUQ, self-improvement, composition</li> <li>Skill Maintenance : When to build a skill, when not to, and keeping skills healthy</li> <li>Skill Ecosystem :Finding, sharing, and distributing skills</li> <li>CLAUDE.md :When to use CLAUDE.md vs. skills</li> <li>Sub-agents :Running skills in isolated context with <code>context: fork</code></li> </ul> <p>External:</p> <ul> <li>Anthropic: Skills documentation : Official reference for all frontmatter fields and behavior</li> <li>Anthropic: Claude Code best practices : Official guidance on structuring projects and skills</li> <li>Claude Skills: 36 Examples : Community collection of real-world skill examples</li> <li>How I Use Every Claude Code Feature : Shrivu Shankar's practitioner walkthrough including skills</li> <li>Anthropic: Hooks reference : For building activation hooks that improve skill triggering</li> </ul>"},{"location":"reference/skills/ecosystem.html","title":"The Skill Ecosystem","text":"<p>You do not have to build everything from scratch. Hundreds of skills already exist.</p> <p>Quick Answer</p> <p>Use this when: You need a skill and want to check if someone already built it, or you want to share your skills with your team.</p> <p>Avoid this when: You are looking for a very specific, customized workflow. Build that yourself.</p> <p>What CC changes: Skills are portable markdown files. No vendor lock-in, no app store approval, no proprietary format. The same skill works in Claude Code, Cursor, and Windsurf. The ecosystem is open.</p> <p>Default move: Check the official marketplace first, then skills.sh, then GitHub repos. Always read the SKILL.md before running a third-party skill.</p>"},{"location":"reference/skills/ecosystem.html#skills-are-portable","title":"Skills are portable","text":"<p>Skills are just markdown files in folders. That means they work everywhere:</p> <ul> <li>Claude Code</li> <li>Cursor</li> <li>Windsurf</li> </ul> <p>Version them in git. Move them between jobs. Share them with your team. No proprietary format locks you in.</p> <p>This portability is what makes the ecosystem possible. Anyone can build, share, and remix skills. No app store approval process.</p>"},{"location":"reference/skills/ecosystem.html#where-to-find-skills","title":"Where to find skills","text":"<p>There are three places to look, each with a different trade-off.</p> <pre><code>%%{init: {'theme': 'dark'}}%%\nflowchart LR\n    M[\"Official Marketplace\\n(curated)\"] --&gt; S[\"skills.sh\\n(community gallery)\"]\n    S --&gt; G[\"GitHub Repos\\n(uncurated)\"]\n\n    style M fill:#16a34a,color:#fff,stroke:#15803d\n    style S fill:#ca8a04,color:#fff,stroke:#a16207\n    style G fill:#6366f1,color:#fff,stroke:#4f46e5</code></pre>"},{"location":"reference/skills/ecosystem.html#1-the-official-marketplace","title":"1. The official marketplace","text":"<p>Claude Code has a built-in plugin marketplace. Access it with <code>/plugins</code>:</p> <ol> <li>Type <code>/plugins</code> and hit enter</li> <li>Tab over to Marketplaces</li> <li>Arrow down to claude-plugins-official</li> <li>Hit Enter, then select Browse plugins</li> </ol> <p>You will see skills and plugins you can install directly. During installation, you choose a scope:</p> Scope Where it installs Who sees it User <code>~/.claude/plugins/cache/</code> Available in all your projects Project <code>.claude/skills/</code> in the repo Everyone who clones the repo Local Local to you, local to this repo Just you, just here <p>Recommended: Start with user scope for personal tools. Use project scope for team skills.</p>"},{"location":"reference/skills/ecosystem.html#2-skillssh-community-gallery","title":"2. skills.sh (community gallery)","text":"<p>skills.sh is a community site run by Vercel. Browse by category, see what is popular, and install with a command:</p> <pre><code>npx skills add &lt;github-url&gt; --skill &lt;name&gt;\n</code></pre> <p>The interactive UI lets you select which agents to install to (Claude Code, Cursor, etc.).</p>"},{"location":"reference/skills/ecosystem.html#3-github-repos","title":"3. GitHub repos","text":"<p>Skills are shared on GitHub. People publish personal collections, companies open-source internal skills, and there are curated lists.</p> <p>Notable collections:</p> <ul> <li>Daniel Avila's claude-code-templates (700+ skills)</li> <li>obra's superpowers (developer workflow skills)</li> <li>Various personal skill repos shared in the Claude Code community</li> </ul> <p>The trade-off: No curation. Use trusted marketplaces when you can. For unfamiliar repos, inspect the skill before running it.</p>"},{"location":"reference/skills/ecosystem.html#evaluating-third-party-skills","title":"Evaluating third-party skills","text":"<p>Before you trust a skill you did not build, check three things:</p> Check What to look for Red flag Read the SKILL.md Clear instructions, well-structured, specific criteria Vague instructions, just a saved prompt with no real logic Check <code>allowed-tools</code> Only the tools the skill legitimately needs <code>Bash</code> access when the skill is just a text generator Inspect the folder Reference files, templates, examples Scripts you do not understand, unexplained executables <p>After passing inspection: Run it on something low-stakes first. Do not run a new skill on real work until you have seen what it produces.</p>"},{"location":"reference/skills/ecosystem.html#skill-scoping-levels","title":"Skill scoping levels","text":"<p>Skills can live at different levels depending on who needs them:</p> Scope Location Who sees it Best for Personal <code>~/.claude/skills/</code> All your projects Cross-project workflows (your writing voice, daily standup) Project <code>.claude/skills/</code> in repo Everyone who clones the repo Codebase-specific tools (PR template, deploy checklist) Plugin Installed via plugin system Where the plugin is installed Distributed skill packs from the community <p>Project-level skills committed to git mean everyone on your team gets the same tools automatically when they clone the repo.</p>"},{"location":"reference/skills/ecosystem.html#sharing-your-skills","title":"Sharing your skills","text":""},{"location":"reference/skills/ecosystem.html#option-1-skills-in-a-repo-simple","title":"Option 1: Skills in a repo (simple)","text":"<p>Put skills in <code>.claude/skills/</code> in a project repo. Anyone who clones the repo gets all the skills automatically. When someone updates a skill, everyone gets the update on their next pull.</p> <p>Best for: Small teams, single-project workflows, getting started quickly.</p>"},{"location":"reference/skills/ecosystem.html#option-2-a-team-marketplace-scalable","title":"Option 2: A team marketplace (scalable)","text":"<p>You can add your own marketplace to Claude Code. It is a Git repo with a <code>.claude-plugin/marketplace.json</code> file. Your teammates add the same URL with <code>/plugin marketplace add</code>, and then they browse and install individual skills, just like the official marketplace.</p> <p>Best for: Organizations with many skills, teams where people need to pick and choose.</p> <pre><code>Repo approach                    Marketplace approach\n--------------                   --------------------\n.claude/skills/ in your repo     A browsable catalog\n\n+ Simple: clone and go           + Pick and choose what to install\n+ Versioned through git          + Scales to lots of skills/people\n- Everyone gets ALL skills       - More setup to get going\n- No pick-and-choose             - Someone needs to maintain it\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"reference/skills/ecosystem.html#rolling-this-out-at-your-company","title":"Rolling this out at your company","text":"<p>If your company is not already doing this, there is a real opportunity. Being the person who sets up a skills system for your team is a visible, high-impact move.</p> <p>The practical steps:</p> <ol> <li>Start with the repo approach. Pick 3-5 skills that would help your team. Put them in <code>.claude/skills/</code> in a shared repo.</li> <li>Get 2-3 people using them. The skills sell themselves once people see the output.</li> <li>Collect feedback. What is working? What is not? What else do people want?</li> <li>Graduate to a marketplace if the collection grows past 10-15 skills.</li> </ol> <p>This is the kind of thing that gets noticed by leadership. You are not just using AI tools. You are building the infrastructure for your team to use them well.</p>"},{"location":"reference/skills/ecosystem.html#common-mistakes","title":"Common mistakes","text":"Mistake What to do instead Installing every skill you find Install only what you will use this week. Unused skills add noise to auto-matching Running third-party skills without reading them Always read the SKILL.md and check <code>allowed-tools</code> before the first run Sharing skills without cleaning them up Document assumptions, test in a clean environment, clean up the description Waiting for the \"perfect\" setup before sharing Start with 3 skills in a shared repo. Iterate from there"},{"location":"reference/skills/ecosystem.html#plug-play","title":"Plug &amp; Play","text":"<p><code>/skill-creator</code> Meta-skill that helps you build other skills. Available in the official marketplace. A good first install.</p>"},{"location":"reference/skills/ecosystem.html#references","title":"References","text":"<p>Internal:</p> <ul> <li>Building Skills : How to write skills before sharing them</li> <li>Skill Maintenance : Keeping shared skills healthy</li> <li>Skill Types : Understanding what type of skill you are looking at</li> </ul> <p>External:</p> <ul> <li>Anthropic: Skills documentation : Official reference including plugin and marketplace setup</li> <li>Anthropic: Claude Code best practices : Team workflow patterns</li> <li>skills.sh : Community skill gallery</li> </ul>"},{"location":"reference/skills/skill-maintenance.html","title":"Skill Maintenance","text":"<p>Not everything should be a skill. And the skills you build need care.</p> <p>Quick Answer</p> <p>Use this when: You are deciding whether to build a skill, or you have existing skills that might be stale.</p> <p>Avoid this when: You are mid-build. Finish the skill first, then apply maintenance thinking.</p> <p>What CC changes: Skills are living documents, not set-and-forget configurations. The difference between someone who uses skills well and someone who wastes time on them is knowing where the line is.</p> <p>Default move: The twice rule. Do it once by prompting. Do it a second time and it is a skill. Review your skills monthly.</p>"},{"location":"reference/skills/skill-maintenance.html#the-decision-framework","title":"The decision framework","text":"<p>Not everything should be a skill. Most things should not be. There are four buckets, and three of them are not \"make a skill.\"</p> <pre><code>%%{init: {'theme': 'dark'}}%%\nflowchart TD\n    Q[\"What is this task?\"]\n    Q --&gt;|\"One-off\"| P[\"Just prompt it\"]\n    Q --&gt;|\"Short, universal preference\"| C[\"Put it in CLAUDE.md\"]\n    Q --&gt;|\"Complex + repeated\"| S[\"Make it a skill\"]\n    Q --&gt;|\"CLAUDE.md is bloated\"| M[\"Move reference to skills\"]\n\n    style Q fill:#374151,color:#f8fafc,stroke:#4b5563\n    style P fill:#6366f1,color:#fff,stroke:#4f46e5\n    style C fill:#ca8a04,color:#fff,stroke:#a16207\n    style S fill:#16a34a,color:#fff,stroke:#15803d\n    style M fill:#0891b2,color:#fff,stroke:#0e7490</code></pre> Bucket When it applies Example Just prompt it You need it once. No skill needed. Just ask A one-off summary, a quick email draft, a format conversion Put it in CLAUDE.md Short, universal preferences that apply to everything \"Use bullet points,\" preferred tone, team names, key paths Make it a skill Complex, multi-step, and you do it regularly Meeting processing, proposal writing, standup generation Move to skills Your CLAUDE.md is over 500 lines and loading too much Break reference material into on-demand skill folders"},{"location":"reference/skills/skill-maintenance.html#the-filtering-questions","title":"The filtering questions","text":"<p>Before building a skill, ask:</p> <ol> <li>Have I done this more than once? If not, just prompt it. Build the skill the second time.</li> <li>Is it complex enough to codify? A skill that says \"summarize this\" is not worth maintaining. A skill with a specific format, criteria, and multi-step process is.</li> <li>Will I use it this month? If not, it is a future problem. Solve present problems first.</li> </ol>"},{"location":"reference/skills/skill-maintenance.html#the-twice-rule","title":"The twice rule","text":"<p>This is the most opinionated guidance in this section. Follow it.</p> <p>Do it once by prompting. If you do it a second time, make it a skill.</p> <p>The first time you do something, you are still figuring out the workflow. You do not know what format works best, what inputs matter, or what steps are essential. Codifying too early means codifying the wrong thing.</p> <p>The second time, you have a pattern. You know what worked and what did not. Now you have something worth preserving.</p>  Bad  Good Build a skill for something you have done once Prompt it the first time. Observe what works. Build the skill the second time Build a skill for something you do once a quarter Just prompt it. Quarterly is not worth the maintenance overhead Build 15 skills before you have used any of them Build the one skill that saves you the most time this week"},{"location":"reference/skills/skill-maintenance.html#the-setup-trap","title":"The setup trap","text":"<p>There is a joke in the Claude Code community:</p> <p>\"Bro I spent all weekend in Claude Code.\" \"Oh nice, what did you build?\" \"Dude my setup is crazy.\"</p> <p>The gut check:</p> <ul> <li>If you are spending more time building skills than using them to get work done, you have crossed the line</li> <li>A skill should save you time, not become a project of its own</li> <li>Start with the one skill that would save you the most time this week, not the most interesting one to build</li> </ul> <p>The test: Would you explain this skill to your manager? \"I automated our meeting processing\" is a good answer. \"I spent three days building a skill that generates commit messages\" is not.</p>"},{"location":"reference/skills/skill-maintenance.html#skills-need-care","title":"Skills need care","text":"<p>Skills do not stay good forever. Three things happen over time:</p> <ol> <li> <p>Your process changes. What you needed three months ago is not what you need now. A stakeholder update format that worked in Q1 might not match Q2's reporting structure.</p> </li> <li> <p>Claude gets better. Something that needed detailed instructions before might just work with a simple prompt now. Older skills can actually constrain Claude from using newer, better capabilities.</p> </li> <li> <p>Tools update. MCPs add features, CLIs change flags, APIs change endpoints. A skill that hardcodes a specific CLI flag that no longer exists will break.</p> </li> </ol> <p>The maintenance loop:</p> <pre><code>%%{init: {'theme': 'dark'}}%%\nflowchart LR\n    B[\"Build\"] --&gt; U[\"Use\"]\n    U --&gt; R[\"Review\\n(monthly)\"]\n    R --&gt;|\"Still useful\"| UP[\"Update\"]\n    R --&gt;|\"No longer needed\"| RT[\"Retire\"]\n    UP --&gt; U\n    RT --&gt; D[\"Delete\"]\n\n    style B fill:#16a34a,color:#fff,stroke:#15803d\n    style U fill:#ca8a04,color:#fff,stroke:#a16207\n    style R fill:#6366f1,color:#fff,stroke:#4f46e5\n    style UP fill:#16a34a,color:#fff,stroke:#15803d\n    style RT fill:#dc2626,color:#fff,stroke:#b91c1c\n    style D fill:#374151,color:#f8fafc,stroke:#4b5563</code></pre> <ul> <li>Check in monthly. Run your skills and see if the output still matches what you want</li> <li>Update the ones you use. Edit the SKILL.md when your process changes</li> <li>Retire the ones you do not. Every unused skill is noise. Fewer skills means better matching when Claude reads descriptions at session start</li> </ul>"},{"location":"reference/skills/skill-maintenance.html#how-many-skills-is-too-many","title":"How many skills is too many?","text":"<p>There is no hard limit, but there is a practical one. Claude reads every skill description at session start to know what is available. More descriptions means more noise and worse matching.</p> Number of skills What happens 3-5 active skills Clean, focused. Claude matches well. Low maintenance overhead 10-15 skills Fine if you use most of them. Some description noise 20+ skills Claude's auto-matching degrades. Manual <code>/skill-name</code> invocation becomes necessary. Maintenance burden grows <p>The audit question: If you have 15 skills and only use 4 regularly, retire the unused ones. They are clutter, not insurance.</p>"},{"location":"reference/skills/skill-maintenance.html#when-not-to-build-a-skill","title":"When NOT to build a skill","text":"Situation Why not What to do instead You have only done it once You do not know the pattern yet Prompt it. Build the skill the second time The task is simple and short The skill adds overhead without saving time Just prompt it CLAUDE.md already handles it well Adding a skill creates two places to maintain the same instructions Leave it in CLAUDE.md You want to impress someone Skills are tools, not trophies Build what saves time, not what looks cool The \"skill\" is just a saved prompt with no logic A command (<code>.claude/commands/</code>) is simpler for this Use a command instead"},{"location":"reference/skills/skill-maintenance.html#skill-retirement-checklist","title":"Skill retirement checklist","text":"<p>When a skill has not been used in a month, ask these questions:</p> <ol> <li>Have I used it in the last 30 days? If no, it is a retirement candidate.</li> <li>Would I notice if it disappeared? If no, delete it.</li> <li>Is the problem it solves still a problem? Processes change. If the meeting format changed, the meeting-processing skill might need a rewrite or retirement.</li> <li>Could Claude handle this with a simple prompt now? Claude gets better over time. What needed a 200-line skill six months ago might be achievable with a 2-line prompt today.</li> </ol> <p>If a skill fails the checklist, delete the folder. You can always rebuild it if the need returns. Stale skills are worse than no skills.</p>"},{"location":"reference/skills/skill-maintenance.html#before-you-share-a-skill","title":"Before you share a skill","text":"<p>Skills are built for your context -- your assumptions, your file structure, your preferences. Before sharing:</p> <ol> <li>Clean up the description. Make it clear what the skill does and when to use it. Write in third person: \"This skill should be used when...\"</li> <li>Document assumptions. What files does it expect? What tools does it need? What naming conventions does it assume?</li> <li>Test it in a clean environment. Does it work without your CLAUDE.md? Without your specific folder structure?</li> <li>Check <code>allowed-tools</code>. Does it request access to tools the recipient might not want to grant?</li> </ol> <p>A skill you share is a commitment to its quality. Sloppy shared skills erode trust in the whole system.</p>"},{"location":"reference/skills/skill-maintenance.html#common-mistakes","title":"Common mistakes","text":"Mistake What to do instead Building skills for everything Apply the twice rule. Most things should be prompts Never revisiting old skills Monthly review. Update or retire Hoarding unused skills \"just in case\" Delete them. Fewer skills means better auto-matching Spending more time building skills than using them Build the one that saves the most time this week Skipping the prompt-first stage Do it manually once. Build the skill the second time Over-engineering skills before validating the workflow Start with a text-only skill. Add techniques when the simple version is not enough"},{"location":"reference/skills/skill-maintenance.html#plug-play","title":"Plug &amp; Play","text":"<p><code>/humanizer</code> Example of a well-maintained skill. Started simple, accumulated corrections over time. The self-improvement pattern reduces maintenance burden.</p> <p><code>/feature-brief</code> Example of a skill worth building. Complex enough to justify codification, used repeatedly, produces consistent output.</p>"},{"location":"reference/skills/skill-maintenance.html#references","title":"References","text":"<p>Internal:</p> <ul> <li>Building Skills : How to write a SKILL.md when you decide to build</li> <li>Skill Types : Identifying the right type before you start building</li> <li>Advanced Techniques : Adding power when the simple version is not enough</li> <li>The Skill Ecosystem : Sharing skills with your team</li> </ul> <p>External:</p> <ul> <li>Anthropic: Skills documentation : Official reference for skill structure</li> <li>Anthropic: Claude Code best practices : Guidance on when and how to use skills</li> </ul>"},{"location":"reference/skills/skill-types.html","title":"Skill Types","text":"<p>Five types, five different jobs. Knowing which type fits your task is how you build the right skill.</p> <p>Quick Answer</p> <p>Use this when: You are deciding what kind of skill to build or trying to understand an existing skill.</p> <p>Avoid this when: You just need to run a skill. You do not need to classify it first.</p> <p>What CC changes: Skills give Claude specialized behavior on demand. Instead of re-explaining your workflow every session, you codify it once and invoke it with a slash command.</p> <p>Default move: Identify the type first, then build. Generate and review skills cover 80% of PM work.</p>"},{"location":"reference/skills/skill-types.html#the-five-types","title":"The five types","text":"<p>Every skill you will encounter falls into one of five categories. They look different, work differently, and solve different problems.</p> <pre><code>%%{init: {'theme': 'dark'}}%%\nflowchart TD\n    G[\"Generate\\ncreates something new\"]\n    RV[\"Review\\nevaluates something existing\"]\n    RS[\"Research\\nfinds and synthesizes\"]\n    W[\"Workflow\\nexecutes a process\"]\n    B[\"Behavioral\\nchanges how Claude thinks\"]\n\n    style G fill:#16a34a,color:#fff,stroke:#15803d\n    style RV fill:#ca8a04,color:#fff,stroke:#a16207\n    style RS fill:#6366f1,color:#fff,stroke:#4f46e5\n    style W fill:#0891b2,color:#fff,stroke:#0e7490\n    style B fill:#9333ea,color:#fff,stroke:#7e22ce</code></pre>"},{"location":"reference/skills/skill-types.html#type-1-generate","title":"Type 1: Generate","text":"<p>A generate skill creates something new. You give it input or context, and it produces an artifact that did not exist before.</p> <pre><code>raw notes ---+\nmeeting ctx --+--&gt; [GENERATE] --&gt; finished artifact\npreferences --+\n</code></pre> <p>What makes it a generate skill: The output is a new document, draft, or deliverable. The skill defines the format, structure, and quality bar.</p> <p>Examples:</p> <ul> <li><code>/feature-brief</code> -- takes product notes, outputs a structured brief</li> <li><code>/draft-followups</code> -- takes meeting outcomes, drafts follow-up messages</li> <li><code>/write-proposal</code> -- takes rough notes, produces a formatted proposal</li> <li><code>/standup</code> -- takes your config and recent work, generates a standup update</li> </ul>  Bad generate skill  Good generate skill \"Write a good feature brief\" \"Read the product notes. Draft a feature brief with: Problem Statement, Proposed Solution, Success Metrics, Risks, Open Questions. Use bullet points for risks. Keep it under 2 pages.\" \"Make a proposal\" \"Read the brief the user provides. Follow the template in <code>references/template.md</code>. Match the tone of the example in <code>references/examples/</code>. Save to the current directory.\" <p>When to build one: You produce the same type of document repeatedly and want consistent format, structure, and quality every time.</p>"},{"location":"reference/skills/skill-types.html#type-2-review","title":"Type 2: Review","text":"<p>A review skill evaluates something that already exists. Instead of creating from nothing, it critiques, flags issues, and suggests improvements based on specific criteria.</p> <pre><code>something that exists --&gt; [CHECK against rules] --&gt; same thing, better\n</code></pre> <p>What makes it a review skill: The input is an existing artifact. The output is feedback, not a new document. The skill defines the criteria to check against.</p> <p>Examples:</p> <ul> <li><code>/humanizer</code> -- checks writing against 24 AI-writing patterns and rewrites violations</li> <li><code>/mom-test-filter</code> -- scans interview guides against three principles and flags leading questions</li> <li><code>/code-review</code> -- evaluates changes for bugs, style issues, and best practices</li> </ul>  Bad review skill  Good review skill \"Review this document\" \"Read the draft. Flag: filler words (just, very, really), passive voice, sentences over 25 words, cliches, and jargon. For each issue, show the original and a rewrite.\" \"Check for problems\" \"Evaluate this interview guide against 3 Mom Test principles: (1) no hypothetical questions, (2) no leading questions, (3) no questions about future behavior. Rewrite each violation.\" <p>When to build one: You have a specific quality bar or checklist you apply repeatedly to the same type of artifact. The criteria are stable enough to codify.</p>"},{"location":"reference/skills/skill-types.html#type-3-research","title":"Type 3: Research","text":"<p>A research skill finds existing information and synthesizes it. The source of the content is different from generate skills. You are not providing the raw material. Claude goes and gets it.</p> <pre><code>topic --&gt; [RESEARCH: find + synthesize] --&gt; organized findings\n              ^\n        external sources\n</code></pre> <p>What makes it a research skill: Claude goes out and finds information (from files, the web, APIs, or other sources) rather than working with what you provide directly.</p> <p>Examples:</p> <ul> <li><code>/news</code> -- searches for recent developments on a topic and produces a structured briefing</li> <li><code>/web-research</code> -- searches the web, reads pages, and synthesizes findings</li> <li><code>/competitive-intel</code> -- pulls competitor data from multiple sources and organizes it</li> </ul>  Bad research skill  Good research skill \"Research this topic\" \"Search for recent developments on the given topic. For each finding: headline, source, one-sentence summary. Then synthesize: what does this mean for our product? Cite sources.\" \"Find information about competitors\" \"For each competitor: pull pricing, key features, enterprise positioning, and recent changes. Compare against our positioning in <code>product-context.md</code>. Flag gaps and opportunities.\" <p>When to build one: You repeatedly need to gather and synthesize information from external sources using a consistent framework.</p>"},{"location":"reference/skills/skill-types.html#type-4-workflow","title":"Type 4: Workflow","text":"<p>A workflow skill executes a series of predefined steps. The main point is not producing a document. The point is that the process got run.</p> <pre><code>/sync-github\n----------------------------&gt;\ngit add -&gt; git commit -&gt; git push -&gt; done\n\nno artifact. the process IS the output.\n</code></pre> <p>What makes it a workflow skill: The value is in the execution of the process, not in a resulting document. When it finishes, something happened (files moved, state changed, systems updated).</p> <p>Examples:</p> <ul> <li><code>/sync-github</code> -- stages, commits, and pushes changes</li> <li><code>/auq</code> -- runs a structured clarification workflow to deeply understand what you need</li> <li><code>/convert-doc</code> -- converts markdown to styled PDF using pandoc</li> <li><code>/print-docs</code> -- converts markdown to styled HTML to PDF to printer</li> </ul>  Bad workflow skill  Good workflow skill \"Sync my files\" \"Check git status. Stage all modified files. Generate a commit message from the diff. Commit. Push to origin. Report what was pushed.\" \"Help me clarify what I need\" \"Ask targeted questions across 5 dimensions (goal, constraints, scope, preferences, edge cases) using AskUserQuestion. One question at a time. After all dimensions are covered, summarize understanding in a structured format.\" <p>When to build one: You have a multi-step process you run regularly and want it executed the same way every time.</p>"},{"location":"reference/skills/skill-types.html#type-5-behavioral","title":"Type 5: Behavioral","text":"<p>A behavioral skill does not produce a deliverable. It changes how Claude approaches a category of work. Think of it as loading a different brain.</p> <pre><code>Same question, different brain:\n\ndefault:   \"try A/B testing your CTA\"\nloaded:    \"endowment effect says...\"\n           \"zero-price psychology...\"\n           \"activation energy...\"\n</code></pre> <p>What makes it a behavioral skill: No output format, no step-by-step process, no generation instructions. It is all knowledge and framing. When the skill is loaded, Claude's advice draws on these models automatically.</p> <p>Examples:</p> <ul> <li><code>/marketing-psychology</code> -- loads 70+ behavioral science mental models for marketing decisions</li> <li><code>/writing-voice</code> -- makes Claude write in your personal voice (and learns from corrections over time)</li> <li><code>/humanizer</code> (also a review skill) -- changes how Claude thinks about writing quality</li> </ul>  Bad behavioral skill  Good behavioral skill \"Be better at marketing\" 70+ specific mental models with definitions, examples, and when-to-use guidance. Claude picks the relevant models based on the question \"Write in my voice\" Specific rules: \"Use contractions. Start paragraphs with the point, not buildup. Never use rhetorical questions. Short sentences. No em dashes.\" Plus a corrections folder that accumulates over time <p>When to build one: You want Claude to think differently about a category of work, not just produce a specific output. The skill is about mode, not deliverable.</p>"},{"location":"reference/skills/skill-types.html#choosing-the-right-type","title":"Choosing the right type","text":"<pre><code>%%{init: {'theme': 'dark'}}%%\nflowchart TD\n    Q[\"What do you need?\"]\n    Q --&gt;|\"A new document or artifact\"| G[\"Generate\"]\n    Q --&gt;|\"Feedback on something existing\"| RV[\"Review\"]\n    Q --&gt;|\"Information gathered and organized\"| RS[\"Research\"]\n    Q --&gt;|\"A process executed\"| W[\"Workflow\"]\n    Q --&gt;|\"Claude to think differently\"| B[\"Behavioral\"]\n\n    style Q fill:#374151,color:#f8fafc,stroke:#4b5563\n    style G fill:#16a34a,color:#fff,stroke:#15803d\n    style RV fill:#ca8a04,color:#fff,stroke:#a16207\n    style RS fill:#6366f1,color:#fff,stroke:#4f46e5\n    style W fill:#0891b2,color:#fff,stroke:#0e7490\n    style B fill:#9333ea,color:#fff,stroke:#7e22ce</code></pre>"},{"location":"reference/skills/skill-types.html#quick-quiz","title":"Quick quiz","text":"Scenario Type Draft a PRD from your notes Generate Check your PRD against a completeness checklist Review Pull competitor pricing from the web and summarize it Research Run your deploy process (build, test, push, tag) Workflow Make Claude always think in terms of user stories Behavioral"},{"location":"reference/skills/skill-types.html#types-combine","title":"Types combine","text":"<p>Skills often combine types. A <code>/feature-brief</code> skill might generate a brief (generate), then spin up a reviewer sub-agent to critique it (review). A <code>/meeting-aftermath</code> skill might process transcripts (generate), run quality checks (review), and update task trackers (workflow).</p> <p>The types are a thinking tool for design, not rigid categories.</p>"},{"location":"reference/skills/skill-types.html#plug-play","title":"Plug &amp; Play","text":"<p><code>/feature-brief</code> Generate skill. Takes product notes, outputs a structured brief with reviewer panel.</p> <p><code>/humanizer</code> Review + behavioral skill. Detects and rewrites 24 AI-writing patterns.</p> <p><code>/mom-test-filter</code> Review skill. Scans interview guides against three Mom Test principles.</p> <p><code>/meeting-aftermath</code> Multi-type composition. Orchestrates 6 sub-skills across generate, review, and workflow types.</p>"},{"location":"reference/skills/skill-types.html#references","title":"References","text":"<p>Internal:</p> <ul> <li>Building Skills : How to write a SKILL.md once you know the type</li> <li>Advanced Techniques : Techniques that make any type more powerful</li> <li>Skill Maintenance : When to build a skill and when not to</li> </ul> <p>External:</p> <ul> <li>Anthropic: Skills documentation : Official reference for skill structure and frontmatter fields</li> </ul>"},{"location":"resources/index.html","title":"Plug &amp; Play","text":"<p>Grab-and-go files, templates, starter kits, and examples. Copy what you need, drop it into your setup, and start using it.</p> <p>Everything in this section is something you can take and use right now. No theory, no long reads. Just ready-to-use assets organized by what they are.</p>"},{"location":"resources/index.html#three-categories","title":"Three categories","text":"Category What it is Example Built into the course Components and templates that ship with CC4PMs Skills, hooks, agent configs, document templates CC4PMs recommended Setups and configurations we've tested and stand behind Starter kits, rules snippets, config patterns External Tools and integrations from the broader ecosystem MCP servers, CLI tools, community resources"},{"location":"resources/index.html#whats-here","title":"What's here","text":"<ul> <li> <p> Starter Kits</p> <p>Pre-configured setups for common PM scenarios. Clone a kit and start working.</p> </li> <li> <p> Components</p> <p>Individual building blocks: skills, agents, hooks, and config files. Mix and match.</p> </li> <li> <p> Templates</p> <p>PM artifact templates: experiment briefs, research plans, PRDs. Fill in the blanks.</p> </li> <li> <p> Examples</p> <p>Real-world output and before/after comparisons. See the techniques in action.</p> </li> </ul>"},{"location":"resources/index.html#how-to-use-this-section","title":"How to use this section","text":"<p>Starting from scratch? Grab a Starter Kit. It gives you a folder structure, a CLAUDE.md, and a handful of skills to get going.</p> <p>Adding to an existing setup? Browse Components for individual skills, hooks, or config patterns you can drop in.</p> <p>Need a specific artifact? Check Templates for document structures you can fill in with Claude's help.</p> <p>Want to see what's possible? Examples shows real output from the workflows taught in the course.</p>"},{"location":"resources/examples.html","title":"Examples","text":"<p>Real-world output from Claude Code workflows. See what the techniques actually produce.</p> <p>This page collects examples of Claude Code output from PM workflows taught in the course. Each example shows the input, the process, and what came out the other side. Where it's useful, we include before/after comparisons.</p> <p>Examples throughout the site</p> <p>Most playbooks and reference pages include inline examples specific to that topic. This page collects the cross-cutting ones and the more visual before/after comparisons.</p>"},{"location":"resources/examples.html#research-from-transcript-to-findings","title":"Research: From transcript to findings","text":"<p>Input: 7 user interview transcripts (45-60 minutes each)</p> <p>Process: <code>/interview-analysis</code> (extraction, verification, synthesis pipeline)</p> <p>Output:</p> <ul> <li>7 individual extraction files with structured findings per participant</li> <li>1 verification report confirming quote accuracy across all extractions</li> <li>1 synthesis document with 5 cross-participant themes, each backed by specific evidence</li> </ul> <p>Time: Under 15 minutes for the full pipeline (vs. 2-3 days manually)</p> <p>What to notice: The synthesis groups findings by described behavior, not by the labels participants used. Two participants who said \"we need better reporting\" and \"I just want to see what's happening\" ended up in the same theme because the underlying need was identical.</p>"},{"location":"resources/examples.html#documents-before-and-after-humanizer","title":"Documents: Before and after humanizer","text":"<p>Before (raw Claude output):</p> <p>Furthermore, it's worth noting that the implementation of this feature represents a significant paradigm shift in how users engage with the platform. The transformative nature of this update cannot be overstated -- it fundamentally reimagines the user experience in ways that are both profound and far-reaching.</p> <p>After (<code>/humanizer</code>):</p> <p>This feature changes how people use the platform. Instead of navigating to reports manually, the data shows up where they're already working. Early testers spent 40% less time context-switching between tools.</p> <p>What changed: Removed inflated claims (\"paradigm shift,\" \"cannot be overstated,\" \"profound and far-reaching\"), replaced vague assertions with a specific data point, and cut the word count in half.</p>"},{"location":"resources/examples.html#meetings-one-command-six-outputs","title":"Meetings: One command, six outputs","text":"<p>Input: A 45-minute product review meeting transcript</p> <p>Process: <code>/meeting-aftermath</code></p> <p>Output (6 artifacts):</p> <ol> <li>Structured transcript with decisions, action items, key quotes, and follow-ups extracted</li> <li>Reality check comparing what happened vs. what the people files predicted</li> <li>People file updates proposing new information learned about 3 stakeholders</li> <li>Action item updates adding 4 new items, marking 2 complete</li> <li>Draft follow-ups with 3 Slack messages and 1 email, each matching the recipient's communication style</li> <li>Status update in BLUF format, under 200 words, ready to paste</li> </ol> <p>What to notice: Everything is proposed, not auto-applied. You review each update before it writes anything. The people file updates are the hidden value: you build institutional memory about stakeholders without actively trying.</p>"},{"location":"resources/examples.html#competitive-intel-from-name-to-landscape-brief","title":"Competitive intel: From name to landscape brief","text":"<p>Input: \"Run a competitive analysis on [3 competitor names] for the SMB segment\"</p> <p>Process: <code>/competitive-intel</code> (web research, review scraping, segmentation, coding, synthesis)</p> <p>Output:</p> <ul> <li>Positioning snapshots for each competitor (from web research)</li> <li>Review data scraped and saved as structured CSVs</li> <li>Reviews segmented by company size (SMB filtered)</li> <li>Inductive coding revealing 8 themes across competitors</li> <li>Landscape brief synthesizing positioning, strengths, weaknesses, and opportunity gaps</li> </ul> <p>What to notice: The inductive coding step lets themes emerge from the data rather than imposing categories. You might expect \"pricing\" to be a major theme and discover that \"implementation complexity\" is what SMB customers actually talk about.</p>"},{"location":"resources/examples.html#building-feature-brief-with-reviewers","title":"Building: Feature brief with reviewers","text":"<p>Input: \"Write a feature brief for in-app notifications\"</p> <p>Process: <code>/feature-brief</code> with three reviewer personas enabled</p> <p>Output:</p> <ul> <li>Draft brief covering problem, solution, scope, metrics, and launch plan</li> <li>Engineering review flagging technical dependencies and suggesting a phased rollout</li> <li>Design review questioning the notification frequency model</li> <li>Strategy review asking about alignment with Q3 OKRs</li> </ul> <p>What to notice: Each reviewer operates in a fresh sub-agent with no knowledge of the others' feedback. The engineering reviewer doesn't soften their critique because design already approved it. You get genuinely independent perspectives.</p>"},{"location":"resources/examples.html#where-to-find-more","title":"Where to find more","text":"<p>Every Playbook includes worked examples specific to that workflow. The examples on this page are meant to show cross-cutting patterns and give you a sense of what the system produces end to end. For technique-specific examples, start with the playbook that matches your use case.</p>"},{"location":"resources/starter-kits.html","title":"Starter Kits","text":"<p>Pre-configured setups for common PM scenarios. Clone one, adjust it, and start working.</p> <p>A starter kit is a folder structure, a CLAUDE.md, and a curated set of skills and rules that work together. Instead of building your setup from scratch, start with a kit that matches your situation and customize from there.</p>"},{"location":"resources/starter-kits.html#lightweight-kit","title":"Lightweight kit","text":"<p>The minimum viable setup. Good for anyone just getting started or working on a single initiative.</p> <pre><code>my-project/\n  CLAUDE.md\n  .claude/\n    rules/\n      file-naming.md\n      writing-style.md\n    skills/\n      humanizer/\n        SKILL.md\n      feature-brief/\n        SKILL.md\n      meeting-aftermath/\n        SKILL.md\n        (sub-skills included)\n  docs/\n  notes/\n</code></pre> <p>CLAUDE.md includes:</p> <ul> <li>Project context (what you're working on, key directories)</li> <li>Skill routing table (which command to use when)</li> <li>Basic standards (file naming, writing tone)</li> </ul> <p>Best for: Individual PMs starting with Claude Code. One project, a few workflows, minimal configuration overhead.</p>"},{"location":"resources/starter-kits.html#research-focused-kit","title":"Research-focused kit","text":"<p>Built for PMs who spend most of their time in discovery, user research, and competitive analysis.</p> <pre><code>research-project/\n  CLAUDE.md\n  .claude/\n    rules/\n      file-naming.md\n      writing-style.md\n      research-standards.md\n    skills/\n      research-design/\n        SKILL.md\n        research-plan-template.md\n      assumption-surfacing/\n        SKILL.md\n      mom-test-filter/\n        SKILL.md\n        mom-test-reference.md\n      interview-extraction/\n        SKILL.md\n      interview-synthesis/\n        SKILL.md\n      quote-verification/\n        SKILL.md\n      interview-analysis/\n        SKILL.md\n      competitive-intel/\n        SKILL.md\n      scrape-reviews/\n        SKILL.md\n      segment-reviews/\n        SKILL.md\n      code-reviews/\n        SKILL.md\n      humanizer/\n        SKILL.md\n    agents/\n      research-reviewer.md\n  data/\n    transcripts/\n    surveys/\n    reviews/\n  docs/\n    research-plans/\n    findings/\n  people/\n</code></pre> <p>CLAUDE.md includes:</p> <ul> <li>Research-specific context (current studies, participant pools, open questions)</li> <li>Data handling rules (quote verification required, sample size thresholds)</li> <li>Skill routing optimized for research workflows</li> <li>People file instructions for interview participants</li> </ul> <p>Best for: PMs in discovery-heavy roles. User researchers. Anyone running a structured research program.</p>"},{"location":"resources/starter-kits.html#data-focused-kit","title":"Data-focused kit","text":"<p>For PMs who work heavily with analytics, experiments, and data-driven decision making.</p> <pre><code>data-project/\n  CLAUDE.md\n  .claude/\n    rules/\n      file-naming.md\n      writing-style.md\n      data-standards.md\n    skills/\n      experiment-check/\n        SKILL.md\n      feature-brief/\n        SKILL.md\n      status-update/\n        SKILL.md\n      humanizer/\n        SKILL.md\n  data/\n    experiments/\n    exports/\n    notebooks/\n  docs/\n    briefs/\n    reports/\n  templates/\n    experiment-brief.md\n</code></pre> <p>CLAUDE.md includes:</p> <ul> <li>Experiment tracking context (active experiments, metrics, thresholds)</li> <li>Data source documentation (where analytics live, how to pull them)</li> <li>Notebook conventions (naming, output expectations)</li> <li>Decision log structure</li> </ul> <p>Best for: PMs focused on experimentation, analytics, and data-informed prioritization.</p>"},{"location":"resources/starter-kits.html#full-os-kit","title":"Full OS kit","text":"<p>The complete setup from the Your PM OS module. Everything integrated, ready for daily use.</p> <pre><code>my-pm-os/\n  CLAUDE.md\n  .claude/\n    settings.json\n    rules/\n      file-naming.md\n      writing-style.md\n      research-standards.md\n      commits.md\n    skills/\n      (all course skills)\n    agents/\n      doc-reviewer.md\n      stakeholder-sim.md\n  docs/\n  data/\n  people/\n  actions/\n  notes/\n  templates/\n</code></pre> <p>CLAUDE.md includes:</p> <ul> <li>Full project context with current priorities</li> <li>People system instructions</li> <li>Action item tracking conventions</li> <li>Skill routing for all workflows</li> <li>Meeting processing pipeline</li> <li>Sync and backup instructions</li> </ul> <p>Best for: PMs who have completed the course and want one workspace that handles everything. This is what the OS module builds toward.</p>"},{"location":"resources/starter-kits.html#how-to-use-a-kit","title":"How to use a kit","text":"<ol> <li>Pick the kit that matches your current focus</li> <li>Create the folder structure in a new directory</li> <li>Copy in the skills you want from <code>.claude/skills/</code> (see Skills)</li> <li>Write your CLAUDE.md using the patterns from Rules &amp; Config</li> <li>Start working and let the setup evolve as you use it</li> </ol> <p>You don't need to get it perfect on day one. Start with the lightweight kit and add complexity as your workflows stabilize. The kits are starting points, not final states.</p>"},{"location":"resources/templates.html","title":"Templates","text":"<p>PM artifact templates you can fill in with Claude's help. Copy the structure, point Claude at it, and let it do the heavy lifting.</p> <p>These templates define the structure of common PM documents. They're not meant to be filled in by hand. The workflow is: copy a template into your project, then ask Claude to populate it using your context (meeting notes, research data, product docs, whatever you have).</p> <p>Each template works well as a standalone file, but they also pair naturally with specific skills. The skill handles the process; the template handles the structure.</p>"},{"location":"resources/templates.html#experiment-brief","title":"Experiment brief","text":"<p>Use when designing a new experiment or A/B test. Pairs with the <code>/experiment-check</code> skill for ongoing monitoring.</p> templates/experiment-brief.md<pre><code># Experiment: [Name]\n\n## Hypothesis\nIf we [change], then [metric] will [direction] because [reasoning].\n\n## Context\n- What triggered this experiment:\n- Current baseline:\n- Related past experiments:\n\n## Design\n- **Type:** A/B test | multivariate | staged rollout\n- **Duration:** [X weeks]\n- **Sample size needed:** [N]\n- **Allocation:** [% control / % variant]\n\n## Metrics\n- **Primary:** [metric] (success = [threshold])\n- **Secondary:** [metric]\n- **Guardrails:** [metrics that must NOT degrade]\n\n## Monitoring plan\n- Check frequency: [daily | weekly]\n- Who reviews: [names]\n- Kill criteria: [when to stop early]\n\n## Decision framework\n- If primary metric hits threshold: [action]\n- If inconclusive after duration: [action]\n- If guardrail violated: [action]\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"resources/templates.html#research-plan","title":"Research plan","text":"<p>Use when scoping a research effort for stakeholder review. Pairs with the <code>/research-design</code> pipeline.</p> templates/research-plan.md<pre><code># Research Plan: [Topic]\n\n## Context\nWhy this research exists and what triggered it.\n\n## Research questions\n1. [Question] - Decision it informs: [if we learn X, we do Y]\n2. [Question] - Decision it informs: [if we learn X, we do Y]\n\n## Assumptions to test\n| Assumption | Currently known? | How we'll test it |\n|-----------|-----------------|-------------------|\n| [assumption] | Know / Assume | [method] |\n\n## Methodology\n- **Method:** Interviews | Survey | Data analysis | Mixed\n- **Participants:** [who, how many, how recruited]\n- **Timeline:** [start to final readout]\n\n## Instruments\n- Interview guide: [link or inline]\n- Survey: [link or inline]\n\n## Success criteria\nWe'll know the answer when:\n- [concrete indicator]\n- [concrete indicator]\n\n## Stakeholders\n- **Sponsor:** [who is funding/approving this]\n- **Consumers:** [who will use the findings]\n- **Readout format:** [deck | doc | async brief]\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"resources/templates.html#prd-structure","title":"PRD structure","text":"<p>A lightweight product requirements document. Not a 30-page spec. Enough structure to align a team and enough flexibility to adapt.</p> templates/prd.md<pre><code># [Feature Name]\n\n## Problem\nWhat user problem does this solve? Who has it? How do we know?\n\n## Proposed solution\nWhat are we building? Keep it to 2-3 paragraphs.\n\n## Goals and success metrics\n| Goal | Metric | Target |\n|------|--------|--------|\n| [goal] | [metric] | [number] |\n\n## Scope\n### In scope\n- [item]\n\n### Out of scope\n- [item]\n\n### Open questions\n- [question] - Owner: [name] - Due: [date]\n\n## User stories\n- As a [persona], I want to [action] so that [outcome]\n\n## Design\n[Link to designs or describe key interactions]\n\n## Technical considerations\n[Anything the engineering team needs to know up front]\n\n## Launch plan\n- **Rollout:** [all at once | phased | feature flag]\n- **Dependencies:** [what needs to happen first]\n- **Risks:** [what could go wrong]\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"resources/templates.html#stakeholder-brief","title":"Stakeholder brief","text":"<p>A one-page summary for executives or cross-functional partners. Designed to be skimmed in under two minutes.</p> templates/stakeholder-brief.md<pre><code># [Topic]: Stakeholder Brief\n\n## Bottom line\n[One sentence: what happened, what we learned, or what we're proposing]\n\n## Context\n[2-3 sentences: why this matters right now]\n\n## Key findings / proposal\n1. [Finding or recommendation]\n2. [Finding or recommendation]\n3. [Finding or recommendation]\n\n## Evidence\n[Bullet points with specific data, quotes, or references]\n\n## What we need from you\n- [ ] [Decision or approval needed]\n- [ ] [Resource or support needed]\n\n## Timeline\n| Milestone | Date |\n|-----------|------|\n| [milestone] | [date] |\n\n## Appendix\n[Links to detailed docs, data, or research for those who want to go deeper]\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"resources/templates.html#using-templates-with-claude","title":"Using templates with Claude","text":"<p>The simplest workflow:</p> <ol> <li>Copy a template into your project</li> <li>Tell Claude: \"Fill in templates/experiment-brief.md using the context in [meeting notes / research folder / product doc]\"</li> <li>Claude reads your source material and populates the template</li> <li>Review, adjust, ship</li> </ol> <p>For a more structured approach, pair templates with skills. The <code>/feature-brief</code> skill, for example, has its own built-in template and walks you through an interview before drafting. The <code>/research-design</code> skill produces a research plan that follows the structure above.</p>"},{"location":"resources/tooling-and-integrations.html","title":"Tooling &amp; Integrations","text":"<p>Recommended MCPs, CLIs, and APIs \u2014 the external tools that pair best with Claude Code.</p> <p>Coming Soon</p> <p>This guide is under development. Check back soon.</p>"},{"location":"resources/components/index.html","title":"Components","text":"<p>Modular building blocks you can drop into any Claude Code setup.</p> <p>Components are individual, self-contained pieces: skills, agents, hooks, and config files. They're designed to be mixed and matched. Pick what you need, ignore what you don't.</p>"},{"location":"resources/components/index.html#whats-here","title":"What's here","text":"<ul> <li> <p> Skills</p> <p>27 ready-to-use SKILL.md files from the course. Research, building, data, documents, OS, and team workflows. Drop them into <code>.claude/skills/</code> and use slash commands.</p> </li> <li> <p> Agents</p> <p>Agent configurations for sub-agent delegation. Research reviewers, stakeholder simulators, and document quality checks.</p> </li> <li> <p> Hooks</p> <p>Event-driven automation you can copy and paste. Safety hooks (block force push, scan for secrets) and productivity hooks (auto-format, notifications).</p> </li> <li> <p> Rules &amp; Config</p> <p>Configuration snippets for <code>.claude/rules/</code>, CLAUDE.md sections, and <code>settings.json</code> patterns. Copy, paste, adjust.</p> </li> </ul>"},{"location":"resources/components/agents.html","title":"Agents","text":"<p>Dedicated agent configurations for common PM tasks. Less mature than skills, but useful for recurring delegation patterns.</p> <p>Agent configurations define specialized sub-agents that handle specific types of work. Unlike skills (which are full workflow scripts), agents are lighter: they set up a persona, context, and set of allowed tools, then let the agent operate within those boundaries.</p> <p>Think of agents as job descriptions for sub-agents. You're not scripting every step. You're saying \"here's who you are, here's what you have access to, go.\"</p> <p>Early days</p> <p>Agent configurations are a newer pattern. Skills are more battle-tested for most PM workflows. Use agents when you want flexible delegation rather than a scripted sequence.</p>"},{"location":"resources/components/agents.html#agent-file-format","title":"Agent file format","text":"<p>Agent definitions live in <code>.claude/agents/</code> as markdown files. Here's the structure:</p> .claude/agents/research-reviewer.md<pre><code>---\nname: research-reviewer\ndescription: Reviews research artifacts for methodological rigor and bias.\nallowed-tools:\n  - Read\n  - Glob\n  - Grep\n---\n\n# Research Reviewer Agent\n\nYou are a senior research methodologist reviewing PM research artifacts.\n\n## Your lens\n- Sample bias: Is the participant pool representative?\n- Question bias: Are questions leading or loaded?\n- Confirmation bias: Do findings only support the hypothesis?\n- Missing perspectives: Who wasn't interviewed?\n\n## How to operate\n1. Read every file in the research folder\n2. Flag issues by severity (blocking, significant, minor)\n3. For each issue, cite the specific passage and explain why it matters\n4. Summarize with a go/no-go recommendation\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"resources/components/agents.html#example-configurations","title":"Example configurations","text":""},{"location":"resources/components/agents.html#stakeholder-simulator","title":"Stakeholder simulator","text":"<p>Useful for pressure-testing a proposal before the real meeting.</p> .claude/agents/stakeholder-sim.md<pre><code>---\nname: stakeholder-sim\ndescription: Simulates a skeptical stakeholder reviewing a proposal or brief.\nallowed-tools:\n  - Read\n  - Glob\n---\n\n# Stakeholder Simulator\n\nYou are simulating a senior stakeholder who has seen too many\nhalf-baked proposals. You are not hostile, but you are skeptical.\n\n## Your default questions\n- What's the opportunity cost of doing this?\n- What data supports the priority claim?\n- Who did you talk to? How many?\n- What happens if we do nothing?\n- What's the smallest version we could ship?\n\n## How to operate\n1. Read the document provided\n2. Ask the five default questions, grounded in what you read\n3. Rate the brief: Ready, Needs Work, or Not Ready\n4. Explain your rating in two sentences\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"resources/components/agents.html#doc-reviewer","title":"Doc reviewer","text":"<p>A general-purpose document quality check.</p> .claude/agents/doc-reviewer.md<pre><code>---\nname: doc-reviewer\ndescription: Reviews PM documents for clarity, completeness, and actionability.\nallowed-tools:\n  - Read\n  - Glob\n  - Grep\n---\n\n# Document Reviewer\n\nYou review PM documents with three questions:\n\n1. **Clarity** - Could someone unfamiliar with the project understand this?\n2. **Completeness** - Are there obvious gaps or unanswered questions?\n3. **Actionability** - Does this lead to a clear next step?\n\n## How to operate\n1. Read the document\n2. Score each dimension 1-5\n3. List specific issues with line references\n4. Suggest concrete fixes, not vague improvements\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"resources/components/agents.html#when-to-use-agents-vs-skills","title":"When to use agents vs. skills","text":"Use an agent when... Use a skill when... The task needs flexible judgment The task follows a repeatable sequence You want a specific perspective or lens You want consistent output every time The work is exploratory The work is procedural You're delegating to a sub-agent You're running a command yourself <p>For most PM workflows, skills are the right call. Agents shine when you need a fresh perspective (like the Builder-Validator pattern) or when the task is too variable to script.</p>"},{"location":"resources/components/hooks.html","title":"Hooks","text":"<p>Ready-to-use hook configurations. Copy the JSON, paste it into your settings, and you have event-driven automation.</p> <p>Hooks run scripts automatically when Claude Code does things. They fire on events like \"before a command runs\" or \"after a file is edited.\" You configure them in <code>.claude/settings.json</code> and they enforce rules without you having to remember them.</p> <p>For the full explanation of how hooks work, see Customization in the Reference section. This page is just the grab-and-go configurations.</p>"},{"location":"resources/components/hooks.html#safety-hooks","title":"Safety hooks","text":""},{"location":"resources/components/hooks.html#prevent-force-push","title":"Prevent force push","text":"<p>Blocks <code>git push --force</code> and <code>git push -f</code> before they execute. Saves you from accidentally rewriting shared history.</p> <pre><code>{\n  \"hooks\": {\n    \"PreToolUse\": [\n      {\n        \"matcher\": \"Bash\",\n        \"hooks\": [\n          {\n            \"type\": \"command\",\n            \"command\": \"if echo \\\"$CC_TOOL_INPUT\\\" | grep -q 'push.*--force\\\\|push.*-f'; then echo 'BLOCK: Force push is not allowed. Use --force-with-lease if you really need to.'; exit 1; fi\"\n          }\n        ]\n      }\n    ]\n  }\n}\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"resources/components/hooks.html#block-commits-to-main","title":"Block commits to main","text":"<p>Prevents direct commits to the main branch. Forces work onto feature branches.</p> <pre><code>{\n  \"hooks\": {\n    \"PreToolUse\": [\n      {\n        \"matcher\": \"Bash\",\n        \"hooks\": [\n          {\n            \"type\": \"command\",\n            \"command\": \"if echo \\\"$CC_TOOL_INPUT\\\" | grep -q 'git commit' &amp;&amp; git branch --show-current | grep -q '^main$'; then echo 'BLOCK: Do not commit directly to main. Create a feature branch first.'; exit 1; fi\"\n          }\n        ]\n      }\n    ]\n  }\n}\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"resources/components/hooks.html#secret-scanning","title":"Secret scanning","text":"<p>Checks file content for common secret patterns before Claude writes to a file. Catches API keys, tokens, and passwords before they hit disk.</p> <pre><code>{\n  \"hooks\": {\n    \"PreToolUse\": [\n      {\n        \"matcher\": \"Write\",\n        \"hooks\": [\n          {\n            \"type\": \"command\",\n            \"command\": \"if echo \\\"$CC_TOOL_INPUT\\\" | grep -qiE '(api_key|api-key|secret_key|password|token)\\\\s*[=:]\\\\s*[\\\"'\\\\'''][A-Za-z0-9]'; then echo 'BLOCK: Possible secret detected in file content. Use environment variables instead.'; exit 1; fi\"\n          }\n        ]\n      }\n    ]\n  }\n}\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"resources/components/hooks.html#productivity-hooks","title":"Productivity hooks","text":""},{"location":"resources/components/hooks.html#auto-format-on-file-write","title":"Auto-format on file write","text":"<p>Runs Prettier (or your formatter of choice) after Claude writes or edits a file. Keeps formatting consistent without thinking about it.</p> <pre><code>{\n  \"hooks\": {\n    \"PostToolUse\": [\n      {\n        \"matcher\": \"Write|Edit\",\n        \"hooks\": [\n          {\n            \"type\": \"command\",\n            \"command\": \"npx prettier --write \\\"$CC_TOOL_INPUT_FILE\\\" 2&gt;/dev/null || true\"\n          }\n        ]\n      }\n    ]\n  }\n}\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"resources/components/hooks.html#notify-on-long-tasks","title":"Notify on long tasks","text":"<p>Sends a system notification when a sub-agent finishes. Useful when you kick off a long research task and switch to something else.</p> <pre><code>{\n  \"hooks\": {\n    \"PostToolUse\": [\n      {\n        \"matcher\": \"Task\",\n        \"hooks\": [\n          {\n            \"type\": \"command\",\n            \"command\": \"osascript -e 'display notification \\\"Sub-agent finished\\\" with title \\\"Claude Code\\\"' 2&gt;/dev/null || true\"\n          }\n        ]\n      }\n    ]\n  }\n}\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"resources/components/hooks.html#how-to-install","title":"How to install","text":"<ol> <li>Open (or create) <code>.claude/settings.json</code> in your project root</li> <li>Copy the hook configuration you want</li> <li>Paste it into the <code>hooks</code> section of your settings file</li> <li>If you already have hooks, merge the new entries into the existing <code>PreToolUse</code> or <code>PostToolUse</code> arrays</li> </ol> <p>Hooks take effect immediately. No restart needed.</p> <p>For more on how hooks work, including the full event lifecycle and how to debug them, see the Customization reference page.</p>"},{"location":"resources/components/rules-and-config.html","title":"Rules &amp; Config","text":"<p>Configuration snippets you can copy into your project. Rules files, CLAUDE.md sections, and settings patterns.</p> <p>This page collects practical configuration patterns for PM work. Each one is something you can copy, paste, and adjust. For the full explanation of how CLAUDE.md and settings work, see the CLAUDE.md and Customization reference pages.</p>"},{"location":"resources/components/rules-and-config.html#rules-files","title":"Rules files","text":"<p>Rules live in <code>.claude/rules/</code> as individual markdown files. Each rule is always loaded into context, so keep them short and specific. Use rules for persistent behavioral instructions that apply across your entire project.</p>"},{"location":"resources/components/rules-and-config.html#file-naming-convention","title":"File naming convention","text":".claude/rules/file-naming.md<pre><code>When creating new files, always use kebab-case for file names\n(e.g., my-new-file.md, not my_new_file.md or MyNewFile.md).\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"resources/components/rules-and-config.html#writing-style","title":"Writing style","text":".claude/rules/writing-style.md<pre><code>When writing documents:\n- Use plain language. No jargon unless the audience expects it.\n- No em dashes. Use commas, periods, or parentheses instead.\n- Keep paragraphs under 4 sentences.\n- Lead with the conclusion, then support it.\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"resources/components/rules-and-config.html#research-standards","title":"Research standards","text":".claude/rules/research-standards.md<pre><code>When working with research data:\n- Never fabricate quotes. Every quote must trace to a source file.\n- Flag sample sizes under 5 as insufficient for pattern claims.\n- Distinguish between \"participants said X\" and \"the data shows X.\"\n- When synthesizing across participants, note the count (e.g., \"4 of 7 participants\").\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"resources/components/rules-and-config.html#commit-conventions","title":"Commit conventions","text":".claude/rules/commits.md<pre><code>When making git commits:\n- Use conventional commit format: type(scope): description\n- Types: feat, fix, docs, refactor, test, chore\n- Keep the subject line under 72 characters\n- Never commit files matching: .env, *.secret, credentials.*\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"resources/components/rules-and-config.html#claudemd-patterns","title":"CLAUDE.md patterns","text":"<p>Your CLAUDE.md is the most important configuration file. Here are sections you can adapt for PM work.</p>"},{"location":"resources/components/rules-and-config.html#project-context-block","title":"Project context block","text":"CLAUDE.md (excerpt)<pre><code>## Project Context\n\nThis is a [product/initiative] workspace for [what it does].\n\n**Key directories:**\n- docs/ : Product documents (PRDs, briefs, research)\n- data/ : Research data, survey exports, analytics pulls\n- people/ : Stakeholder profiles and communication preferences\n- actions/ : Action item tracking\n\n**Current focus:** [What you're working on this quarter]\n\n**Key decisions made:**\n- [Date]: Decided to [decision] because [reason]\n- [Date]: Chose [option] over [alternative] based on [evidence]\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"resources/components/rules-and-config.html#people-system-instructions","title":"People system instructions","text":"CLAUDE.md (excerpt)<pre><code>## People Files\n\nStakeholder profiles live in people/. Each file tracks:\n- Communication style and preferences\n- Known concerns and priorities\n- History of key interactions\n- How to frame proposals for this person\n\nWhen drafting communications, always read the recipient's people\nfile first. Match their preferred format and level of detail.\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"resources/components/rules-and-config.html#skill-routing","title":"Skill routing","text":"CLAUDE.md (excerpt)<pre><code>## Available Skills\n\n| Command | When to use |\n|---------|------------|\n| /meeting-aftermath | After any meeting with a transcript |\n| /research-design | Starting a new research effort |\n| /feature-brief | Scoping a new feature |\n| /experiment-check | Checking in on a running experiment |\n| /os-audit | Periodic review of this workspace |\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"resources/components/rules-and-config.html#settingsjson-patterns","title":"settings.json patterns","text":"<p>The settings file controls permissions, environment variables, and hooks. Here are useful patterns.</p>"},{"location":"resources/components/rules-and-config.html#minimal-pm-setup","title":"Minimal PM setup","text":".claude/settings.json<pre><code>{\n  \"permissions\": {\n    \"allow\": [\n      \"Read\",\n      \"Write\",\n      \"Edit\",\n      \"Glob\",\n      \"Grep\"\n    ],\n    \"deny\": [\n      \"Bash(rm -rf *)\",\n      \"Bash(git push --force)\"\n    ]\n  }\n}\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"resources/components/rules-and-config.html#with-mcp-tools-allowed","title":"With MCP tools allowed","text":".claude/settings.json<pre><code>{\n  \"permissions\": {\n    \"allow\": [\n      \"Read\",\n      \"Write\",\n      \"Edit\",\n      \"Glob\",\n      \"Grep\",\n      \"Bash\",\n      \"mcp__slack__*\",\n      \"mcp__analytics__*\"\n    ],\n    \"deny\": [\n      \"Bash(rm -rf *)\",\n      \"Bash(git push --force)\"\n    ]\n  }\n}\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"resources/components/rules-and-config.html#putting-it-together","title":"Putting it together","text":"<p>A typical PM project might have:</p> <pre><code>.claude/\n  settings.json          # Permissions and hooks\n  rules/\n    file-naming.md       # Naming conventions\n    writing-style.md     # Tone and format rules\n    commits.md           # Git commit standards\n  skills/\n    meeting-aftermath/   # Meeting processing\n    feature-brief/       # Brief generation\n    humanizer/           # AI writing cleanup\n  agents/\n    doc-reviewer.md      # Document quality check\nCLAUDE.md                # Project context, routing, standards\n</code></pre> <p>Start with CLAUDE.md and one or two rules. Add skills as your workflows stabilize. Add hooks when you find yourself repeatedly enforcing the same standards manually.</p>"},{"location":"resources/components/skills.html","title":"Skills","text":"<p>Ready-to-use SKILL.md files from the CC4PMs course. Drop them into <code>.claude/skills/</code> and start using slash commands.</p> <p>These are the non-lesson skills that ship with the course. Each one is a standalone workflow you keep and use in your own projects. They're organized by the type of PM work they support.</p>"},{"location":"resources/components/skills.html#how-to-install","title":"How to install","text":"<ol> <li>Copy the skill folder into your project's <code>.claude/skills/</code> directory</li> <li>Each folder contains a <code>SKILL.md</code> file (and sometimes supporting reference files)</li> <li>Use the slash command (e.g., <code>/interview-analysis</code>) to trigger it</li> </ol>"},{"location":"resources/components/skills.html#research","title":"Research","text":"<p>Skills for designing studies, running interviews, and turning raw conversations into findings.</p> Skill What it does assumption-surfacing Surfaces hidden assumptions before research, planning, or scoping. Runs an interview-style session that maps what you know vs. what you're assuming. research-design Full research design pipeline: assumption surfacing, question design with Mom Test filter, instrument creation, and plan compilation. research-plan Compiles assumptions, instruments, and decision criteria into a stakeholder-ready research plan document. mom-test-filter Reviews interview questions against Mom Test principles. Flags questions that would get polite lies instead of truth. interview-extraction Runs parallel per-transcript extraction. One sub-agent per transcript, isolated context, consistent criteria across all files. interview-analysis Full interview pipeline end to end: extraction, verification, synthesis. One command for a complete batch of transcripts. interview-synthesis Cross-participant theme identification from verified extractions. Groups findings by described need, not labels. quote-verification Builder-validator pattern for research. A fresh agent checks every quoted claim against original source transcripts."},{"location":"resources/components/skills.html#building","title":"Building","text":"<p>Skills for creating artifacts, briefs, and presentations.</p> Skill What it does feature-brief Drafts a full feature brief from a name or idea, grounded in product context. Optional reviewer feedback from engineering, design, or strategy perspectives. frontend-slides Creates animation-rich HTML presentations from scratch or by converting PowerPoint files. Zero dependencies, single HTML file output. experiment-check Runs a contextual check-in on a running experiment. Reads the monitoring plan, checks metrics against success criteria and guardrails, and delivers a structured report."},{"location":"resources/components/skills.html#data","title":"Data","text":"<p>Skills for scraping, segmenting, and coding qualitative and quantitative data.</p> Skill What it does competitive-intel Orchestrates a full competitive intelligence pipeline: web research, review scraping, segmentation, inductive coding, and synthesis into a landscape brief. scrape-reviews Scrapes G2 product reviews using Apify actors. Saves structured review data as CSV with a consistent schema. segment-reviews Filters a review CSV by any field: company size, job title, date range, star rating, or verification status. Outputs a filtered subset. code-reviews Runs inductive coding on review pros and/or cons fields. Groups results by competitor with coded themes, definitions, and example quotes."},{"location":"resources/components/skills.html#documents","title":"Documents","text":"<p>Skills for processing meetings, drafting communications, and cleaning up AI writing.</p> Skill What it does meeting-aftermath One-command meeting processing. Runs six sub-skills in sequence: transcript processing, reality check, people updates, action items, follow-up drafts, and status update. process-transcript Extracts structured data from a meeting transcript: decisions, action items, key quotes, and follow-ups. draft-followups Drafts follow-up Slack messages and emails from meeting outcomes. Matches tone to each recipient using people files. status-update Generates a BLUF-format status update from meeting outputs. Under 200 words, ready to paste into Slack or email. humanizer Removes signs of AI-generated writing. Detects and fixes 24+ patterns including inflated symbolism, em dash overuse, and AI vocabulary. review-comments Finds all <code>{{comment}}</code> markers in a file and resolves each one by pulling from project context or asking for your judgment."},{"location":"resources/components/skills.html#os","title":"OS","text":"<p>Skills for building and maintaining your personal PM operating system.</p> Skill What it does os-audit Audits your personal OS and maps each area to the maturity framework. Reads your workspace, assesses what exists, and identifies gaps. sync-github Backs up your OS to a private GitHub repository. Walks through setup and handles the sync process."},{"location":"resources/components/skills.html#team","title":"Team","text":"<p>Skills for managing stakeholder information and tracking commitments.</p> Skill What it does update-people Proposes updates to people files based on meeting outcomes. Surfaces new preferences, concerns, and decisions per stakeholder. update-actions Cross-references meeting notes against existing action items. Proposes additions, completions, and reassignments. reality-check Compares what actually happened in a meeting against what people files predicted. The gaps reveal what's missing from your understanding of each stakeholder. meeting-cost Analyzes meeting cost by reading a schedule, estimating attendee salaries by role, and calculating total cost. Then suggests ways to reduce overhead."},{"location":"resources/components/skills.html#skill-composition","title":"Skill composition","text":"<p>Many of these skills work together. The <code>/meeting-aftermath</code> orchestrator, for example, chains six skills in sequence. The <code>/interview-analysis</code> skill chains extraction, verification, and synthesis. The <code>/competitive-intel</code> skill chains scraping, segmentation, and coding.</p> <p>You can also compose them yourself. Run <code>/assumption-surfacing</code> before <code>/research-design</code>. Run <code>/mom-test-filter</code> on your interview guide before going into the field. Run <code>/humanizer</code> on any document before sharing it.</p> <p>For more on how skill composition works, see Advanced Techniques in the Reference section.</p>"},{"location":"toolkit/index.html","title":"Tool Guides","text":"<p>Technical capabilities Claude Code unlocks for PMs. No engineering background required.</p> <p>The tools covered here used to require engineering support or dedicated technical skills. Claude Code makes them accessible. You don't need to master Git, Jupyter, or Mermaid syntax. You need to know what they can do for you and how to ask Claude to use them.</p>"},{"location":"toolkit/index.html#whats-here","title":"What's here","text":"<ul> <li> <p> Git &amp; GitHub for PMs</p> <p>Version control without the learning curve. Track changes, collaborate on docs, manage project files, and use GitHub as a sync and backup layer.</p> </li> <li> <p> Jupyter Notebooks</p> <p>Interactive data analysis and visualization. Ask Claude to build notebooks that explore your data, create charts, and tell a story with numbers.</p> </li> <li> <p> Diagrams &amp; Visuals</p> <p>Mermaid diagrams, flowcharts, sequence diagrams, and architecture visuals. Generated from descriptions, embedded in your docs.</p> </li> </ul>"},{"location":"toolkit/diagrams-and-visuals.html","title":"Diagrams &amp; Visuals","text":"<p>Mermaid diagrams, visual communication, and embedding diagrams directly in your documents. Describe what you want, Claude writes the code.</p> <p>Quick Answer</p> <p>Use this when: You need a diagram in a document -- architecture, flow, timeline, sequence, state machine -- and you do not want to open a separate diagramming tool.</p> <p>Avoid this when: You need pixel-perfect design work or brand-specific illustrations. Use Figma or AI image generation for those.</p> <p>What CC changes: Describe a process in plain English, get a rendered diagram back. No dragging boxes, no aligning arrows, no separate tool. The diagram lives inside your document and versions with git.</p> <p>Default move: Describe the flow or architecture you want. Claude writes the Mermaid code. Paste it in your markdown. It renders everywhere.</p>"},{"location":"toolkit/diagrams-and-visuals.html#why-mermaid","title":"Why Mermaid","text":"<p>Mermaid is a text-based diagram language. You write a description in a code block, and it renders as a visual diagram. GitHub renders it. VS Code renders it. Obsidian renders it. Anywhere you write markdown, Mermaid just works.</p> <pre><code>flowchart LR\n    DESC[\"Describe what\\nyou want\"] --&gt; CODE[\"Claude writes\\nMermaid code\"]\n    CODE --&gt; RENDER[\"Diagram renders\\nin your document\"]</code></pre> <p>The advantage over traditional diagramming tools:</p> Mermaid Traditional (Lucidchart, Figma, etc.) Text-based -- lives inside your markdown Link to an external tool Versions with git Separate file, separate version history Embeds in PRDs, status updates, decision docs \"See diagram in Lucidchart (link)\" Describe it in words, get a diagram Drag boxes, align arrows, fight the grid Updates in seconds -- change the text Open the tool, find the element, move things around <p>A PM who puts clean architecture diagrams in their PRD stands out with everyone in the room, not just the engineers.</p>"},{"location":"toolkit/diagrams-and-visuals.html#diagram-types","title":"Diagram Types","text":"<p>Mermaid supports several diagram types. Each one fits different PM communication needs.</p>"},{"location":"toolkit/diagrams-and-visuals.html#flowchart","title":"Flowchart","text":"<p>Best for: processes, decision trees, architecture.</p> <pre><code>flowchart TD\n    A[\"User clicks Upgrade\"] --&gt; B{Has payment method?}\n    B --&gt;|Yes| C[\"Show plan comparison\"]\n    B --&gt;|No| D[\"Collect payment info\"]\n    D --&gt; C\n    C --&gt; E[\"User selects plan\"]\n    E --&gt; F[\"Confirm and provision\"]\n</code></pre> <pre><code>flowchart TD\n    A[\"User clicks Upgrade\"] --&gt; B{Has payment method?}\n    B --&gt;|Yes| C[\"Show plan comparison\"]\n    B --&gt;|No| D[\"Collect payment info\"]\n    D --&gt; C\n    C --&gt; E[\"User selects plan\"]\n    E --&gt; F[\"Confirm and provision\"]</code></pre>"},{"location":"toolkit/diagrams-and-visuals.html#sequence-diagram","title":"Sequence Diagram","text":"<p>Best for: API flows, service interactions, multi-system processes.</p> <pre><code>sequenceDiagram\n    participant U as User\n    participant W as Wizard\n    participant API as Backend\n    participant E as Email\n\n    U-&gt;&gt;W: Start team setup\n    W-&gt;&gt;U: Ask team size\n    U-&gt;&gt;W: \"5 people\"\n    W-&gt;&gt;API: Create workspace\n    API--&gt;&gt;W: Workspace ID\n    W-&gt;&gt;E: Send invites\n    E--&gt;&gt;U: Invite emails sent\n</code></pre> <pre><code>sequenceDiagram\n    participant U as User\n    participant W as Wizard\n    participant API as Backend\n    participant E as Email\n\n    U-&gt;&gt;W: Start team setup\n    W-&gt;&gt;U: Ask team size\n    U-&gt;&gt;W: \"5 people\"\n    W-&gt;&gt;API: Create workspace\n    API--&gt;&gt;W: Workspace ID\n    W-&gt;&gt;E: Send invites\n    E--&gt;&gt;U: Invite emails sent</code></pre>"},{"location":"toolkit/diagrams-and-visuals.html#gantt-chart","title":"Gantt Chart","text":"<p>Best for: timelines, project schedules, experiment durations.</p> <pre><code>gantt\n    title Experiment Timeline\n    dateFormat  YYYY-MM-DD\n    section Setup\n    Instrumentation     :a1, 2025-01-06, 5d\n    QA &amp; validation     :a2, after a1, 3d\n    section Experiment\n    Ramp to 50%         :b1, after a2, 7d\n    Full rollout        :b2, after b1, 14d\n    section Analysis\n    Data collection     :c1, after b2, 3d\n    Final analysis      :c2, after c1, 5d\n</code></pre> <pre><code>gantt\n    title Experiment Timeline\n    dateFormat  YYYY-MM-DD\n    section Setup\n    Instrumentation     :a1, 2025-01-06, 5d\n    QA &amp; validation     :a2, after a1, 3d\n    section Experiment\n    Ramp to 50%         :b1, after a2, 7d\n    Full rollout        :b2, after b1, 14d\n    section Analysis\n    Data collection     :c1, after b2, 3d\n    Final analysis      :c2, after c1, 5d</code></pre>"},{"location":"toolkit/diagrams-and-visuals.html#state-diagram","title":"State Diagram","text":"<p>Best for: user states, feature states, lifecycle models.</p> <pre><code>stateDiagram-v2\n    [*] --&gt; Free\n    Free --&gt; Trial: Starts trial\n    Trial --&gt; Starter: Converts\n    Trial --&gt; Free: Trial expires\n    Starter --&gt; Growth: Upgrades\n    Starter --&gt; Churned: Cancels\n    Growth --&gt; Churned: Cancels\n    Churned --&gt; Starter: Reactivates\n</code></pre> <pre><code>stateDiagram-v2\n    [*] --&gt; Free\n    Free --&gt; Trial: Starts trial\n    Trial --&gt; Starter: Converts\n    Trial --&gt; Free: Trial expires\n    Starter --&gt; Growth: Upgrades\n    Starter --&gt; Churned: Cancels\n    Growth --&gt; Churned: Cancels\n    Churned --&gt; Starter: Reactivates</code></pre>"},{"location":"toolkit/diagrams-and-visuals.html#pie-chart","title":"Pie Chart","text":"<p>Best for: simple proportional breakdowns. Use sparingly -- tables are usually better for precise data.</p> <pre><code>pie title User Distribution by Plan\n    \"Free\" : 2400\n    \"Starter\" : 380\n    \"Growth\" : 45\n</code></pre> <pre><code>pie title User Distribution by Plan\n    \"Free\" : 2400\n    \"Starter\" : 380\n    \"Growth\" : 45</code></pre>"},{"location":"toolkit/diagrams-and-visuals.html#choosing-the-right-diagram-type","title":"Choosing the Right Diagram Type","text":"<pre><code>flowchart TD\n    Q[\"What are you\\ncommunicating?\"] --&gt; P{Type?}\n    P --&gt;|\"Process or\\ndecision tree\"| FL[\"Flowchart\"]\n    P --&gt;|\"Multi-system\\ninteraction\"| SQ[\"Sequence\\nDiagram\"]\n    P --&gt;|\"Timeline or\\nschedule\"| GA[\"Gantt Chart\"]\n    P --&gt;|\"User/feature\\nlifecycle\"| ST[\"State\\nDiagram\"]\n    P --&gt;|\"Simple\\nproportions\"| PI[\"Pie Chart\"]</code></pre> Need Diagram Type Example Show a process with decision points Flowchart Upgrade flow, onboarding steps Show how systems talk to each other Sequence diagram API flow, service architecture Show a timeline with dependencies Gantt chart Experiment schedule, launch plan Show states and transitions State diagram User lifecycle, feature rollout stages Show proportional breakdown Pie chart User distribution, revenue split"},{"location":"toolkit/diagrams-and-visuals.html#embedding-in-documents","title":"Embedding in Documents","text":"<p>Mermaid diagrams embed directly in markdown. Drop the code block in your PRD, status update, or decision doc and it renders inline.</p>  Bad  Good \"See architecture diagram (Lucidchart link)\" -- requires clicking out to another tool Mermaid diagram renders inline in the PRD. Reader sees it without leaving the doc. Diagram is a screenshot. Outdated within a week. Mermaid code updates in seconds. Change the text, diagram updates. Diagram lives in someone's personal Figma. Nobody knows where it is. Diagram lives in the markdown file. Versions with git. Always findable. <p>Where to embed diagrams:</p> <ul> <li>PRDs: Architecture comparisons, user flows, system interactions</li> <li>Status updates: Timeline progress, milestone tracking</li> <li>Decision docs: Option comparison flows, decision trees</li> <li>Experiment briefs: Experiment timeline, variant flow</li> <li>Onboarding docs: Process diagrams, architecture overview</li> </ul>"},{"location":"toolkit/diagrams-and-visuals.html#the-cc-advantage","title":"The CC Advantage","text":"<p>You do not need to learn Mermaid syntax. Describe what you want, Claude writes the code.</p> <pre><code>\"Write me a Mermaid flowchart showing the upgrade path\nfrom Free to Starter to Growth, with a decision node\nfor whether the user has a payment method.\"\n</code></pre> <p>Claude generates the Mermaid code. You paste it in your document. It renders. If you want changes, describe them in words.</p> <pre><code>\"Add a branch for users who came from an enterprise invite --\nthey skip the payment step.\"\n</code></pre> <p>Claude updates the code. The diagram updates. No dragging, no aligning, no fighting with a canvas.</p>"},{"location":"toolkit/diagrams-and-visuals.html#styling-tips","title":"Styling Tips","text":"<p>Mermaid supports basic styling to make diagrams clearer:</p> Technique Syntax When to Use Highlight a node <code>style NodeID fill:#fff4f0,stroke:#f74a4a</code> Draw attention to a specific step Shape for decisions <code>{Decision text}</code> (diamond) Decision points in flowcharts Shape for processes <code>[\"Process text\"]</code> (rectangle) Standard process steps Subgraphs <code>subgraph \"Group Name\"</code> Group related steps visually Link labels <code>--&gt;\\|\"label\"\\|</code> Explain what triggers each transition <p>Keep diagrams focused. If it needs more than 10-12 nodes, it is probably two diagrams.</p>"},{"location":"toolkit/diagrams-and-visuals.html#beyond-mermaid","title":"Beyond Mermaid","text":"<p>Mermaid handles structured diagrams well. For visuals that go beyond boxes and arrows:</p> Need Tool Structured diagrams (flows, sequences, timelines) Mermaid User journey illustrations, concept art AI image generation (Nano Banana, etc.) Pixel-perfect mockups Figma Data visualization (charts from real data) Jupyter Notebooks with matplotlib Full slide decks Frontend-slides skill or PowerPoint tools"},{"location":"toolkit/diagrams-and-visuals.html#plug-play","title":"Plug &amp; Play","text":"<p><code>/frontend-slides</code> Generates full HTML slide decks with embedded Mermaid diagrams, brand styling, and animations.</p> <p>Components: Templates Presentation outline template with guidance on when to use each diagram type.</p>"},{"location":"toolkit/diagrams-and-visuals.html#references","title":"References","text":"<p>Internal:</p> <ul> <li>Jupyter Notebooks : Data visualization with matplotlib for chart-based analysis</li> <li>Doc-as-Context : Documents where diagrams enhance the analytical interface</li> <li>Git &amp; GitHub for PMs : Mermaid diagrams version with git like any other text file</li> </ul> <p>External:</p> <ul> <li>Mermaid Documentation : Full syntax reference for all diagram types</li> <li>Mermaid Live Editor : Browser-based editor for testing Mermaid code</li> <li>Anthropic: Claude Code best practices : Guidance on visual output generation</li> </ul>"},{"location":"toolkit/git-and-github.html","title":"Git &amp; GitHub for PMs","text":"<p>Git is version control. It tracks every change you make, lets you undo anything, and makes sharing work with your team safe. You don't need to learn git commands. Claude Code handles the syntax. You just need to understand four concepts.</p> <p>Quick Answer</p> <p>Use this when: You're building anything in Claude Code that you want to save, share, or collaborate on.</p> <p>Avoid this when: Never. If you're using Claude Code, you should be using git.</p> <p>What CC changes: You never type git commands. You say \"commit my changes\" or \"create a PR\" and Claude does it. Git becomes invisible.</p> <p>Default move: Commit after every successful change. Branch before every experiment.</p>"},{"location":"toolkit/git-and-github.html#the-four-concepts","title":"The Four Concepts","text":"<p>Everything in git comes down to four operations. You already understand all of them from tools you use daily.</p> <pre><code>flowchart TD\n    A[\"Clone\\n(grab a copy)\"] --&gt; B[\"Edit\\n(make changes)\"]\n    B --&gt; C[\"Commit\\n(save a snapshot)\"]\n    C --&gt; D[\"Push\\n(share it back)\"]\n    D --&gt; E[\"Pull Request\\n(propose + review)\"]\n    E --&gt;|\"approved\"| F[\"Merge\"]\n    F --&gt;|\"next change\"| B</code></pre>"},{"location":"toolkit/git-and-github.html#clone-grab-a-copy","title":"Clone (grab a copy)","text":"<p>Download a project from GitHub to your computer. Like downloading a Google Doc, except you get the entire folder with full history.</p> <pre><code>Clone the team toolkit repo to my computer\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"toolkit/git-and-github.html#commit-save-a-snapshot","title":"Commit (save a snapshot)","text":"<p>Save your current changes with a short description. Like hitting \"save\" except every save is permanent and you can go back to any previous save.</p> <pre><code>Commit my changes with the message \"Add market risk question\nto the thinking framework\"\n</code></pre>  Bad commit message  Good commit message \"updates\" \"Add market risk question to think-it-through skill\" \"fix stuff\" \"Fix typo in prioritization rule description\" \"changes\" \"Update toolkit README to list new security rule\" <p>Claude Code writes commit messages for you when you say \"commit my changes.\" These examples show what good ones look like so you can judge the quality, but you'll rarely need to write them yourself.</p>"},{"location":"toolkit/git-and-github.html#push-share-it-back","title":"Push (share it back)","text":"<p>Send your commits to GitHub so others can see them.</p> <pre><code>Push my changes to GitHub\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"toolkit/git-and-github.html#pull-request-propose-review","title":"Pull Request (propose + review)","text":"<p>Instead of pushing directly to the shared version, you propose your changes. Others review them before they go live. Like suggesting an edit in Google Docs, but with a formal approval step.</p> <pre><code>Create a PR with the title \"Add market risk question\" and explain\nthat the VP flagged market consolidation risk in the Q2 meeting\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"toolkit/git-and-github.html#the-safety-net","title":"The Safety Net","text":"<p>Git gives you three layers of protection. This is why it matters for working with AI.</p> Layer What It Does How to Use It Commits Permanent save points you can return to \"Commit my changes\" after every successful step Branches Isolated copies for experiments \"Create a branch called experiment-pricing\" before trying something risky Diffs See exactly what changed \"Show me what changed since my last commit\""},{"location":"toolkit/git-and-github.html#commit-before-every-prompt","title":"Commit Before Every Prompt","text":"<p>This is the most important habit. Before you ask Claude to make the next change, commit what you have.</p> <p>Why: if Claude's next change breaks something, you can go back to the last commit. Without commits, you're stuck trying to untangle what went wrong.</p> <pre><code>Commit what we have so far, then let's try adding the\nnotification feature\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"toolkit/git-and-github.html#branch-before-every-experiment","title":"Branch Before Every Experiment","text":"<p>Branches let you try things without risking your working code. If the experiment works, merge it. If it doesn't, delete the branch. Main stays clean.</p> <pre><code>Create a new branch called \"test-new-layout\" and switch to it\n</code></pre> <p>CC Advantage</p> <p>You never have to remember branch commands. Say \"create a branch,\" \"switch back to main,\" \"merge this branch.\" Claude handles the syntax. The concepts matter, not the commands.</p>"},{"location":"toolkit/git-and-github.html#read-the-diff","title":"Read the Diff","text":"<p>After Claude makes changes, the diff shows you exactly what changed. This is your review step. You already know how to do this if you've ever looked at \"suggesting mode\" in Google Docs.</p> <pre><code>Show me what changed since the last commit\n</code></pre> <p>If the diff looks wrong, you can undo it:</p> <pre><code>Undo the last change and go back to the previous commit\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"toolkit/git-and-github.html#the-pr-workflow","title":"The PR Workflow","text":"<p>Pull requests are how you share changes with your team. Here's the complete cycle:</p> <pre><code>flowchart LR\n    B[\"Branch\"] --&gt; E[\"Edit\"]\n    E --&gt; C[\"Commit\"]\n    C --&gt; P[\"Push\"]\n    P --&gt; PR[\"Create PR\"]\n    PR --&gt; R[\"Review\"]\n    R --&gt;|\"approved\"| M[\"Merge\"]\n    R --&gt;|\"changes needed\"| E</code></pre> <p>In practice, this is one conversation with Claude:</p> <pre><code>Create a branch called \"add-security-question\". Add a question\nabout data security to the think-it-through skill. Commit,\npush, and create a PR explaining why we're adding it.\n</code></pre> <p>Claude does all of it: creates the branch, makes the edit, commits with a descriptive message, pushes, and opens the PR. You review the PR on GitHub to make sure it looks right, then merge.</p>"},{"location":"toolkit/git-and-github.html#what-you-dont-need-to-know","title":"What You Don't Need to Know","text":"<p>Git has hundreds of commands. PMs need about five concepts and zero memorized commands. Claude handles the rest.</p> <p>Skip these entirely:</p> <ul> <li>Git internals (objects, index, HEAD)</li> <li>Rebasing (too risky, rarely needed)</li> <li>Stashing (Claude can handle this if needed)</li> <li>Cherry-picking (advanced, not for daily PM work)</li> <li>Managing remotes or forks (the <code>/sync-github</code> skill handles setup)</li> </ul> <p>These will come up naturally as you need them:</p> <ul> <li>Merge conflicts (Claude resolves most of them automatically and asks you to confirm the result)</li> <li>Reverting commits (just say \"undo the last commit\")</li> <li>Viewing history (just say \"show me the recent changes\")</li> </ul>"},{"location":"toolkit/git-and-github.html#common-mistakes","title":"Common Mistakes","text":"Mistake What to Do Instead Not committing before the next prompt Commit after every successful change. This is your undo button Working directly on main Create a branch first. Main should always be in a working state Giant commits with 50 files Commit small, logical chunks. One commit per change, not one commit per day Vague commit messages (\"updates\") Describe what changed and why (\"Add market risk question after VP feedback\") Pushing without reviewing the diff Always look at what changed before pushing. \"Show me the diff\" takes 5 seconds Committing API keys or secrets Never commit <code>.env</code> files or credentials. Use <code>.gitignore</code> to exclude them"},{"location":"toolkit/git-and-github.html#setting-up-git","title":"Setting Up Git","text":"<p>If you haven't set up git yet, the <code>/sync-github</code> skill handles everything:</p> <pre><code>Run /sync-github\n</code></pre> <p>It checks if git is initialized, creates a <code>.gitignore</code> with sensible defaults, creates a private GitHub repo, and pushes your first commit. You'll need the GitHub CLI (<code>gh</code>) installed. Claude will prompt you to install it if it's missing.</p>"},{"location":"toolkit/git-and-github.html#plug-play","title":"Plug &amp; Play","text":"<p><code>/sync-github</code> One-command backup. Initializes git, creates a private repo, commits everything, and pushes. Run it whenever you want to save your work.</p>"},{"location":"toolkit/git-and-github.html#references","title":"References","text":"<p>Internal:</p> <ul> <li>Shipping Code : The full git workflow for building features (branches, PRs, reviews)</li> <li>Team Toolkit : Setting up a shared repo for distributing skills across your team</li> <li>Building Skills : Skills committed to <code>.claude/skills/</code> auto-distribute via git</li> </ul> <p>External:</p> <ul> <li>The Non-Technical Guide to Git for Product Managers : Yanet Morales Ramirez's beginner-friendly walkthrough</li> <li>Git for Vibe Coders and Non-Programmers : Practical guide for people using AI coding tools</li> <li>Automate Your AI Workflows with Claude Code Hooks : GitButler's guide to git safety hooks with Claude Code</li> <li>Parallel Claude Code Sessions : Running multiple Claude sessions with GitButler branches</li> <li>GitHub: Getting started : Official GitHub documentation for beginners</li> <li>Anthropic: Claude Code best practices : Official guidance including git workflows</li> <li>Anthropic: Common workflows : Step-by-step guides for everyday Claude Code tasks</li> </ul>"},{"location":"toolkit/jupyter-notebooks.html","title":"Jupyter Notebooks","text":"<p>Data analysis as a PM superpower. Every chart has the code that made it, every number is traceable, and your VP can read it top to bottom.</p> <p>Quick Answer</p> <p>Use this when: You need to analyze data and present findings where every number is traceable. Launch reviews, experiment check-ins, funnel diagnostics, any data-driven PM work.</p> <p>Avoid this when: You just need a quick summary of a dataset. A regular conversation with Claude handles that. Notebooks are for when traceability and presentation matter.</p> <p>What CC changes: Claude writes the Python code, creates the charts, and structures the narrative. You describe what you want to analyze, Claude builds the notebook. Your VP reads top to bottom. Code cells prove the analysis.</p> <p>Default move: Point Claude at a brief plus a CSV and ask for a notebook. The brief defines what to measure, the data provides the numbers, the notebook makes it traceable.</p>"},{"location":"toolkit/jupyter-notebooks.html#why-notebooks","title":"Why Notebooks","text":"<p>The biggest question PMs have about doing analysis with Claude: how can you trust it? If your VP asks where you got those numbers, you cannot just say \"Claude did the analysis.\"</p> <p>Jupyter notebooks solve this. Every chart has the code that made it right above it. Your analysts can audit it. Stakeholders can trace any number. You are not asking people to trust the AI -- you are showing them the work.</p> <p>And it keeps Claude honest. Claude cannot hallucinate a number when the code that produced it is sitting right there.</p> <pre><code>flowchart TD\n    Q[\"PM's Question\\n'How is Growth doing?'\"] --&gt; NB[\"Jupyter Notebook\"]\n\n    subgraph \"Three Layers\"\n        MD[\"Markdown Cell\\nNarrative: what &amp; why\"]\n        CD[\"Code Cell\\nComputation: how\"]\n        OU[\"Output Cell\\nResults: the proof\"]\n    end\n\n    NB --&gt; MD\n    MD --&gt; CD\n    CD --&gt; OU\n\n    OU --&gt; VP[\"VP reads top to bottom\\nEvery number traceable\"]</code></pre>"},{"location":"toolkit/jupyter-notebooks.html#the-three-cell-types","title":"The Three Cell Types","text":"<p>A notebook has three types of cells. Together they create a complete audit trail from question to conclusion.</p> Cell Type What It Contains Who It Serves Markdown Narrative, headings, explanations. The story layer. Anyone reading the notebook. Sets up the question before the code answers it. Code Python that runs the analysis. The proof layer. Analysts and anyone who wants to verify. Output Charts, tables, numbers. The result layer. Everyone. The visual answer to the question. <pre><code>+----------------------------------+\n|  Markdown    what &amp; why          |\n|  \u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500 |\n|  Code        how                 |\n|  \u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500 |\n|  Output      the proof           |\n+----------------------------------+\n     anyone can follow the trail\n</code></pre>  Bad (No Notebook)  Good (Notebook) \"Conversion dropped 12%\" in a Slack message. VP asks: \"Where'd you get that?\" Notebook cell shows the exact query, filter, and calculation. VP opens it and sees the proof. Claude says \"retention is 85%.\" You trust it and share it. Turns out the filter was wrong. Code cell shows the filter. Analyst catches the error before it reaches leadership. Charts in a Google Doc with no source. \"Who made this? Is this current?\" Chart renders from code. Re-run the cell with new data and the chart updates."},{"location":"toolkit/jupyter-notebooks.html#setup","title":"Setup","text":"<p>Claude handles the setup. The standard stack:</p> Tool What It Does Python 3 The language that runs notebooks uv Fast Python package manager jupyter The notebook engine pandas Data manipulation library matplotlib Charting library <p>Claude handles setup automatically when you ask it to create a notebook. If you want to set up the environment ahead of time:</p> <p>Tell Claude: \"Set up a Python environment with Jupyter, pandas, and matplotlib.\" Claude installs everything in a virtual environment that stays isolated from your system.</p>"},{"location":"toolkit/jupyter-notebooks.html#what-a-good-notebook-looks-like","title":"What a Good Notebook Looks Like","text":"<p>Structure matters. A notebook is a PM deliverable, not a data science scratch pad.</p> <pre><code>flowchart TD\n    ES[\"Executive Summary\\n(markdown)\"] --&gt; S1[\"Section 1: Metric A\\n(markdown + code + chart)\"]\n    S1 --&gt; S2[\"Section 2: Metric B\\n(markdown + code + chart)\"]\n    S2 --&gt; S3[\"Section 3: Guardrails\\n(markdown + code + chart)\"]\n    S3 --&gt; REC[\"Recommendations\\n(markdown)\"]</code></pre> <p>The pattern for each section:</p> <ol> <li>Markdown cell: State the question and why it matters</li> <li>Code cell: Load the data, apply the filter, run the calculation</li> <li>Output cell: Chart or table that answers the question</li> <li>Markdown cell: Interpret the result in plain language</li> </ol>  Bad Notebook  Good Notebook 20 code cells with no explanation Every code cell has a markdown cell above it explaining what it does and why Raw dataframe dumps with no context Clean charts with titles, labels, and callout text No executive summary -- reader must scroll through everything Executive summary at the top with key findings and recommendation Conclusions buried in code comments Conclusions in markdown cells that non-technical readers can follow <p>Example structure for a launch review:</p> <pre><code># Growth Plan Launch Review\n\n## Executive Summary\n[Key findings, caveats, recommendation]\n\n## Adoption\n[Question: How many users converted to Growth?]\n[Code: user counts, signup rate]\n[Chart: adoption over time]\n[Interpretation: 45 users in 2 weeks, promising but small sample]\n\n## Retention\n[Question: Are Growth users sticking around?]\n[Code: 7-day, 14-day retention by cohort]\n[Chart: retention curves]\n[Interpretation: Solid early signal, need more time]\n\n## Guardrails\n[Question: Did anything break?]\n[Code: overall conversion trend]\n[Chart: conversion before vs. after launch]\n[Interpretation: Free-to-Paid conversion dropped -- needs investigation]\n\n## Recommendations\n[Next steps based on the analysis]\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"toolkit/jupyter-notebooks.html#the-trust-layer","title":"The Trust Layer","text":"<p>Notebooks are the trust layer for AI-driven analysis. They address the three questions every stakeholder asks:</p> Question How Notebooks Answer It \"Where'd you get that number?\" Open the notebook. The code cell shows the exact data source, filter, and calculation. \"Is this current?\" Re-run the notebook with fresh data. Charts update automatically. \"Can I trust this?\" Your analyst can audit every cell. The code is the proof. <p>This is the CC advantage for PMs: Claude writes the code, you get the traceability. Your VP reads the narrative top to bottom. Your data team audits the code. Everyone trusts the output because everyone can verify it.</p>"},{"location":"toolkit/jupyter-notebooks.html#notebooks-as-pm-deliverables","title":"Notebooks as PM Deliverables","text":"<p>Notebooks are not just for analysis. They are the deliverable you share.</p> Deliverable What the Notebook Contains Launch review Success metrics, guardrail checks, executive summary Funnel diagnostic Step-by-step conversion analysis, drop-off identification Experiment check-in Primary metrics, secondary metrics, guardrails, qualitative cross-reference Recommendation Options modeled with revenue math, sensitivity analysis Weekly metrics report Key metrics with trend analysis and anomaly flags <pre><code>Tell Claude:\n\n\"Load @usage-data.csv and create a launch review notebook\nbased on the analysis plan from @growth-launch-brief.md\"\n\nClaude reads the brief, finds the success metrics and\nguardrails, and builds a notebook that evaluates each one.\n</code></pre> <p>This is the Doc-as-Context pattern in action. The brief defines what to measure. The notebook measures it. Every number traceable.</p>"},{"location":"toolkit/jupyter-notebooks.html#working-with-notebooks-in-your-editor","title":"Working With Notebooks in Your Editor","text":"<p>Notebooks (<code>.ipynb</code> files) render directly in VS Code and Cursor. You see the markdown, code, and output all in one view.</p> Action How Run a cell Click the play button next to the code cell Run all cells Click \"Run All\" in the toolbar Add a cell Click the + button between cells Switch cell type Toggle between Markdown and Code in the cell toolbar Select a kernel When prompted, pick the Python environment (usually <code>.venv</code>) <p>If your editor asks you to select a kernel on first run, pick the recommended option. That is just telling the notebook which Python to use.</p>"},{"location":"toolkit/jupyter-notebooks.html#plug-play","title":"Plug &amp; Play","text":"<p><code>/experiment-check</code> Creates a contextual check-in notebook from an experiment brief.</p> <p>Components: Templates Launch review template, diagnostic funnel template, and other analysis-ready documents.</p>"},{"location":"toolkit/jupyter-notebooks.html#references","title":"References","text":"<p>Internal:</p> <ul> <li>Doc-as-Context : The pattern that makes notebooks powerful -- the brief defines the analysis</li> <li>Diagrams &amp; Visuals : Mermaid diagrams complement notebook charts</li> <li>Git &amp; GitHub for PMs : Version-control your notebooks alongside your other work</li> </ul> <p>External:</p> <ul> <li>Jupyter Documentation : Official Jupyter project docs</li> <li>Pandas Documentation : Data manipulation library reference</li> <li>Anthropic: Claude Code best practices : Context management for analytical work</li> </ul>"}]}